<SLUG> BC-BBA-ANGELS-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
ANGELS GET THREE FOR SECOND BASE
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By JOE HAAKENSON  
 San Gabriel Valley Tribune  
<TEXT>
<P>
   After last season's trade of Randy Velarde to Oakland, the
Anaheim Angels finished the season with Double-A player Trent
Durrington at second base. Friday, they signed three second basemen
in an effort to find someone who can be productive at that
position.
</P>
<P>
   The Angels signed Scott Spiezio to a major-league contract, and
signed Pat Kelly and Jason Bates to minor-league contracts for the
2000 season.
</P>
<P>
   Spiezio, who was added to the 40-man roster, split time between
Oakland and the A's Triple-A affiliate in Vancouver in 1999. In 89
games for the A's, Spiezio, 27, hit .243 with eight homers and 33
RBI.
</P>
<P>
   ``One of our goals during this offseason was to develop depth at
the second base position,'' Angels general manager Bill Stoneman
said. ``With the addition of these three players, we expect good
competition in the infield during spring training.''
</P>
<P>
   Kelly, 31, played in 37 games for the Blue Jays last season,
hitting .267 with six homers and 20 RBI. Kelly has also played with
the Yankees and Cardinals.
</P>
<P>
   Bates, 28, was in the Tigers organization last season but did
not play because of bone spurs in his left foot. He played from
1995-98 with the Colorado Rockies, hitting .239 in 319 games.
</P>
<P>
   Kelly and Bates will attend spring training as non-roster
invitees.
</P>
</TEXT>
