<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BKN-KNICKS-MAGIC-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
KNICKS SURVIVE ORLANDO, 94-86 
</HEADLINE>
  (mk) 
 By SELENA ROBERTS   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   ORLANDO, Fla. _ The New York Knicks tried to clamp down on their
prosperity as tightly as on a chew toy Friday night, but they
nearly allowed the aggressive Orlando Magic to tear it away.
</P>
<P>
   The Knicks held a 16-point lead with five and a half minutes
left in the game, and watched it melt to six before squeezing by
with a 94-86 victory, their third straight. Although they were
slow-footed on most rebounds, getting beaten on the boards, 58-39,
the Knicks were able to counter the energy of the Magic by
unleashing Allan Houston (23 points), Latrell Sprewell (19 points)
and Patrick Ewing (18 points) on the home team. The Knicks' wave of
talent saved them from humiliation at the Orlando Arena.
</P>
<P>
   Over the last month, the Knicks have allowed six double-digit
leads to evaporate and have turned apparent blowouts into narrow
escapes or losses. This time the Knicks held the Magic to just 35
percent shooting from the field but could not overcome their
penchant for mishandling advantages. With 1 minute 39 seconds
remaining, Darrell Armstrong hit two free throws to cut the Knicks'
lead to 92-84.
</P>
<P>
   A traveling call on Larry Johnson with 1:15 remaining gave the
Magic hope. The rookie Corey Maggette then hit a jumper with 52
seconds left to pull Orlando to 92-86.
</P>
<P>
   After Ewing missed two free throws with 35 seconds to play, the
Knicks (20-12) were able to prevent the Magic (16-17) from pulling
off a miracle finish by shutting it down in its last two
possessions.
</P>
<P>
   The Magic's group of misfits from around the world _ highlighted
by a Continental Basketball Association castaway, Armstrong, and a
European find out of Penn State, John Amaechi _ began by showing
the Knicks how the hunger of the unknowns could keep up with their
hefty-priced talent.
</P>
<P>
   The Magic players embarrassed the Knicks as they scraped up
enough extra shots to stay close, down by just 41-40 at the half.
Once again, the low-energy Knicks were lethargic and trailed the
athletic Magic on the boards, 33-22, including 12-3 in offensive
rebounding.
</P>
<P>
   Once the Knicks picked up their energy and began to create some
opportunities by forcing the Magic into bad shots and untimely
turnovers, they were able to take a 75-64 lead after the third
quarter.
</P>
<P>
   Sprewell, who went 1 for 7 in the first half, was a big part of
the personality boost. Much more alive after halftime, he shot 5
for 6 in the third quarter and played harder on defense.
</P>
<P>
   Unearthing that kind of drive was a long process, though. The
Knicks labored through the first half, particularly on the
offensive boards. Marcus Camby, usually the Knicks' energetic
weapon, was of little help because of early foul trouble, a problem
that has plagued him for two weeks.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
