<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-EDIT-GAY-TROOPS-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
EDITORIAL: THE DEBATE OVER GAY TROOPS 
</HEADLINE>
  (mk) 
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   The New York Times said in an editorial for Saturday, Jan. 8:
</P>
<P>
   Both Democratic presidential candidates, Vice President Al Gore
and former Sen. Bill Bradley, said strongly and unequivocally this
week that they would allow gays to serve openly in the military.
That is the only fair and rational course now that five years of
experience has shown the compromise policy of ``don't ask, don't
tell'' to be a failure that should be abolished.
</P>
<P>
   There appeared at first to be a subtle but important difference
between the two Democrats in the debate Wednesday night. Gore said
he would require in advance that his appointees to the Joint Chiefs
of Staff be in agreement with his position. Bradley had the better
formulation, saying simply that he would expect his appointees to
carry out the policy of their commander in chief on gays in the
military. That put the emphasis where it belongs, on the need for
military obedience to lawful orders rather than on the personal
beliefs of the officers. On Friday Gore adjusted his stance by
asserting that he did not intend to ask nominees for the Joint
Chiefs or other high military positions about their personal views
or ideology on this or any other issue. He said he, too, would
simply expect them to follow orders.
</P>
<P>
   The Republican candidates, by contrast, all oppose lifting the
ban on openly gay troops. Sen. John McCain said he would retain the
``don't ask, don't tell'' policy. He asserted that it was working
despite ample evidence that it has accelerated the dismissal of gay
service members. Gov. George W. Bush of Texas also said he backed
``don't ask, don't tell,'' but made things worse by inventing a
litmus test against liberalizing the policy. He said he would not
appoint anyone to the Joint Chiefs who advocated allowing gays to
serve openly in the military, thus elevating bigotry as a defining
criterion for selecting military leaders.
</P>
<P>
   The Democratic candidates are taking a risk in standing up for
principle on this issue. But by asserting the primacy of civilian
command, they may be able to avoid the trouble that befell
President Clinton. Clinton supported ending the ban on gay troops.
But once in office he was forced to retreat because Gen. Colin
Powell, then chairman of the Joint Chiefs, and others publicly
denounced that policy. Congress later blocked the lifting of the
ban and wrote ``don't ask, don't tell'' into law.
</P>
<P>
   A new president who wants to change the policy would have to
work with Congress to rewrite the law. But the starting point has
to be a presidential commitment to the right of gay people to serve
on an equal basis in the armed forces.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
