<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BKC-UCLA-ANALYSIS-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
UCLA FACES DESPERATE SITUATION EARLY
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By JON WILNER  
 c.2000 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   BELLEVUE, Wash. _ UCLA guard Earl Watson tossed and turned
Thursday night before dozing off at 4 a.m. Coach Steve Lavin
watched the disturbing game film until 2:30 a.m., then stared at
the ceiling for hours. After three years, he knows every nook and
cranny.
</P>
<P>
   Pacific Northwest insomnia has become as common for the Bruins
as suspensions, injuries, first-round losses and NCAA
investigations. It's part of the chaos that's consumed the program
since the 1995 NCAA championship.
</P>
<P>
   In the Lavin era, the Bruins are 4-6 at Oregon, Oregon State and
Washington. That includes a wrenching 63-62 loss Thursday night in
Seattle, where they haven't won in four years.
</P>
<P>
   Nor have they dominated today's opponent, Washington State, with
three victories by a combined seven points. And if they aren't
careful this afternoon, they'll depart the dreary, wind-swept
Palouse 0-2 in conference play. Washington State isn't very good,
but neither is Washington.
</P>
<P>
   ``The main thing is to make sure we get rid of that loss and not
let it linger,'' senior forward Sean Farnham said. ``No matter what
happened with USC and Washington State (the Trojans won handily),
we know Washington State will give us their best effort.
</P>
<P>
   ``Our focus is solely on Washington State. We can't look ahead
to USC (next week) and we can't look behind to Washington ... That
was a huge loss, but if we don't move on, it'll be a long season.''
</P>
<P>
   Resiliency is as much a part of UCLA's character as sloppiness
and lethargy. Three years ago, the Bruins lost at Stanford by a
school-record 48 points but recovered to defeat Cal two days later.
Last season, they lost 65-63 at Oregon State, then responded with a
65-63 victory over Oregon behind Baron Davis' 22 points.
</P>
<P>
   But rarely has the situation seemed so desperate in part because
the Bruins (8-3, 0-1) don't have Davis, in part because they've
performed poorly against mediocre opponents that force them to win
with fundamentals, not athletic ability.
</P>
<P>
   The Bruins committed 19 turnovers against Washington's passive
zone defense. (Inexcusable.) They shot 42 percent from the field.
They made 9 of 19 free throws. They scored just six points in a
6:28 stretch late in the game.
</P>
<P>
   Defensively, the Bruins had one assignment _ stop Huskies gunner
Deon Luton _ and didn't come close. Luton scored 26 points and hit
the big shots while his teammates were a pathetic 14 of 46 from the
field. Time and again, UCLA defenders were out of position, a sign
they were poorly prepared for Washington's half-court attack.
</P>
<P>
   ``We knew he had to have that kind of game to beat us,'' Lavin
said. ``That's disappointing. We had the information and couldn't
apply it.
</P>
<P>
   ``My biggest concerns are free throws, having better execution
in late-game situations, taking better shots in late-game
situations, and turnovers.
</P>
<P>
   ``If you shoot 42 percent on free throws on the road and have 19
turnovers in a limited-possession game, then you're digging a
deeper hole.''
</P>
<P>
   Most of all, Thursday's defeat reduced the Bruins' margin for
error. They must win 10 of their last 19 to reach the 18-victory
plateau that should secure an NCAA Tournament bid. That won't be
easy considering the upcoming schedule: at USC and North Carolina
next week, then Arizona, then a trip to Oregon, then Stanford. If
the Bruins don't correct their problems quickly, they'll be 11-9
after the first round of league play.
</P>
<P>
   ``No question, we're in a very tough stretch,'' Lavin said. ``My
feeling is we have 19 games left and the majority will be like this
... dogfights.''
</P>
<P>
   It's a bit early in the season for must-win games, but that's
exactly what the Bruins face today against the worst team in the
Pac-10. Forget the conference title; an invitation to March Madness
depends on it.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm worried about getting back on the right track,'' Watson
said. ``We can't keep losing every three or four games. We're in a
bad position for the Pac-10.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-01-08-00 0020EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
