A0155 &Cx1f; kan-z
r a BC-CELLPHONES2TAKES-KAN &LR;      01-08 0906
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CELL </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
KC STATE REPRESENTATIVE INTRODUCES CELL PHONE RESTRICTION BILL 
</HEADLINE>
 PHONES 2TAKES-KAN   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By LORI O'TOOLE and KATIE HOLLAR  
<TEXT>
<P>
   KANSAS CITY, Mo. _Kathy Bremer quit using her cellular phone in
the car after she caught herself zipping through a red light, right
past a police officer.
</P>
<P>
   She didn't hit anyone, and she didn't get a ticket. But the
experience was a powerful lesson, and she no longer uses the cell
phone while driving.
</P>
<P>
   ``Not a smart thing for me to do,'' said Bremer, a Kansas City
resident and cellular user for more than five years. ``I could have
hurt someone.''
</P>
<P>
   Joining a growing national trend, a Missouri legislator has
introduced a bill aimed at cutting down on the potential for
accidents caused by drivers using cell phones.
</P>
<P>
   Rep. Marsha Campbell, a Kansas City Democrat, said her bill
would prohibit the use of cellular telephones while driving, except
in emergencies. Violation of the law, a misdemeanor, would be
punishable by either a $500 fine or six months in jail, or both. If
a cellular user caused an accident, the consequences would be a
$1,000 fine or one year in jail, or both.
</P>
<P>
   ``To have a cell phone in the car is a great safety measure,''
Campbell said. ``I have a cell phone, and I like it. But I'm not
sure if anyone's phone call is worth another's life.''
</P>
<P>
   Campbell said she always pulled over to use her phone and
suggested that others do the same.
</P>
<P>
   She decided to introduce a bill after some constituents
contacted her about restricting cell phone use. During her morning
walks and commutes to the capital, she, too, had noticed
absent-minded drivers using cell phones.
</P>
<P>
   Campbell's cell phone bill makes Missouri one of 11 states
considering such legislation. The National Conference of State
Legislatures says that last year, 22 states considered legislation
regarding cell phones and driving. The proposals vary, from
complete bans to mandating proper use of cell phones.
</P>
<P>
   In eight states, cell phone legislation has failed, but laws
were passed in California, Florida and Massachusetts. None of the
three states has a complete ban; in Massachusetts, for example,
drivers who do not keep at least one hand on the wheel while using
a cell phone may face fines of $35 to $150, depending on whether
they have previous violations.
</P>
<P>
   No similar bill has been proposed in Kansas.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's definitely an issue that's gaining momentum among state
legislators,'' said Matt Sundeen, transportation policy specialist
for Denver-based National Conference of State Legislatures. Sundeen
has been tracking such legislation for two years.
</P>
<P>
   ``The sheer volume of cell phone use is causing representatives
to be more concerned,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   That volume is considerable: The federal Department of
Transportation estimates that 80 million cellular phones will be in
use this year nationwide. In the Kansas City area, 43.7 percent of
residents had cell phones in 1999, according to research by the
Minnesota Opinion Research Institute for The Kansas City Star.
</P>
<P>
   Nationally, 85 percent of cell phone users talk in the car,
according to the National Highway Traffic Safety Administration. In
1998, the agency studied the correlation between cell phone use and
traffic accidents. Researchers found that cell phones were major
contributors to the most common cause of accidents: inattention.
While cell phone users were busy dialing, conversing, answering the
phone or hanging up, their attention simply was not on the road.
</P>
<P>
   In Missouri, driver inattention contributed to 754 accident
deaths, 47,064 injuries and 78,722 instances of property damage in
1998, said Sgt. John Hotz of the Missouri Highway Patrol. Hotz said
cellular phone use was one of many causes of driver inattention.
</P>
<P>
   But that's not the only problem researchers have found related
to driving and using a cellular phone. In Finland, where cellular
phones are more popular than in the United States, another study
concluded last year that talking on a cell phone resulted in an
average half-second delay in brake reaction whether a hands-free
phone or a hand-held phone was used.
</P>
<P>
   A 1991 study funded by the American Automobile Association found
that 151 subjects in simulated driving situations failed to respond
or had slower response times to traffic situations with hand-held
or hands-free cellular phones.
</P>
<P>
   The study participants failed to respond 30 percent of the time
while using cell phones.
</P>
<P>
   The more intense the phone conversation, the slower the response
time became. Even those who used a cell phone often had delayed
response times.
</P>
<P>
   The National Highway Traffic Safety Administration report
detailed a number of cell phone-related accidents. In a majority of
the cases, the cell phone users struck cars or other large objects
in clear view.
</P>
<P>
   Such accidents can be serious, even fatal. Two Missouri fatal
car wrecks were traced to cellular phone use in 1995, the report
said.
</P>
<P>
   In January 1998, a truck driver talking on a cellular phone in
Portland, Ore., drove his truck into the path of an oncoming
freight train, according to The Oregonian newspaper. He was killed
instantly.
</P>
<P>
   Just two months ago, a 2-year-old girl in Hilltown, Pa., was
killed when the car in which she was riding was struck by a driver
who ran a stop sign while using a cell phone, according to the
Tri-State Media News Network.
(MORE)
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
