A0156 &Cx1f; kan-z
r a BC-CELLPHONES2NDTAKE-KAN     01-08 0570
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CELL </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
KC STATE REPRESENTATIVE INTRODUCES CELL PHONE RESTRICTION BILL 
</HEADLINE>
 PHONES 2ND TAKE-KAN   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By LORI O'TOOLE and KATIE HOLLAR  
<TEXT>
<P>
   KANSAS CITY, Mo. _ Although area police departments don't keep
data specifically on accidents caused by cellular phone use, phone
calls and driving can be a bad combination, said Sgt. Randy Sims of
the Kansas City Police Department.
</P>
<P>
   ``There have been some accidents where the person will say,
`Yeah, it's my fault. I was talking on my cell phone and not paying
attention,' &UR; '' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Sims said Campbell's bill would be a good safety measure, but it
would be difficult to enforce, especially with hands-free phones.
</P>
<P>
   ``You couldn't tell if they were talking to themselves or
singing,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Officer Bill Pross, Independence police spokesman, agreed. He
said his department did not have the resources to enforce such a
law.
</P>
<P>
   ``We focus on the things that we know lead to serious car
crashes: speed, failing to yield right of way, following too
closely,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Pross said he did not see the need for such a bill because
driver inattentiveness comes from many different sources.
</P>
<P>
   ``On the way to work, there's women applying makeup, men
shaving,'' he said. ``I don't see any distinction.''
</P>
<P>
   Neither does Stephanie Faul, communications director of AAA
Foundation for Traffic Safety in Washington, who said legislators
focused too much on cell phones as hazards.
</P>
<P>
   ``The truth is, people are distracted all the time,'' Faul said.
``People are using cell phones, eating Big Macs, fiddling with CDs,
yelling at kids in the back seat. People just aren't paying
attention.''
</P>
<P>
   The solution, say cellular phone dealers, is education, not
legislation.
</P>
<P>
   Wireless carriers place a priority on customer education, said
Tom Murphy, spokesman for Sprint PCS. Sprint customers receive a
packet from the Cellular Telecommunication Industry Association
offering safety tips.
</P>
<P>
   ``We've supported safe driving since day one,'' he said. ``We
take it very, very seriously. But we don't believe legislation is
the answer.''
</P>
<P>
   Murphy said that the Missouri bill was not in the public
interest and that Sprint would lobby against it.
</P>
<P>
   ``Wireless phones do too much good for people who use them in
their vehicle,'' he said. ``People call police when they see a
drunk driver. People call 911.''
</P>
<P>
   Campbell's bill has not been assigned to a committee, and formal
debate has not begun. She could not predict the bill's odds for
adoption, but said she had received a lot of supportive e-mails and
letters from constituents. In addition, ``quite a few'' legislators
have told her they agree with the need.
</P>
<P>
   ``There have been some who agree in general, but they think it
needs some work,'' she said ``That's typical. Rarely do you come up
with a perfect bill.''
</P>
<P>
   Bremer, the reformed cell phone user, said she had mixed
feelings about the proposed bill. Banning cell phone use while
behind the wheel would be a good safety measure, she said, but she
isn't sure it should be a crime.
</P>
<P>
   ``I have a litle girl,'' she said. ``Talking on the cell phone
with her in the car is just an accident waiting to happen. But I
don't think it's worth a ticket.''
</P>
<P>
   The cellular phone legislation is HB1184 (Campbell). Legislation
is available on the Missouri General Assembly site at http:
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
