<SLUG> BC-FBN-HOUSTON-CASSERLY-HNS </SLUG>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
McNair, Casserly talk as Saints hold breath
<TEXT>
<P>
   By JOHN McCLAIN
</P>
<P>
   Houston Chronicle
</P>
<P>
   Although they had spoken on the telephone several times since
Houston defeated Los Angeles for the NFL's 32nd franchise, Bob
McNair and former Washington Redskins general manager Charley
Casserly had their first face-to-face meeting Friday.
</P>
<P>
   Casserly was the first candidate interviewed by McNair for the
job of vice president of football operations, which will be the
most important position in the front office of Houston's expansion
team.
</P>
<P>
   Casserly, who is the No. 1 candidate of New Orleans owner Tom
Benson, interviewed with McNair and executive vice president Steve
Patterson on Friday.
</P>
<P>
   ``There's a window of opportunity for us to talk with Charley
and other candidates,'' McNair said after almost a full day of
interviewing Casserly. ``Because teams are looking for good people
_ and I'm not talking about New Orleans specifically _ the window's
small, and it's compressed the time a little bit.
</P>
<P>
   ``There's a limited amount of time in which this game of musical
chairs plays out.''
</P>
<P>
   Until new Redskins owner Daniel Snyder fired him before the
season, Casserly had spent his entire NFL career with Washington,
working his way up the organization from getting coffee for former
coach George Allen to becoming the general manager of a Super Bowl
champion.
</P>
<P>
   Casserly earned three Super Bowl rings with the Redskins.
</P>
<P>
   ``I kind of like that,'' McNair said about Casserly having Super
Bowl rings. ``I'm impressed by that.
</P>
<P>
   ``You want somebody who's been with a successful organization,
someone who's accustomed to winning and doing things in a
first-class manner. Charley's got those kind of (credentials).''
</P>
<P>
   Reports in New Orleans say Benson is ready to make Casserly the
Saints' president/chief executive officer/general manager, which
means he would be in charge of the entire organization, including
the personnel and administrative sides.
</P>
<P>
   ``I've said all along that Houston's going to be a premier
franchise,'' Casserly said. ``I'm excited about the opportunity to
interview in Houston. I think if we started now, we'd have a better
chance for the future.
</P>
<P>
   ``You're flattered when people are interested, but you have to
use good judgment when trying to make the best decisions. In this
process, I'm taking it one day at a time. We'll just have to wait
and see what happens.''
</P>
<P>
   McNair plans to interview other candidates, including Joe Mack,
who worked in Washington, Carolina and Cleveland.
</P>
<P>
   $$$
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-01-08-00 0105EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
