<SLUG> BC-WORKERS-COMP-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
WORKER'S COMP COSTS JUMP
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By Dereck Andrade  
 c.2000 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   Workers' compensation insurance premiums statewide have
skyrocketed 18 percent to 25 percent during the first week of 2000
in what industry officials say is a reflection of the true cost of
doing business -- and insuring businesses -- in the state.
</P>
<P>
   Industry officials say the startling rate hikes were endorsed by
the state Insurance Commissioner's Office, but officials with the
agency say they didn't force the companies to increase premiums.
</P>
<P>
   ``We have advocated a rate increase of 18.4 percent, but we
don't have the authority to tell (insurance companies) to raise
their rates by that much,'' said Tim Taylor, a legislative analyst
with the Insurance Commissioner's Office.
</P>
<P>
   While not mandatory, the proposed decision signed Oct. 29 by
Michael A. Kelly, chief deputy to Insurance Commissioner Chuck
Quackenbush, does give the green light for an increase of nearly 20
percent to any insurance company that filed plans with the agency
by Dec. 31 to raise its rates.
</P>
<P>
   Neither Quackenbush nor Kelly returned messages left at their
offices this week.
</P>
<P>
   Industry officials blame the 1995 deregulation of the state's
workers' compensation market for this year's hike, in a round-about
way. When state lawmakers deregulated the industry, insurance
providers engaged in price slashing in an attempt to gain market
share.
</P>
<P>
   ``The result has been that prices have remained very flat,
increasing only by a certain percentage each year,'' Hanson said.
``But this is while the cost of the workers' compensation system
has skyrocketed.''
</P>
<P>
   The Workers' Compensation Insurance Rating Bureau said carriers
have been paying out $1.41 in workers' compensation claims to
policy holders for every dollar they charge.
</P>
<P>
   The rate increase applies to new and renewal policies that take
effect on or after Jan. 1. Some insurance brokers said they have
already seen their clients' premiums double overnight.
</P>
<P>
   ``Prices are going up dramatically, and we're trying to lower
commissions to ease the pain of our customers,'' said Fritz Mutter,
president of Golden Pacific Insurance Services Inc. in Pasadena, an
insurance brokerage firm.
</P>
<P>
   Kathy Fairbanks, vice president with the California Chamber of
Commerce in Sacramento, said she wasn't surprised by the increases.
</P>
<P>
   ``Something has to be done to the system,'' Fairbanks said.
``It's out of whack.''
</P>
<P>
   Troy Hanson, a legal analyst for Chicago-based CCH Inc., a
business and financial services firm that covers the workers'
compensation industry, called the 18 percent increase ``an enormous
jump.''
</P>
<P>
   Insurance companies had until Dec. 31 to file their rate
increases for 2000 with the state Insurance Commissioner's Office,
a normal step taken each year.
</P>
<P>
   Three of the state's top workers' compensation insurance firms
-- Superior National in Calabasas, Fremont Compensation in Glendale
and State Compensation Insurance Fund in San Francisco -- have
raised rates across the board, according to insurance experts.
</P>
<P>
   ``Since open-rating in 1995, we've seen really artificially low
premiums over those years, so employers have been really getting an
outstanding deal,'' Taylor said. ``This is really just a market
move that is inevitable.''
</P>
<P>
   Ron Christensen, a spokesman for State Compensation Insurance
Fund, said regional offices statewide have been inundated this week
with calls from businesses asking for new rate quotes.
</P>
<P>
   ``It looks like January is going to be a very good month for
us,'' he said. ``Industry-wide, in order to get market share,
insurers in many cases were selling their insurance under what it
cost to pay out for claims.''
</P>
<P>
   Superior National issued a report Dec. 20 to its insurance
agents in an effort to explain to its policyholders why premiums
would begin rising on Jan. 1.
</P>
<P>
   The report blamed open-rating, in which employers received a
substantial decrease in the overall price of workers' compensation
premiums. But at the same time, the underlying costs of the
insurance product to carriers have increased ``at an alarming
rate.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Now it's `pay the piper' time,'' said one insurance industry
official, who asked that his name not be used.
</P>
<P>
   X X X
</P>
