<HEADER>
A0169 &Cx1f; ttx-z
r s BC-FBN-GEORGE-TEX     01-08 1129
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FBN-GEORGE-TEX </SLUG>
 
Vikings quarterback Jeff George appears poised to shed his
``loser'' label. 
(For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By RICHIE WHITT 
c.2000 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   EDEN PRAIRIE, Minn. _ Beware NFL: Jeff is no longer a Boy
George.
</P>
<P>
   Matured, if not totally humbled, by a tumultuous 10-year career,
Minnesota Vikings quarterback Jeff George is poised to grow out of
the ``loser'' label earned with wild incompletions, sideline spats
and postgame pouts during failed stints with the Indianapolis
Colts, Atlanta Falcons and Oakland Raiders.
</P>
<P>
   Fittingly in this weirdest of all NFL seasons, George actually
led a team to the playoffs.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't look back, because what's in the past is in the
past,'' said George, who will lead the Vikings against the Cowboys
in tomorrow's NFC wild-card playoff game at 11:30 a.m. at the
Metrodome. ``There are things I'm not proud of, but we all make
mistakes. I'm basically the same person, but now I'm on a winning
team. The main thing is I've got a great chance with a great team
to erase a bad rap, a bad reputation. If I can play like I'm
capable and we can win some games, people will look at me
differently.''
</P>
<P>
   Like the spoiled brat who reneged on a oral promise to attend
Miami, transferred from Purdue to Illinois, whined with the Colts
and yelled at coach June Jones on the sideline with the Falcons,
George is still smirky, cocky, and overwhelmingly talented. He
credits his overhaul not to a personality face lift, but to a
significant upgrade in targets _ Randy Moss and Cris Carter.
</P>
<P>
   In catching George's bullets,] Moss and Carter have also caught
George's reputation from behind.
</P>
<P>
   ``In all honesty? What you see right now is the same that I've
been for 10 years,'' said George, who began the season as a backup
to Randall Cunningham but now has the Vikings streaking into the
playoffs having won eight of 10. ``It just so happens that during
the course of the game, when you're winning, if you have a shouting
match on the sidelines it's not magnified. When you're losing, it
was. So I'm just as vocal on the sidelines as I've been in the
past; it's just that I've been in some bad situations.''
</P>
<P>
   After the Raiders failed to offer George a contract last spring,
his career hit the two-minute warning. He was a 33-year-old with a
37-74 record as a starter and the tag of being more negative than
George Costanza.
</P>
<P>
   When he signed with Vikings in April, it was only a minimum
$400,000 insurance policy after Minnesota traded backup Brad
Johnson to the Washington Redskins. On the eve of their first
playoff game since last year's heartbreaking loss in the NFC
Championship Game, George is now Minneapolis' most unlikely hero
since Gov. Jesse Ventura.
</P>
<P>
   ``What he's done is remarkable,'' Vikings coach Dennis Green
said. ``We went to him almost out of desperation, and he's been
sensational.''
</P>
<P>
   Green paced into the locker room, his 2-3 Vikings trailing the
Detroit Lions 19-0 at halftime Oct. 17 at the Silverdome. His move
to bench Cunningham and insert George didn't save a game, but it
certainly rescued a season.
</P>
<P>
   In half of precision passing and impassioned play, the supposed
pariah George rallied the Vikings to a 23-22 lead, only to watch
the Lions mount a last-minute drive for the game-winning field
goal. Despite the loss, it was that second half that ignited a
five-game winning streak and re-established the Vikings as one of
the most dangerous teams in the NFL.
</P>
<P>
   ``Seeing how things have turned out, it's hard to argue with the
decision, isn't it?'' said Cunningham, who led the Vikings to a
15-1 regular-season record and within one field goal of the Super
Bowl last season. ``This year has been Jeff's time to shine.''
</P>
<P>
   George's reincarnation changed the course of the season, the way
the Vikings practice, the way receivers run routes and the way
opposing defenses prepare game plans. Under George, the receivers
had to become much more alert. Cunningham has a longer windup,
meaning receivers had plenty of warning a pass was coming. He was
also more likely to lock in on a receiver.
</P>
<P>
   George's release is one of the quickest in football, and he
makes his reads _ looking from one receiver to another _ with
similar speed.
</P>
<P>
   ``Jeff likes to run a lot of slant patterns,'' Carter said.
``And he's going to get the ball to you quicker on those slant
patterns. Your adjustment there is it might come to you out of the
break, or he might hold it until you run through the zone a little
bit.''
</P>
<P>
   One reason Cunningham struggled was defenses had committed to
taking away Moss on deep patterns. Of Cunningham's 124 completions
this season, 77 (62 percent) went to wide receivers. Of George's
177 completions this season, 140 (79 percent) have gone to wide
receivers _ the strength of the team.
</P>
<P>
   The bottom line? The Vikings finished No. 3 in yards gained,
only one spot behind last year's record-setting offense. During the
final 10 games, with George at quarterback, the Vikings averaged 28
points per game.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm not going to sit here and take all the credit,'' said
George, who threw 23 touchdowns, only 12 interceptions and will
likely command $6 million as a free agent in the off-season. ``This
was a fantastic offense last year when I was in Oakland. I've just
gotten the ball to the right people and let them make plays. They
make a quarterback's job easy.''
</P>
<P>
   Though leery of George's unique physical skills, the Cowboys
aren't yet convinced of his mental maturation. Sure he can throw
25-yard slant patterns without having his feet set, but how will he
hold up in a playoff game under heavy pressure?
</P>
<P>
   In both of his losses as a starter (at Tampa Bay and Kansas
City), George had turnovers returned for touchdowns.
</P>
<P>
   ``When you put pressure on him he's been known to crumple in the
pocket,'' said Cowboys defensive end Ebenezer Ekuban. ``I think he
can be rattled a little bit.''
</P>
<P>
   George, who threw three second-half touchdowns in Minnesota's
10-point victory over Dallas in November, scoffs at the mounting
pressure. He has been the No. 1 overall pick in the NFL, the
run-and-shoot quarterback who threw for 4,100 yards, and he has
been the scapegoat.
</P>
<P>
   What he has never been, however, is champion.
</P>
<P>
   ``Everyone wants to win,'' he said. ``That's the ultimate goal.
But I'm not out to prove anyone wrong. I know where I want to go,
and I know where this team wants to go. And that's to win the big
one. To come from where I was, and me not knowing my situation ...
yes, it's exciting. But there's nothing to prove. It's not me.
We're 8-2 as a team. Not one guy can do it. I'm just around a great
group of guys, a great supporting cast and just trying to win like
the other guys.''
</P>
<P>
   By George, he's finally got it. nn
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
