<HEADLINE>
CORNERBACK STARTER OPPOSITE SANDERS STILL UNDECIDED
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By CLARENCE E. HILL JR. 
c.2000 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   IRVING, Texas _ After their final day of practice before
tomorrow's NFC wild-card game against the Minnesota Vikings, the
Cowboys still don't know who will line up at cornerback opposite
Deion Sanders.
</P>
<P>
   Veterans Kevin Mathis (sprained knee) and Kevin Smith (strained
hamstring), who were hobbled the last month of the season by
injuries, practiced yesterday for the third consecutive day.
</P>
<P>
   Cowboys coach Chan Gailey, who is not as enthusiastic about
Smith's progress as he is Mathis', said it will likely come down to
a game-time decision.
</P>
<P>
   If he is ready, the eight-year veteran Smith will start. If not
Smith, then it could be Mathis or reserve Charlie Williams.
</P>
<P>
   ``Kevin \RSmith\S has improved, but he didn't take the jump we'd
have liked,'' Gailey said. ``Mathis looks to be a little closer.''
</P>
<P>
   Gailey was noncommittal on a starter largely because of the
uncertainty surrounding the game readiness of both players.
</P>
<P>
   Gailey understands that some times it takes injured players a
few plays to get back in a groove. Any hesitancy could be crippling
against the Vikings and their arsenal of big-play receivers.
COWBOYS CONFIDENT
</P>
<P>
   Few people outside their circle of friends are giving the
Cowboys much chance in tomorrow's game, but they are not without
confidence.
</P>
<P>
   Chan Gailey said his team has practiced with a lot of energy and
focus this week.
</P>
<P>
   ``The guys believe, and they feel good about themselves,''
Gailey said.
</P>
<P>
   Cowboys quarterback Troy Aikman said: ``We're not taking a
psychology course this week to tell ourselves that `we can do it.'
We know we can do it. We've just got to go out and play.''
</P>
<P>
   Safety George Teague agreed, saying, ``If at some point we
actually play our best game and put it all together, there's not
anybody we can't beat and no reason we can't make it all the way to
the Super Bowl.'' TUCKER WONDERING
</P>
<P>
   Attention, Vikings coach Denny Green: Cowboys receiver Jason
Tucker wants to know what you think of him.
</P>
<P>
   The New York Giants didn't think much of him, even after his
128-yard breakout game against the New Orleans Saints, and he
burned the Giants for a 90-yard touchdown reception. Will the
Giants show him more defensive attention or will they dare him to
beat them?
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't know what they are going to do,'' Tucker said. ``I'm
sure they'll pay more attention to Raghib Ismail. I'm going to
continue to try to make plays to help us win. Nobody expected
anything from me a few weeks ago; I hope they still don't.''
BRIEFLY
</P>
<P>
   The Cowboys are 2-0 in playoff games at Minnesota, winning there
in 1971 and 1975.
</P>
<P>
   The Cowboys have made more playoff appearances (26), played in
more playoff games (52) and have more playoff wins (32) than any
team in the postseason. Of course, the Cowboys are 0-2 in the
playoffs since defeating the Vikings in a 1996 NFC wild-card game.
Running back Emmitt Smith is the NFL's all-time playoff leader in
rushing touchdowns with 18. He needs 70 yards rushing to pass
Franco Harris for the top spot in that category. nn
</P>
</TEXT>
