<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BKC-SMU-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SMU QUIETLY SNEAKING UP ON COLLEGE BASKETBALL'S ELITE
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By JOHNNY PAUL 
c.2000 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
DALLAS _ SMU's Mike Dement views his men's basketball program as
``a work in progress.'' 
<TEXT>
<P>
   A 12-2 record, though, arouses curiosity and provokes a question
not heard recently around University Park: &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Could these Mustangs, off the third-best start in school
history, be the real deal? &QL;
</P>
<P>
   ``We'll have to wait and see,'' said Jeryl Sasser, SMU's
normally brash and flamboyant guard. ``I'm wondering if we are. I
feel in my heart that we are, and I see us everyday in practice.'' &QL;
</P>
<P>
   The evidence supports Sasser's conviction, and if so, SMU, which
begins conference play today at home against Rice, could be on
track for its first NCAA Tournament appearance since the 1992-93
Mustangs captured the Southwest Conference title. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   The Mustangs have road victories at Southwest Missouri State,
Houston and Tennessee-Chattanooga and home victories against
Richmond, New Mexico State and Lamar. SMU's only losses are by
three at 7-5 Missouri and by five at 10-2 Tulane. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Based on non-conference play, SMU might be the WAC's most
formidable challenger to 22nd-ranked Tulsa, which opened conference
play with a 94-73 victory at TCU on Thursday night.
</P>
<P>
   As well as the Mustangs have played, Dement, in his fifth
season, said they are a long way from being where they want to be,
advancing from a mid-level status to an annual NCAA Tournament
qualifier.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think that's the hardest jump,'' Dement said. ``It's like a
ceiling. There are a lot of us trying to get through it, and it's
difficult. I don't know if we have everything in place yet to do
that. It's kind of a work in progress right now.''
</P>
<P>
   Dement fielded the 12th-youngest team in Division I a year ago
with nine players either freshmen or sophomores. Those Mustangs
limped from the gate and lost seven of their first 10 games. A
late-season rush _ seven victories in their final 10 games _ served
as a sign of better times ahead.
</P>
<P>
   The Mustangs reached the WAC Tournament semifinals before being
eliminated by New Mexico in a one-point loss. The early-season skid
likely cost SMU a berth in the National Invitation Tournament.
</P>
<P>
   ``We sat in that locker room and talked amongst ourselves, and
we said that we had to start this season where we left off last
season,'' point guard Stephen Woods said. ``We were committed to
that.''
</P>
<P>
   Sasser, Woods and forward Willie Davis, whom Dement said ``has
played the best basketball,'' provide the Mustangs a potent 1-2-3
punch. Sasser, the WAC's Mountain Division Player of the Year as a
sophomore, leads the Mustangs in scoring (17.7) and assists (4.6)
and ranks second to Davis in rebounding (9.2).
</P>
<P>
   Woods, a senior, averages 14.5 points and 3.3 assists per game,
and Davis provides the Mustangs an inside threat, contributing 17.3
points and 9.5 rebounds per game. That trifecta makes the Mustangs
difficult to break.
</P>
<P>
   ``They can't stop all three of us at the same time,'' Davis
said. ``Somebody's going to score.''
</P>
<P>
   Dement acknowledges as much, but the Mustangs need a little more
to crack that next echelon.
</P>
<P>
   ``Those three guys are going to be tough to handle for
anybody,'' Dement said. ``They're going to draw a lot of attention,
which means that fourth and fifth \Rscoring options\S become the
key.''
</P>
<P>
   That's where guards Damon Hancock and Quinton Ross, fourth and
fifth on the team in minutes played, enter the equation, but the
lack of another presence inside could be SMU's Achilles' heel
unless either Jon Forinash, DeWayne Floyd, Mike Niemi or a
combination of the three provide the Mustangs rebounds, defense and
a few baskets along the way.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're going to need that big man,'' Dement said. ``We need
somebody to emerge.''
</P>
<P>
   That could be all that separates the Mustangs from a date with
March Madness.
</P>
<P>
   ``We've got to go to the NCAA Tournament,'' Sasser said.
``That's the foremost thing on everybody's mind.'' nn
</P>
</TEXT>
