<HEADLINE>
NELSON IS SUSPENDED ONE GAME
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By DWAIN PRICE AND JOHNNY PAUL 
c.2000 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   DALLAS _ For the first time in his 148-game coaching tenure with
the Mavericks, Don Nelson has been suspended.
</P>
<P>
   Nelson was suspended yesterday for one game and fined $10,000
for his confrontation with Karl Malone of the Utah Jazz and for
bumping referee Scott Wall in the Mavericks' 105-92 loss Thursday
night.
</P>
<P>
   Malone was fined $10,000 for throwing an elbow at center Shawn
Bradley, and for engaging in the confrontation with Nelson.
</P>
<P>
   Assistant coach Donnie Nelson will coach tonight's home game
against the Atlanta Hawks.
</P>
<P>
   Thursday marked only the second time Nelson had been ejected
from a regular-season game since he started coaching the Mavericks
on Dec. 4, 1997. His other ejection was also at Reunion Arena
against Utah, on March 27, 1998.
</P>
<P>
   Nelson, saying he will not be ``intimidated by Karl Malone or
anybody else,'' defended his role in the fracas yesterday.
</P>
<P>
   ``I didn't do it for any reason other than to protect my team,''
Nelson said. ``I thought there were a couple of dirty plays, and I
thought he tried to hurt my players. So, I went to their defense.
I'll do it every time. I'm not intimidated by Karl Malone or
anybody else. That's just the way I am.''
</P>
<P>
   Nelson went onto the court after being ejected by Wall with 6:04
remaining in the third quarter. Nelson objected after Bradley was
whistled for a foul against Malone, whose knee struck Bradley's
midsection as Bradley tried to draw a charge. Bradley was on the
floor for several minutes before he was helped to the locker room.
</P>
<P>
   Nelson continued to argue the call after Bradley left the court,
and Wall ejected Nelson. The Mavericks' coach then confronted
Malone, bumping Malone before the two were separated. Nelson was
escorted out of the arena. Malone was also called for a technical
foul.
</P>
<P>
   ``I was taught when I was little to respect my elders, but
you're totally out of line when you get in a player's face,''
Malone said. ``He crossed the line, and I have no respect for
that.''
</P>
<P>
   Nelson declined to label Malone ``a dirty player.''
</P>
<P>
   ``I wouldn't go as far as to say that,'' Nelson said, ``but
definitely he has a history.''
</P>
<P>
   Bradley suffered an abdominal contusion from the collision and
left the game before returning. The on-court argument between
Nelson and Malone escalated to the point that the Mavericks' coach
bumped the player before being restrained.
</P>
<P>
   The game was tied at 54 before Nelson's first technical, and
Utah outscored the Mavericks 51-38 during the final 18 minutes for
a 105-92 victory.
</P>
<P>
   ``They kept their composure and got the ball to the right
players,'' said Michael Finley, who scored 30 points for the
Mavericks, who have lost nine of their past 10 games.
</P>
<P>
   Finley played in his 329th consecutive game, third-longest
active streak in the league. nn
</P>
</TEXT>
