A0173 &Cx1f; ttx-z
r s BC-FBN-REEVES-COLUMN-TEX     01-08 0801
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FBN-REEVES-COLUMN-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
A GIVEN SUNDAY MIGHT BE ALL COWBOYS NEED
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By JIM REEVES 
c.2000 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   There is more than a touch of irony that in the same week that
Oliver Stone's testament to NFL excess, ``On Any Given Sunday'',
was in theaters across the country, Cowboys' fans were yawning at
the prospect of their team venturing to Minnesota for a wild-card
playoff game.
</P>
<P>
   Why bother? That was the talk-show message delivered by
know-it-all hosts and callers alike. This clearly is a team not
going anywhere, they all said. End the suffering, take a better
draft position and start planning for next year.
</P>
<P>
   Are we spoiled, or what?
</P>
<P>
   Super Bowl or nothing for our gang. No crackers and cheese for
these minions. Only caviar _ Beluga's best, please _ will do. And
forget the root beer. Dom Perignon, nicely chilled, or we'll take
our business elsewhere.
</P>
<P>
   Give me a break.
</P>
<P>
   Tomorrow's game at the Metrodome is all about what the Pete
Rozelles and Tex Schramms and George Halases always tried to tell
us was at the heart and soul of the NFL game.
</P>
<P>
   It's about heart and grit and determination. It's about dreams
and want-to and a chance, just a chance. How many times have we
begged for a team we loved to have just a chance?
</P>
<P>
   One more chance.
</P>
<P>
   Oh, sure, we think we know this Cowboys' team all too well. It
has no chance, the cynics will be quick to assure you, and maybe
they're right. Maybe this team has no heart and no soul. Certainly
it has played like it plenty of times.
</P>
<P>
   But the Cowboys are in the playoffs because they earned it, even
at 8-8. That's a record we normally throw back around here, but
this isn't your normal NFL any more, and maybe it's time we got
used to it. Maybe it's time we began to understand that this isn't
the early '90s any more and that the rules have changed.
</P>
<P>
   Jimmy Johnson has been gone for six long years now, and maybe he
understood better than any of us how things would be in the new
NFL. More irony: Johnson's Miami Dolphins back-doored their way
into the playoffs, too, at 9-7.
</P>
<P>
   The easy thing is to tell ourselves that the Cowboys can't win
tomorrow against the offensively talented Vikings. They blew a
17-point lead there earlier in the season, and maybe we're kidding
ourselves when we keep saying that things would have been different
if Emmitt Smith hadn't been sidelined after the first half with a
broken hand following an impressive 140-yard performance.
</P>
<P>
   Better to think the worst and not be disappointed. I suppose
that's the theory. At least if the Cowboys go on and lose, the talk
show know-it-alls can tell us, `See, I told you they had no chance,
the bums.'
</P>
<P>
   But what a miserable way to live life, never believing in
anything, being afraid to hope or dream.
</P>
<P>
   Think of what a great story it'll make if the Cowboys not only
win tomorrow, but begin to play as we thought they could this
season. What if Troy Aikman catches fire? Or Jason Tucker continues
to look more and more like Patrick Jeffers? Or Emmitt Smith becomes
Walter Payton incarnate one more time? Or two? Or three?
</P>
<P>
   What if? Isn't that what the NFL had in mind when it coined the
phrase ``On any given Sunday?''
</P>
<P>
   OK, so no 8-8 team has ever won an NFL playoff game. Does that
make it impossible? Hardly.
</P>
<P>
   So here's my advice for you this weekend. Go ahead, dream a
little. Forget the naysayers. They'll always be there. Allow
yourself to hope.
</P>
<P>
   If there's no room for hope this season, of all seasons, then
there will never be. Never has the NFC championship race seemed so
wide open. Yes, the Rams have had a glorious season _ a dream
season, if you will _ but they're still the Rams, after all. Who
knows how they'll react under playoff pressure?
</P>
<P>
   Anybody else out there scare you? The 49ers are but a memory.
The Pack isn't back. There are no Monsters of the Midway lurking
around the corner.
</P>
<P>
   Instead, the way to the Super Bowl is littered with not-so-scary
characters like the Rams, the Bucs and the Redskins, already twice
beaten by the Cowboys. Tomorrow's game, in fact, could be as tough
as any the Cowboys play if they should continue their postseason
journey. At least as tough as anything this side of Atlanta.
</P>
<P>
   The Cowboys have been an enigmatic team, unable to win on the
road since the season opener in Washington, unable to beat anyone
outside of their own division on the road since 1997, unable to
sustain anything beyond a one-game winning streak since starting
the year 3-0.
</P>
<P>
   Yet, 15 of their players own Super Bowl rings. They know what it
takes. They have made this trip before.
</P>
<P>
   Maybe all the Cowboys need is that one given Sunday, when it all
comes together. Or maybe even three.
</P>
<P>
   Just think what a movie that journey would make.
nn
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-01-08-00 0126EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
