<HEADLINE>
GAHAN HAPPY SHE JOINED IOWA STATE ON THE FAMILY PLAN
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By MAC ENGEL 
c.2000 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Tracy Gahan insists that playing at Iowa State wasn't a plan
concocted by her parents or her brother. It just happened.
</P>
<P>
   Her mother, Terry, and her father, John, both graduated from
Iowa State. And her older brother, Jeff, is an All-American swimmer
there.
</P>
<P>
   ``Iowa State didn't start recruiting me until the end of my
junior year,'' said the former McKinney High School star, who
averages 5.6 points and 4.1 rebounds as a sophomore for the
10th-ranked Cyclones. ``Me coming here had nothing to do with my
parents or brother. They were happy that I came here, but they
would've supported me wherever I went. I just loved the coaches
here, and I liked it.''
</P>
<P>
   Her parents were pleased that their daughter selected their alma
mater over TCU and Oklahoma, but Gahan is even more pleased,
considering ISU is 10-2 and the favorite to win the Big 12 title.
It's a luxury that her brother is there and that when their parents
come up, it's their trip down memory lane.
</P>
<P>
   ``That's all my mom does when she comes up. She likes to tell me
what she did when she was here,'' said Gahan, who was the Texas
Class 4A player of the year in her senior year. ``My brother and I
weren't close at all in high school. It was never like I wanted to
follow him to college. We're pretty close now.''
</P>
<P>
   For Gahan, Ames was an easy choice. Iowa State has made three
consecutive NCAA appearances and reached the Elite Eight last
season. The only thing she finds tough is dispelling misconceptions
high school friends have about the Iowa's vast farmland.
</P>
<P>
   ``Yeah, there is more to do around Dallas, but Ames is a great
town,'' she said. ``Everyone thinks it's all cornfields, but there
is stuff to do here.''
FAST BREAKS WHO'S BETTER? Today's game between No. 1 UConn and No.
2 Tennessee (3 p.m., KTVT/Ch. 11) features the two best teams of
the '90s. Save for the Lady Vols' slip in the first game of the
season, a 69-64 defeat against Louisiana Tech, both teams have been
dominant this season.
</P>
<P>
   Through 11 games, No. 1 Connecticut is undefeated and winning by
an average of 38.7 points.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think Geno \RAuriemma\S has had some great teams, but this
may be his best ever,'' Tennessee coach Pat Summitt said. ``It is
difficult to see what you are looking for when most of the games
are blowouts.''
</P>
<P>
   Before you give UConn the national title, however, remember what
happened to the Huskies last season. At the same point last season,
Connecticut was undefeated and winning by an average of 28.2 points
and didn't lose until game No. 14.
</P>
<P>
   But, UConn didn't make the Final Four, losing to Iowa State in a
regional final. A MEANINGFUL HOOP Kimberly James, a sophomore
forward at Bethune-Cookman, scored the first points of the 2000s in
college basketball when she hit a layup at the 19:02 mark of the
Wildcats' 61-59 victory against Jan. 1.
</P>
<P>
   Talk about making your basket counts. It was James' only two
points of the game. GOT A SPARE $600,000 Empty your pockets; the
Philadelphia coordinating committee for the Women's Final Four
needs an additional $600,000 for promotions planned around the
event played March 31-April 2. Philadelphia Women's Basketball 2000
has already raised $1.4 million to pay for pep rallies, uniforms
for volunteers, parties and other details.
</P>
<P>
   The City of Not-So Brotherly Love shouldn't feel too bad. At the
same time last year San Jose, Calif., which hosted the 1999 Final
Four, was $300,000 short of its $1.6 million target and it achieved
its goal in time. A FAMILIAR SIGHT Texas A&AMP;M junior transfer
Jaynetta Saunders has been named the Big 12 Conference rookie of
the week in three of the five times the award has been given. She
leads A&AMP;M with 20 blocks and 16.6 points per game and is the
league's top shooter, hitting 63.5 percent.
</P>
<P>
   The only other Big 12 players to be rookie of the week three
times or more are Jennifer Crow of Oklahoma State, three times in
1996-97; Julie Helm of Missouri, three times in 1996-97; Megan
Taylor of Iowa State, five times in 1997-98; and LaNeishea Caufield
of Oklahoma, four times in 1998-99. nn
</P>
</TEXT>
