<HEADLINE>
MAVERICKS ROOKIE BEGINS CLASSWORK
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By DWAIN PRICE 
c.2000 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   DALLAS _ Leon Smith left a Dallas psychiatric clinic and flew to
Houston yesterday while the Mavericks continued discussing the
rookie forward's future with the team.
</P>
<P>
   Mavericks president and chief executive officer Terdema Ussery
declined to say whether the Mavericks will make Smith a free agent
by terminating his three-year, $1.5 million contract. Billy Hunter,
executive director of the National Basketball Players Association,
wants Smith released from his contract so he can get a shot with
another NBA team.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm talking to Hunter about a lot of things,'' Ussery said.
``We've talked about everything from A to Z, but we're not going to
know for sure what's going to happen until we get everything
done.''
</P>
<P>
   Purvis Short, director of player programs for the players union,
said Smith will be taking college courses in Houston that are
available to every NBA player. They include a financial education
program, player assistance program, career education program and a
basic health-education program.
</P>
<P>
   Short also said Smith's routine will not include workouts with
future Hall-of-Fame center Moses Malone.
</P>
<P>
   ``We do have some people who are going to be training with Leon,
but Moses is not one of them,'' Short said. ``We have not even
talked to Moses about anything like that.''
</P>
<P>
   Smith will live in an apartment with a roommate provided by the
NBPA. He also will continue his psychiatric treatments and
counseling sessions in Houston.
nn
</P>
</TEXT>
