<HEADLINE>
MARKING FIVE-YEAR ANNIVERSARY, HOUSE REPUBLICANS REGROUP
</HEADLINE>
   (Eds: Southern Exposure is the weekly political notebook from the
Washington Bureau of the New York Times Regional Newspapers) (rk) 
 By CARL HULSE AND SEAN LOUGHLIN   
 New York Times Regional Newspaper Group   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ Five years after Republicans took control of the
House with a rallying cry emphasizing family values, GOP lawmakers
are looking for something else to talk about in time for the 2000
elections.
</P>
<P>
   Their focus on virtue took a big hit during President Clinton's
impeachment saga when several Republican leaders were forced to
address their own personal infidelities.
</P>
<P>
   So, Republicans are doing all they can to distance themselves
from former House Speaker Newt Gingrich, their onetime hero and
leader whose righteous calls for a new morality in America stirred
conservatives but later rang hollow amid revelations of his own
long-running extramarital affair.
</P>
<P>
   Recently divorced, Gingrich wasn't even invited to the GOP
anniversary celebration on Capitol Hill, even though he is widely
viewed as the architect of the successful 1994 Republican
revolution.
</P>
<P>
   ``The fact that Newt had a reversal of fortune doesn't in any
way distract from the accomplishments of the Republican Congress,''
said Rep. Spencer Bachus R-Ala., who cited welfare reform as one
example. ``I think we've been splendidly successfully.''
</P>
<P>
   These days, Capitol Hill Republicans prefer to talk about money,
not morality. They cite their record on balancing the budget and
promise tax cuts.
</P>
<P>
   ``We've gone from running in the red to running in the black,''
Bachus said.
</P>
<P>
   While many economists point to the 1993 balanced budget deal _
crafted by Clinton and congressional leaders _ as a key turning
point in the nation's fiscal health, Republicans say they deserve
the credit.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think we've done a far better job of managing the taxpayers'
money,'' said Rep. Howard Coble, R-N.C.
</P>
<P>
   ANCHORS AWAY
</P>
<P>
   Sen. Richard Shelby, R-Ala., recently made the pages of The
Washington Post's Sunday magazine, but he probably could have done
without the recognition.
</P>
<P>
   Under the headline ``Filipinos Float Shelby A Loaner,'' the
article detailed a congressional trip to the Philippines taken in
September by members of Senate Select Committee on Intelligence,
which Shelby heads.
</P>
<P>
   Shelby's desire to visit a strategic island in Manila Bay was
delayed by engine trouble on his boat. The solution? The Philippine
president authorized use of his yacht for the Shelby entourage.
</P>
<P>
   ``It turned out to be much more luxurious than they had asked
for,'' said Shelby spokeswoman Andrea Andrews, who described the
trip as productive, saying it allowed senators and staffers to
learn about U.S. intelligence needs in that region.
</P>
<P>
   LABOR PAINS
</P>
<P>
   Republicans are not about to let an apparent victory get in the
way of what may turn out to be a potent political issue.
</P>
<P>
   Hit by a barrage of GOP criticism for its statement that federal
health and safety regulations apply to at-home workers, the Labor
Department quickly retreated from that stand, promising to study
the issue instead.
</P>
<P>
   GOP lawmakers didn't relent in their criticism and promised to
hold their own hearings. ``The secretary has not ruled out
reissuing this advisory at a later date,'' noted Rep. Jim DeMint,
R-S.C.
</P>
<P>
   Rep. Cass Ballenger, the North Carolina Republican who chairs a
key House work force subcommittee, said the prospect of federal
regulations applied to home workers ``would result in many
employers rethinking flexible, family-friendly arrangements.''
</P>
<P>
   MONEY TALKS
</P>
<P>
   The two major political parties have their own wealthy patrons,
according to a new study that concludes politicians are sinking
deeper into the money chase.
</P>
<P>
   The Buying of the President 2000 by the Center for Public
Integrity found that both Democrats and Republicans have long lists
of corporate and special interests that regularly fill party
coffers with millions of dollars.
</P>
<P>
   Topping the list of soft-money contributors to the Republican
National Committee was tobacco giant Philip Morris Inc., which
donated $6.2 million between 1991 and 1999. Amway Corp. came in
second with $4.5 million, followed by the American Financial Group
with $3.5 million, Nabisco with $3.2 million and At&AMP;T Corp. with $3
million.
</P>
<P>
   During that same period, the Democratic National Committee
collected most of its donations from unions, notably the American
Federation of State, County and Municipal Employees with $3.7
million, followed by the Communication Workers of America with $3.6
million. The Seagram Co. donated $2.7 million, the National
Education Association gave $2.6 million, and the American
Federation of Teachers coughed up $2 million.
</P>
<P>
   ``Politicians have become so deeply enmeshed in the money chase
and personally tied to powerful economic interest that they have
lost the esteem and trust of the American people,'' said Charles
Lewis, director of the group.
</P>
<P>
   (Carl Hulse and Sean Loughlin are in the Washington Bureau of
the New York Times Regional Newspapers.)
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
