<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-01-08 02:19 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A0203 &Cx1f; ttc-z
r s BC-BKN-LAKERS-HORNETS-LA     01-08 0763
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BKN-LAKERS-HORNETS-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
LAKERS HOLD OFF HORNETS
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By HOWARD BECK  
 c.2000 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOS ANGELES _ Eddie Jones could only play spectator. Glen Rice's
play, first a spectacle, became spectacular.
</P>
<P>
   And when the principals in the The Trade finally shared the
floor Friday night, Rice did his best to justify the March 1999
deal that made him a Laker, and made L.A. fan favorite Jones a
Charlotte Hornet.
</P>
<P>
   Rice scored 10 of his 17 points in the fourth, including a
momentum-turning 3-pointer in the final three minutes, as the Los
Angeles Lakers narrowly escaped with an 87-83 victory over the
Hornets at Staples Center.
</P>
<P>
   Rice started slowly and was 1 for 6 entering the final quarter.
Then he was suddenly everywhere. He grabbed six rebounds in the
fourth quarter and hit the biggest shot of the night.
</P>
<P>
   His 3-pointer capped a 20-5 Lakers run that brought them back
from a 13-point deficit and gave them, incredibly, their first lead
of the night,80-78
</P>
<P>
   The Hornets sans the injured Jones with ex-Laker Elden Campbell
on the bench after fouling out fell behind by six but were within
two, 85-83, with 13.4 seconds left. Bobby Phills had the chance to
hit the potential game-winner, but with 3.5 seconds left, he
stepped out of bounds in the left corner while attempting a
3-pointer.
</P>
<P>
   Rice, the onetime Hornet, then nailed two game-clinching free
throws with 3 seconds remaining, and the Lakers extended their
winning streak to13. The Hornets lost their fourth in a row and are
2-6 since Jones injured his left elbow in late December.
</P>
<P>
   The Lakers never needed Rice's scoring more than they did
against his old team. Shaquille O'Neal struggled to navigate the
Hornets' sea of big bodies, including Campbell, and finished with a
below-average 23 points. Kobe Bryant, Jones' close friend, seemed
out of sorts and missed 14 of19 shots to finish with 13 points and
10 rebounds.
</P>
<P>
   With Jones in the house, and Campbell in the lineup, Bryant
conceded there was a special element to the game.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's just motivation as far as being competitive because you
played together and you don't want him beating you,'' he said.
``I'm sure he doesn't want us beating him, just for bragging
rights.''
</P>
<P>
   On a more-significant level, the game pitted the Lakers, one of
the top teams in the West, against the Hornets, who until recently
had the best record in the East. Until Jones went down with an
injury.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is a team to be reckoned with in the Eastern
Conference,'' Bryant said. ``They've been struggling as of late of
course, that's due to a couple injuries they have, but they're
definitely a team to be reckoned with.''
</P>
<P>
   The bad omens came early for the Lakers. Jones got the most
applause despite not playing (and appearing as a member of the
opposing team), Rice was misfiring from the outset, O'Neal's
3-footers were 3 inches short.
</P>
<P>
   And then there was this: The Lakers never got a lead in the
first halfand trailed 47-44 at halftime. That had only happened
twice before this season, and both games ended in Lakers losses, to
Houston and Toronto./ep In the first upset of the evening, O'Neal,
Rice and Bryant all were held to single-digit scoring in the first
half. The trio combined to make 5 of 22 shots, with Bryant going 2
for 12.
</P>
<P>
   A resurgent Derek Fisher scored nine points for the only Lakers
highlight of the half.
</P>
<P>
   Fans wasted no time welcoming Jones back to L.A.. His first
ovation came before pregame intros, before the National Anthem,
before Denzel Washington had even taken his courtside seat.
</P>
<P>
   Jones strolled out of the tunnel with his teammates, his face
beamed live on the jumbo video screen, and received a heartfelt
welcome.
</P>
<P>
   But it wasn't the return Jones had in mind.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm not playing, so I'm not back,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Despite the expectations of suspicious Lakers staffers, Jones is
still several days away from playing and had no chance of suiting
up Friday.
</P>
<P>
   ``I can't even straighten my arm out,'' he said. ``I don't want
to come back to the team just because we lost a few games. I'm not
100 percent. .. I don't want to fall again, land on my elbow again,
then I have to have surgery. That's one step I don't want to go.''
</P>
<P>
   Instead, Jones will look forward to March 10, when he returns to
Staples to play the Clippers, and to Feb. 16, when the Lakers head
to Charlotte though, he admitted, ``it won't be the same'' as
facing his old mates in L.A.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'll be ready in a month,'' he said. ``I'll be healed all
up.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-01-08-00 0219EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT20000108.0038 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-01-08 02:21 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A0204 &Cx1f; ttc-z
r s BC-BKW-USC-WASHINGTONSTA     01-08 0309
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BKW-USC-WASHINGTONSTATE-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
USC WOMEN SURVIVE AGAINST WASHINGTON ST.
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By SCOTT WOLF  
 c.2000 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOS ANGELES _ The USC women's basketball team barely survived
its 71-61 victory over Washington State on Friday night at the Lyon
Center, but the Trojans were more than happy to take it, since it
was the first good news they had all week.
</P>
<P>
   The program is still reeling from last week's death of
administrative assistant Barbara Williams from a brain aneurism,
and an emotional funeral service was held Thursday.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was a struggle. I think emotionally, we were just spent,''
USC coach Chris Gobrecht said. ``We did not have a good week of
practice for obvious reasons. It was a very, very emotional time.
We were pretty flat.''
</P>
<P>
   Fortunately for the Trojans (6-5, 1-0), senior guard Erica
Mashia had one of the best games of her career, tying a
school-record with six 3-pointers and finished with 20 points.
Mashia made six of nine 3-point shots.
</P>
<P>
   ``Thank God for Erica's shooting,'' Gobrecht said.
</P>
<P>
   USC also got an unexpected boost from walk-on freshman Erin
Young, who had a career-high nine points and three rebounds. Young
played 21 minutes, 14 more than her career-best. Forward Tiffany
Washington had 11 points and 11 rebounds.
</P>
<P>
   Washington State (3-8, 0-1) stayed close thanks to senior guard
Jennifer Kerns, who had 25 points. The Cougars also benefited from
USC's 24 turnovers.
</P>
<P>
   ``I though the biggest thing was we turned the ball over too
much,'' Gobrecht said. ``The turnovers were just really the biggest
indicator of us not being sharp.''
</P>
<P>
   USC also played shorthanded. Third-leading scorer Tiffany Elmore
missed the game with a sprained ankle and reserve point guard
Camille Norwood was suspended for disciplinary reasons.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-01-08-00 0221EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT20000108.0039 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-01-08 02:24 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A0205 &Cx1f; ttc-z
r s BC-BKN-CROUSE-COLUMN-LAD     01-08 0718
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BKN-CROUSE-COLUMN-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
DREAM TEAM VOTERS FELL ASLEEP FOR SURE
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By KAREN CROUSE  
 c.2000 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOS ANGELES _ We're sorry, but this year's Golden Globetrotters
are a joke. It's the worst snub we've seen since the Academy
overlooked Jim Carrey's performance in ``The Truman Show.''
</P>
<P>
   If the 11-member committee choosing the U.S. Olympic men's
basketball team had been entrusted with Golden Globe nominations,
it probably would have left Michael Clarke Duncan off the Best
Supporting Actor list for his performance in ``The Green Mile''
because it wasn't sufficiently impressed with his body of work.
</P>
<P>
   Pedro Martinez being left off some voters' MVP ballots this past
baseball season was borderline burlesque. USA basketball leaving
Kobe Bryant, Allen Iverson, Vince Carter and Jason Williams off the
12-man team that will represent the U.S. at the Summer Olympics in
Sydney is downright farcical.
</P>
<P>
   Chosen ones Ray Allen, Steve Smith and Allan Houston are solid
players, don't get us wrong. And they've been in the NBA longer
than cornrows and braids.
</P>
<P>
   Compared to Bryant, Carter and Williams, they're the old
guard(s). That clearly was no small consideration.
</P>
<P>
   When representing Old Glory, it's apparently of utmost
importance to have earned one's stripes.
</P>
<P>
   That maturity mattered more than mastery or marketing is
curious, given that the Summer Games are the Mount Olympus of
commercialism. Why, they make David Stern's NBA look almost, well,
quaint.
</P>
<P>
   Bryant said he wanted to be on the U.S. team that will compete
in Sydney, but he didn't go out of his way to campaign for it.
Silly him, he thought it would be enough to do his canvassing on
the court.
</P>
<P>
   ``Absolutely, I wanted to represent my country in the 2000
Olympics,'' Bryant said Friday before the Lakers' game against
Charlotte at the Staples Center. ``Ever since they made the
conversion from college players to pros (in 1992) I've really
wanted to play in the Olympics. I was hoping it would be in 2000,
but at the same time I'm going to have other chances.''
</P>
<P>
   His health willing, he'll be a lock in 2004. But if Bryant is
talented enough now, why hold him back? Olympic historian Bud
Greenspan's films are chock-full of U.S. athletes who unseated
their elders on their way to fame and glory.
</P>
<P>
   Gymnast Mary Lou Retton had a slimmer resume than teammate Kathy
Johnson in 1984 but took home more gold. A high school star
supplanted one of the sport's trail blazers in the pitching
rotation of the softball team that went on to win the gold medal in
1996.
</P>
<P>
   In the big picture, USA Basketball's insistence on recognizing
age over pure ability seems no less archaic than the amateur ideals
upon which the modern Olympic movement was founded.
</P>
<P>
   Dream Team?
</P>
<P>
   Dream On.
</P>
<P>
   This wasn't a team selection, these were political appointments.
</P>
<P>
   ``Kobe, Vince Carter, they're too young, both of them,'' Lakers
coach Phil Jackson said Friday. ``They've got to pay their dues.''
</P>
<P>
   Fine, Lakers center Shaquille O'Neal said dismissively, but
it'll cost them.
</P>
<P>
   Forget the fact that a few of the planet's premier players will
be missing from the world's stage. ``Those guys don't understand
marketing,'' said O'Neal, who turned down an Olympic invitation,
assuring Alonzo Mourning a berth to Sydney.
</P>
<P>
   ``How do you leave out Kobe, Iverson, Stephon Marbury?'' O'Neal
added, shaking his head. ``I don't know how you leave out my two
favorite players, Jason Williams and Vince Carter. Vince Carter on
the wing, that's excitement. That's money. And do you know how many
Jason Williams jerseys they would have sold?''
</P>
<P>
   If nothing else, USA Basketball should have waited to name its
team until, say, July or August, the same time the U.S. Olympic
swimming and track and field squads will be culled. Why, by then
Tim Hardaway could be fully recovered from his knee injury and Vin
Baker might have found the All-Star form he seems to have
misplaced.
</P>
<P>
   Hardaway and Baker are among the Sydney dozen, begging the
question, Have spies from the Croatian team infiltrated USA
Basketball or what?
</P>
<P>
   ``Who's on the committee?'' Bryant said. ``I don't even know.
I'd like to. Just out of curiosity.''
</P>
<P>
   He has every reason to wonder.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-01-08-00 0224EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
