A0210 &Cx1f; ttc-z
r a BC-GRIDLOCK-EMERGENCY-LA     01-08 0933
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-GRIDLOCK-EMERGENCY-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
QUICK FIX SOUGHT FOR 101-405 EXCHANGE
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By Steve Carney  
 c.2000 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOS ANGELES -- Declaring the 101-405 freeway interchange a
``gridlock emergency'' of earthquake proportions, California
Assemblyman Tom McClintock hs proposed legislation aimed at
speeding improvements to ease congestion.
</P>
<P>
   McClintock, R-Granada Hills, said fixing ground zero for
gridlock in Los Angeles' San Fernando Valley should be done as
quickly as the 66 days Caltrans needed after the Northridge
Earthquake to repair the 10 Freeway in Santa Monica.
</P>
<P>
   ``Gov. Wilson was able to invoke emergency powers to cut through
industrial-sized spools of red tape,'' he said at a news conference
held Friday beside the 405 Freeway.
</P>
<P>
   ``What's the difference between a highway made impassable by an
act of God and one made impassable by 25 years of neglect by man?''
said McClintock, vice chairman of the Assembly's Transportation
Committee.
</P>
<P>
   He said three decades of minimal freeway construction has led to
the traffic problem, and he wants to empower the governor to
expedite construction by declaring a ``gridlock emergency'' if a
certain stretch of freeway has reached 3,000 hours of delay per
day. That figure, calculated from traffic and congestion numbers,
is reached at several traffic bottlenecks throughout L.A.,
including the much-maligned intersection of the 101 and 405
freeways.
</P>
<P>
   A Los Angeles Daily News series in 1997 identified that
intersection as the nucleus of San Fernando Valley gridlock, and a
recent survey named it the seventh-most-congested junction in the
country. The worst was the intersection of the 405 and 10 freeways.
</P>
<P>
   Work to improve and expand the 101-405 interchange is set to
begin later this year, however, and the $7.9 million project will
be complete by 2002. It will add an auxiliary lane to the
northbound 405, and add a second connector lane from the north 405
to the eastbound 101 Freeway.
</P>
<P>
   McClintock said the State Highway Account is expected to have a
$2 billion surplus this year, earmarked for projects that Caltrans
doesn't have time to get to.
</P>
<P>
   ``Adding an additional lane to that freeway,'' he said,
gesturing to traffic passing on the 405, ``is no problem for a
contractor -- if the bureaucracy is swept away. It doesn't take
that long to build a freeway.''
</P>
<P>
   McClintock said time could be saved by running federal and state
environmental reviews concurrently, by contracting out engineering
work instead of requiring that it be done by Caltrans, and by
speeding up the bid process.
</P>
<P>
   Caltrans is remaining neutral on the issue, said agency
spokesman John Robin Witt. But he warned that any time saved by an
abbreviated process could be eaten up by court battles, from losing
bidders challenging an abridged selection process, concerned
residential neighbors or angry environmentalists opposing
accelerated reviews.
</P>
<P>
   After the Northridge Quake, Caltrans saved time by having
bidders submit plans along with their bids, eliminating a step. But
Witt said that also made the process more complex and pulled
Caltrans employees off other jobs.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't think that's something you want to do on an everyday
basis,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   And an environmental review, he said, is ``probably the single
most sensitive and time-consuming part of the project. Under the
best circumstances, that's going to take six months.'' But they can
last even longer if the area being built upon is discovered to have
historical significance and requires an archeological study, or
contains endangered species that have to be relocated, he said.
</P>
<P>
   McClintock said there should be no difference between the
Northridge situation, in which existing freeway bridges had to be
rebuilt, and new projects to add lanes to traffic-choked freeways.
</P>
<P>
   Gov. Gray Davis said the freeway problem is mainly a money
issue, according to deputy press secretary Hilary McLean. During
his State of the State address Wednesday, he said local
transportation agencies are sitting on $1.7 billion in unspent
federal funds.
</P>
<P>
   ``There are available transportation dollars. Let's get these
projects under way so we won't have these problems,'' McLean said.
</P>
<P>
   ``The governor agrees with the Republicans -- under the Wilson
administration, Caltrans needed a swift kick to get a move on,''
she said.
</P>
<P>
   The act that Wilson invoked, the state Emergency Services Act,
which gives the governor increased authority in times of crisis,
covers disasters of all kinds -- but not bad traffic, said Jaime
Arteaga, information officer with the governor's Office of
Emergency Services.
</P>
<P>
   ``What happened after Northridge, it was caused by the disaster.
It was imperative that the roads could be fixed so folks could get
back to work and what have you,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Last year Gov. Davis signed a bill sponsored by Assemblyman
Wally Knox, D-Los Angeles, which enabled Caltrans to fast-track
construction on certain projects, picked by the agency's director.
The bill, AB 405, was named for the 101-405 interchange, where Knox
has long championed improvement efforts.
</P>
<P>
   McClintock's proposal would let the governor decide which
freeways are in a state of gridlock emergency and in need of
immediate relief, and take the decision out of Caltrans' hands.
</P>
<P>
   ``Instead of building highways, (Caltrans has) become the single
biggest impediment to highway construction,'' he said. ``As a
practical matter it's a lot easier to do it this way than to change
the whole system.''
</P>
<P>
   X X X
</P>
</TEXT>
