<DOCNO> NYT20000108.0046 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-01-08 03:41 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A0217 &Cx1f; ttc-z
r f BC-BIG-COMPANY-LADN     01-08 0834
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BIG-COMPANY-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
BIOTECH GIANT TOPPLES DISNEY AS CORPORATE TOP DOG
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By Jason Z. Cohen  
 c.2000 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOS ANGELES -- Mickey Mouse is no longer king of the
California's Southland.
</P>
<P>
   Reflecting the changing landscape of the California economy,
biotechnology giant Amgen overtook the Walt Disney Co. on Friday as
the largest publicly traded company headquartered in the
five-county Los Angeles area, at least as measured by Wall Street.
</P>
<P>
   The total value of Amgen's shares surpassed that of
Burbank-based Disney on Friday. Amgen, the Thousand Oaks-based
biotech drug maker, now has a market capitalization of $69.46
billion, while Disney stands at $63.47 billion.
</P>
<P>
   The growth of companies such as Amgen and the technology firms
that dot the west San Fernando Valley and east Ventura County
demonstrates a greater shift in the economic makeup of the region,
said Jack Kyser, chief economist for the Los Angeles Economic
Development Corp.
</P>
<P>
   ``If you go back somewhere in the '60s and '70s, the Los Angeles
economy was a three-legged economy: You had aerospace,
entertainment and tourism,'' Kyser said. Now, ``I'd say we have
easily about 10 or 12 legs, and more are getting ready to sprout.''
</P>
<P>
   Disney itself has become more of a powerhouse than it was two
decades ago, Kyser said.
</P>
<P>
   ``Back in the '70s, it was basically a very small studio. Now,
it's up in the big three with Time Warner and CBS-Viacom,'' Kyser
said.
</P>
<P>
   Today, Amgen and Disney are much larger than other Los
Angeles-area companies. Atlantic Richfield Co. is the
fourth-largest publicly traded company in the Los Angeles region,
after Orange County-based Broadcom, but at $25.96 billion Arco is
less than one-half the size of Disney or Amgen.
</P>
<P>
   San Diego-based Qualcomm is the largest publicly traded company
headquartered in Southern California thanks to the stratospheric
run-up of its stock price in 1999. Qualcomm's market capitalization
-- that is, its stock price multiplied by the number of shares --
was under $5 billion in January 1999; it was valued at $98.97
billion on Friday.
</P>
<P>
   Just a few years ago, Disney reigned over the region. Amgen was
the area's second-largest company in 1997, but was only one-fourth
Disney's size.
</P>
<P>
   At that time, Amgen's market capitalization was $13 billion.
</P>
<P>
   Particularly in 1999, however, Amgen's shares have been one of
Wall Street's darlings as investors have taken note of the pipeline
of drugs that Amgen is developing.
</P>
<P>
   Its growth over the past three years has turned Amgen into a
company with a greater market value than some of the nation's most
famous companies. For example, Amgen's market capitalization is now
greater than Ford Motor Co., the nation's largest automaker; and
Boeing Co., the world's largest aerospace company.
</P>
<P>
   ``Our stock has enjoyed rapid growth in each of the last two
years, based upon a growing appreciation of our primarily near-term
product pipeline,'' said Amgen spokesman David Kaye. ``With several
important drugs nearing potential approval, certainly that has
raised interest in our stock.''
</P>
<P>
   Among the products the company is preparing for presentation to
the federal Food and Drug Administration are follow-ups to its
franchise products, the blockbuster drugs Epogen and Neupogen.
</P>
<P>
   Both products have generated more than $1 billion in annual
sales for Amgen. The next-generation versions offer longer dosing
and, according to analysts, could each match that level of annual
sales.
</P>
<P>
   ``It has really been our ability to sustain the growth of our
two franchise products as well as invest in our pipeline,'' Kaye
said. ``We hope that pipeline is about to bear fruit.''
</P>
<P>
   While Amgen's market cap has skyrocketed in the past three
years, Disney's has been relatively flat after a precipitous drop
18 months ago.
</P>
<P>
   At its peak, Disney's market cap hit $83 billion in April 1998,
but its years of rapid expansion in the early 1990s began to take
their toll at the end of the decade.
</P>
<P>
   Earnings began to slide, and the stock price followed suit,
dipping from an early-1999 peak of $41 to its November low of
$23.50 per share. On Friday, Disney shares closed at $31.125.
</P>
<P>
   The decline in Disney's price, rather than making it
unattractive, makes Disney's stock a bargain, said Douglas
Christopher, an analyst with Los Angeles investment firm Crowell
Weedon who follows both companies.
</P>
<P>
   ``Disney, on a price-to-cash-flow basis, is one of the cheapest
blue chip stocks we can find,'' Christopher said. ``Our price
target within the next 12 months is almost $50 a share.''
</P>
<P>
   It's very possible Disney could mount a comeback, Christopher
said, and regain its title as the largest publicly traded company
headquartered in Southern California.
</P>
<P>
   ``Currently, Disney has been somewhat out of favor with the
market,'' Kyser said. ``Rule of thumb: You never write off the
Mouse House. It always comes back.''
</P>
<P>
   X X X
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-01-08-00 0341EST &QL; 
