<SLUG> BC-THISWEEK-REVIEW-2TAKES-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
NEWS OF THE WEEK IN REVIEW 
</HEADLINE>
   (The Week in Review)  
(NOTE TO INTERNATIONAL CLIENTS: For international clients' use by
special arrangement only. Asian and European points: contact Karl
Horwitz in Paris for details and prices (Phone: 47 42 17 11; FAX:
47-42-80-44). Latin American points: contact Olivia Vasquez in Los
Angeles (Phone: 310-996-0075; FAX: 310-996-0089) 
(bl) 
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   Politics in the New Russian Style &QL;
</P>
<P>
   In Russia, perhaps even more than in New Hampshire, politics is
currently everything, and its exemplar is Acting President Vladimir
Putin. He campaigned throughout the week as if he were not the
runaway favorite in presidential elections now scheduled for March
26; he proclaimed tighter foreign currency controls, summoned
parliamentary leaders for a strategy session and, at one point, let
his close-cropped hair down in a nationally broadcast television
interview about what it was like to replace Boris Yeltsin in the
Kremlin.
</P>
<P>
   His principal rival, former Prime Minister Yevgeny Primakov,
remained stoic, refusing to say whether he would run for president
as he had indicated he would last month, before Yeltsin resigned
and gave Putin an almost unbeatable head start.
</P>
<P>
   The one cloud on Putin's horizon was a black one indeed: The war
in Chechnya, until now a Russian cakewalk, became pitched. Urban
warfare around Chechnya's capital, Grozny, proved so tough for the
attacking Russians that offensive operations were suspended and the
top command was shuffled.
</P>
<P>
   Yeltsin, meanwhile, seemed only semiretired: visiting Israel to
observe Christmas, he was treated everywhere like a revered head of
state, and seemed to relish it. His spokesman said he was not
Russia's former president, but its first one. Yeltsin underscored
that: ``I haven't retired yet,'' he said, in what may or may not
have been a joke.
</P>
<P>
   _ MICHAEL WINES
</P>
<P>
   Fighting Sticker Shock
</P>
<P>
   Throughout the 1990s, top-ranked colleges and universities
across the United States watched their endowments skyrocket along
with the stock market. Still, the cost of attending them kept
climbing.
</P>
<P>
   Now one such college, Williams, has decided not to raise
tuition, room, board or fees _ which total $31,520 annually, about
half the institution's actual cost _ in the next academic year. For
Williams, a 2,000-student campus in western Massachusetts, it is
the first halt in increases since 1954.
</P>
<P>
   Such highly selective institutions operate in a fiercely
competitive environment, and experts predict that others will
follow suit. One criticism of these institutions has been that they
were reluctant to free up money from their rapidly expanding
endowments to hold down costs to students; that, in fact, is the
course Williams now plans to take. Even as tuition and fees
increased 50 percent there, from $20,760, since 1990, the endowment
was tripling, from $333 million to more than $1 billion.
</P>
<P>
   Williams is hardly the only institution in such a situation:
Harvard, the leader, has an endowment near $14 billion _ and a
current sticker price of $34,682.
</P>
<P>
   _ JODI WILGOREN
</P>
<P>
   Another 4-Year Term For Greenspan
</P>
<P>
   President Clinton nominated Alan Greenspan to a fourth term as
chairman of the Federal Reserve, joining Wall Street, economists
and politicians from both parties in crediting him with deftly
nurturing the nation's long run of prosperity.
</P>
<P>
   Greenspan's reappointment insured some continuity in economic
policy as Democrats and Republicans fight for control of the White
House and Congress. With the economy steaming along at a
potentially inflationary pace, it also removed the possibility that
Greenspan might feel under pressure to hold off on raising interest
rates in order to ensure he could keep his job.
</P>
<P>
   Investors saw Greenspan's renomination as confirmation of their
fears that the Fed will raise rates aggressively this year,
providing further reason for them to cash in the big profits from
last year's runup in equity prices. Stocks tumbled through much of
the week, led by some of those technology-company high fliers,
before appearing to stabilize.
</P>
<P>
   _ RICHARD W. STEVENSON
</P>
<P>
   Bush and Gore Get Key Endorsements
</P>
<P>
   Texas Gov. George Bush got an enthusiastic endorsement from a
former rival for the Republican presidential nomination, Elizabeth
Dole, and spent his first full day back on the campaign trail in
the new year showcasing Mrs. Dole and hoping that she would bring
over women and independents to help him beat back Sen. John McCain
in New Hampshire.
</P>
<P>
   In the Democratic race, Vice President Al Gore won the backing
of Sen. Edward M. Kennedy of Massachusetts, Washington's reigning
liberal. The Gore campaign was looking for Kennedy to provide a
boost in the Northeast, where support for Gore's rival, former Sen.
Bill Bradley, is the strongest.
</P>
<P>
   The reaction of the insurgent McCain and Bradley campaigns was
identical: They said the endorsements showed their rivals were
creatures of the establishment.
</P>
<P>
   _ ALISON MITCHELL
</P>
<P>
   nn
</P>
<P>
   Problems? What Problems?
</P>
<P>
   Don't believe anyone who tells you there were no year 2000
computer problems. There was a baby with a birth certificate
stating she was 100 years old. A couple of people briefly had small
fortunes magically appear in their bank accounts. A Web site
reviewing the performance of mutual funds appeared to be reporting
from the year 19100.
</P>
<P>
   There were tens of thousands of other hiccups too, not all of
them amusing. But there were no disasters of the kind that had
prompted huge numbers of potential travelers to lie low over the
holiday and abstain from using airlines in particular. So by
mid-week, corporate and government command centers that had been
staffed to the gills with specialists prepared to leap into action
had all the bustle of exhibits in a wax museum. Many shut down
ahead of schedule.
</P>
<P>
   Managers who had overseen the fixes, especially in financial
circles, stuck firmly to their belief that hard work had allowed
the world to dodge a bullet. Some said it was too soon to declare
victory. But the most visible signs of Y2K turmoil were in Internet
chat rooms where the forecasters of disaster, known as gloomers,
expressed disbelief and their longtime opponents, the pollies
(short for Pollyanna's) gloated mercilessly.
</P>
<P>
   _ BARNABY J. FEDER
</P>
<P>
   An Internet Stock Adviser Is Charged With Fraud
</P>
<P>
   In the highest-profile Internet stock fraud case yet, the
Securities and Exchange Commission sued Yun Soo Oh Park, one of the
Web's best-known stock gurus, for fraud. Regulators said Park had
lied about his picks' returns, secretly accepted stock in a company
in exchange for recommending it to his almost 4,000 subscribers and
repeatedly urged subscribers to buy the same stocks that he was
selling.
</P>
<P>
   Park, 50, will fight the charges, his lawyer said. But the case,
which raises First Amendment issues, is a clear signal that
securities regulators are determined to rein in fraud on the wild
wild Web.
</P>
<P>
   _ GRETCHEN MORGENSON
</P>
<P>
   An Election Changes The Rulers of Croatia
</P>
<P>
   In what Washington hopes will be a model for Slobodan
Milosevic's Serbia, the voters of Croatia gave their democratic
opposition a sweeping victory in parliamentary elections,
dethroning the Croatian Democratic Union of the late president,
Franjo Tudjman, who died in December.
</P>
<P>
   A six-party opposition coalition will have a stable majority,
but it may be a month before the likely new prime minister, Ivica
Racan, a thoughtful former Communist, can take office. Presidential
elections are on Jan. 24, and the opposition hopes to elect Racan
partner Drazen Budisa over the current foreign minister, Mate
Granic, a relative moderate in the Tudjman party.
</P>
<P>
   _ STEVEN ERLANGER
</P>
<P>
   Dozens Feared Dead In Norway Train Wreck
</P>
<P>
   Two trains collided near Rena, Norway, in the country's worst
train wreck ever. As many as 35 people were thought to have died;
the number remained uncertain because the authorities were unsure
how many people were aboard. Agence France Press reported Saturday
that 18 bodies had been recovered thus far.
</P>
<P>
   Moving Day (Sort Of) For the Clintons  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Hillary Rodham Clinton, the Senate candidate, and her husband,
William Jefferson Clinton, the president, moved into their new home
in Chappaqua, N.Y., a year before the lease runs out on their
current home in Washington.
</P>
<P>
   Actually, Mrs. Clinton had planned to move in alone Thursday to
unpack, but the president, at the last minute, changed his plans
and accompanied her for an overnight stay. Mrs. Clinton's mother,
Dorothy Rodham, stayed, too.
</P>
<P>
   White House press secretary Joe Lockhart would not say what the
couple ate for their first dinner in their new home, a $1.7
million, 111-year-old house north of New York City that will be
Mrs. Clinton's base during her first political campaign, but he
said it was delivered by a friend, Jill Iscol of Pound Ridge, N.Y.
He said the couple was ``very excited'' about the move.
</P>
<P>
   China's Military Resumes U.S. Contacts
</P>
<P>
   After a prolonged chill, China has agreed to resume military
contacts with the United States, dispatching a senior army general
for two days of talks in Washington later this month.
</P>
<P>
   The Pentagon considers ``military-to-military'' exchanges
important to stability in Asia, but it is not clear how committed
the Chinese military is to the idea. China remains deeply wary of
American motives after NATO's bombing of its embassy in Belgrade
during the war against Yugoslavia last May.
</P>
<P>
   _ STEVEN LEE MYERS
</P>
<P>
   New Arrests In Suspected Terror Plot
</P>
<P>
   Two more Algerians were arrested, one in Brooklyn and the other
in Seattle, in the broadening investigation of a terrorist bomb
plot that authorities say was interrupted with the arrest in
December of Ahmed Ressam as he crossed into the United States near
Seattle.
</P>
<P>
   The new arrests, which included one man taken into custody at
Kennedy International Airport on New Year's Day as he was preparing
to leave on a flight to Paris, came amid indications that the
authorities were focusing their efforts on a network of Algerians
in New York, Seattle, and Boston. The intended target of the bomb
plot remained unknown.
</P>
<P>
   _ BENJAMIN WEISER
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
