<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-NORWAY-SWEDEN-REVIEW-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
LEIF TO LARS: DROP DEAD, NEIGHBOR! 
</HEADLINE>
   (The Week in Review)  
(NOTE TO INTERNATIONAL CLIENTS: For international clients' use by
special arrangement only. Asian and European points: contact Karl
Horwitz in Paris for details and prices (Phone: 47 42 17 11; FAX:
47-42-80-44). Latin American points: contact Olivia Vasquez in Los
Angeles (Phone: 310-996-0075; FAX: 310-996-0089) 
(bl) 
 By WALTER GIBBS   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   OSLO, Norway _ To the untrained observer, Swedes and Norwegians
(aka the Olsons and the Olsens) may seem interchangeable. Both are
prosperous, blue-eyed and reserved. On the world stage, they hand
out peace prizes and preach global cooperation while saving their
aggressions, if any, for the ski slope.
</P>
<P>
   However, in the privacy of their snowbound peninsula, Sweden and
Norway have lately resembled ``two blind men slugging it out on a
highway,'' in the words of a Danish commentator.
</P>
<P>
   Officially the countries are having a business disagreement. A
$50 billion merger between the Swedish and Norwegian state-owned
telecommunications companies has unraveled. Unofficially, this
telephone tiff has exposed a dark current of national chauvinism
and aggression _ just the sort of thing the new age of globalism is
said to be rendering obsolete.
</P>
<P>
   In recent weeks, a Swedish government minister derided Norway as
``the last Soviet state.'' Top Norwegian officials called the
Swedes liars and questioned whether they could read. The chief
executive of the briefly merged company even shoved a radio
journalist to the sidewalk and kicked him in the back, explaining
later, by form of apology, ``He looked like a drug addict.''
</P>
<P>
   Tension between Sweden and Norway is traditionally defused by
low humor. When a Swedish newspaper columnist denounced Norway over
the fiasco, a Norwegian retorted in print, ``I hope you gain 12
kilos during Christmas and grow a wart on your nose.'' But it
didn't work this time. Millennium's end had been soured by the
re-enactment of painful colonial-era dynamics.
</P>
<P>
   Norwegians believed that each side in the enterprise was to have
equal say in strategic matters. So when a dubious double vote by
the Swedish board chairman made cosmopolitan Stockholm rather than
rustic Oslo the headquarters of the all-important cellular
telephony division, Norwegians felt betrayed. They suffered a
collective flashback to a century ago, when Sweden's King Oscar
repeatedly used his veto power to humiliate the provincial
Norwegian parliament.
</P>
<P>
   By contrast, the cell phone grab was cheered in Stockholm, where
the tabloid Expressen headlined its cover story, ``Ha, ha,
Norway!''
</P>
<P>
   In Oslo, the normally fractious Parliament erupted as one to
demand that Prime Minister Kjell Magne Bondevik dynamite the
merger, which he did. It was not clear how that helped Norwegian
telephone customers or the development of Norwegian technology, but
as a battle tactic it had precedent. Twice in earlier centuries,
residents of the Norwegian border town of Halden burned their city
to the ground to drive out the Swedes.
</P>
<P>
   Today, 94 years after breaking free of imperial Sweden and 30
years after striking oil in the North Sea, Norway, whose mostly
rural population of 4.4 million is half that of more urbanized
Sweden's, continues to savor independence and to search for its own
identity.
</P>
<P>
   ``Norway still defines itself in terms of its relationship to
Sweden,'' said the Norwegian author Tor Bomann-Larsen. ``To be free
and independent means to be rid of the Swedes.''
</P>
<P>
   In daily life the rivalry is usually good-natured. Norwegians
love to shop in Swedish stores while Swedes seek serenity in the
mountains of Norway. According to Aake Daun, an ethnologist at the
University of Stockholm, Swedes see Norwegians as ``healthy and
honest, reliable and sporty,'' though not usually business-partner
material.
</P>
<P>
   ``Swedes think unreflectively that Sweden is the biggest and
most advanced and most creative of the Scandinavian countries,''
Professor Daun said. ``When they talk to Norwegians about how
things are done in Sweden, it is like a schoolteacher telling how
things are done in the grown-up world.''
</P>
<P>
   Norway's development of vast offshore oil reserves has boosted
its social stock, but most Swedes consider Volvo, Electrolux and
other big Swedish manufacturing companies more worthy of esteem. To
them it was a no-brainer to locate the proposed bi-national mobile
phone service in Stockholm, where the mobile-phone giant Ericsson
would provide synergy.
</P>
<P>
   Norway blames Swedish arrogance rather than Norwegian
nationalism for destroying what could have been a global showcase
for Scandinavia's vaunted wireless technology. But the boundary
between it and the Swedes is now also the fault line of the
burgeoning European Union. Twice Norwegians have rejected EU
membership against sound business advice, and their isolation from
Europe is deepening.
</P>
<P>
   Victor Norman, a Norwegian economist, said the telecom nightmare
could send Norway further into its shell while Sweden turns to
another former colony, Finland, for a telecom partner. If that
merger succeeds it might be deserving of the Nobel Peace Prize.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-01-08-00 1053EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
