<DOCNO> NYT20000108.0060 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-01-08 11:01 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A0243 &Cx1f; var-z
u a BC-CANDIDATES-MEDICAL-RE     01-08 0878
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CANDIDATES-MEDICAL-REVIEW-2TAKES-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
FOR CANDIDATES, HOW HEALTHY IS HEALTHY ENOUGH? 
</HEADLINE>
   (The Week in Review)  
(NOTE TO INTERNATIONAL CLIENTS: For international clients' use by
special arrangement only. Asian and European points: contact Karl
Horwitz in Paris for details and prices (Phone: 47 42 17 11; FAX:
47-42-80-44). Latin American points: contact Olivia Vasquez in Los
Angeles (Phone: 310-996-0075; FAX: 310-996-0089) 
(bl) 
 By DENISE GRADY   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   When questions surfaced about Sen. John McCain's emotional
stability, he put them to rest last month with a deluge of paper:
1,500 pages of medical records, going back to 1973. And that was
the abridged version.
</P>
<P>
   Americans now know that, psychologically, McCain is a rock, in
the opinion of his doctors. But they also now know about the mole
on his shoulder, about his arthritis, hay fever and intestinal
polyps, as well as the size of his prostate gland.
</P>
<P>
   No law forces candidates to bare their medical histories. But
the news media and political rivals press for revelations, hinting
that those who decline may have something to hide. Some people
maintain that the public interest demands that the usual right to
confidentiality be waived. Others question whether the public
needs, wants or has a right to such information.
</P>
<P>
   When word got out that McCain was planning to release his
records, he was urged not to do so by Dr. Claire Dixon-Lee,
president of the American Health Information Management
Association, whose 40,000 members maintain medical records at
hospitals and insurance companies.
</P>
<P>
   ``It would be devastating if releases of health information by
presidential candidates served as a catalyst for demands for this
kind of information from Americans when they apply for jobs or
loans, get married or partake in routine activities,'' Dr.
Dixon-Lee wrote. She suggested instead that candidates have their
doctors write ``comprehensive summaries,'' including only the
information pertinent to running for office.
</P>
<P>
   Sen. Bill Bradley has taken that approach, releasing a statement
from his doctor saying that he is in good health and that his
abnormal heart rhythms should not interfere with his work. His
staff has promised more data should he become the nominee.
</P>
<P>
   The New York Times has regularly sought medical information
about presidential candidates, assigning Lawrence K. Altman, a
reporter who is also a physician, to review medical histories and
to conduct extensive interviews with candidates and their personal
doctors. Joseph Lelyveld, the executive editor, said it was the
newspaper's responsibility to provide readers with information
``pertinent to an individual's ability to do the job of
president.''
</P>
<P>
   He cited former Sen. Paul Tsongas as an example of why medical
information is important, and why a letter from the candidate's
doctor is not sufficient. After telling voters he had been
successfully treated for cancer, Tsongas won the 1992 Democratic
presidential primary in New Hampshire. But he later left the race
and acknowledged under pressure that he and his doctors had
concealed a recurrence. He died of cancer in 1997, after having
publicly endorsed the formation of a presidential commission to
study the issue of how much medical information candidates should
disclose.
</P>
<P>
   ``We happen to have a doctor on our staff who doesn't seek to
examine the candidates themselves but who is qualified to examine
medical records, ask reasonable questions and draw conclusions,''
Lelyveld said. ``We don't need to publish everything he sees.''
</P>
<P>
   Certainly, candidates who have hidden their illnesses have been
elected and have governed effectively. Beyond his paralysis from
polio, which the press helped to play down by not photographing him
in his wheelchair, Franklin D. Roosevelt suffered from severe heart
disease and hypertension. His doctors knew he was severely ill when
he ran for a fourth term in 1944, but they concealed it, supposedly
as a matter of national security, because the nation was at war.
Roosevelt died a few months into the term.
</P>
<P>
   Dwight D. Eisenhower had heart disease and was secretly advised
by his doctor that he might not live through a second term. John F.
Kennedy did not tell voters he had Addison's disease, a serious
failure of the adrenal glands that required treatment with
steroids. And Abraham Lincoln is widely believed to have suffered
from lifelong bouts with depression.
</P>
<P>
   Would Americans have voted differently in any of those cases had
they known the truth? In Kennedy's case, the 1960 election was so
close that some historians say public knowledge of his health might
have given the victory to Richard M. Nixon. But some would argue
that Lincoln's, Kennedy's and Eisenhower's ability to function in
office prove that candidates should not be disqualified or judged
on the basis of health problems. Roosevelt may have been another
matter, but even if voters had known of his condition, it is hard
to imagine that they would have turned against him in wartime.
</P>
<P>
   Dr. Daniel Callahan, an ethicist and co-founder of the Hastings
Center for Bioethics in Garrison, N.Y., argued that medical privacy
should be suspended for presidential candidates.
</P>
<P>
   nn
</P>
<P>
   ``When you're running, you're giving up your privacy, and
justifiably so,'' he said. ``The reason very simply is that the
health of somebody who is going to be president will bear on the
performance of that person once in the job. It's as relevant to
know somebody's health as their positions on the issues.''
</P>
<P>
   Callahan said he found it hard to think of any exceptions. Even
though millions of people live normal lives with treatable
conditions like high blood pressure or diabetes, they should be
disclosed, he said, along with any other disorder that carries a
higher than average likelihood of illness or death. Genes that
predispose a person to breast cancer or Alzheimer's disease are
also relevant, he said, as well as psychiatric treatment.
</P>
<P>
   ``Recurrent depression would certainly be something you'd want
to know about,'' Callahan said. ``Manic depression would be even
more worrisome, with someone who was hysterical at some times and
flat-out depressed at others. I guess I'd like to see a letter from
a doctor that went over the main features of mental and physical
health, but didn't present the reading of every test that was
taken. But the physician should be neutral, not a crony or pal of
the patient.''
</P>
<P>
   Dr. Talmadge King, chief of medicine at San Francisco General
Hospital, questioned the relevance of medical information. ``I
don't know if it helps us make a more learned decision about the
candidates,'' he said. ``It may potentially just play into people's
phobias and biases. We've had a number of amazing leaders who had
disabilities.''
</P>
<P>
   George Annas, chairman of the health law department at Boston
University, said a letter from a doctor vouching for a candidate's
health should be enough. He said the rigors of campaigning would
take their toll on anyone who did not have the stamina to be
president, and that voters would see that for themselves without
the media's examining medical records.
</P>
<P>
   ``Have they ever found out anything that mattered?'' he asked.
``I don't think there's any magic in medical records, that we're
going to learn something essential about candidates by rooting
around in their records. If there's a terminal illness, you'd want
to know. That is fair, but that's it.''
</P>
<P>
   Nor should candidates be expected to disclose whether they have
ever consulted a psychiatrist, Annas said, because the stigma
attached to psychiatric treatment might cause politicians who need
it to forgo it rather than risk being forced to admit it. He
pointed to the case of Sen. Thomas Eagleton, who in 1972 was
dropped as the Democratic vice-presidential nominee after it became
known that he had failed to tell his running mate, Sen. George
McGovern, that he had received electroshock treatments for
depression.
</P>
<P>
   King said he was ``willing to bet'' that many people with
depression or manic depression had been successful politicians. He
suggested that if a psychiatric disorder was severe enough to
interfere with a person's ability to function, it would be obvious
to voters anyway.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-01-08-00 1101EST &QL; 
