<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-01-08 11:04 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A0245 &Cx1f; var-z
u a BC-ROCKER-RACISM-REVIEW-     01-08 0909
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-ROCKER-RACISM-REVIEW-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
WEIGHING THERAPY FOR A NARROW MIND 
</HEADLINE>
   (The Week in Review)  
(NOTE TO INTERNATIONAL CLIENTS: For international clients' use by
special arrangement only. Asian and European points: contact Karl
Horwitz in Paris for details and prices (Phone: 47 42 17 11; FAX:
47-42-80-44). Latin American points: contact Olivia Vasquez in Los
Angeles (Phone: 310-996-0075; FAX: 310-996-0089) 
(bl) 
 By JAMES C. McKINLEY Jr.   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   Is making racist and xenophobic remarks a sign of mental
illness?
</P>
<P>
   Major League Baseball seemed to suggest it was last week when
commissioner Bud Selig demanded that John Rocker, the ace relief
pitcher for the Atlanta Braves, undergo psychological testing,
three weeks after his remarks about immigrants and blacks were
reported in Sports Illustrated.
</P>
<P>
   But Selig's move may have more to do with politics and a desire
to save Rocker's career than with worries about his mental health,
say experts who study sports.
</P>
<P>
   The consensus among psychiatrists and psychologists is that
racism in and of itself is not a mental illness, unless combined
with other problems. If it were, a huge swath of American society
would be considered ill, they say..
</P>
<P>
   ``A lot of people have these thoughts but simply don't express
them,'' said Chris Crandall, a social psychologist at the
University of Kansas who studies prejudice. ``I think the guy just
didn't have his mental editor turned on.''
</P>
<P>
   Rocker, 25, seems to have better control over his 95-mph
fastball than his tongue. During last year's playoffs, he engaged
in vituperative battles with New York Mets fans, spitting at them
and venting his hatred of the city.
</P>
<P>
   But Rocker went even further in comments to a magazine writer
who accompanied him on a recent hunting trip. Among other things,
Rocker called an overweight black team-mate ``a fat monkey,''
complained about what ``degenerates'' New York fans were and said,
``the biggest thing I don't like about New York are the
foreigners.''
</P>
<P>
   Rocker also likened riding the subway to Shea Stadium to driving
through Beirut, and described the passengers as ``some kid with
purple hair next to some queer with AIDS right next to some dude
who just got out of jail for the fourth time, right next to some
20-year-old mom with four kids.''
</P>
<P>
   But as abhorrent as those views are to many, they are not
necessarily insane, Dr. Daniel Borenstein, the president-elect of
the American Psychiatric Association, said. ``A tendency toward
bias is a normal human characteristic,'' he said. ``An extreme form
of bias is racism, but none of that is a mental disorder in
itself.''
</P>
<P>
   What makes Rocker's outbursts scary, some sociologists say, is
that many Americans share his views though they know it is
politically verboten to express them. ``Vast majorities of white
Americans hold stereotypical views of people of color that are not
far from Rocker's views,'' said Richard Lapchick, founder of the
Center for the Study of Sport in Society.
</P>
<P>
   Lapchick said the center's surveys suggest racism is on the rise
among young Americans over the last 15 years. To expect sports to
remain insulated from such trends is naive. ``We are not going to
get baseball or basketball teams free of people who have the
attitudes of Rocker,'' he said. ``We can at least make our players
and people in our front offices understand there are consequences
for going across certain lines.''
</P>
<P>
   Baseball officials have said Rocker's evaluation is a prelude
toward meting out a fine, a suspension or some other discipline.
Officials said the idea of testing Rocker before deciding how
severe punishment should be was a compromise reached with the Major
League Baseball Players Association, the players' union.
</P>
<P>
   ``The remarks made by Rocker were pretty reprehensible,'' said
Richard Levin, a spokesman for Major League Baseball. ``It's not
something we can overlook. Something has to be done and this is a
first step.''
</P>
<P>
   His mental health aside, Rocker's diatribe has not been good for
baseball's image, which is not good for business. Nor will it be
easy for him to keep working for the Braves, whose starting lineup
last year regularly included black and Hispanic players.
</P>
<P>
   The Atlanta City Council, which represents a city where
minorities are the majority, has passed a resolution calling on the
Braves to dismiss Rocker. Some team mates have also made it plain
that they do not look forward to working with him this year.
</P>
<P>
   But the pitcher's value may outweigh all that. He was a
dominating closer for the Braves as they won the 1999 National
League Pennant with 38 regular season saves.
</P>
<P>
   While Rocker can exercise his First Amendment rights, the
Constitution shields him only from governmental actions to limit
speech, say civil liberties lawyers. Courts have held a private
company or organization can still discipline or dismiss an employee
for statements if they interfere with an employee's ability to do
his job or damage the employer's image.
</P>
<P>
   It is perhaps a measure of Rocker's talent that Braves president
Stan Kasten, the son of a Polish immigrant whose family was killed
in a Nazi concentration camp, has said the pitcher deserves ``a
second chance.''
</P>
<P>
   ``The value of Rocker's case is it gets us talking about racism
again,'' Lapchick said. ``One of the great problems of racism in
America is that we tend, unless it is thrown up in our faces, to
avoid it.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-01-08-00 1104EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT20000108.0065 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-01-08 11:04 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
