</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MIDEAST-TALKS-REVIEW-2TAKES-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
LOOKING FOR CAMP DAVID ON THE MAP OF SHEPHERDSTOWN 
</HEADLINE>
   (The Week in Review)  
(NOTE TO INTERNATIONAL CLIENTS: For international clients' use by
special arrangement only. Asian and European points: contact Karl
Horwitz in Paris for details and prices (Phone: 47 42 17 11; FAX:
47-42-80-44). Latin American points: contact Olivia Vasquez in Los
Angeles (Phone: 310-996-0075; FAX: 310-996-0089) 
(bl) 
 By DEBORAH SONTAG  
 
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   JERUSALEM _ Before President Clinton left Washington for his
first meeting with Israeli and Syrian leaders at a Shepherdstown,
W.Va., retreat, his aides requested a copy of the Camp David
agreement to review the formulations that forged peace between
Egypt and Israel some 20 years ago.
</P>
<P>
   Similarly, in Jerusalem, Israeli officials feverishly studied
the negotiations with Jewish settlers evacuated from the Sinai as a
result of that accord. Clearly, that first evacuation, which broke
the Zionist taboo against abandoning a settlement, would serve as
the historical template _ complete with do's and don'ts _ for what
may be Israel's next one, from the Golan Heights.
</P>
<P>
   ``The whole Camp David process is the yardstick, whether it
should be or shouldn't be,'' said Gerald Steinberg, a diplomacy
expert at Bar-Ilan University.
</P>
<P>
   Even in quaint Shepherdstown itself, the memory of Camp David
asserted itself in the 20-year-old Hebrew-Arabic-English peace
posters that decorated the store windows last week. Following the
Egyptian-Israeli peace treaty, a Jewish grandmother had given the
posters to her granddaughter, now a town resident. Save them for
the day that Israel makes peace with the rest of its enemies, she
had said.
</P>
<P>
   In some ways, the comparison is unfair. Camp David _ 12
excruciatingly long days in which Jimmy Carter, Menachem Begin and
Anwar Sadat hammered out a framework of peace _ was the climax of a
process. Shepherdstown, where bilateral contact has been limited to
clipped utterances of ``Lobby, please'' in the hotel elevator, is
an opening scene.
</P>
<P>
   But the comparing and contrasting of Camp David and
Shepherdstown is inevitable, because parallels are so explicit.
</P>
<P>
   For Israel, the parallel begins with the basic formula of
trading peace for land occupied during a war _ then the Sinai, now
the Golan Heights. There is the uprooting of Jewish settlements
planted by the Israeli government _ then some 5,800 residents, now
17,000. And there is the attempt to not just declare
non-belligerency but to normalize relations with the most
influential foe of the Jewish homeland in the Arab world _ then
Egypt, now Syria.
</P>
<P>
   For Syrian President Hafez Assad, the Camp David deal is
something to equal or best, especially since he declined Sadat's
invitation to join in his peace negotiations with Israel in the
1970s.
</P>
<P>
   ``He has to trump Sadat, or else why has he waited 20 years,
especially after criticizing Sadat so strongly for making too many
concessions,'' said Shibley Telhami, who holds the University of
Maryland's Anwar Sadat Chair for Population, Development and Peace.
</P>
<P>
   For both sides, there is the American purse that bankrolls the
effort. After Camp David, that meant $3 billion in annual aid to
Israel and $2.3 billion to Egypt over 20 years, and an
understanding that the amounts were linked, to rise or fall
together.
</P>
<P>
   And finally, despite the cold peace that emerged from the
beginnings of a more promising relationship, there is the fact that
the fundamental peace stuck: There have been no conflicts, no
skirmishes, no large military exercises on the Israeli-Egyptian
border.
</P>
<P>
   The world has changed much, of course, since the Camp David
talks in September 1978. Egypt was a key client state of the Soviet
Union, and the cold war hovered over the forging of that first
melting of hostilities in the Middle East. That was a factor
crucial for the avid American participation.
</P>
<P>
   Since then, besides the breakup of the Soviet Union, peace has
been forged with Jordan. The peace effort with the Palestinians,
which tentatively began with agreement at Camp David that the
Palestinians had a right to full autonomy, has chugged into its
final stages. Camp David itself broke up Egypt's alliance with
Syria.
</P>
<P>
   Headlines from Israeli newspapers in the late 1970s bear an
eerie resemblance to current ones. Right-wing parties threaten to
quit the governing coalition; settlers mobilize rallies in their
own defense; Israelis express anxiety about increasing dependence
on the Americans, and some accuse the government of ignoring
domestic concerns in its focus on peace.
</P>
<P>
   Recently, one Jerusalem newspaper, after sneaking a
correspondent into Syria, gave in to pages of rapture about Syria
itself _ the warmth of the people, the smoothness of the hummus. It
recalled the euphoria that Sadat engendered in the Israelis.
</P>
<P>
   But in general, this time, there is very little enthusiasm for
the prospects of what peace will bring beside an end to war. That
is a product of Assad's tough persona. But it is a lesson of Camp
David, too. The fact that the peace with Egypt remains so cool
fuels some of the opposition to the negotiations with Syria. And
even for supporters, it mutes expectations.
</P>
<P>
   ``We learned our lesson not to expect too much from a major Arab
power that has its own internal agenda and problems,'' said Joseph
Alpher, director of the American Jewish Committee in Israel. ``The
inclination is to build a kind of equation. Despite Sadat's warmth,
we got a cold peace with Egypt. So with Assad's coldness, we're
going to have a frigid peace with Syria.''
</P>
<P>
   nn
</P>
<P>
   After painful wrangling, the Egyptians got the full Israeli
withdrawal they wanted. Now Syria, too, is pushing for a full
withdrawal. ``For every inch of the Sinai that Sadat got, Assad
wants a little more,'' Professor Steinberg said. But unlike with
Israel and Egypt, where both sides accepted the international
borders, Syria wants Israel to pull back another seven square miles
beyond the international border to the line that stood between them
on June 4, 1967.
</P>
<P>
   And unlike with Egypt, which repossessed a 124-mile stretch of
desert that served as a natural buffer with Israel, the heights of
the Golan confer a military advantage on Syria. This changes the
dynamic of the negotiation over land, with Israel putting a high
value on the security controls that could be provided by early
warning stations.
</P>
<P>
   Those who question the use of Camp David as a model also argue
that Sadat, in braving rifts with the Arab world, was the one who
took the risks and that Assad should not be rewarded for waiting
this long. And they point to what they see as a bitter fruit:
Egypt's sophisticated military capability, a potential threat to
Israel.
</P>
<P>
   Others, though, note the peculiar cooperation that has developed
between Israel and Egypt, which, since their aid levels are linked,
almost jointly lobby Congress every year for continued high levels
of financing. They say that if Syria were brought into the U.S.
orbit, it would give the Americans and Israelis leverage. Assad too
is reportedly looking to establish a close economic, military and
strategic relationship with the United States.
</P>
<P>
   That Assad is not present in Shepherdstown could be a reflection
solely of his ill health. But it is likely that it is another
signal of how he wants to do things differently than Sadat at Camp
David. Many Egyptians, and many Arabs in general, were disappointed
with that accord, and believed that Sadat had caved in to U.S.
demands and had sold out the Palestinians to regain the Sinai. .
</P>
<P>
   Israeli Prime Minister Ehud Barak drew a direct parallel with
the Israeli-Egyptian conflict and its resolution before leaving for
Shepherdstown. He visited the spiritual leader of the
ultra-Orthodox Shas party, Rabbi Ovadia Yosef, seeking an
endorsement of his peace effort.
</P>
<P>
   ``There were once those who said that Sharm el-Sheikh without
peace was preferable,'' he said. ``Then,'' he continued, referring
to the 1973 war, ``we had 3,000 graves and the picture changed.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
