<P>
   &UR; FOR SUNDAY AMs &LR;
</P>
<P>
   Here are today's top news stories from The New York Times News
Service for AMs of Sunday, Jan. 9:
</P>
<P>
   &UR; INTERNATIONAL &LR;  (Moving in ``i'' news file.)
</P>
<P>
   MEXICO-DRUGS-I (Tijuana, Mexico) _ The first of a two-part
series on how drugs and crime have corrupted Mexico. By Tim Golden.
(EDS: Two versions of this story will move: full-length _ 3,700
words _ as it appears in The Times and an abridged version,
MEXICO-DRUGS-I-ABR, at less than half that length. The full-length
version will move by noon EST.) With a map.
</P>
<P>
   RUSSIA-YELTSIN (Moscow) _ This grand nation boasts a 1,100-year
lineage of autocrats, from Ivan the Terrible to Peter the Great;
from Aleksei the Quietest One to Uncle Joe Stalin. So the question
arises: what to call its first democratic leader, Boris
Nikolayevich Yeltsin? By Michael Wines.
</P>
<P>
   RUSSIA-CHECHNYA (Mozdok, Russia) _ News Analysis on the shakeup
of the Russian command around the Chechen capital, Grozny, and
whether the move signals a change of strategy by the Kremlin. By
Michael R. Gordon.
</P>
<P>
   MIDEAST-TALKS (Shepherdstown, W.Va.) _ From hilltops in this
pre-Civil War town where Israel and Syria have negotiated all week,
you can just make out the farm across the Potomac River where
Abraham Lincoln met Gen. George B. McClellan in a tent and
complained that he suffered from ``the slows'' after the battle of
Antietam. Last week, traveling here almost daily to deal with a
very different conflict, Bill Clinton found himself struggling to
cure the same affliction. By David E. Sanger.
</P>
<P>
   BRAZIL-ECON (Rio de Janeiro, Brazil) _ One year after a currency
crisis sparked fears that the Brazilian economy was heading toward
an Asian-style meltdown, growth has resumed, calm has returned and
it is once again business as usual here. In other words, Brazil's
Congress is acting as if the crisis never occurred and
procrastinating about approving the government's economic program.
By Larry Rohter. (With a map.)
</P>
<P>
   CHILE-POLITICS (Santiago, Chile) _ A look at the political
skills of Joaquin Lavin, the first conservative candidate with a
chance to win Chile's presidency since Gen. Augusto Pinochet left
power in 1990. By Clifford Krauss.
</P>
<P>
   CZECH-SEX-HARASSMENT (Prague, Czech Republic) _ When the
European Union asks its applicants for admission what men do to
women in the workplace, the countries of Central Europe will
apparently have some explaining to do. To the shock of many Czechs,
a recent study commissioned by the daily Lidove Noviny indicated
that almost half of the country's working women have been subjected
to sexual harassment in the workplace. By Ladka Bauerova.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; NATIONAL &LR;  (Moving in ``a'' news file.)
</P>
<P>
   Y2K-ASSESS (Undated) _ Whether it is with scorn, anger or
resignation, most computer experts and year 2000 program managers
brush off suggestions that they overreacted to the Y2K threat,
taken in by computer companies and consultants positioned to profit
from fear. Still, like the skeptics, many wonder: How did countries
that started so late _ and appeared to do so little _ manage to
enter 2000 as smoothly as nations like the United States and
Britain that got an early jump? By Barnaby J. Feder.
</P>
<P>
   LA-EDWARDS-TRIAL (Baton Rouge, La.) _ For a quarter century,
Edwin W. Edwards was Louisiana's great guilty pleasure, the
four-term governor whose breezy misbehavior amused the voters while
infuriating several generations of federal law-enforcement
officers. But beginning on Monday, the former governor will face
what almost everyone acknowledges is the most serious prosecution
of his career, one that he may have difficulty eluding with the
Cajun wit that always beguiled previous juries. David Firestone.
</P>
<P>
   CUBA-BOY (Miami) _ The heated political battle over the custody
of the 6-year-old boy Elian Gonzalez showed no signs of subsiding
Saturday after a House Republican leader subpoenaed the boy to
testify before Congress in an effort to keep him in the United
States. By Lizette Alvarez.
</P>
<P>
   ATIICA-SETTLEMENT (Undated) _ Robert Lavinski is a piano teacher
in Rochester, N.Y., who is partial to Ravel, Chopin and Chick
Corea. Arthur Bobby Harrison volunteers as a boxing coach in
downtown Syracuse. George Alexander Shorts Jr. is a Brooklyn
resident who has never been able to work because of his broken
toes. What they have in common is that they are all former inmates
at Attica who survived the bloodiest incident in the history of
America's prisons: the uprising and siege of 1971 in which 43
people were killed and more than 80 wounded. A settlement proposed
on Tuesday that would give up to 1,281 inmates a total of $8
million as compensation for the abuse they suffered 29 years ago
has rekindled interest in the siege. By David W. Chen and Randal C.
Archibold.
</P>
<P>
   CIVILSUPPORT-AGENCY (Norfolk, Va.) _ One year ago, Brig. Gen.
Bruce M. Lawlor was a small-town Vermont lawyer whose duties in the
national guard included hauling water to livestock during summer
droughts and rescuing farmers in winter ice storms. Last month,
Lawlor became the first commander of a sensitive new military
operation that would respond if the United States were struck by a
chemical, germ or nuclear attack. By Elizabeth Becker.
</P>
<P>
   MICH-ICEFISHING-RISKS (Harrison Township, Mich.) _ Ice fishing
has long been a big part of winter life in Michigan. Indians
engaged in the sport long before white settlers arrived, and the
state's Department of Natural Resources estimates that 300,000
people still go ice fishing each winter. But a string of accidents,
combined with a succession of fairly mild winters, has provoked an
acrimonious fight in the Michigan Legislature over whether new laws
are needed to discourage ice anglers from taking excessive risks.
By Keith Bradsher.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; POLITICS &LR;  (Moving in ``p'' news file.)
</P>
<P>
   DEMS-MONEY (Portsmouth, N.H.) _ Many prominent Democrats say
they are deeply troubled that the Republican Party is collecting so
much more money than the Democrats that it will enjoy an
insurmountable financial advantage _ perhaps enough to cost them
the White House. By Richard L. Berke.
</P>
<P>
   BRADLEY-FUNDRAISING (Washington) _ To the surprise of many
political analysts, Bill Bradley raised more than $27 million for
his underdog quest for the Democratic nomination last year, just $2
million less than his rival, Vice President Al Gore. Though his
contributor list is laced with names of the rich and powerful, the
story of how Bradley kept pace with Gore is mainly filled with
lesser-known figures. By James Dao.
</P>
<P>
   TRUMP-POLITICS (Undated) _ There may be many reasons to run for
president of the United States, but the chance to turn a profit on
the campaign trail is generally not one of them. Unless the
office-seeker happens to be Donald Trump. By Leslie Eaton.
</P>
<P>
   DEMS-DEBATE _ Vice President Al Gore and former Sen. Bill
Bradley debate in Iowa beginning at 2 p.m. EST. By Katharine Q.
Seelye.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; WASHINGTON &LR;  (Moving in ``w'' news file.)
</P>
<P>
   NUKE-SECRETS-LEE (Washington) _ There are really two trials
taking shape in the case of Wen Ho Lee, the former Los Alamos
scientist charged with compromising nuclear secrets. By James
Risen.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; COLUMNS &LR;  (Moving in ``k'' news file.)
</P>
<P>
   DOWD-COLUMN (Washington) _ Bill Clinton's Heartbreak Hotel. By
Maureen Dowd.
</P>
<P>
   KRUGMAN-COLUMN _ Triumph of the Nerds. By Paul Krugman.
</P>
