<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-01-08 11:49 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A0256 &Cx1f; taf-z
u i BC-CHILE-POLITICS-2TAKES     01-08 1138
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CHILE-POLITICS-2TAKES(1100)-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
CHILEAN'S HOMESPUN RECORD COULD MAKE HIM PRESIDENT
</HEADLINE>
  (nk) 
 By CLIFFORD KRAUSS    
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   SANTIAGO, Chile _ Joaquin Lavin, the first conservative
candidate with a chance to win Chile's presidency since Gen.
Augusto Pinochet left power in 1990, has never managed anything
larger than a neighborhood of 250,000 people on the east side of
Santiago.
</P>
<P>
   The neighborhood, Las Condes, is a redoubt of mansions, soaring
glassy banks, luxury high-rise apartments and a city hall decorated
with prints celebrating the world of polo and golf _ hardly the
usual testing ground for a candidate who wants to govern a complex
country of nearly 16 million people.
</P>
<P>
   Lavin's resume lacks the heft of that of his opponent, Ricardo
Lagos, who headed ministries in the two previous, center-left
governments. But the 46-year-old conservative has a strong chance
of winning next Sunday's election, a showing that has much to do
with the broadly held perception that he governed little Las Condes
with imagination and creativity.
</P>
<P>
   ``People don't vote based on parties and ideology anymore,''
Lavin said in a televised debate with Lagos. ``They vote for the
candidate they believe will solve their daily problems.''
</P>
<P>
   In nearly seven years as mayor, he borrowed entire chapters from
political textbooks devised in cities as far away as New York,
Geneva and Singapore in an effort to find free-market solutions to
social problems. But more than anything else, his innovations in
education and health care are softening the image of the Chilean
right, which still carries the baggage of the human rights abuses
of the Pinochet dictatorship.
</P>
<P>
   Lavin is also part of a new wave of younger politicians who
appear committed to overturning the traditionally highly
centralized power structures of Latin America, parlaying local
government success into capturing national attention, and even high
office.
</P>
<P>
   Late last year, the mayor of Buenos Aires, Fernando de la Rua,
was elected president of Argentina, following similar victories by
mayors in Colombia, El Salvador and Nicaragua in recent years. In
both Peru and Mexico, a mayor and former mayor are contenders in
presidential elections this year.
</P>
<P>
   The man from Las Condes has used a fat budget nourished by
plentiful real estate taxes to inaugurate projects big and small,
all smartly packaged for maximum media coverage. He eased traffic
jams with battery-powered mobile traffic lights turned on and off
depending on traffic flows. He spruced up old buildings by
providing matching funds to tenants for repainting.
</P>
<P>
   Lavin created three charter schools that have improved student
performance, and he channeled people released from prison into
sanitation jobs. A devout Roman Catholic, he provided counseling
for single pregnant women _ including those who used drugs or had
been raped _ to urge them to give birth and either to rear their
own babies or to give them up for adoption.
</P>
<P>
   (BEGIN OPTIONAL TRIM)
</P>
<P>
   With advice from William J. Bratton, the former New York City
police commissioner, Lavin instituted community policing. And with
guidance from the Manhattan Institute, a conservative research
group, he modeled a new school for dropouts and gang members on the
Wildcat Academy in Lower Manhattan, an alternative high school.
</P>
<P>
   (END OPTIONAL TRIM)
</P>
<P>
   The man who might one day negotiate arms and trade deals with
Washington and Buenos Aires does not talk much about foreign policy
on the campaign trail. Instead, he goes to great lengths to spell
out how he will reduce the time patients wait for attention at
public health clinics. No subject is too small as Lavin explains
how to clean up graffiti by giving juvenile delinquents paint
brushes, provide day care for working mothers and offer college
loans to achieving students.
</P>
<P>
   Lavin began using his nuts-and-bolts philosophy for political
gain after he lost a bruising congressional race in 1989 as a
right-wing ideologue who defended Pinochet and went by the nickname
``the fighting cock.'' He reoriented his political compass to
squeak out his 1992 electoral victory with a campaign that put bus
service before any ideology.
</P>
<P>
   Four years later, he was re-elected with 78 percent of the vote
_ a result that catapulted his presidential candidacy over more
traditional conservative politicians. Last year, he resigned as
mayor to run for president. In last month's first-round balloting,
Lavin shocked the political establishment by attracting better than
47 percent of the vote and virtually tying Lagos, who only a few
months ago was expected to win easily.
</P>
<P>
   Detractors say that Lavin's programs are paternalistic and
token, and that his statements about helping the poor are meant to
confuse voters and hide his past as a low-level official in
Pinochet's planning ministry. A country with 10 percent
unemployment and a primitive infrastructure in the rural provinces,
they say, will need more than Lavin's Las Condes-style tinkering.
</P>
<P>
   ``The man is a demagogue,'' said former President Patricio
Aylwin, who is campaigning hard for Lagos.
</P>
<P>
   But analysts say Lavin attracted tens of thousands of
lower-income voters in last month's vote by promoting his pragmatic
approaches.
</P>
<P>
   ``Lavin built a reputation in Las Condes as a person who
delivers practical solutions,'' said Ricardo Israel, a political
scientist at the University of Chile. ``He never fails to say on
the campaign trail, `I can do for you what I have done for the poor
of Las Condes.'''
</P>
<P>
   While most of Las Condes is well-to-do, it has several
working-class barrios that have attracted Lavin's particular
attention.
</P>
<P>
   In Colon Oriente, for instance, he built a public gymnasium and
swimming pool. He set up clubs for the elderly, where they were
provided powdered milk, classes in floral arrangements and
counseling for emotional problems. He set up kiosks where people
could file crime complaints without traveling long distances to
police stations.
</P>
<P>
   When a wealthy landowner threatened to drive away 52 families
living in shacks on her land so that a supermarket could be built
there, Lavin bought the land and, in a joint undertaking with the
Housing Ministry, built public housing for the families. Lavin's
effort was in marked contrast to the policies of Pinochet, who
drove squatters out of Las Condes whenever he had the chance.
</P>
<P>
   ``I've never seen a mayor do so much,'' said Regina Zuniga, a
43-year-old resident of the project. Ms. Zuniga, an unemployed
domestic worker, voted for the two previous presidential candidates
of the center-left government. But this time she is voting for
Lavin because, she says, ``he will provide work for all the
people.''
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   nn
</P>
<P>
   On the campaign trail, Lavin talks constantly about how he
improved health care in Las Condes. He provided limited health
insurance free to 2,000 of the lowest-income men who headed
households, covering operations for ailments like varicose veins
and hernias that could otherwise put them out of work. So his
constituents would not have to wait months for various services at
public clinics, he donated a building to a private clinic in
exchange for its providing free annual examinations to 1,200
low-income people.
</P>
<P>
   And he built small neighborhood infirmaries outfitted with cars
so doctors and nurses could make house calls to those too sick to
leave home. The model for the free house calls came from British
socialized medicine.
</P>
<P>
   Attracted by Lavin's heterodoxy, Dr. Djamila Calixtro, an
immigrant from Cuba who worked for years there in family health
care, sought employment in one of the infirmaries. ``I'm
integrating what I learned in Cuba to work for Mayor Lavin,'' she
said in a comment that would surely make Fidel Castro cringe.
</P>
<P>
   A patient in Calixtro's infirmary, Nelson Meza, said he was
finally giving up alcohol thanks to the counseling he was receiving
there. An unemployed bus driver, Meza, 48, said he voted for the
Communist presidential candidate in 1993, but this year would vote
for Lavin.
</P>
<P>
   ``We need a young man who will work for the poor,'' he said.
``If he becomes president, it will be a new country.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
