<HEADER>
A0258 &Cx1f; var-z
u a BC-FOOTBALL-COACHES-REVI     01-08 0774
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FOOTBALL-COACHES-REVIEW-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
MAYBE THE COACH IS A LITTLE TOO INDISPENSABLE 
</HEADLINE>
   (The Week in Review)  
(DUPLICATION NOTICE: Also moving in `s' category as
FBN-COACHES-REVIEW) 
(NOTE TO INTERNATIONAL CLIENTS: For international clients' use by
special arrangement only. Asian and European points: contact Karl
Horwitz in Paris for details and prices (Phone: 47 42 17 11; FAX:
47-42-80-44). Latin American points: contact Olivia Vasquez in Los
Angeles (Phone: 310-996-0075; FAX: 310-996-0089) 
 
(bl) 
 By ALLEN BARRA   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   ``Kee-ripes,'' lamented W.W. ``Pudge'' Heffelfinger in his 1954
book ``This Was Football.'' ``How different modern football is from
the old days when the coach wouldn't dare make a decision without
first consulting the team captain.''
</P>
<P>
   Team captain? How quaint. In the current National Football
League, the most important function of a captain is knowing when to
drop the Gatorade bucket on the coach.
</P>
<P>
   Heffelfinger, who was Walter Camp's first All-America selection
back in 1892 and the game's first professional _ $500 for a game
between the Allegheny Athletic Association and the Pittsburgh
Athletic Club _ wouldn't have known what to make of a game where
coaches have come to dominate everything from player drafts to
strategy. Or a game where the serial retirements of the New York
Jets head coach Bill Parcells and his designated successor,
defensive coordinator Bill Belichick, would dominate sports
headlines for days.
</P>
<P>
   Or, for that matter, a game that required something called a
defensive coordinator. ``Your head coach today,'' Heffelfinger
railed in 1954, ``has become an absolute dictator. He not only
picks the team, designs the plays and relegates the captain to a
corporal's status, but during the game he frequently governs the
choice of plays.''
</P>
<P>
   In the early years of the game, not only were coaches not the
venerated figures we know today; they were, on occasion, forcibly
ejected from the field by players when they became too dictatorial.
But by the end of the century, a top football coach like Parcells _
who turned three successive losing teams, the Giants, Patriots and
Jets, into winners _ had achieved the superstar free-agent status
that team owners succeeded in denying the players.
</P>
<P>
   What happened? Most historians pinpoint the 1920s, when football
began to change from a sporting contest organized for the enjoyment
of college athletes and spectators to a money-making proposition
for the universities _ and later, of course, for the owners of
professional teams.
</P>
<P>
   A century after Pudge Heffelfinger's exploits for Yale, football
has all but ceased to exist outside of an organized structure.
Travel the country and you'll see pickup games of basketball and
baseball, but outside of a high school field, where do children
still play football?
</P>
<P>
   It is not even clear that they would know how. The game has
gotten so complex that no one but the coaches truly understands it.
The head coach has evolved from a man who carried a bucket and
helped the captain to a man who coaches coaches, a swarm of
coordinators and assistants and quarterback coaches and line
coaches and receiver coaches from whom consensus must be drawn
before a single play can be allowed. Forget Pudge Heffelfinger _
Vince Lombardi wouldn't recognize this game.
</P>
<P>
   In the biggest game of his life, the 1967 ``Ice Bowl'' NFL
Championship against Dallas, with the ball on the 1-yard line and
13 seconds to play, Lombardi was asked by his captain, quarterback
Bart Starr, what he wanted. ``Score a touchdown,'' replied the
greatest coach in NFL history.
</P>
<P>
   What Lombardi meant was: ``I've already done my part of the job;
now you do yours. You know better than I do what has to be done.''
(And Starr did. He called his own number and won the game on a
quarterback sneak.)
</P>
<P>
   Compare the Lombardi-Starr moment with that of the head coach at
Alabama a couple of years ago who, when asked why his team had lost
the biggest game of the year on a boneheaded last-minute pass play,
replied, ``I didn't know we were calling a pass.'' He had delegated
a decision on which his job might depend _ not to the quarterback
(heaven forbid), but to a sub-coach.
</P>
<P>
   The only alternative to such chaos seems to be coaches like
Parcells, who are too much in control, so much so that their
players often appear as automatons. There may be a law to the
modern game, something to the effect that the better the coach, the
duller his team.
</P>
<P>
   There may be a second law: the more in control the coach
becomes, the faster he burns out. Bill Parcells has now burned out
three times.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-01-08-00 1151EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT20000108.0081 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-01-08 11:51 </DATE_TIME>
