<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-01-08 11:54 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A0260 &Cx1f; taf-z
u p BC-BRADLEY-FUNDRAISING-2     01-08 1071
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BRADLEY-FUNDRAISING-2TAKES(TRIMS)-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
FOR BRADLEY, AN INNOVATIVE MONEY TRAIN 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ATTN: Fla., Calif.)  (nk) 
 By JAMES DAO    
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ Last summer, Adrienne Arsht, chairwoman of
TotalBank in Miami, read Bill Bradley's book, ``Values of the
Game.'' A fan of women's sports, Ms. Arsht liked what Bradley, a
former New York Knick, had to say about teamwork, discipline and
responsibility. So she volunteered to help his insurgent campaign
for president.
</P>
<P>
   Within weeks, the Bradley campaign called. Could she be the host
of a fund-raiser? ``I said, do we do tea sandwiches or what?'' Ms.
Arsht, 57, recalled. ``I had never done anything close to this in
my life. Not since 1968, when I left my father's law firm in
Delaware and went to work for Eugene McCarthy.''
</P>
<P>
   Still, Ms. Arsht and her co-hosts managed to cajole 150 friends
and business associates into paying as much as $1,000 each to hear
Bradley speak at her home in October. When he left, his campaign
was $100,000 richer.
</P>
<P>
   To the surprise of many political analysts, Bradley raised more
than $27 million for his underdog quest for the Democratic
nomination last year, just $2 million less than his rival, Vice
President Al Gore, the party's front-runner. Though his contributor
list is laced with names of the rich and powerful, the story of how
Bradley kept pace with Gore is mainly filled with lesser-known
figures like Ms. Arsht.
</P>
<P>
   With no political machine at his fingertips, and no powerhouse
fund-raisers like Terry McAuliffe, who solicited $27 million for
the 1996 Clinton-Gore campaign, Bradley turned to a loose network
of longtime friends and supporters to be his money gatherers.
</P>
<P>
   Many were old friends from Princeton, his alma mater, the
National Basketball Association or the Senate, where he served
three terms. But others were people like Ms. Arsht who had never
met him, only read his books, heard him lecture or seen him play
basketball. Still others supported him simply because he had never
been part of the Clinton administration. Most had no political
fund-raising experience. But they were affluent people with
affluent friends willing to open their Rolodexes to help him get
elected.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was not what you'd describe as a national organization,''
said Leonard Riggio, chairman of Barnes &AMP; Noble. ``It was a whole
bunch of people who Bill has met over the years, and who were
waiting for him, waiting for the signal. It hasn't been the kind of
campaign others have run where they had superstar fund-raisers.
It's been a whole bunch of people who just helped out. A lot of
soldiers and no generals.''
</P>
<P>
   By tapping into so many veins of money, many of them from
outside the usual Democratic contributor lists, Bradley sidestepped
what many people had considered a towering obstacle to his
campaign: Gore's early success at locking up many of the best-known
and most-loyal Democratic fund-raisers and contributors.
</P>
<P>
   By summer, Bradley _ with much help from Wall Street _ had begun
nearly matching Gore's fund-raising. By late fall, he was
out-raising Gore 2-to-1. And now, as the campaign begins the
expensive sprint toward the Iowa caucuses of Jan. 24 and the
delegate-rich primaries of March, Bradley, thanks to his more
frugal spending, seems likely to have more cash available _ at
least $19 million _ than Gore.
</P>
<P>
   To many political analysts, Bradley's fund-raising success is
the main reason he has turned a once seemingly lopsided race into
one of the liveliest Democratic primary battles in decades. Money
has given him not just the power to contest Gore deep into the
primary season, they say, but also credibility among Democratic
activists, contributors and voters. But Bradley's successes have
also raised questions among advocates of campaign finance reform
about his devotion to revamping the fund-raising system, a central
part of his campaign.
</P>
<P>
   ``To the extent that he's an effective fund-raiser, he loses
some of the edge on being for reform,'' said Larry Makinson,
executive director of the Center for Responsive Politics, an
independent group that tracks campaign finance.
</P>
<P>
   Yet just a year ago, Bradley was starting virtually from
scratch. When he announced his candidacy in late 1998, his
fund-raising machinery consisted essentially of an old list of
Senate contributors and two aides: Betty Sapoch, of Princeton,
N.J., who had raised money for his three Senate races, and Richard
Wright, a former Princeton basketball teammate and former Carter
administration official.
</P>
<P>
   Though neither had raised money for a presidential campaign,
they knew most of Bradley's longtime supporters, and their job was
to knit them together into what Mrs. Sapoch called ``Bradley
cells.''
</P>
<P>
   It was also Wright's task to convince the fund-raisers that
there were sources of money beyond the Democratic deep pockets
already in the Gore camp. ``We were going into a world where we
were told we couldn't raise a cent because all the lists were
gone,'' Wright said.
</P>
<P>
   In many cities, their first calls were to Princeton alumni.
Bradley, class of '64, was not only the university's most famous
basketball player, but also a member of its board of trustees. The
alumni appeals worked so well that Wright began joking that he had
met all 1,500 of Bradley's roommates during the campaign.
</P>
<P>
   (BEGIN OPTIONAL TRIM)
</P>
<P>
   In San Diego, Lawrence Lucchino, class of '66 and president of
the Padres baseball team, held a party at the stadium in April that
raised $300,000. In Chicago, Mellody Hobson, a 30-year-old money
manager whom Bradley recruited for Princeton, helped organize a
March event that brought in $1.5 million. And in San Francisco,
John D. Diekman, a venture capitalist, used his extensive
connections with the class of '65 to sell tickets for an April
event that raised $1.1 million.
</P>
<P>
   (END OPTIONAL TRIM)
</P>
<P>
   ``The Princeton Rolodex was very important in that early
period,'' said John Scully, a partner in an investment firm who
graduated a year behind Bradley.
</P>
<P>
   In that early period, Bradley played a major role in soliciting
contributions. Though he once wrote that his aggressive
fund-raising for his 1990 re-election campaign made him feel like
he wore ``a scarlet dollar sign,'' he devoted several hours a day
early last year to calling donors. He also personally recruited
most of his major fund-raisers.
</P>
<P>
   nn
</P>
<P>
   One of them was Michael King, a New Jersey native and
co-chairman of King World Productions, a syndicator of several hit
television programs. King, who had long admired but never met
Bradley, agreed to help organize a June fund-raiser in Los Angeles
that brought in nearly $1 million. Michael D. Eisner, the chairman
of the Walt Disney Co., and Barry Diller, the media executive, were
among the Hollywood figures there.
</P>
<P>
   Bradley also signed up John L. Thornton, president of Goldman
Sachs, at a dinner meeting at Thornton's London home a year ago
that had been arranged by mutual friends. In July, Thornton
organized an event with Americans living in London that raised more
than $200,000.
</P>
<P>
   Goldman employees have contributed more than $209,000 to
Bradley, making the company his single largest source of money. One
reason is that about 15 company executives are Bradley supporters.
But another reason, Thornton said, is that the candidate's style
and record are appealing to investment bankers and entrepreneurs,
even those who do not always agree with his policies.
</P>
<P>
   ``Bradley is clearly the most genuinely accomplished person in
the race,'' Thornton said. ``Everything he's done is through sheer
determination. And that's a trait professional,
achievement-oriented people are attracted to.''
</P>
<P>
   (BEGIN OPTIONAL TRIM)
</P>
<P>
   In his meticulous way, Bradley actually began laying the
foundations for his campaign in 1997, after he retired from the
Senate, a period when he taught at Stanford, made paid speeches
around the country and was a $300,000-a-year consultant to J.P.
Morgan.
</P>
<P>
   The Morgan experience seems to have paid off in support from
company officials. Douglas A. Warner 3rd, the company's chairman,
has contributed $1,000 to his campaign. And Morgan employees gave
more than $39,000 to Bradley last year, compared with about $2,000
to Gore.
</P>
<P>
   While at Stanford, Bradley used much of his spare time to meet
lawyers, bankers and executives in Silicon Valley and San
Francisco, areas where Gore was thought to be particularly strong.
Bradley has now raised more money in California than the vice
president.
</P>
<P>
   ``Part of it was for him to get to know the valley, but part was
to develop relationships that might help him in a presidential
campaign,'' said John Roos, a Palo Alto lawyer who introduced
Bradley to several of his Silicon Valley clients.
</P>
<P>
   At the behest of Bonnie Reiss, another supporter, Bradley also
met with about 50 longtime supporters in New York in 1998, before
he had announced his candidacy. Many of those people had been
disappointed that he had not run in 1992, and Ms. Reiss felt he
needed to smooth things over before starting a new campaign. The
smoothing worked, and the group raised $1.2 million at an event
last April.
</P>
<P>
   While such large events were going on, Bradley's friends from
the NBA were organizing smaller parties around the country. Dave
Bing in Detroit, Dave DeBusschere in West Hampton, N.Y., and Abe
Pollin, owner of the Washington Wizards, gave house parties that
raised hundreds of thousands of dollars each.
</P>
<P>
   Oscar Robertson, John Havlicek, Willis Reed, Phil Jackson and
many others contributed money, called friends and spoke at
fund-raising events. And a cast of 20 Hall of Fame players appeared
alongside Bradley at a Madison Square Garden event in November that
raised $1.5 million.
</P>
<P>
   The Garden event provided a prime example of how the Bradley
campaign chiefs marketed their candidate to diverse audiences.
Tickets were distributed widely on the liberal Upper West Side and
in central Brooklyn, bastions of support for Bradley. But friends
of Bradley's also sold many tickets to members of a New York
lawyers' basketball league, including to many Republicans.
</P>
<P>
   (END OPTIONAL TRIM)
</P>
<P>
   Under federal rules, the Democratic candidates have raised
nearly as much money as they will be allowed to spend for the
primaries, about $33 million each. Wright says he has already
reduced his staff by 60 percent, and fund-raisers around the
country are being asked to devote themselves to political work for
the next few months, decommissioned by their own success.
</P>
<P>
   ``I've got my earmuffs ready for New Hampshire,'' Ms. Arsht
said.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
