<DOCNO> NYT20000108.0106 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-01-08 13:12 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A0285 &Cx1f; taf-z
u i BC-RUSSIA-CHECHNYA-790&AMP;A     01-08 1088
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-RUSSIA-CHECHNYA-790&AMP;ADD-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
NEWS ANALYSIS: HALT IN ATTACK ON CHECHNYA SERVES SEVERAL PURPOSES 
</HEADLINE>
  (lb) 
 By MICHAEL R. GORDON   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   MOZDOK, Russia _ The suspension of Russia's barrage of Grozny
was not, in a sense, much of a surprise, since it made a virtue out
of a military necessity.
</P>
<P>
   Acting President Vladimir Putin, attending a Christmas service
for the Orthodox in Moscow late Friday, said that the decision to
suspend the bombardment of Grozny, the Chechen capital, was taken
to spare civilians and to honor both the Orthodox feast and a
Muslim holiday this weekend.
</P>
<P>
   Putin's explanation differed from that of the military,
suggesting that the halt to the bombardment was at least partly a
matter of packaging and public relations. And far from signaling an
end to Grozny's ordeal, the suspension appears to be a prelude to
an even more furious assault on the Chechen capital.
</P>
<P>
   Russian generals have said they intend to use the moratorium to
rest and reorganize their forces around the besieged capital of
Chechnya for another round of fighting. They have also suggested
that artillery and air raids will be more intense when they are
resumed, and they have warned the tens of thousands of civilians in
Grozny to use the lull to escape.
</P>
<P>
   Even before the suspension was announced, the dense fog
blanketing much of Chechnya compelled the military to slow down its
operations. Russian spotters have found it difficult to direct
artillery strikes, and much of the Russian air force and the fleet
of helicopter gunships have been grounded.
</P>
<P>
   Firepower is essential for the Russian military's strategy to
take the city. It is an important advantage that Russian forces
have over the rebels, and Russian troops are unable to venture deep
into the streets of Grozny without it.
</P>
<P>
   The suspension also serves another purpose. With Russian
casualties on the rise, Russian commanders want to try again to
persuade the unknown number of civilians still left in Grozny to
leave, so that the military's artillery and aircraft can have a
freer hand in pummeling the city.
</P>
<P>
   Last month the Russian military dropped leaflets warning
residents to flee or risk death, with little effect. Many of the
civilians who remain appear to be too old, too weak or too
frightened to try to run the gantlet out of the city. The halt
gives Russian commanders another chance to try to empty out the
city, and leaflets are once again being dropped imploring civilians
to leave.
</P>
<P>
   ``We will also use this as a short break for our personnel,''
said Lt. Gen. Gennady Troshev, the deputy commander of Russian
forces in the North Caucasus region, at the Russian military base
here, just northwest of Chechnya. ``We will regroup, and when we
feel that the civilians have left Grozny, we will inflict a
resolute and final blow against the militants who sit in Grozny.''
</P>
<P>
   Using firepower to hold down Russian military casualties is not
only important for the generals. It is also important for Putin,
who is campaigning to become Russia's second president in elections
on March 26. Putin has been the driving force behind the war and
his popularity has soared among many Russians, who welcome a strong
hand and have never had much love for the predominantly Muslim
Chechens.
</P>
<P>
   The two peoples have a long history of uneasy accommodation or
open conflict, most recently seen in the 1994-96 war, which ended
in heavy losses and humiliation for the Russian army and left
Chechnya's status unresolved and its territory increasingly
lawless.
</P>
<P>
   As the toll of Russian dead and wounded increases, however, this
current war may emerge as more of a political issue. Russia's
independent NTV television station, for example, recently broadcast
the emotional funeral of senior officers of the Yekaterinburg
militia, who were trapped by rebels in the streets of Grozny and
killed.
</P>
<P>
   While the military aims of the suspension seem clear, the
official justifications have varied.
</P>
<P>
   Troshev, who was removed on Friday as commander of Eastern
forces in Chechnya but retains his parallel responsibility as
deputy commander of the Russian army in the North Caucasus, said
the moratorium was needed because tanks of chlorine and ammonia had
exploded, releasing a poisonous cloud of gas in the city. He called
Grozny a ``zone of ecological danger'' and said it was urgent that
civilians flee.
</P>
<P>
   Putin, however, did not cite the environmental hazard when he
confirmed the suspension on Friday night. He said the halt was
ordered because the bad weather had increased the risk that
civilians might be shelled by mistake, and out of respect for
Christmas and the end of the Muslim holiday of Ramadan.
</P>
<P>
   ``As for Grozny, remember what day it is now for Orthodox
Christians and tomorrow for Muslims,'' Putin said. ``We will not
forget that, and we will respect the feelings of believers.''
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE _ OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   It remained unclear, however, why Russian forces intend to mark
the religious holidays in the Grozny area while pressing on with
their campaign in the mountainous areas of southern Chechnya _ an
operation less susceptible to the thick fog that hampers air
assaults.
</P>
<P>
   While Russian commanders have suspended artillery and air
strikes against Grozny, Russian motorized infantry units have moved
to surround Vedeno, a southern Chechen town and the birthplace of
Shamil Basayev, the rebel commander. No moratorium appears to have
been declared in that region.
</P>
<P>
   ``The suspension does not mean we will not continue military
actions,'' Troshev said. ``They are conducted 24 hours a day.''
</P>
<P>
   Nor is it clear how long the suspension will last or what the
Russian military will do if the civilians trapped in Grozny again
decide not to risk trying to escape. Several of the few thousand
refugees who took advantage of Russian pleas last month to get out
of Grozny said they were shot at by unidentified gunmen while
making their perilous flight.
</P>
<P>
   What is clear is that the suspension has not altered the
Kremlin's fundamental political or military strategy. The Russian
government is still not interested in negotiating with the
militants or abandoning its plan to subdue Chechnya by force.
</P>
<P>
   Putin, speaking to reporters in Moscow's vast Orthodox
cathedral, where he attended a Christmas service along with other
politicians, said as much.
</P>
<P>
   ``Our aims remain unchanged and they will be achieved,'' Putin
said. ``Have a good holiday.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
