<HEADER>
A0294 &Cx1f; taf-z
u i BC-CZECH-SEX-HARASSMENT-     01-08 1170
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CZECH-SEX-HARASSMENT-(TRIMS)-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
FOR CZECHS, BLIND EYE ON HARASSMENT 
</HEADLINE>
  (js) 
 By LADKA BAUEROVA    
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   PRAGUE, Czech Republic _ When the European Union asks its
applicants for admission what men do to women in the workplace, the
countries of Central Europe will apparently have some explaining to
do.
</P>
<P>
   To the shock of many Czechs, a recent study commissioned by the
newspaper Lidove Noviny indicated that almost half of the country's
working women have been subjected to sexual harassment in the
workplace. Reports from other post-Communist countries indicate
that sexual harassment, though seldom identified as such, is
widespread.
</P>
<P>
   The study found that 45 percent of Czech women had been sexually
harassed, many of them repeatedly. Women's rights advocates said
that the real figures are probably even higher.
</P>
<P>
   ``Sexual harassment is something like folklore in the Czech
Republic,'' said Lenka Simerska, a sociologist at the Gender
Studies Center in Prague. ``It's omnipresent, but it's not
considered a serious problem. You're supposed to laugh about it and
say that it's a stupid invention of hysterical American feminists,
and that, actually, it does not exist here at all.''
</P>
<P>
   Oh, but it does, she said. Obscene jokes, suggestive remarks,
unwelcome advances, gentle slaps on one's buttocks _ these are all
part of a regular day for many women who work and who do not
complain for fear of being ridiculed or even losing their job.
</P>
<P>
   Indeed, the term often used for sexual harassment in the Czech
Republic, ``sexualni haraseni,'' discourages serious discussion.
Coined by an exiled Czech writer, Josef Skvorecky, in the early
1990s, sexualni haraseni, phonetically similar to the English term,
translates as ``sexual buzz'' or ``sexual rumble,'' with the tacit
understanding that whoever complains about harassment is making an
unnecessary fuss.
</P>
<P>
   Sex is not considered taboo in this country. But the concept of
sexual harassment is widely perceived as a Western plague that
threatens to spoil ``natural'' relations between men and women.
</P>
<P>
   Jana Klepetarova, a foreign-student coordinator at Charles
University in Prague, said that while she agreed that sexual
harassment was a problem, she would hate to see the chemistry
between men and women disappear in the workplace. Flirting, she
noted, is fun, and makes the working day more enjoyable.
</P>
<P>
   ``If a colleague of mine comes to work in a new jacket or a tie,
of course I will compliment him,'' she said. ``By the same token, I
expect to be complimented when I come in something new that looks
good. And if a boss takes his female secretary around her shoulders
and says, `Let's take a look at this problem together,' then I
don't think it's sexual harassment. It's indecent. It's graceless
paternalism.
</P>
<P>
   ``Look, a well-aimed slap can solve anything,'' she added with a
laugh.
</P>
<P>
   Perhaps not everything. The few lawsuits reported in Central
Europe throughout the 1990s showed that women have a very spare
legal arsenal with which to fight unwelcome advances from their
colleagues. Since none of the Central European countries have
codified sexual harassment as a criminal offense, victims usually
sue for violation of the labor code, which provides a more vaguely
defined right to a harmless working environment.
</P>
<P>
   Centrum Praw Kobiet, the women's rights center in Poland, has
counseled dozens of sexual harassment victims, but only one of them
could claim any sort of legal success. The harassed woman, an
employee of a large multinational corporation, won a payment equal
to a year's salary as compensation, but she was still forced to
leave her job.
</P>
<P>
   (BEGIN OPTIONAL TRIM)
</P>
<P>
   ``This one was lucky, because the company was international and
was concerned about its reputation,'' said Eleonora Zielinska, a
law professor from Warsaw. ``But usually the victims are entitled
only to three months' pay if they agree to leave the job. That is
nothing compared to the compensation a woman would get in the West.
And if they refuse to leave, they get no compensation at all, and
they still have to cope with the hostile environment, of course.''
</P>
<P>
   The situation is similar in Hungary where, despite the
raunchiness of many Budapest night clubs and widely displayed
pornographic magazines, it is considered bad form to discuss sex in
public. ``Sexuality was taboo in Hungary during socialism,'' said
Judit Sandor, the head of the gender studies department at the
Central European University in Budapest. ``People don't feel
comfortable interpreting these problems. And that includes judges,
who are generally unfavorable to women.''
</P>
<P>
   It also includes politicians, Ms. Sandor said, who tend to blame
women for soliciting attention with high heels, short skirts and
low-cut necklines. Very few women in Hungary dare to go public with
their reports of harassment, she said, because they fear a backlash
from the society.
</P>
<P>
   (END OPTIONAL TRIM)
</P>
<P>
   Ten years after the fall of Communism, some things are gradually
changing. Some post-Communist countries have begun the process of
passing laws to combat sexual harassment in order to harmonize
their legislation with laws in the European Union, which all aspire
to join.
</P>
<P>
   Slovenia hopes to pass a law sometime in the spring, while the
Czech government just sent a draft law for its first reading in
Parliament. The task still lies ahead for Poland, Hungary and
Slovakia, not to mention Balkan countries further back in the line
to join the European Union.
</P>
<P>
   Legal protection will not immediately change the deeply rooted
attitudes and social climate in the countries of Central and
Eastern Europe, where feminism is a dirty word and debates about
gender issues almost nonexistent. Although almost all women work
and bring home income, they are still expected to take care of the
household and child-rearing. And the few who dare to speak out can
not expect any sympathy from those around them.
</P>
<P>
   Dagmar Frysakova knows all about the difficulty of such cases.
She was the first woman in the Czech Republic to win a sexual
harassment lawsuit.
</P>
<P>
   A few weeks before her wedding, Ms. Frysakova, a university
student, was approached by a teaching assistant in the library.
When she refused his advances, the man forced her hand to his
genitals and ejaculated on her skirt.
</P>
<P>
   The similarity with the story of Monica Lewinsky's blue dress
did not go unnoticed, especially since the incident happened at the
height of the impeachment proceedings in Washington, and Ms.
Frysakova's story became the subject of jokes at the university.
</P>
<P>
   Thanks to the stained skirt she won the lawsuit, but the
teaching assistant received only an eight-month suspended sentence
and remained at the university.
</P>
<P>
   The university staff members have become hostile toward her, and
Ms. Frysakova fears that she will be forced to leave the
university. ``If I had known what I was going to go through,'' she
said, ``I would have never said a thing.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
