<DATE_TIME> 2000-01-08 13:29 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A0299 &Cx1f; taf-z
u w BC-NUKE-SECRETS-LEE-1010     01-08 1038
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-NUKE-SECRETS-LEE-1010(2TAKES)-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
ATOM SCIENTIST TAKES CASE TO COURT OF PUBLIC OPINION 
</HEADLINE>
  (lb) 
 By JAMES RISEN    
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ There are really two trials taking shape in the
case of Wen Ho Lee, the former Los Alamos scientist charged with
compromising nuclear secrets.
</P>
<P>
   One is the relatively narrow criminal case brought in New Mexico
by government prosecutors, who charged Lee with transferring secret
nuclear-weapons data from classified computers at Los Alamos
National Laboratory to computer tapes that are now missing.
</P>
<P>
   But prosecutors have not charged that the Taiwan-born Lee
committed espionage by giving the data to a foreign country, and
because the case first grew from charges of Chinese nuclear
espionage, that has left an opening for Lee's lawyers to try to
conduct their own trials, in two federal courts and in the court of
public opinion.
</P>
<P>
   Through a media campaign and alliances with Asian-American
groups, and in arguments in both the criminal trial and a separate
civil lawsuit filed against the government, Lee's lawyers are
spotlighting what they say is a racist witch hunt meant to cloak
flaws in the government's counterintelligence efforts.
</P>
<P>
   The civil lawsuit filed by Lee and his wife, Sylvia, charges
that the case against Lee was pursued in part to ``divert
attention'' from the government's ``inability to maintain proper
security procedures at the nation's nuclear laboratories.''
</P>
<P>
   Long before the government discovered evidence of computer
transfers by Lee, he was investigated at least three times in his
20-year career at Los Alamos. The last of these inquiries led to
his firing.
</P>
<P>
   An inquiry in 1995, based on evidence that Beijing had stolen
secrets related to the United States' most advanced nuclear
warhead, the submarine-launched W-88, led to a full criminal
investigation by the FBI in 1996. Lee, then working in the
secretive X Division at Los Alamos, where the W-88 had been
designed, quickly emerged as the prime suspect.
</P>
<P>
   A three-year investigation by the FBI was unable to prove any
involvement by Lee. But last March he was fired for a series of
security violations uncovered in the W-88 inquiry, including his
failure to report contacts with foreign officials, and evidence
that he had mishandled three classified documents.
</P>
<P>
   It was only after he was fired that the FBI and Los Alamos
computer experts found the computer downloads that led to his
arrest on Dec. 10. Those transfers are at the core of the
government's prosecution.
</P>
<P>
   Government lawyers now argue that flaws in the original W-88
inquiry are largely irrelevant to the case against Lee.
</P>
<P>
   ``This investigation resulting in this indictment has no
connection whatsoever with the original W-88 investigation,'' an
FBI agent, Robert Messemer, told a federal magistrate during a
hearing last month.
</P>
<P>
   Officials said Lee consented to a search of his office and his
office computer before he was fired. Evidence gathered at the lab
led to a search of Lee's home in April. There agents found a
notebook listing the files that he is charged with transferring and
copying.
</P>
<P>
   Lee's lawyers have indicated that they would challenge the
admissibility of evidence gained from the search of his home.
</P>
<P>
   To convict Lee on all charges, the government must prove that he
acted with the intention of injuring the United States and aiding a
foreign power. Prosecutors must present circumstantial evidence
that Lee intended to pass the data to another country, while
acknowledging they cannot prove he is a spy.
</P>
<P>
   In two hearings in December to determine whether Lee would be
released on bail, Los Alamos officials and a senior FBI agent
provided the first glimpses of how the government hopes to make
that case.
</P>
<P>
   Dr. Stephen Younger, the director of nuclear-weapons programs at
Los Alamos, said the very scale of Lee's computer transfers, which
included 806 megabytes of classified data on virtually every
critical nuclear-weapons code at Los Alamos, indicates his intent
to hurt the United States and aid another country.
</P>
<P>
   The missing tapes would only be useful to a country or group
trying to replicate U.S. nuclear-weapons designs, Younger said.
</P>
<P>
   ``These codes and their associated databases, and the input
files, combined with someone that knew how to use them, could, in
my opinion, in the wrong hands, change the global strategic
balance,'' Younger said.
</P>
<P>
   Messemer testified that the clandestine manner in which Lee
downloaded and copied the data in 1993, 1994 and 1997 indicated his
intent to keep his actions secret.
</P>
<P>
   Lee did it mostly at night and on weekends, and then copied the
data onto tapes by using computers in other offices at Los Alamos.
And in January and February 1999, after he was questioned in the
W-88 investigation, Lee began deleting the transferred files from
the unclassified network at the lab.
</P>
<P>
   Messemer also said that Lee's downloading in 1993 and 1994 came
when he had been notified that he might be laid off as a result of
budget cuts. At the same time, he began sending job inquiries to
Europe and Asia, including Taiwan and Hong Kong. At a subsequent
bail hearing, government witnesses said Lee had remotely accessed
the files he had downloaded, while he was visiting Taiwan.
</P>
<P>
   Lee's lawyers hope to outflank the prosecution on several
fronts. The defense argues that Lee downloaded the files after
computer crashes at Los Alamos, and later destroyed the seven tapes
that are now missing. During cross-examinations, the defense has
focused on the government's failure to disprove Lee's explanations.
</P>
<P>
   A defense motion this month cast further light on his planned
defense.
</P>
<P>
   The motion stated that Lee and his lawyers need access to the
portable computer tapes recovered by the government to explore the
possibility that most or all of the downloaded material had
previously been published, so Lee could not have meant to harm the
United States through his transfers. The defense also said it wants
to show that the tapes contained material that Lee needed for his
work, and so possession of it was not unauthorized.
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE _ OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   nn
</P>
<P>
   The lawyers also asked the court to ease restrictions on their
ability to share classified material with defense witnesses, and to
instruct prosecutors to allay concerns among Los Alamos employees
that they might face retribution for talking with the defense.
Those requests suggest that the defense hopes to call witnesses who
will say that downloading of classified data is widespread at Los
Alamos, and that Lee has been the victim of selective prosecution.
</P>
<P>
   More broadly, however, Lee's lawyers have attacked the W-88
inquiry and the subsequent media coverage that identified Lee as a
suspect long before he was arrested.
</P>
<P>
   In a statement when Lee was arrested on Dec. 10, Mark Holscher,
his Los Angeles lawyer, argued that the decision to prosecute had
been influenced by ``other branches of government whose political
motives and agendas are suspect.'' That was a reference to a
congressional committee chaired by Rep. Christopher Cox, R-Calif.,
that investigated illicit transfers of technology to China.
</P>
<P>
   In addition, Lee's lawyers have charged in the separate civil
lawsuit in Washington that personal information about Lee that was
published in the press, including articles in The New York Times,
violated his privacy. The ``selectively disclosed information'' was
designed to show that Lee and his wife ``were spies'' for China,
Holscher charged.
</P>
<P>
   The defense has also maintained that Lee was turned into a
scapegoat for the broader security failures at Los Alamos.
</P>
<P>
   The defense will use statements by a former Los Alamos
counterintelligence official, Robert Vrooman, that Lee was singled
out for investigation because of his Chinese ethnicity.
</P>
<P>
   Vrooman, who was disciplined last year for failures in the W-88
investigation, has claimed that he complained about the targeting
of Lee long before his own mishandling of the inquiry came under
scrutiny, but senior FBI and Energy Department officials dispute
that.
</P>
<P>
   Vrooman's charged statements about racism have helped rally
support for Lee from Asian-American groups.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
