<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-01-08 13:31 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A0302 &Cx1f; taf-z
u a BC-MICH-ICEFISHING-RISKS     01-08 1005
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MICH-ICEFISHING-RISKS-ART-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
ACCIDENTS PROMPT DEBATE ON LAWS FOR ICE FISHING 
</HEADLINE>
  (ART ADV: Locator map is being sent to NYT graphic clients.
Nonsubscribers can make individual purchase by calling 888-603-1036
or 888-346-9867.) 
(mk) 
 By KEITH BRADSHER    
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   HARRISON TOWNSHIP, Mich. _ Wearing insulated beige overalls, a
brown camouflage jacket and warm boots, Joe Burkhardt cautiously
walked a few feet onto the ice of Lake St. Clair on Friday morning
as murky light shone through the low, gray clouds above.
</P>
<P>
   He raised high into the air his ``spud'': a basic piece of ice
fishing equipment that consists of a 6-foot-long steel pipe with a
spike on the bottom and is used for testing the firmness of the
ice. He plunged the spud through the ice several times, about 18
inches from his feet; water bubbled in the holes.
</P>
<P>
   ``See, it goes right through,'' he said. ``I'm not going out.''
</P>
<P>
   A firefighter nearby, Sgt. Frank Share, received a radio call: A
soaked ice fisherman had just staggered out of a canal several
miles away and into the home of an elderly couple. Jumping into his
pickup truck, Share raced across town.
</P>
<P>
   Shivering uncontrollably, Eric Zwierzchowski, the 24-year-old
ice fisherman, stood in the couple's house here on the northeastern
outskirts of Detroit. Two other firefighters were attaching the
leads for a heart monitor to Zwierzchowski's chest. Then they
helped lower him onto a stretcher and wheeled him out to a rescue
truck for the trip to the hospital, where he would be treated for
mild hypothermia.
</P>
<P>
   Lying in the truck, Zwierzchowski said he was through with ice
fishing. ``I'm done, no question,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Ice fishing has long been a big part of winter life in Michigan.
Indians engaged in the sport long before white settlers arrived,
and the state's Department of Natural Resources estimates that
300,000 people still go ice fishing each winter. But a string of
accidents, combined with a succession of fairly mild winters, has
provoked an acrimonious fight in the Michigan Legislature over
whether new laws are needed to discourage ice anglers from taking
excessive risks.
</P>
<P>
   The most serious accident took place last winter, when 17
anglers were trapped on an ice floe the size of a city block that
broke off at sunset from the shore of Lake St. Clair. The floe
began floating out across the 20-mile-wide lake just as a powerful
snowstorm arrived. Firefighters began ferrying the anglers to
shore, using a Hovercraft and a skiff.
</P>
<P>
   But with wind speeds reaching 60 mph, the water was soon lashed
into 6-foot waves. The Hovercraft and the skiff sank, plunging
several firefighters into the freezing water. The ice floe broke
into 2-foot-thick blocks, and the waves hurled the blocks together,
knocking firefighters and anglers into the water, where they
struggled to avoid being crushed between the crashing slabs.
</P>
<P>
   The crew of a Coast Guard helicopter had great difficulty
finding people in the water at night in blinding snow and had to
make several trips to rescue everyone.
</P>
<P>
   Remarkably, no one was killed or injured. But although that
incident involved an unusually large number of anglers, a
surprising number of ice fishermen need to be rescued each year
after falling through the ice or becoming trapped on floes that
float away. The Coast Guard, which tends to handle the most
dangerous cases, has rescued 421 people from ice or ice-filled
water in the last five years in the Great Lakes region. All but 48
were in Michigan and almost all were ice fishermen. Few women
engage in ice fishing. Local fire departments have rescued many
more.
</P>
<P>
   State Sen. David Jaye, a Republican, said he watched the movie
``Titanic'' soon after the 17 anglers were rescued on Lake St.
Clair. One of the movie's last scenes, in which the young man
played by Leonardo DiCaprio freezes to death while clinging to ship
debris in the North Atlantic, inspired him to draft legislation,
Jaye said.
</P>
<P>
   His law would impose a $5 fine the first time someone is rescued
from the ice, a $200 fine the second time and a $500 fine the third
time; after a third rescue, a person's fishing license would also
be revoked for three years. Fines would be imposed only on people
who ventured onto the ice when ``a reasonable individual'' would
have concluded it was unsafe. State and federal agencies would
continue to pay for rescues.
</P>
<P>
   The law passed the Michigan Senate in November, but appears dead
in the House because of opposition from the Michigan United
Conservation Clubs. With 100,000 members and 500 affiliated hunting
and fishing clubs, the group mainly opposes gun control, but has
taken on Jaye's bill out of concern that it would penalize ice
anglers unfairly and might set a precedent for imposing rescue fees
on other outdoorsmen.
</P>
<P>
   Going out on the ice to fish and then needing to be rescued ``is
no different than my going deer hunting and getting my vehicle
stuck and calling'' for help, said State Rep. Dale Sheltrown, a
Republican from central Michigan.
</P>
<P>
   State conservation officers pull hunters' vehicles out of deep
mud and other difficulties. The officers charge nothing, but
sometimes tell hunters with badly stuck vehicles to call commercial
tow trucks.
</P>
<P>
   Anglers interviewed Friday as they fished on the ice of a boat
basin were divided on fines. Dennis Hartwig, a retired lawyer, said
that while irresponsible anglers should be penalized, it was wrong
to penalize others who exercised common sense but had misfortune.
</P>
<P>
   Share said he was opposed to any fines. He said that people
should be allowed to pursue any sport, and that it was the
firefighters' job to rescue those who got in trouble. ``We get paid
to help people out when they make a mistake _ people go out and
drive when there's a winter weather advisory and get in accidents
too,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Jaye said such sentiments were so strong that ``it seems
unlikely at this time the House is going to move until there's
another disaster.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
