<SLUG> BC-FBN-VECSEY-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SPORTS COLUMN: LOUNGE ACTS OPEN NFL POSTSEASON
</HEADLINE>
   (rk) 
 By GEORGE VECSEY    
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   LANDOVER, Md. _ So confident is the NFL of its hold over the
housebound populace in January that it offers a series of warm-up
acts for the first round of the playoffs.
</P>
<P>
   No sense throwing the headliners out on the stage so soon after
the new year. First, give the public eight teams that by and large
resemble Bill Murray's prototypical cocktail-lounge singer with his
shirt open to his navel, crooning erratically into a squawky mike.
</P>
<P>
   The league did not lack for charisma and excellence this season.
Kurt Warner of St. Louis emerged, Unitas-like, from that spectacle
known as Arena Football, while Peyton Manning became a skilled
veteran in his second season with Indianapolis.
</P>
<P>
   Unfortunately, neither was on display this weekend while
pear-shaped America settled into the sofa and ripped open a month's
supply of beer and chips.
</P>
<P>
   What with Washington and Detroit clanking helmets here Saturday
afternoon, and three other wild-card games over the weekend, the
league was offering eight teams with a collective record of 78
victories and 50 losses.
</P>
<P>
   This lukewarm record was a monument to parity and a tribute to
the very American concept that all men are created equal. Besides
which, it is generally cold outdoors in January, and what are
people going to watch: C-Span?
</P>
<P>
   The NFL was hoping for a nice pleasant weekend of games between
mediocrities, with no throat-slashing gestures, no wounded linemen
whacking officials, no breaking-and-entering arrests, no legal
troubles at all, after a season that included tragedy and
embarrassment. The league was quite willing to settle for the
normal mayhem on the run, even if perpetrated by second-line teams.
</P>
<P>
   It isn't saying much for pro football when the biggest
entertainment of the century to date has been Bill Belichick's
stunning the Jets with his emotional rendition of that old Johnny
Paycheck country music staple, ``Take This Job and Shove it.''
</P>
<P>
   Look at the numbers. The Lions lumbered in here Saturday with an
8-8 record, while the home team had a 10-6 record and actually
finished first in its dreadful division.
</P>
<P>
   The only matchup with any glitter was in Saturday's early game
in Nashville, where Tennessee held a glowing 13-3 record against
Buffalo (11-5), whose coach, Wade Phillips, planned a mighty gamble
in switching Rob Johnson for Doug Flutie, who merely got the Bills
to the playoffs in the first place.
</P>
<P>
   One hates to be a spoilsport but Sunday is even drearier. Dallas
(8-8) plays in Minnesota (10-6), after which Miami (9-7) plays at
Seattle (also 9-7), not exactly how Dan Marino would like his
career to end.
</P>
<P>
   No other sport offers such also-rans playing each other in the
first round of its tournament. Since 1985, college basketball has
held a 64-team version of March Madness with the Prairie Views and
Coastal Carolinas of the world seeded 16th but with top-seeded
teams also mandated to get out there and produce in the first
round.
</P>
<P>
   Baseball's elongated ``postseason'' (Uncle Bud will come around
and twist your ear lobes if you call it ``the playoffs'') has
cheapened the World Series, but at least the Yanks and the Braves
have to wear down their arms like everyone else in the first round.
</P>
<P>
   Pro basketball and pro hockey playoffs involve just about
everybody, and tend to go on forever. In fact, they may actually
have started, but nobody has notified us. At least the best teams
have to play the dog qualifiers in the first round, which means no
rest for the weary.
</P>
<P>
   On the other hand, pro football, the most dangerous and
debilitating team sport yet devised by humankind, actually gives
the four best teams a bye in the first round. Doesn't this violate
the Geneva Convention or something?
</P>
<P>
   While these eight pretenders slugged it out on Amateur Weekend,
Indianapolis and St. Louis and Jacksonville and Tampa Bay were
lolling in their respective whirlpools.
</P>
<P>
   They know the odds. Only three teams have lasted four games and
won the Super Bowl _ Oakland in the 1980 season as a wild card,
Washington in 1982 in a 16-team playoff after the labor troubles,
and Denver in 1997 as a wild card. Buffalo in 1992 and New England
in 1985 reached the Super Bowl after three victories and lost.
</P>
<P>
   Fortunately, neither the players nor the fans stops to think
about this gloomy prognosis.
</P>
<P>
   Cars were streaming into FedEx Stadium, known until recently as
Jack Kent Cooke Stadium, after the megalomaniac who built it only
to have his name quickly pried off the facade after his death.
</P>
<P>
   So much change. The new Washington owner, Daniel Snyder, has
dismissed many of his experienced staff members, while threatening
his coach, Norv Turner, with unemployment and taking on other tasks
large and small with Steinbrennerian gusto.
</P>
<P>
   Perhaps out of fear of their owner, or just maybe out of skill
and professionalism, the Washington players finished two games
above .500, a veritable dynasty in this league.
</P>
<P>
   Detroit managed to stumble into the wild card despite the loss
of its great running back, Barry Sanders, who got so tired of
losing that he retired. In his absence, the Lions upgraded
themselves to average.
</P>
<P>
   There's a moral to that story somewhere. Maybe it will become
apparent while the secondary teams beat each other into submission,
and the main acts take the stage.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-01-08-00 1333EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT20000108.0118 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-01-08 13:34 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A0307 &Cx1f; tib-z
u k BC-KRUGMAN-COLUMN-NYT &LR;      01-08 0748
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-KRUGMAN-COLUMN-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
COMMENTARY: TRIUMPH OF THE NERDS 
</HEADLINE>
  (bl) 
 By PAUL KRUGMAN    
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   This weekend Boston played host to the annual meeting of the
American Economic Association. It was a meeting of college
professors; but it was also a conclave of some of the world's
movers and shakers. Academic economists used to expect to affect
policy only at third or fourth hand; but lately they have, in
unprecedented numbers, moved into the corridors of power.
</P>
<P>
   The most conspicuous example of the trend is Lawrence Summers,
the academic whiz kid who became treasury secretary. But Harvard
professors have attained high office before, and will again. What
is different this time is that Summers is only the most prominent
of a wave of professors-turned-policy-makers. Even if a year from
now Summers himself is forced to seek alternative employment
(spokesman for Jenny Craig? Sorry, couldn't help myself), there
will still be dozens of other former professors in key policy
positions from the International Monetary Fund to the Bank of
England.
</P>
<P>
   What accounts for this growing academic influence over economic
policy? One reason is that in the 1990s the professoriate
effectively repelled the challenges, from both right and left, that
had called its authority into question in the '80s.
</P>
<P>
   The challenge from the right was more serious. Supply-siders _
who argued that high taxes were the root of all evil and ridiculed
the concern of conventional economists with things like budget
deficits _ were initially dismissed as cranks. But with ready
access to the pages of The Wall Street Journal and Forbes, they had
no trouble getting their message out. And they claimed that the
economic growth of their disciple, Ronald Reagan, vindicated their
doctrine.
</P>
<P>
   But after eight years and counting of expansion under manifestly
non-Reaganite policies that claim is, to put it mildly,
unconvincing. (Yes, the faithful insist that our current prosperity
is the result of their hero's 1982 tax cut; but I don't recall them
giving Lyndon Johnson credit for the boom in 1983.) And 20 years
on, the supply-siders themselves still sound like, well, cranks.
They haven't gone away _ any doctrine that appeals to the
prejudices of rich old men is assured of a certain basic level of
financial support, and its adherents will always be able to find
sinecures in the world of right-wing think tanks _ but they have
gone into remission.
</P>
<P>
   The challengers from the left were suaver, though less well
financed. In the pages of intellectual magazines like The Atlantic
Monthly, well-spoken men argued that the government-guided growth
of Japan and other Asian economies contradicted the free-market
implications of standard economic theory. Economists might shake
their heads at mangled logic and garbled statistics; but in the
early '90s, many thoughtful Americans, William Jefferson Clinton
among them, found them convincing. Then Japan's economic engine
started to sputter; a few years later Asia plunged into crisis; and
those who had trumpeted the superiority of an ``Asian system''
became very quiet.
</P>
<P>
   In recent years, in other words, conventional economics has been
vindicated in at least a negative way: ``Not as silly as our
critics'' isn't exactly a stirring slogan, but it more or less sums
it up.
</P>
<P>
   There is, however, another reason for the new policy prominence
of economists: it is part of a broader social trend, the triumph of
the nerds. Once upon a time important men weren't supposed to be
too obviously clever; the technical brilliance of someone like
Summers or the IMF's Stanley Fischer would in itself have marked
them as unsound. In the business world of the '90s, however, the
propeller heads consistently outperformed the suits, and that
affected overall perceptions of what it takes to get the job done.
A world in which Bill Gates is the ultimate businessman is a world
in which Larry Summers can be treasury secretary.
</P>
<P>
   Still, one suspects that the role of academic economists as
policy makers is a transitory phenomenon _ perhaps even a Pyrrhic
victory. New challenges to orthodoxy, like the growing backlash
against globalization, are already brewing. These challenges may be
ill-informed, but no matter. Economics is an inherently political
subject, on which everyone has an opinion; it is hard to believe
that the public will be willing to defer on a sustained basis to
the expertise of professors, however brilliant.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
