<HEADLINE>
WEATHER 
</HEADLINE>
  (Editors: The following text accompanies the weather map for
Sunday, Jan. 9, sent to computer graphics clients of The New York
Times News Service. For information call: 888-603-1036.) 
(mk) 
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service  
<TEXT>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   NATIONAL FORECAST
</P>
<P>
   A broad flow of high-level winds from west to east will continue
to deliver rather mild Pacific air masses across most of the
nation. As the moist winds impinge upon west-facing mountain
slopes, locally heavy mountain snow will be common from the
Cascades to the central and northern Rockies. Farther east, many
small disturbances embedded in the fast winds aloft will lead to
unsettled conditions from the Mississippi Valley to the Atlantic
coast.
</P>
<P>
   Moist, gusty winds will sweep across the Northwest, promoting
coastal showers and mountain snow in the Northwestern states. Snow
levels between 2,000 and 3,000 feet will be common from the
Cascades to the Bitterroots. East of the Cascades, after a period
of rain in the valleys Sunday morning, gradual drying will develop
in the wake of a front. Farther south, high pressure will keep the
Southwestern states dry and seasonable.
</P>
<P>
   A weak front accompanied by patchy clouds will move east from
the northern and central Plains. In the wake of the front, sunshine
will be ample and temperatures will remain far above the seasonal
average.
</P>
<P>
   Clouds, patchy rain and drizzle will surround a weakening
low-pressure system as it moves toward the eastern Ohio Valley. A
band of heavier showers will occur in the interior Southeast where
humid air will flow north from the Gulf of Mexico. Meanwhile, the
Northeast and Middle Atlantic coasts will have some sunshine early
which will fade behind increasing clouds as increasingly mild and
moist breezes from the south develop.
</P>
<P>
   Focus: Two Jet Streams
</P>
<P>
   On average, the jet stream patterns in the northern and southern
hemispheres are very different. Jet stream winds are driven by
horizontal temperature contrasts. The thermal difference from
equator to pole is the primary source of energy for the jet stream.
In the north, which has more land and topography than the south,
the additional temperature contrasts between land and ocean promote
a serpentine jet stream flow. The current straight west-to-east jet
stream winds in the north are similar to the typical southern
hemisphere flow which keeps arctic air restricted to polar regions.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-01-08-00 1347EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
