<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-01-08 13:58 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A0332 &Cx1f; taf-z
u a BC-LA-EDWARDS-TRIAL-575(     01-08 0949
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-LA-EDWARDS-TRIAL-575(2TAKES)-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
FORMER GOVERNOR OF LOUISIANA FACES THE TRIAL OF HIS LIFE 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ATTN: La., Calif., Texas)  (bl) 
 By DAVID FIRESTONE    
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   BATON ROUGE, La. _ For a quarter century, Edwin Edwards was
Louisiana's great guilty pleasure, the four-term governor whose
breezy misbehavior amused the voters while infuriating several
generations of federal law-enforcement officers.
</P>
<P>
   They charged him with rigging hospital licenses for cash in
1985, but the trial ended in a hung jury. They retried him the next
year, and he was acquitted. There has barely been a deal or a
handshake since then that some prosecutor or detective has not
scrutinized. One lawyer who is close to Edwards said that for 25
years, prosecutors had asked suspects in unrelated cases if they
had any damaging information on him.
</P>
<P>
   But beginning Monday, the former governor will face what almost
everyone acknowledges is the most serious prosecution of his
career, one that he may have difficulty eluding with the Cajun wit
that always beguiled previous juries.
</P>
<P>
   This time, when the jury and the people of Louisiana hear his
sleepy drawl in the U.S. Courthouse in Baton Rouge, he will not be
cracking wise about the women or the poker chips that have passed
through his hands. Instead, his voice will resonate from thousands
of hours of audio and video tapes secretly recorded by the FBI in
his home, office, car and a private plane. The government says the
tapes will show him directing extortion and fraud involving
riverboat casino licenses that brought him and his associates more
than $3 million.
</P>
<P>
   For the first time in his various prosecutions, the government
will present former accomplices who will testify about repeated
acts of corruption to support the 28 felony counts against him. The
star witness will be Edward J. DeBartolo Jr., the former chairman
of the San Francisco 49ers, who is scheduled to testify that he
gave Edwards a briefcase containing $400,000 after Edwards warned
him that his application for a casino license would otherwise be
imperiled. DeBartolo negotiated a plea agreement in exchange for
his testimony.
</P>
<P>
   For the first time, Edwards will be tried not in easygoing New
Orleans, where many black residents still support him, but in this
more conservative and staid capital city. ``Baton Rouge is more
suburban, more middle-class than New Orleans,'' said Bernie
Pinsonat, a local poll taker. ``A Baton Rouge jury is far less
likely to be mesmerized.''
</P>
<P>
   Most frustrating of all, from the perspective of a master
charmer like Edwards, is an order from a dour and exacting federal
judge that prohibits him and lawyers for both sides from speaking
publicly about the case in any way, spelling an end to his defense
by uproarious sound bite. The clowning is over _ he will not be
riding to Judge Frank Polozola's courthouse in a horse and buggy,
as he once did in a previous trial.
</P>
<P>
   All this has led to a gathering sense in Louisiana that Edwards,
72, is no longer quite as slippery as he used to be. Many Edwards
watchers were particularly surprised that he was careless enough to
be caught on tape.
</P>
<P>
   ``There's a feeling now that Governor Edwards could really be on
the ropes,'' said Harry Rosenberg, the former U.S. attorney for the
district that includes New Orleans. ``We don't yet know all of
what's on the tapes, but all indications would lead us to believe
that the contents of those tapes will certainly change the public's
perception of Edwin Edwards. And they will perhaps change the
likelihood of a conviction.''
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   Through Edwards' four terms, voters put up with his gambling and
womanizing _ and what most assumed was much worse _ because he
taxed the oil business instead of them, cared about the poor and
kept them smiling even as they shook their heads in disbelief.
</P>
<P>
   ``I work hard, play hard, move fast and get things done,'' he
once said, and so episodes that would have been scandals for a
lesser politician were just another venial sin for him.
</P>
<P>
   ``He always believed he was following the law, but he loved to
give the appearance of not following it,'' said an old friend,
former state Sen. Edgar Mouton. ``That was his strength and
weakness at the same time. For everyone who said he was the biggest
thief ever to hit Louisiana, there was someone else who said he was
the greatest governor we ever had.''
</P>
<P>
   All this has led some people to believe that he is unshakable,
no matter the evidence against him. ``He's too smart to catch,''
said Donnie Hotard, a contractor at the Exxon chemical plant who
was shopping last week at the Wal-Mart in Port Allen, a grimy city
that is the kind of place where Edwards, a Democrat, has always
been popular. ``I don't think this trial or any trial is ever going
to change that.''
</P>
<P>
   The Nov. 6, 1998, indictment of Edwards and his five
co-defendants, one of whom is his son, Stephen Edwards, depicts a
man far more venal and calculating than his roguish public image.
The indictment says that while he was governor and after he left
office in 1996, Edwards and his aides devised five schemes to
manipulate the awarding of riverboat gambling licenses, extorting
millions from companies seeking the licenses, including
DeBartolo's.
</P>
<P>
   At one point in February 1997, the indictment says, Edwards, his
son and another co-defendant were taped discussing how to disguise
payments from a casino operator. Edwards suggested that they buy a
tugboat and rent it to the casino, then ``jack up the rental'' by
the amount of the payment, about $90,000 a month, the indictment
said.
</P>
<P>
   nn
</P>
<P>
   A month later, the indictment says, Edwards handed DeBartolo a
piece of paper at a Baton Rouge bar with the figure $400,000 on it,
and told DeBartolo that there would be problems with his casino
application if he did not pay it. A week later, Edwards flew to San
Francisco to pick up the cash, using a money vest to transport the
$100 bills to Louisiana, prosecutors say.
</P>
<P>
   He was also charged with hiring a Mississippi man to wiretap the
home of the lead FBI agent in the case, to learn about the case
against him.
</P>
<P>
   Edwards, who pleaded not guilty, has not been able to comment
since Polozola restricted his speech a few days after the
indictment. But earlier he said that as strange as it might seem,
he was merely accepting payments as a consultant to the casino
industry. Friends say he remains supremely confident of acquittal.
</P>
<P>
   The trial, which is expected to last up to three months, is only
the first of what may be a series of prosecutions stemming from the
two-year investigation. Edwards was also charged with fraud in a
separate case, in which he was accused of helping Cascade Insurance
Co. evade millions of dollars in state payments. And he was named
an unindicted co-conspirator in a case in which former Houston
Mayor Fred Hofheinz was accused of bribing an Edwards aide in order
to win state contracts.
</P>
<P>
   If convicted of all the charges against him in the casino case,
Edwards would face 350 years in prison and a fine of $7.25 million.
But the United States attorney heading the case, Eddie Jordan, has
made it clear that there is far more at stake here than the final
years of a gambler's life. Along with Edwards, what is really on
trial this week is an acceptance of political corruption that dates
to the days of Huey and Earl Long.
</P>
<P>
   ``Hopefully,'' Jordan said in charging Edwards, ``our efforts to
hold those accountable for the brazen acts of corruption described
in the indictment will eventually bring about a heightened
awareness among our citizens and those of other states that we will
not tolerate political and economic corruption here in Louisiana.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
