<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-01-08 14:13 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A0338 &Cx1f; tad-z
u f BC-CAREERS09-COX     01-08 0594
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CAREERS09-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Resources to aid a career change
 &HT;    By Brian Stevens
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   DAYTON, Ohio _ Could the new year mean a new career with new
goals for you? January provides a perfect opportunity to evaluate
careerobjectives. Where do you want your career to go in the new
century and how can you take it there?
</P>
<P>
   Cheryl Krueger, director of the Wright State University Office
of Career Services, said exploration is essential.
</P>
<P>
   ``Even if you don't have a specific career idea in mind, take
time to do some exploration to know what skills you offer and what
resources are available to you,'' Krueger said.
</P>
<P>
   Krueger said the best career counselors work one on one to
prompt ideas and identify resources and how best to implement them.
</P>
<P>
   ``Look at your transferable skills,'' Krueger said. Can you put
your skills and knowledge to work for you? For example, experience
may make you competitive in a new field or help you move up in your
present field, Krueger said.
</P>
<P>
   ``Determine the similarities and differences between where you
are now and where you'd like to be,'' Krueger said.
</P>
<P>
   Krueger suggests talking with others in and outside your field
``to help you realize skills you don't know you have.''
</P>
<P>
   One career-oriented Web site, with the humble title monster.com,
offers tips on career strategies. On it, career counselor Barbara
Reinhold outlines five steps to success on the job, beginning with
the promise, ``I will prepare for career success in the 21st
century by doing these five things everyday.'' Those five
resolutions:
</P>
<P>
   _ When something goes right, I'll take unqualified credit; when
I goof, I'll answer for it openly without feeling ashamed or
diminished.
</P>
<P>
   _ I will learn something new every day and figure out how to
apply it to be even better at my work.
</P>
<P>
   _ I will begin each day by programming into that day three
things that will bring me real pleasure, before, during, or after
work.
</P>
<P>
   _ I will be sure that I listen attentively more than I talk each
day, no matter my line of work or position.
</P>
<P>
   _ I will give honest feedback to people as an essential part of
how I do my job, emphasizing the positive as much as possible.
</P>
<P>
   Reinhold suggests selecting a friend or colleague to hold you to
these five steps _ someone who can help you challenge and evaluate
yourself.
</P>
<P>
   Pat Boer, another monster.com ``career guru,'' said ``a trusted
and powerful mentor,'' is your best ticket to career advancement.
</P>
<P>
   ``From the beginning, a mentor shows you the ropes, introduces
you to the right people and points you in the right direction,
suggesting training and professional development opportunities,''
Boer said.
</P>
<P>
   RESOURCES
</P>
<P>
   Cheryl Krueger, director of the Wright State University Office
of Career Services, said there is no end to available career
resources. ``There are a lot of different philosophies and
resources out there, and people should take advantage of them
all.''
</P>
<P>
   _ www.labor.state.ny.us: This site, from the New York State
Department of Labor, offers the following career-planning steps:
</P>
<P>
   _ Make a personal profile, including your interests, skills,
personal preferences and needs, accomplishments and values.
</P>
<P>
   _ Investigate careers and occupations that match your personal
profile.
</P>
<P>
   _ Understand the job market, including occupations, the
employment outlook, industries and the local economy.
</P>
<P>
   _ Identify your goal and then make a plan for achieving it.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
