<DATE_TIME> 2000-01-08 14:13 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A0339 &Cx1f; tad-z
u e BC-CINEMATHERAPY09-COX     01-08 1421
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CINEMATHERAPY09-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Authors prescribe movies as''self-medication'' to improve mood
 &HT;    By Stephanie Allmon
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   WACO, Texas _ For this therapy session, you need to dim the
lights, cuddle a quilt, and pop, pour or scoop a snack plump with
fat grams.
</P>
<P>
   Now insert a movie into the VCR, usurp the remote and let the
therapeutic powers of the illuminated screen channel through your
body.
</P>
<P>
   This is ``cinematherapy.'' And you, the mentally distracted one,
get to choose your own counselor to straighten out the kvetches
forcing your personal world to spin a little lopsided at the
moment.
</P>
<P>
   Feeling used and abused by your boss and your time clock? Dolly
Parton and Lily Tomlin will let you kick back and listen to their
own complaints about their ``Nine to Five'' job.
</P>
<P>
   Did you get dumped? Are you out for blood? Take some lessons
from Kathy Bates' character in ``Misery,'' (or at least fantasize
about cutting the phone lines and breaking his ankles).
</P>
<P>
   And if it's been an overall bad hair day that's caused your
nervous ends to split, Sandra Bullock, Bill Pullman and Peter
Gallagher will help recondition your psyche and massage your aching
head all ``While You Were Sleeping.''
</P>
<P>
   Whatever the mood, the funk, or the time of the month, a movie
exists to pull you through _ at least temporarily. That's according
to the authors of the book ``Cinematherapy _ The Girl's Guide to
Movies for Every Mood.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Movies are more than entertainment: they're self-medication,''
said co-author Nancy Peske.
</P>
<P>
   And while she and co-author and first-cousin Beverly West admit
they conducted little psychological research to back their claim,
the self-proclaimed movie fanatics offer plenty of personal
evidence as proof.
</P>
<P>
   Movies helped ease the pain of West's divorce and helped Peske
turn her career efforts from editing to writing, she said.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think a lot of times women will watch movies to bring up
issues in their lives,'' Peske says. ``Sometimes we want to laugh
at life, sometimes we watch movies in order to wallow in our mood,
and sometimes it's to snap out of it. Even when movies are pure
entertainment, we're connecting to them for very emotional
reasons.''
</P>
<P>
   Connecting is a basic human need, said Annita Maxwell, a
licensed professional counselor in private practice. When there's
not another human to provide comfort or escape from a situation,
movies are a good way to receive that, she said.
</P>
<P>
   ``I sometimes recommend entertainment (in stress-management
seminars) to help change that stress and sometimes even for people
who are mildly depressed,'' she said. ``It's good to be able to see
someone else in the same situation.''
</P>
<P>
   The authors' prescription was so convincing that cable network
Romance Classics has bought the rights to the book and will begin
airing a nightly program called ``Cinematherapy'' on Feb. 1.
</P>
<P>
   On the show, two fictional ``cinematherapists'' will introduce
the night's movie by providing humorous advice on the therapeutic
benefits of that night's featured film. Peske and West serve as
creative consultants and write the scripts for the program.
</P>
<P>
   Advice the cinematherapists dish out could come from the
authors' ``Handy Hunk Chart,'' which rates male movie stars based
on their amount of raw unpredictable masculinity and whether they
have a drowsy drool or bedroom eyes. Or they might classify movies
as having dresses to die for (``Age of Innocence'') or apartments
to die for (``Breakfast at Tiffany's''). Or how to avoid ``Phony
Gal Films'' that make us mad like ``Spice World'' and ``Jerry
Maguire.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Television acts as somewhere (women) can go to disconnect from
the demands of everyday life,'' said Jennifer Geisser, vice
president of public relations for Romance Classics. ``We want them
to be able to put (''Cinematherapy'') on and relax and unwind and
rejuvenate.''
</P>
<P>
   Film scholars have studied the influence of movies on people's
lives since the beginning of the cinema, said Garth S. Jowett,
professor of communication at the University of Houston and author
of ``Children and the Movies: Media Influences and Payne Fund
Controversy.''
</P>
<P>
   He said no historical research shows that movies impact women
more emotionally than men. But so-called ``chick flicks'' usually
deal with women's emotional needs more than men's because women are
more encouraged to show their emotions publicly, he said.
</P>
<P>
   ``Masculine films,'' more action in nature, influence men in
more tangible ways like how to dress or how to behave, he said.
</P>
<P>
   Jowett said good screenwriters and film makers consider the kind
of mood they will create for the audience when they are making a
film.
</P>
<P>
   But just taking enough time to watch a movie can be therapeutic
for anyone, Maxwell said.
</P>
<P>
   ``So many people don't get enough entertainment because they're
too busy with their family and children,'' she said. ``Each of us
have a different demand from ourself to have time alone, and it is
a growth, a regeneration. That's important for good mental
health.''
</P>
<P>
   Some movies, such as ``Titanic,'' (recommended as a
``men-behaving-well movie'') are better viewed on the big screen,
Peske said. But most of the time, cinematherapy can be conducted in
your own home, with friends or alone. Just make sure there aren't
any interruptions, including commercials, during your ``session.''
</P>
<P>
   ``The important fact is that it's two hours uninterrupted,''
Peske said. ``Taking that time out for yourself is very important,
and sometimes you want to share it with others, and sometimes you
want to take charge of your own remote. It's so important to
recharge your batteries.''
</P>
<P>
   Need a movie to match your mood? Try these from ``Cinemetherapy:
The Girl's Guide to Movies for Every Mood.''
</P>
<P>
   WELL, I KNOW SHE'S MY MOM, BUT SHE'S DRIVING ME NUTS:
MOTHER-ISSUE MOVIES
</P>
<P>
   _ ``The Glass Menagerie'' (1987): Starring Joanne Woodward, John
Malkovich, Karen Allen and James Naughton, this movie is the
apotheosis of the daughter-as-ultimate-victim genre, told in the
lazy lyricism of the bayou.
</P>
<P>
   _ ``Postcards from the Edge'' (1990): Starring Meryl Streep,
Shirley MacLaine, Dennis Quaid and Gene Hackman, this
coming-of-age-and-out-of-mom's shadow movie is a loosely
fictionalized autobiography of Carrie Fisher's life as the
star-stunted daughter of Debbie Reynolds.
</P>
<P>
   Others to try: ``Terms of Endearment'' (1983); ``'Night,
Mother'' (1986); ``This is My Life'' (1992); ``Secrets and Lies''
(1996); and ``Drop Dead Fred'' (1991).
</P>
<P>
   BUT HE HAS GOT SUCH POTENTIAL, AND I KNOW THAT HE CAN CHANGE:
EARTH MOTHER MOVIES
</P>
<P>
   _ ``Prince of Tides'' (1991): Tom (played by Nick Nolte) comes
from an abusive family and is woefully out of touch with his
emotions. A psychiatrist (Barbra Streisand) who is treating Tom's
sister ends up dealing a lot more with Tom, who learns to love
again in no time.
</P>
<P>
   _ ``Edward Scissorhands'' (1990): Starring Jonny Depp and Winona
Ryder, ``Edward Scissorhands'' is a futuristic allegory about a New
Age Frankenstein monster with soulful eyes, drop-dead dimples and
garden shears for hands who spreads love and tasteful styling tips
everywhere he goes. Unfortunately, he cannot hold hands with his
lady love without causing permanent scarring.
</P>
<P>
   _ ``Four Weddings and a Funeral'' (1994). Hugh Grant, at his
stuttering best, and Andie MacDowell have the good fortune of
bumping into each other at various weddings, eventually leading
them to contemplate their own union.
</P>
<P>
   _ Others to try: ``Coming Home'' (1978); ``The King and I''
(1956); and ``Jacknife'' (1989).
</P>
<P>
   I JUST WASHED MY HAIR AND I CAN'T DO A THING WITH IT: BAD HAIR
DAY MOVIES
</P>
<P>
   _ ``Hairspray'' (1988): Where else but in a Bad Hair Day Movie
would a chubby girl from Queens named Tracy Turnblad (Ricki Lake)
win a beauty contest and go on to inspire a hip line of plus-size
fashions, a dance craze and a bouffant Jackie O-like hairdo?
</P>
<P>
   _ ``A Stolen Life'' (1946): Painter Kate (Bette Davis ) is
delightfully forward and honest, and therefore, destined to be
kicked by the man she loves. Just when her evil twin sister (also
played by Davis) is about to ruin Kate's life, a soap opera plot
twist gives Kate the chance to nab that fella once and for all.
</P>
<P>
   _ Others to try: ``Bringing Up Baby'' (1938); ``The Snake Pit''
(1948); ``Marty'' (1955); ``The Truth About Cats and Dogs'' (1996);
``White Palace'' (1991).
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
