<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-01-08 14:14 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A0340 &Cx1f; tad-z
u i BC-COX-CUBA-EXILES-0109     01-08 1037
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-COX-CUBA-EXILES-0109 </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    FOR MIAMI'S EXILES, PASSIONS ABOUT COMMUNIST CUBA, CASTRO RUN
DEEP
 &HT;    Moving in both (i) International and (w) Washington categories.
 &HT;    By Mike Williams 
 &HT;    c.2000 Cox News Service 
<TEXT>
<P>
   MIAMI _ Dressed in a stylish business suit and heels, investment
banker Lourdes Blanco didn't look the part of an angry protestor
demonstrating against the decision to send 6-year-old Cuban rafter
Elian Gonzalez back to his father in Cuba.
</P>
<P>
   But even if she didn't carry a Cuban flag and chant
``Libertad!'' the 30-something executive still felt passionately
enough about the boy's fate to turn out during her lunch hour for
the protest.
</P>
<P>
   ``I came here at six years old from Cuba, and my family went
through a lot,'' she said, speaking in calm tones and impeccable
English. ``My mother was a political prisoner. She was in jail just
before I was born. People in this country don't understand. You
have to experience living in Cuba to know what goes on in that
country.''
</P>
<P>
   Outside South Florida, young Elian's story seems sad but simple
to many Americans: Blood ties are more important than politics, so
in the best interests of the child, send him back to his father.
</P>
<P>
   But for Cuban-Americans _ or exiles, as they are called _ the
issue is much more complex, and emotional. For many of them,
politics isn't about abstract policies or ideas. It is intensely
personal, born of pain, loss and separation. It is about morals and
principles.
</P>
<P>
   And passion.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's important to remember that 75 percent of Cuban-Americans
in this country were born in Cuba,'' said Dario Moreno, himself a
Cuban immigrant who now teaches political science at Miami's
Florida International University. ``They remember Cuba and what
they lost when they left there. For them it is black and white,
good and evil. Fidel is the devil incarnate, Cuba is hell on earth
and sending a six-year-old boy back to that hell is immoral.''
</P>
<P>
   That said, students of exile politics say Miami's Cuban
immigrants aren't as unified _ or as rabid _ as televised images of
the protests might make it seem.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're talking about a few hundred people who are going from
place to place to have these protests,'' said Max Castro, another
Cuban immigrant who is a research associate at the University of
Miami's North-South Center. ``Surveys here have shown that about 75
percent of Cuban-Americans want Elian to stay in Miami. But about
68 percent of (Miami-Dade) county's Hispanics don't approve of the
protests blocking the streets and disrupting traffic.''
</P>
<P>
   Miami's Cuban-American community _ which numbers more than
750,000 _ has captured headlines through the years, earning the
reputation as a place of extreme opinions and a knee-jerk
anti-Communism that at times has provoked disbelief and even scorn
in other parts of the country.
</P>
<P>
   Miami, the joke goes, is one of the few cities in the country
where a leader's stand on foreign policy issues is more important
than his or her position on garbage collection, property taxes or
the other traditional bread-and-butter issues of local politics.
</P>
<P>
   Through the years, Miami's leaders have made headlines for
taking stands that would be unheard of in other local political
arenas. In the early 1990s, they triggered a national boycott by
African-Americans when they snubbed visiting South African hero
Nelson Mandela because of his friendship with Castro.
</P>
<P>
   In another case, city officials refused to host a Special
Olympics competition on municipal property because handicapped
children from Cuba were to attend.
</P>
<P>
   In a nation that was founded on the principle of tolerance and
strives for a stated goal of inclusion for all, the Cuban exiles
have appeared to some as bombastic, unreasonable, extreme.
</P>
<P>
   And the case of Elian has reinforced that image. Nothing could
be more heart-rending than the story of a child witnessing his
mother drowning at sea and then barely surviving himself. And to
many Americans, nothing could be more heartless than to keep the
child from his loving father, to place politics ahead of one of the
most deeply felt and universal of human emotions, the bond between
parent and child.
</P>
<P>
   For all the show and bluster of the protests, it's clear the
case is very troubling to many Cuban-Americans.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm Cuban, but I'm a parent,'' said Tanay Alonso, who lives
only a few houses down from the home where Elian has been staying
with his relatives in Miami's Little Havana section. ``If something
should happen to my husband, I'd want my kids to be with me.''
</P>
<P>
   Max Castro agrees.
</P>
<P>
   ``The decision by the Immigration and Naturalization Service was
absolutely correct and courageous,'' he said. ``None of the facts
can overcome that there is a loving father and four loving
grandparents in Cuba who want this child back.''
</P>
<P>
   Thousands of other Cuban immigrants may hold such opinions, but
may be reluctant to state them. Many, too, may feel that while
Elian would be better off in Miami, it is wrong to do anything more
than write a letter or make a telephone call to express that
opinion.
</P>
<P>
   In the end, the small number of activists will probably continue
to set the agenda _ and get the most media attention _ in Miami.
Protests by a few hundred committed people will create the image of
an entire community on the verge of exploding in anger.
</P>
<P>
   And even the experts who say the range of opinion is more subtle
than news accounts have shown agree that if Elian finally goes to
Cuba, the event will probably draw thousands to the streets instead
of hundreds.
</P>
<P>
   Because for too many Cuban-Americans, the pain of their own
experience _ or that of relatives left behind in Castro's Communist
Cuba _ is still too vivid to allow any shadings of their beliefs.
</P>
<P>
   ``When I came here from Cuba, my own son was six years old,''
said Oscar Garcia, 68, who joined in a protest in downtown Miami
this week. ``It was the hardest decision of my life, because like
everyone, I came with my pockets out. We had nothing. But I did it
for my son. Today, he is a successful architect. That is the kind
of future I want for Elian.''
</P>
<P>
   ENDIT
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
