<DOCNO> NYT20000108.0133 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-01-08 14:14 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A0341 &Cx1f; tad-z
u i BC-GILBERTS-STORY09-COX     01-08 2858
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-GILBERTS-STORY09-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Love bridges war, separation and uncertainty for two Rwandan
refugees
 &HT;    By Brad Buchholz
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   AUSTIN, Texas _ I stumbled onto Gilbert's Story by accident _
which, for me, is a great part of its beauty. I was teaching a
remedial writing class, in 1997, at Austin Community College.
Gilbert was a student. Right away, I noticed that Gilbert carried
himself with a rare sense of grace. He was cheerful, yet earnest
about his studies. He sat in the first row. A teacher's dream.
</P>
<P>
   One day, early in the semester, Gilbert turned in an essay about
marriage. In his paper, he wrote that a good marriage required
patience, and compromise, and faith. In terms of structure, the
paper was flawless. Yet Gilbert was nowhere to be found in his own
story.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is a fine essay,'' I said. ``But you left me wondering:
Are these observations grounded in personal experience? Are you
really married?''
</P>
<P>
   ``Oh yes!'' Gilbert responded brightly.
</P>
<P>
   We agreed, in his revision, that Gilbert would explain himself _
that he would share with the reader how he came to understand these
great truths.
</P>
<P>
   A few days later, Gilbert returned with a new essay, rich with
unexpected detail _ about his homeland of Rwanda, about the
genocide of 1994, about tragedy and flight, about his new life as
an African refugee in America. It told the story of how he met his
wife, how he lost his wife and how he feared for her safety even
now _ for she was still stranded in Africa. Would he ever see her
again?
</P>
<P>
   I read Gilbert's Story, during class, as the students took a
test _ and I was numb to the behind-the-books giggles of some of
the students. Then I looked at Gilbert, diligently lost in his
work, a man who exuded the most beautiful sense of optimism in the
face of tragedy. What a remarkable story, I thought. And it had
only just begun ...
</P>
<P>
   THE CHILD OF KIGALI
</P>
<P>
   Rwanda is a small country _ not even twice the size,
geographically, of the Dallas-Fort Worth metropolitan area. It's a
beautiful place: the country of ``Gorillas in the Mist.'' The
Rwandans have a name for their homeland: Imisozi Igihumbi. The Land
of a Thousand Hills.
</P>
<P>
   Gilbert Habarurema grew up in Kigali, the capital of Rwanda. It
was at a baptism, in 1992, when he met Felicite _ a stately beauty
with soulful dark eyes. They quickly fell in love. ``It was
wonderful,'' says Gilbert shyly, recalling their courtship. It's a
bold statement, for him, for his is a culture of understatement.
</P>
<P>
   Sadly, marriage was not an option _ at least not then. ``In
Rwanda, you have to have a way to take care of a wife. And I did
not have that yet,'' says Gilbert. He was 24 in 1992, still living
at home with his parents, splitting time between school and his job
at the bank. Felicite was a year younger, studying economics.
</P>
<P>
   Years passed. The lovers grew close, and a nation cracked apart.
For generations, the sorrow of Rwanda has been the rivalry between
Hutus and Tutsis _ an ethnic division incited by Europeans and
their churches, years ago, as a way to divide the nation from
itself and maintain colonial authority. These tensions continued to
boil in independent Rwanda until April 6, 1994 _ when the country
went berserk on the day its president, moderate Hutu Juvenal
Habyarimana, died in a mysterious airplane crash.
</P>
<P>
   On that day, radical Hutus ran wild in the streets of Kigali.
They slaughtered Tutsis. They slaughtered Tutsi sympathizers. They
slaughtered Habyarimana's moderate confidants. They slaughtered
Hutus who merely looked like Tutsi's.
</P>
<P>
   Gilbert's family was slaughtered, too, when the mob overran the
house on the first night _ for his father was known as a Tutsi
sympathizer. Gilbert lost his mother, his father, two brothers and
a sister. Gilbert survived only by hiding in the attic during the
attack. He waited hours _ two full days, actually _ to come down,
never sure if it would be safe in the light of day.
</P>
<P>
   TAKING FLIGHT
</P>
<P>
   When he did emerge, Gilbert sought the help of a neighbor _ who
helped him leave Kigali by night and flee to neighboring Zaire, 50
miles to the west. Behind him, the slaughter continued, as more
than 500,000 Rwandans died during the systematic, nationwide
genocide of 1994.
</P>
<P>
   When armed Tutsi rebels wrested power from the Hutu militiamen
in July, Gilbert returned to Kigali _ only to find his family's
house overrun by refugees from Burundi. Gilbert's quest to regain
his home was met with indignation. Word spread that he was his
family's sole survivor. What's more, there was no sign of Felicite.
</P>
<P>
   After learning of a plot to kill him, Gilbert fled again in
November 1994 _ crossing the border into Uganda and then into
Kenya, a three-day journey covering more than 500 miles. At the
Uganda-Kenya border, he befriended a pastor who put him on a
midnight bus and bribed a border guard to gain safe passage.
</P>
<P>
   By the time he found sanctuary in Nairobi, Kenya, Gilbert had
lost everything: his home, his family, his livelihood, and
certainly his innocence. Through the United Nations, he applied for
refugee status in the United States _ and waited. Nairobi was a
hellhole, swarming with displaced Rwandans. Gilbert still feared
for his life _ for he had to share the streets with radical Hutu
refugees who had participated in the Kigali slaughter.
</P>
<P>
   And what of Felicite? ``I could not imagine her,'' says Gilbert,
``because I did not know where she was.''
</P>
<P>
   Six months later _ June 1995 _ Gilbert ran into an old friend
from Kigali who passed on miraculous news: Felicite was alive. He
had seen her, walking on the streets of Mombasa, in eastern Kenya.
Gilbert scrounged money for a bus ticket _ and within a matter of
days, he found her. Felicite was living with a sympathetic Kenyan
family, playing indoors with their young children, when Gilbert
arrived late in the afternoon.
</P>
<P>
   ``When I saw Felicite and called her in her name, she looked at
me as if she could not believe it was me,'' he says. ``We hugged
each other and could not restrain our tears. We spent almost 30
minutes without saying any word to each other, mostly because of
the emotion.''
</P>
<P>
   Felicite had survived the first wave of genocide _ she had been
on holiday, outside of Kigali, in April 1994 _ but she had been
forced to separate from her mother and father and go into hiding
with another family.
</P>
<P>
   ``There were problems with women and soldiers. Rape,'' says
Gilbert. ``A soldier could ask marriage _ by force _ and there was
nothing for the woman to do. And that's why she had to flee'' in
May 1995.
</P>
<P>
   Gilbert and Felicite returned to Nairobi, where they were
married March 11, 1996. There would be no church wedding; no white
dress; no diamond ring. ``I didn't have much money in Kenya,'' says
Gilbert. ``I bought a ring, outside the court where we got married.
It was very cheap, the kind of ring people on the street sell to
couples who maybe forgot their ring on the way to the wedding. It
was all I could afford.''
</P>
<P>
   As a married couple, Gilbert and Felicite shared a single week
in Nairobi. Then, on March 18, Gilbert reluctantly boarded an
airplane to the United States _ alone _ having been approved for
refugee status. In accordance with U.S. immigration laws, Felicite
would have to apply on her own, a process that could take as long
as four years. Worlds apart, husband and wife would have little to
hold on to _ a $4 band of silver, a wedding photograph and the
reluctant hope that fate might bring them together again.
</P>
<P>
   COMING TO TEXAS
</P>
<P>
   In Austin, Gilbert diligently set up a new life for himself with
the assistance of Caritas. He got a job baking bread at H-E-B. He
took English classes. He enrolled at ACC. He shared an apartment
for a while, then got a place of his own. Surely, his wife would
join him soon. Surely ...
</P>
<P>
   ``I was going crazy at that time,'' says Gilbert, ``I didn't
know what to do. I would ask everybody, what to do, trying to get
information. I worried about her at night. There are so many
thieves in Nairobi. They might rape her or steal what was in her
bag. Even if there are police watching, it does not matter. There
are so many people who are desperate.''
</P>
<P>
   It was during this time _ 1997 _ that Gilbert attended my class
at ACC. There was no outward sign that he was in pain _ crazy with
doubt and fear. His essays were meticulously prepared, thorough. I
could tell he was investing huge amounts of time on revisions _ a
remarkable act of discipline considering that he was also drafting
letters to U.S. Rep. Lloyd Doggett and refugee information centers
in Washington, D.C.
</P>
<P>
   Gilbert placed out of my class midway through the term. Yet he
asked permission to stay anyway _ for he thought it the responsible
thing to do. Sometimes, he would come to class with letters to
Washington, asking, shyly, if I might make a telephone call to the
State Department on his behalf. I was supposed to be a journalist,
after all. Someone who could make things happen.
</P>
<P>
   During the next year, I would run into Gilbert when I shopped at
H-E-B. Always smiling, looking so unfamiliar in his white apron and
paper hat, he would tell me that a breakthrough was expected ``any
day now'' for months on end. He had learned, however, that Felicite
had found refuge in a convent _ an island of safety in crazy
Nairobi.
</P>
<P>
   One day I encountered Gilbert at a time of great crisis. It
involved a birthday cake. Two college-age women were agitated,
registering their animated complaints to the Rwandan baker.
Everything had been ruined! The party would be spoiled! A name had
been misspelled, perhaps. Or the frosting was pink instead of blue.
</P>
<P>
   Gilbert stood behind the counter, patiently taking on all
accusations _ though I'd bet my job that he'd had nothing to do
with the decoration of the hapless cake. He was doing a marvelous
job, in fact, handling the trivial complaint with the familiar
sense of dignity and calm that I had come to know in class. Yet I
couldn't resist butting in.
</P>
<P>
   ``Leave this guy alone,'' I said, so clumsy in the light of
Gilbert's grace. ``You have no idea! This guy is a hero, the
bravest man you'll ever know. ...''
</P>
<P>
   THE REUNION
</P>
<P>
   Gilbert's good news came late in 1997. Thanks to changes in U.S.
immigration policy and Rep. Doggett's attention to the petition
process, Felicite's passage to America had been finalized. She
arrived just before Christmas elated and exhausted. She was
hospitalized within days.
</P>
<P>
   ``The doctors think she had malaria,'' Gilbert said,
matter-of-factly, at the H-E-B. Then we talked about little things.
After genocide, separation, worry and more separation, a little
skirmish with malaria was nothing. As Gilbert talked, I marveled at
his poise, the way he smiled.
</P>
<P>
   HAPPY ENDINGS
</P>
<P>
   In the season of Thanksgiving, 1999, I drive to a nondescript
apartment complex to visit Gilbert and Felicite at home for the
first time _ and to speak with them as a journalist. I hesitate at
the door because I know Gilbert doesn't like to talk about his
past. It hurts me to be a party to his pain. Still, I try to
reassure him _ and myself _ that his story is too triumphant, too
relevant, not to share.
</P>
<P>
   By American standards, Gilbert and Felicite lead a difficult
life. Money is tight. Opportunity is limited. Gilbert, now 31, no
longer bakes bread. Instead, he works from 4:30 p.m. to 3 a.m. at
National Instruments, helping to construct computer hardware. He
attends class at ACC during the day, working for his associate's
degree. Felicite works a day-time shift as a housekeeper at Seton
Hospital.
</P>
<P>
   Gilbert and Felicite greet me warmly. Inside their American
apartment, however, my eye wanders. I catch sight of three African
animals _ elephant, antelope, giraffe, carved from wood _ near the
television set. Below: the most delicate little black-and-white
baskets, with tall lids in the shape of inverted funnels.
</P>
<P>
   ``The baskets are from Rwanda,'' says Felicite. But even those
were bought on the run, in Kenya. There is no other trace of their
homeland: no photos of lost family, no keepsakes from lost
childhoods. Yet the sad, sweet beauty of Gilbert and Felicite's
story is that they have the most important thing _ each other _ and
now, an 8-month-old daughter.
</P>
<P>
   ``We named her Savannah, after the land, so that she'll think of
Kenya whenever she hears her name,'' says Gilbert. In Gilbert's
Story, Kenya means hope, and reunion, and the start of a new life.
</P>
<P>
   In the spirit of Thanksgiving, Gilbert and Felicite hand me a
list of friends who have helped them adjust. They thank their
employers. They thank Rep. Doggett and aide Martha Ralston. They
thank Charles Sikes, who befriended Felicite at the hospital and
rounded up baby clothes and day-care connections for Savannah.
Finally, they thank Jo Ann Diller, a former ACC counselor who
befriended Gilbert and helped him refine his letters to Washington.
Diller has shared Thanksgiving dinner for three years in a row now,
and she was at the hospital for Savannah's birth.
</P>
<P>
   ``Sometimes you have one chance to say thank you _ but the words
just aren't enough,'' says Gilbert. He says he's grateful for his
life, grateful to God for the gift of his marriage. ``Living
without her ... I don't know if it would be possible to be happy
right now. I just don't know.''
</P>
<P>
   GILBERT'S STORY
</P>
<P>
   The beauty of Gilbert's Story is that he still dreams, and most
of those dreams involve Savannah. Sitting with his African family
on an American sofa, Gilbert talks about getting married in a
church someday _ to make the union ``official'' _ and for Savannah
to be old enough to stand beside them, to understand the story and
the spirit of the marriage.
</P>
<P>
   ``Though it may be late (in life) for us now, we want to be able
to provide for Savannah,'' he says. ``We know that we don't have
things, here, that our daughter can use to be successful in this
life ... We don't have parents who were born here or would give us
some stuff. Everything must come from us.
</P>
<P>
   ``If we don't succeed in this life, in this society, it will be
hard for our children to succeed. That's why I try to work hard so
that I can have a higher education, which would allow me to get a
job that would pay better, so I can provide basic things.''
</P>
<P>
   Though he once lived in an apartment with no furniture, Gilbert
declines offers of financial aid. He worries that people might not
appreciate his sense of responsibility.
</P>
<P>
   ``People may want to know about you, feel sorry about you _ and
sometimes that's not good,'' he says. ``It's better to do yourself
in order to achieve something. Sometimes, the Diller family will
ask, 'What can we do for you?' I say, 'I think it's best (to accept
nothing) until we have maybe a serious problem, that's when we can
tell you we need help.'''
</P>
<P>
   Jo Ann Diller, like most who know Gilbert, shakes her head at
such talk _ because she knows that Gilbert frequently works and
studies on two hours' sleep, that he worries about the availability
of child care, that his is a life without luxury. And yet Gilbert
and Felicite would never think to complain.
</P>
<P>
   ``I get excited when I think of Gilbert and his wife _ and I
think so many Americans can learn from their story,'' says Diller.
``Here's a family that's really going to make it, despite all the
heartbreak, all the suffering. There's something very confirming in
their story. ... Gilbert and his wife are survivors. They have
inner strength _ strength they have gained through their suffering.
</P>
<P>
   ``You know, we're so pampered in America. There's so much 'woe
is me.' But here's a guy who came here with nothing but the clothes
on his back _ and yet the possibilities of his life are endless! I
think America should make itself available to refugees like Gilbert
because these people are going to be great contributors to society.
They are, in fact, what America is all about.''
</P>
<P>
   I try to explain these things to Gilbert, but he will not hear
them. He sees in me _ the teacher of coordinating conjunctions _
someone who has attained ``insight'' and the ``secure life'' that
will be a part of his future. How can I convey the notion that his
story humbles all of us? I'll never handle the smallest tragedy
with Gilbert's grace. I am his pupil, the one who is still learning
the lessons about courage, and dignity, and thanksgiving. And yes,
even forgiveness _ for Gilbert tells me he still dreams of
returning to Rwanda someday.
</P>
<P>
   ``I would like our baby to know where we came from,'' Gilbert
says softly, glancing at Savannah. ``Yes, I've lost my family. But
it is my country. I mean: You always remember where you grew up,
where you went to school. And one day in life, you want to return
to where you grew up and went to school. Maybe something you knew
is still there. Maybe someone you knew is still there. I don't know
quite how to explain it.''
</P>
<P>
   Driving home, I consider Gilbert, and loss, and love _ and the
suggestion of his return to Rwanda. His is a remarkable story. And
it has only just begun.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
