<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-01-08 14:15 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A0343 &Cx1f; taf-z
u a BC-CIVILSUPPORT-AGENCY-A     01-08 1129
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CIVILSUPPORT-AGENCY-ART-910&AMP;ADD-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
ANTI-TERRORISM OPERATION HAS CIVILIAN FOCUS 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ATTN: Vt.)  (ART ADV: Photo is being sent to NYT photo clients. Nonsubscribers
can make individual purchase by calling (888) 603-1036 or (888)
346-9867.) 
(lb) 
 By ELIZABETH BECKER    
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   NORFOLK, Va. _ One year ago, Brig. Gen. Bruce Lawlor was a
small-town Vermont lawyer whose duties in the National Guard
included hauling water to livestock during summer droughts and
rescuing farmers in winter ice storms.
</P>
<P>
   Last month Lawlor became the first commander of a sensitive new
military operation that would respond if the United States were
struck by a chemical, germ or nuclear attack.
</P>
<P>
   Lawlor, a one-star Army general who had never served on active
duty until last year, was given a position just two links removed
from President Clinton in the chain of command precisely because of
his homespun background.
</P>
<P>
   ``He can talk to civilians,'' said John Hamre, the deputy
secretary of defense.
</P>
<P>
   Lawlor's three-story barracks-style headquarters is here, his
budget is a modest $4 million and his staff of 28 experts could be
the vanguard of a much larger operation.
</P>
<P>
   Originally the Pentagon contemplated creating a commander in
chief for the defense of the United States _ a ``homeland defense
command,'' in military shorthand. Civil rights groups of all
political persuasions knocked down that idea out of fear that it
would open the door to an increase in the military's influence
inside the country.
</P>
<P>
   ``We probably were premature,'' Secretary of Defense William
Cohen said in an interview.
</P>
<P>
   Lawlor's scaled-down command is known by a less evocative
phrase: Joint Task Force Civil Support.
</P>
<P>
   When the Pentagon's senior military and civilian leaders first
broached the idea with Clinton, they said the military was the only
institution that could aid citizens after an attack by nuclear,
chemical or germ weapons or a large conventional explosion like the
attack on the Oklahoma City federal building.
</P>
<P>
   That was long before the recent spate of warnings that
terrorists might attack in the United States during Year 2000
celebrations, a threat that seemed especially significant after the
recent arrests of Algerian expatriates charged with planning a
bombing.
</P>
<P>
   In the event of an attack, all of the military's resources _
from helicopters and cargo planes to fleets of trucks _ could be
used to haul emergency supplies to devastated cities, but always
under the authority of civilians.
</P>
<P>
   Working with civilian agencies, the military would set up
whatever was needed, whether hospitals or decontamination units.
Above all, the military would bring order to the expected chaos and
panic that would follow a terrorist attack.
</P>
<P>
   ``We posed it as an idea,'' Cohen said. ``Who are you going to
turn to when there is a catastrophic event?''
</P>
<P>
   Despite the fears of civil libertarians, the idea has not been
abandoned, and Lawlor's command has been given the mission.
</P>
<P>
   Because Clinton shares the military's conviction that terrorists
and countries like Libya and North Korea pose the greatest threats
to the United States today, he was intrigued with the homeland
defense idea.
</P>
<P>
   For several years the Pentagon has planned for terrorist attacks
overseas by requiring specific military units to be vaccinated
against anthrax, considered the most likely biological weapon to be
used by terrorists against U.S. troops.
</P>
<P>
   Lawlor's mission is to broaden those preparations to care for
civilians throughout the United States.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're taking a war-fighting force and focusing it on public
safety,'' Lawlor said. ``We don't do law enforcement, or arrests.
We will save lives, prevent human suffering and restore as fast as
possible critical life-support systems in the community.''
</P>
<P>
   But this command is more than a miniature military version of
the Red Cross. It is nestled in the enormous Joint Forces Command,
formerly known as the Atlantic Command, which supervises more than
half of the nation's armed forces. Through his immediate
supervisor, Adm. Harold Gehman Jr., the commander in chief here,
Lawlor will be able to call on nearly all of the military units
based in the United States.
</P>
<P>
   In the meantime, he and his staff are putting together what
amounts to the Pentagon's first detailed preparation for how to
work with the major civilian agencies to respond to a chemical,
biological or nuclear attack.
</P>
<P>
   No such plan was in place in 1993 when the World Trade Center in
New York was bombed with a weapon that had been laced with cyanide.
It was meant to explode like a chemical weapon and kill thousands,
but the cyanide burned up in the detonation, said military
officials who cite that attack as one reason the Pentagon set up
this command.
</P>
<P>
   Since the bombing, New York and 119 other cities have become
part of a Pentagon program that teaches the chiefs of local
services like the fire and police departments how to react to an
attack.
</P>
<P>
   In all likelihood, city and state officials would take little
time asking the president for help, especially if terrorists use
nuclear weapons. Then, at the president's direction, the Joint Task
Force Civil Support would jump into action.
</P>
<P>
   The command's job now is to plan for the unexpected.
</P>
<P>
   Military officers working with scientists and civilian experts
will make computer simulations of various attacks, figure out what
will be needed and, with the approval of civilian agencies, write
their playbooks.
</P>
<P>
   In turn, the command will test the plans in exercises involving
the military, the National Guards, the FBI, the Federal Emergency
Management Agency and others, sometimes including top
administration and congressional officials.
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE _ OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   That kind of coordination was part of Lawlor's life in the
Guard, which is at the governor's disposal. A native of Bellow
Falls, Vt., he was recruited by the CIA while a student at George
Washington University and became an intelligence officer in Vietnam
during the war, working with the South Vietnamese civilian police.
</P>
<P>
   Later he was offered a commission with naval intelligence and
joined the National Guard when he returned home to Vermont.
</P>
<P>
   As a lawyer for more than 20 years, and a former member of the
Vermont Legislature, Lawlor said he was especially sensitive to
charges that his command could violate the Posse Comitatus Act,
which prohibits the military from performing police duties in the
United States.
</P>
<P>
   Lawlor said part of his role was to ensure that the public
understood that his command would always be under the control of a
civilian agency and that the military had no intention of expanding
its powers.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
