<DOCNO> NYT20000108.0136 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-01-08 14:20 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A0344 &Cx1f; taf-z
u s BC-FBN-VIOLENCE-3TAKES(T     01-08 1046
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FBN-VIOLENCE-3TAKES(TRIMS)-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
STAINS FROM POLICE BLOTTER LEAVE MANY IN NFL FEELING EMBARRASSED
</HEADLINE>
   (rk) 
 By MIKE FREEMAN    
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   The emergence of Peyton Manning and other talented young
quarterbacks and the decline of fabled franchises like the San
Francisco 49ers have dominated events on the field in the NFL this
season. But the headlines that left the most indelible image of
professional football have come from the police blotter.
</P>
<P>
   A linebacker in Baltimore was arrested on a charge of punching a
woman in a Maryland bar. A safety in Denver was arrested for
punching a topless dancer. Two Buffalo players were arrested for
sexually assaulting off-duty female police officers in a nightclub.
On Long Island, two current and one former member of the Jets were
charged with setting off a barroom brawl.
</P>
<P>
   And in Charlotte, a wide receiver faces the death penalty,
accused of orchestrating the drive-by shooting of his pregnant
girlfriend. Rae Carruth is the first active NFL player to be
charged with murder, the Pro Football Hall of Fame said. A veteran
football executive called Carruth's indictment ``the darkest moment
in the history of our league.''
</P>
<P>
   The spate of off-field violence, nearly all of it directed at
women, has profoundly embarrassed many NFL players, coaches and
owners. They have begun demanding that the league act much more
forcefully against those who do not restrain their aggression when
they leave the playing field.
</P>
<P>
   ``We are role models,'' said Cory Schlesinger, a fifth-year
fullback on the Detroit Lions. ``As far as I'm concerned, and I
know other guys on this team and around the league feel the same
way: get rid of the bad apples because they have no place in our
league.''
</P>
<P>
   While nearly a dozen highly publicized arrests of NFL players in
recent months for violence against women have created a public
relations nightmare for professional football, some league
officials say that the image belies a more complicated reality.
</P>
<P>
   The number of players arrested for violent crimes has actually
declined over the last three years, NFL executives say. They
attribute the reduction to programs the league created in March
1997 that use counseling, fines and the threat of suspension or
banishment to deter players from violent crime.
</P>
<P>
   But interviews with dozens of NFL players, coaches and team
executives showed a deep consensus within professional football:
people think the league is still not doing enough to combat
off-field violence.
</P>
<P>
   Many people in the NFL want the league to come down much harder
on violent criminals in their ranks, with some advocating for the
league to suspend immediately all first-time offenders and to
banish players who commit serious crimes, including domestic
violence.
</P>
<P>
   Some critics note that the NFL has not suspended any player
found guilty of committing a violent crime, although several
individual teams did so last month. They also say that the fines
levied by the league so far have been modest, with most below
$10,000 _ basically an insignificant sum to athletes who make
hundreds of thousands or even millions of dollars a year.
</P>
<P>
   The lack of teeth in the penalties has meant that players do not
fear league sanctions for violent acts the way they fear
suspensions and fines for violating NFL drug and steroid rules,
many players said.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't know the statistics, so I can't sit here definitely
and say if the policy works or not,'' Schlesinger said. ``I can
tell you I do know players, and they don't care about this policy.
It doesn't scare anybody. Guys are still getting in fights off the
field and beating up their girlfriends or wives.
</P>
<P>
   ``The policy needs to be, `Beat up your wife, you are out of the
league, period.'''
</P>
<P>
   Jimmy Johnson, coach of the Miami Dolphins, had a similar view,
as did Art Modell, majority owner of the Baltimore Ravens.
</P>
<P>
   ``Is it a deterrent?'' Johnson said. ``Maybe, just maybe, for a
player who has already been punished under it. Otherwise, probably
not.''
</P>
<P>
   Modell said he was in favor of ``anything that will try to
reduce some of the problems we have.''
</P>
<P>
   ``And we do have some significant problems now with our players
and violent crime,'' Modell said. ``But you can't outlaw
misbehavior. It is a policy that at best may focus attention on it,
but let's be honest, I don't know if it works. It is not a
deterrent.''
</P>
<P>
   Some league executives insist that their policies are having an
impact. ``Most people who criticize the policy are talking off the
cuff,'' said Lem Burnham, the NFL's vice president for player
development, who is one of the league officials overseeing the
anti-violence efforts. ``If they really examined it, they would
know it works.''
</P>
<P>
   In 1997, 38 players were arrested for violent crimes, an NFL
official said. In 1998, 35 players were arrested and last year 26
players were arrested.
</P>
<P>
   The number of convictions has also declined, the official said.
In 1997, 23 players were convicted of violent crimes or accepted
plea bargains. In 1998, 14 were convicted or pleaded guilty. Last
year, five players were convicted or pleaded guilty, as of the end
of September.
</P>
<P>
   ``The numbers are dropping,'' Burnham said. ``There is no
question what we are doing is succeeding.''
</P>
<P>
   The league's approach relies heavily on counseling, based on the
NFL's strong belief that therapy helps players curb violent
tendencies. Since the policy was adopted, about 100 players have
been ordered by league officials to seek therapy in anger
management, according to team and league executives. Some coaches
and front office officials have also been ordered into therapy and
fined, according to league executives, who declined to identify the
coaches and officials.
</P>
<P>
   At least two dozen players have been fined by the league, an NFL
executive said. The first was Keith Poole, a third-year wide
receiver for the New Orleans Saints, who was sentenced to two
months of probation in November 1998 for attacking a man with a
golf club. He was fined $4,500, team and league officials said.
</P>
<P>
   ``If I'm fined $5,000, that's nothing,'' said a player who spoke
on the condition of anonymity. ``I spend that much money on long
distance phone calls.''
</P>
<P>
   nn
</P>
<P>
   (BEGIN OPTIONAL TRIM)
</P>
<P>
   Only a tiny fraction of the NFL's 1,600 players have been
accused of serious crimes. But over the last few months, the
notorious nature of many of the charges and the wide coverage
afforded them by the news media have created a broad perception
that pro football players cannot control themselves off the playing
field.
</P>
<P>
   Late last month, for example, Darrius Johnson, a starting
defensive back in his fourth year with the Broncos, was arrested on
charges of punching an exotic dancer in the face at a strip club
after she rejected his advances, the Denver police said.
</P>
<P>
   That came shortly after Cecil Collins, a rookie running back for
the Miami Dolphins, was charged with breaking into the apartment of
a neighboring couple in the middle of the night. The woman told the
police that Collins had been stalking her and had asked her out,
even though she was married.
</P>
<P>
   Collins was suspended indefinitely by the Dolphins and his
career is in jeopardy, because he faces jail time. In 1998, before
he came to the Dolphins, Collins was charged twice with
unauthorized entry. One of those incidents involved a 17-year-old
girl, who accused Collins of exposing himself.
</P>
<P>
   But the accusations against Johnson and Collins pale when
compared with those confronting Rae Carruth, a third-year wide
receiver for the Carolina Panthers. Carruth was indicted for murder
last month after being accused of plotting with three acquaintances
to kill his pregnant girlfriend, Cherica Adams. Prosecutors have
said they will pursue the death penalty against Carruth.
</P>
<P>
   There have been many other embarrassing charges against players
lately. Steve Muhammad, a rookie defensive back for the
Indianapolis Colts, was charged with misdemeanor battery in
November for beating his pregnant wife. His wife, Nicole, died 10
days after he was arrested, but a coroner determined that her death
had been caused by injuries incurred in a seemingly minor auto
accident, and not by the alleged beating. While the case is
pending, Muhammad is playing for the Colts.
</P>
<P>
   Also last month, Ray Lewis, a third-year Baltimore Ravens
linebacker, was charged with assault, accused of punching a woman
in a Maryland bar.
</P>
<P>
   Two Jets offensive linemen were indicted last month by a grand
jury in Nassau County on charges stemming from a bar brawl in Long
Beach last July. Tackle Jumbo Elliott, a 12-year veteran in the
league, was charged with assault after having been accused of
punching a woman and a man at the bar; he was also charged with
disorderly conduct for urinating in the women's bathroom sink.
Jason Fabini, a second-year tackle, was charged with disorderly
conduct.
</P>
<P>
   A former Jets player, Matt O'Dwyer, was also arrested in the
incident. O'Dwyer has been sued by three police officers, who
accused the 300-pound offensive lineman of kicking out the window
of a police car from inside, sending shattered glass into the
officers' eyes.
</P>
<P>
   In November, two members of the Buffalo Bills and a former
teammate were arrested after being accused of sexually attacking
two off-duty Buffalo police officers in a downtown nightclub.
</P>
<P>
   Marcus Spriggs, a third-year offensive tackle; Jeremy McDaniel,
a rookie wide receiver; and Brian Edwards, a former running back,
were hit with a blizzard of serious charges related to the
incident.
</P>
<P>
   The police accused Edwards of grabbing one of the female
officers by the crotch. When the officer objected, the police said,
McDaniel punched her in the eye and kicked her in the stomach.
Spriggs, who is 6 feet 3 inches and weighs about 300 pounds,
grabbed the second officer, who was trying to help her friend, and
threw the 100-pound woman to the ground, according to the police.
All three men were accused of fighting with other police officers
who tried to arrest them.
</P>
<P>
   All of these arrests _ and many more _ occurred even while the
league was trying to use its new programs to curb violence.
</P>
<P>
   ``If we were sitting here in a do-nothing mode, then we should
be harshly criticized,'' said Burnham, the NFL vice president.
``But we are aggressively trying to stop these problems.''
</P>
<P>
   (END OPTIONAL TRIM)
</P>
<P>
   Some people question whether a sport in which violence is so
integral to the game can effectively prevent players from
misbehaving off the field _ or even if it is reasonable to expect
that the league could.
</P>
<P>
   Some also wonder whether talented players feel a sense of
license, assuming that if a team releases them because of problems
off the field, there will be another team waiting with open arms.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think our society's worship of elite athletes, because we
coddle and fawn over them, in some ways we've created anti-social
beings who believe their needs come first,'' said Merrill J.
Melnick, a sports sociologist at the State University of New York
at Brockport.
</P>
<P>
   In 1996, Dan Wilkinson, then a third-year defensive lineman with
the Cincinnati Bengals, was found guilty of punching his pregnant
girlfriend in the stomach; he received a suspended sentence and a
$200 fine. Despite the attack, two years later the Washington
Redskins sent the Bengals first- and third-round draft picks in a
trade for Wilkinson, and then signed him to a five-year, $21.4
million contract.
</P>
<P>
   Or is it simply the machismo of the sport that affects behavior?
Greg Blache, the Chicago Bears' defensive coordinator, awarded
single bullets to his players this season for big plays, like sacks
or solid tackles. When Blache was asked about the wisdom of using
such a motivational ploy, especially in light of the Carruth
indictment, he shrugged off the question as news media hype. The
NFL contacted the Bears last month and told them to cease the
practice.
</P>
<P>
</P>
<P>
   No definitive work has ever been done studying the changes, if
any, the sport of football may have on players. But an article last
year by Alfred Blumstein and Jeff Benedict in Chance magazine,
which is published by the American Statistical Association,
reported that the crime rate among professional football players
was much lower than for their counterparts of the same age and
racial background in society.
</P>
<P>
   Still, the litany of violent crimes against women has prompted
many players, coaches and NFL executives to say that the league
should do more to combat off-field violence. Many people said that
the league should drastically increase fines and aggressively
suspend players who are found guilty of such crimes.
</P>
<P>
   ``Do that and there would be no violence by players,'' said a
Pro Bowl wide receiver who spoke only on the condition of
anonymity. ``It would disappear. Guys would be too afraid to lose
paychecks.''
</P>
<P>
   League officials say, however, that there are limits to what
they can do. Burnham said that calls for suspending or banishing
players after a first conviction were based on emotion and not
reason.
</P>
<P>
   ``If you just kick guys out of the league immediately, you're
going against a number of right-to-work laws and some state and
federal laws,'' he said. He added that the NFL would be
``contributing to the criminal element of society'' if teams
dismissed players permanently, putting them on the street without
counseling.
</P>
<P>
   The league's violent-crime policy was introduced at a meeting of
NFL team owners in March 1997 as the cornerstone of a new attack on
preventing criminal behavior among NFL players. Commissioner Paul
Tagliabue said at the time that the league ``felt a growing concern
over detrimental conduct.''
</P>
<P>
   ``We want to deter the misconduct and one way to deter
misconduct is to impose discipline,'' he said. ``Another way is to
have counseling.''
</P>
<P>
   League officials were no doubt sincere in wanting to address the
problem, but there were also public relations considerations. Then,
as now, the league had to deal with embarrassing arrests of high
profile players.
</P>
<P>
   (BEGIN OPTIONAL TRIM)
</P>
<P>
   One was linebacker Cornelius Bennett, who has played in five
Super Bowls with teams in Buffalo and Atlanta. He pleaded guilty to
sexual misconduct in 1997 in an attack on a female acquaintance in
a Buffalo hotel room. Bennett served 35 days in jail and later
received counseling under the league's program.
</P>
<P>
   The NFL's policy was in its infancy when Bennett was arrested.
At the time, players accused of violent crimes were subject to
counseling, but not punishment. Would Bennett have feared the
policy in its current form, he was asked, and thus been able to
avoid the sexual abuse charge for fear of fines or suspension by
the league?
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't know, probably not at that time,'' said Bennett, who
now plays for the Indianapolis Colts. ``I thought I was a good
person then, but I wasn't as good a person as I believed. I don't
know if a piece of paper would have changed anything.''
</P>
<P>
   (END OPTIONAL TRIM)
</P>
<P>
   Crimes that fall under the league's programs include the use or
threat of physical violence, the use of a deadly weapon, illegal
possession of a weapon, hate crimes, the destruction of property
and domestic violence. Any NFL employee or player charged with one
of these crimes must undergo counseling. A conviction or guilty
plea subjects a player to a fine or suspension without pay. A
longer suspension, and possibly banishment, follows a second
conviction. The amount of a fine or the length of suspension is up
to the commissioner.
</P>
<P>
   The league also holds sessions each year for rookies, trying to
impress upon them that off-field misbehavior could end a career.
And the NFL has actors perform skits for teams on subjects like
date rape.
</P>
<P>
   ``The NFL has done a better job of coming team to team to talk
about issues like violent crime,'' said Mike Shanahan, the Denver
Broncos' coach. ``The awareness is getting better and better. It's
not a perfect world, but we're getting there.''
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   League executives hope that counseling and tougher sanctions
will cause the number of players arrested each year for violent
crimes to diminish further.
</P>
<P>
   Bennett is among the players who believe that therapy can be
extremely useful. ``I made a mistake and where counseling really
helps is that I know I will never make another mistake like that
again,'' he said. ``I can't speak for everybody in the league, but
I don't think the violent crime policy necessarily stops guys from
making mistakes. But if they do, I think therapy can really help.
It helped with me.''  &QL; 
 &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
