<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-HOLLYWOOD-CONDOMS-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
WEST HOLLYWOOD DEBATES CONDOM EFFORT FOR BARS 
</HEADLINE>
  (mk) 
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   WEST HOLLYWOOD, Calif. _ Officials, health workers and nightclub
owners have been arguing for months over developing a municipal
policy to get the denizens of the freewheeling night life mecca
here to obtain and use condoms.
</P>
<P>
   On Monday, the West Hollywood City Council approved a plan to
give 320,000 free condoms this year to 33 gay bars, which would
voluntarily supply the condoms to their clientele by placing
condoms in jars. But, feeling the step insufficient, the AIDS
Healthcare Foundation, which treats 5,000 patients throughout the
Los Angeles area, has proposed a competing initiative that would
ask West Hollywood voters to make the program apply to all bars in
the city _ not just those with a predominantly gay clientele _ and
would require participation, rather than allowing the program to be
voluntary.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's about protecting the public health,'' said Michael
Weinstein, the foundation's president. ``Not only the public health
in HIV transmission, but unwanted pregnancy and other sexually
transmitted diseases. We're in an epidemic in West Hollywood, and
we're not doing all we can do.''
</P>
<P>
   The toughest opponents may be the bar patrons themselves. To a
man, customers at the gay discotheque Revolver said they were
skeptical of government sponsorship of such programs, because they
believed those matters were a personal responsibility, or better
handled by volunteers, or simply because they believed the programs
would not work.
</P>
<P>
   ``You can put condoms in their faces, but it's up to them if
they use them,'' said Les Kurkendaal, a 33-year-old actor. ``We've
had condoms for years, but people still have unsafe sex.''
</P>
<P>
   In part, the debate reveals much about the character of West
Hollywood, a 2-square-mile, 40,000-resident enclave flanked on
three sides by Los Angeles and on the fourth by Beverly Hills. It
is a premier night life destination known for its risque Halloween
parade where costumes have included Monica Lewinsky's cigar and a
bunch of pansies.
</P>
<P>
   The debate has not been about whether the program is right or
wrong, only how extensive it should be.
</P>
<P>
   In West Hollywood, where roughly a third of the residents _ and
many more of its club and bar patrons _ are gay men, there is
concern over a return of promiscuity brought on by the success of
protease inhibitors in treating HIV and AIDS, combined with a new
generation of less careful men who, for the most part, have not
lost friends to the disease the way older gay men have.
</P>
<P>
   City officials and AIDS care workers note that although West
Hollywood has only one-half of 1 percent of Los Angeles County's
population, it has 7 percent of the county's AIDS cases. And, in
data soon to be released as part of a nationwide study by the
Centers for Disease Control and Prevention, half of 548 men under
age 30 surveyed in West Hollywood said they had had unprotected sex
with other men in the previous six months. Among the survey
respondents the rate of HIV infection was 10 percent.
</P>
<P>
   Other than the House of Blues, which has made free condoms
available to patrons over the years and supports the city program,
West Hollywood's straight bars a few blocks away on Sunset
Boulevard have been silent on the issue. But managers of the gay
bars that line Santa Monica Boulevard have strongly opposed a
mandatory program and chafe at having it specifically tailored to
their gay clientele, saying the proposed measure is an example of
government discrimination.
</P>
<P>
   Michel LeChasseur, the general manager at Rage, a dance club,
said his establishment had been making condoms available for five
years, and he accused the AIDS Healthcare Foundation of seeking a
mandatory policy to make money. He contended that the foundation
might benefit financially, perhaps by supplying the condoms. The
foundation rejected the assertion.
</P>
<P>
   Others said the government should focus on prevention and
education, and not on dictating how nightclubs should be run.
</P>
<P>
   West Hollywood has had a condom distribution program for eight
years, and in June increased the number it gives out under pressure
from Weinstein's group, which had threatened to force a ballot
initiative if the program did not become more aggressive. When it
became clear that the city's measure would be voluntary, Weinstein
began his petition drive again, and on Wednesday turned in more
than 4,600 signatures in support of the initiative, double the
number required. Supporters hope the measure will be on the
November ballot.
</P>
<P>
   ``Safer sex has died as an issue,'' Weinstein said.
</P>
<P>
   ``I need to do something to say, `We don't want any more
clients. We want this to end.'''
</P>
</TEXT>
