<SLUG> BC-YACHT-AMERICAS-CUP-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
CONNER'S STARS AND STRIPES TRAILS AMERICA ONE
</HEADLINE>
   (rk) 
 By CHRISTOPHER CLAREY    
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   AUCKLAND, New Zealand _ The legal implications of Stars and
Stripes' decision to use a rudder manufactured in Australia earlier
in this round remain uncertain, but as racing resumed Saturday in
the America's Cup challenger semifinals, at least the pecking order
looked clearer.
</P>
<P>
   The leader here is now America One, which represents the St.
Francis Yacht Club in San Francisco and which beat Stars and
Stripes convincingly Saturday by 2 minutes 43 seconds after
building a large lead on the first leg. Paul Cayard's crew has a
4-1 record midway through this round, which will ultimately trim
the challenger field from six to two.
</P>
<P>
   And what makes America One, in its new boat USA 61, look even
more imposing is that it has performed well in very different
weather conditions. Its only loss came when it sustained jib
failure with a significant lead against America True in the second
race of the semifinals.
</P>
<P>
   ``We really feel like we're hitting our groove here,'' Cayard
said. ``We're improving as a team with the crew work and the
pre-start and the handling of the boat. We're more confident in
what we're doing, and the boat is a good all-around boat.''
</P>
<P>
   In Cayard's immediate wake are Stars and Stripes, no longer
unbeaten at 3-1, and Prada Challenge, now 3-2. After compiling the
best record in the preliminary rounds, Prada was on the brink of
crisis on Friday against Le Defi Francais but managed to overcome
two penalties to win. Saturday, it put together one of its more
poised and tactically sound efforts to defeat the Nippon Challenge
by 1:33 .
</P>
<P>
   ``I think Prada, Nippon, Stars and Stripes and us are all pretty
close,'' Cayard said. ``It's really hard to predict who will come
out on top.''
</P>
<P>
   In the light winds that prevailed Saturday and delayed racing
for more than an hour, it was easier to predict that Dennis
Conner's team might have a hard time. Stars and Stripes had not
raced since Wednesday, after being granted 48 hours to repair
damage to its stern scoop sustained in a collision. According to
Conner's tactician Tom Whidden, Stars and Stripes' USA 55 ``comes
alive'' at 10 to 12 knots, and the wind was often slightly below
that.
</P>
<P>
   Bringing up the rear in this regatta and with little chance of
qualifying for the challenger finals are America True of the San
Francisco Yacht Club and Le Defi, which beat America True by 36
seconds Saturday. America True is now 1-3; Le Defi is 1-4.
</P>
<P>
   Nippon is 2-3 and has lost two in a row _ to America One and to
Prada _ but the bigger issue here is whether Nippon can beat Stars
and Stripes off the water. The Japanese, who lost to Conner's boat
on Day 1 of this round, have protested to the international jury
that Stars and Stripes used a rudder that was in breach of article
19 of the America's Cup protocol because it was not made in the
United States or in New Zealand (after the syndicate arrived here).
</P>
<P>
   As it turned out, the rudder was designed by Americans but
manufactured in Australia at McConaghy Boats in Sydney with
materials shipped from the United States. The rudder was originally
intended for use in the third round-robin preliminaries but did not
arrive in Auckland in time and was installed for the semifinals. It
was then quickly removed after the opening victory over Nippon and
replaced by a rudder of wholly American origin.
</P>
<P>
   Why the hasty change after a victory? Conner isn't telling.
``It's a little bit like Monica Lewinsky talking about her case
while it's still going on; it's not really appropriate,'' Conner
said Saturday. ``But we're quite confident that we'll be fine and
we haven't violated any rules and that we'll be totally
vindicated.''
</P>
<P>
   The other syndicates believe the rudder was replaced because
America True had asked the arbitration panel for an interpretation
of article 19. ``When we heard the rumor about Stars and Stripes'
rudder, we asked for the clarification'' Dawn Riley, America True's
skipper, said.
</P>
<P>
   After the jury met Friday night, the arbitration panel opened
deliberations on the issue Saturday morning and asked each
semifinalist to provide an interpretation of article 19. The panel
plans to reconsider the case on Sunday morning, issue a formal
interpretation and then refer the issue back to the jury for action
if it is required.
</P>
<P>
   Penalties could include forcing Stars and Stripes to rerace
Nippon, granting a point to the Japanese, stripping a point from
the Americans or even expelling Stars and Stripes from the event on
the grounds that it would no longer be eligible to compete in the
America's Cup finals against New Zealand should it win the
challenger series.
</P>
<P>
   Conner has spent much of his career navigating amid America's
Cup controversy. ``There's nothing in the rules that says the
rudder can't be made in Australia,'' he said. ``We'll let the
arbitration panel decide.''
</P>
<P>
   Until then, his crew will be sailing under extra pressure.
``It's a huge issue for us,'' the helmsman Ken Read said. ``But we
have to be very conscious that we don't make it a sailing
distraction. Can we pull that off? History will tell that.
Obviously, we feel like we're right and will fight to the end to
prove we're right.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
