u p BC-DEMS-MONEY-2TAKES-1ST     01-08 1273
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-DEMS-MONEY-2TAKES-1STLD-WRITETHRU-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
DEMOCRATS WORRY THAT GOP WAR CHEST COULD COST THEM THE WHITE HOUSE
</HEADLINE>
 
(ATTN: Calif., Ohio, Ill., Del., Pa.)   (Eds: SUBS first optional graf, Those who ..., to delete
extranesous `and' to make clear that Dimon is the former president
of Citigroup.) 
(nk) 
 By RICHARD L. BERKE    
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   PORTSMOUTH, N.H. _ Many prominent Democrats say they are deeply
troubled that the Republican Party is collecting so much more money
than them that it will enjoy an insurmountable financial advantage
_ perhaps enough to cost the Democrats the White House.
</P>
<P>
   These Democrats have a recurring fear: that their nominee,
either Al Gore or Bill Bradley, will emerge in late March from the
peak presidential primary season battered, bruised and broke.
</P>
<P>
   And if at that time the Republican National Committee has a big
surplus of unregulated ``soft money'' over the Democratic
counterpart, they say, the Democratic candidate would face a
relentless blizzard of television commercials condemning Democratic
programs.
</P>
<P>
   Echoing other Democratic officials, Sen. Robert G. Torricelli of
New Jersey, chairman of the Democratic Senatorial Campaign
Committee, said the Republicans could ``easily have a 3- or
4-to-1'' advantage over Democrats. ``I'd be surprised if we could
put together more than $30 million in soft money,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Torricelli even speculated that the Republicans could amass $200
million, a figure Republican officials called overblown.
</P>
<P>
   ``We could be faced with a situation where in the early spring
the Republicans begin generic advertising with soft money and never
leave the air,'' Torricelli said. ``And the electorate could
conceivably not hear from the Democratic Party until the national
conventions. You could have, literally, months of unanswered
political advertising.''
</P>
<P>
   That would be a reversal from four years ago, when President
Clinton's campaign was flush and the Democrats began to broadcast
commercials against Bob Dole, his Republican opponent, a strategy
credited with badly damaging Dole.
</P>
<P>
   The worries about money have stirred some resentment toward
Clinton. Some Democrats complain that the president _ distracted by
his efforts to collect money for his library; the Senate campaign
in New York of his wife, Hillary; his legal defense fund; and his
support for the millennium festivities _ has neglected his own
party. Several Democrats also said that while their committees to
help House and Senate candidates were doing quite well, they feared
that the Republicans' soft money edge would hurt Democrats running
for Congress.
</P>
<P>
   While there has traditionally been a financial disparity between
Democrats and Republicans, a confluence of circumstances and events
has created a particularly serious dilemma for the Democratic Party
this year.
</P>
<P>
   Some donors expressed qualms about the party's prospects for the
White House. Others said they had been tapped for other causes,
like the president's library. Another factor is disarray in the
party, which has not had a finance chairman for more than three
months.
</P>
<P>
   Unlike the Democrats, who start the year with less than $2.5
million in the bank, Republican Party officials said they had
already stockpiled roughly $10 million.
</P>
<P>
   This money is separate from the donations to the presidential
candidates, which is strictly regulated. Soft money given to
parties is intended for ``party building'' activities, not
campaigns, but it is used for advertising on issues and therefore
plays a key role in shaping the broad electoral debates.
</P>
<P>
   Democratic Party officials said there was time for them to catch
up. But none predicted that the party would be at anywhere near
parity with the Republicans.
</P>
<P>
   ``The concern is a real one,'' said Alan Solomont, a veteran
Democratic fund-raiser who was the national party's finance
chairman in 1997. ``I don't think our fund-raising operation as a
party has really kicked into high gear. Democrats need a little
kick in the behind. The problem is we have a relatively small base
of donors and so much is asked of them. A lot of us are
stretched.''
</P>
<P>
   The public expressions of alarm could be seen as an attempt to
provide just the kind of ``kick'' Solomont mentioned. And the
worriers do not mention another factor, the huge independent
spending campaigns by organized labor, which mainly favors
Democratic priorities.
</P>
<P>
   But in weeks of interviewing, nine other well-connected
Democrats _ including officials on Capitol Hill, at the White House
and at the Democratic Party itself _ have all privately admitted
similar concerns.
</P>
<P>
   A striking demonstration of the Democrats' lack of preparedness
is that at the start of a crucial election year, the post of
finance chairman of the Democratic National Committee has been
vacant since Beth Dozoretz quit more than three months ago.
</P>
<P>
   Party officials said they had been unable to persuade big names
in the fund-raising world to take the job full time and instead
last week settled on three people to share the job. They said they
would announce the triumvirate on Monday: Joel Hyatt, an
unsuccessful Senate candidate from Ohio in 1994, who now runs a
business in Silicon Valley; Joe Cari, a lawyer in Chicago; and
Carol Pensky, a former national party treasurer, who will work out
of Democratic headquarters in Washington.
</P>
<P>
   (BEGIN OPTIONAL TRIM)
</P>
<P>
   Those who resisted entreaties to head the finance effort, party
officials said, were David Steiner, a New Jersey financier; Steven
Rattner, deputy chief executive officer of Lazard Freres &AMP; Co.; E.
John Rosenwald Jr., vice chairman of Bear Stearns; and James E.
Dimon, the former president of Citigroup. Party officials also said
they tried to court Orin S. Kramer, an investment banker who worked
in the Carter administration.
</P>
<P>
   The biggest disappointment for party officials was that Terence
R. McAuliffe, the premier Democratic fund-raiser who has turned his
attention to raising money for several of Clinton's projects, as
well as Hillary Rodham Clinton's campaign, did not want a major
role with the Democratic National Committee. Peter Knight, a major
fund-raiser and confidant of Gore, also was not interested.
</P>
<P>
   (END OPTIONAL TRIM)
</P>
<P>
   Magnifying the dilemma for Democrats is the colossal
fund-raising success of Gov. George W. Bush of Texas, the leading
Republican contender. His campaign is so flush that the governor
has eschewed federal matching funds, which come with spending
limits, and is now helping the party collect soft money.
</P>
<P>
   Adding to its difficulties, the Democratic Party has experienced
significant setbacks in soliciting money for its national
convention in Los Angeles in August. And there has been such a lack
of coordination between the national party and its House and Senate
campaign committees that those committees, for more than a year,
have been holding joint fund-raising efforts on their own instead
of sharing the proceeds with the Democratic National Committee.
</P>
<P>
   Ed Rendell, the general chairman of the national committee,
conceded that the competition for the Democratic fund-raising pie
had been fierce because Gore and Bradley were hitting up many of
the same donors as Democratic congressional candidates.
</P>
<P>
   ``It is tough,'' Rendell said. ``We are a little bit the victim
of our own success. There's a finite pool of money and the pie can
be cut only so many ways. But the good news is we don't have to
match them dollar for dollar. We just have to have enough to get
our message across and I am confident we are going to do that.''
</P>
<P>
   nn
</P>
<P>
   Rendell, a former mayor of Philadelphia, chosen by Clinton
because of his reputation as a prodigious fund-raiser, said the
party was better off today than four years ago, when it was several
million dollars in debt.
</P>
<P>
   And he said the party, with the help of appearances by the
president, was embarking on an aggressive drive for money,
especially in smaller cities not usually tapped by the party like
Wilmington, Del., Trenton, N.J., and Toledo, Ohio.
</P>
<P>
   Several Democrats said the party had been distracted by the
battle between Gore and Bradley.
</P>
<P>
   ``While Democratic supporters and major donors are somewhat
preoccupied at the present time by the hand-to-hand combat going on
in the nominating process,'' said Steven Grossman, a former
chairman of the Democratic National Committee and prolific
fund-raiser, ``once that process resolves and we have a nominee, I
believe there will be intense focus'' on raising money.
</P>
<P>
   Still, some Democratic officials conceded that donors were
reluctant to give because they were worried about the party's
prospects for the White House and did not consider Gore, the
front-runner for the nomination, a particularly electrifying
contender.
</P>
<P>
   ``The most significant and inspiring fund-raiser of the last
seven or eight years has been Bill Clinton because he painted a
picture of what we could do and he went out and did it,'' Solomont
said. ``He's one of the reasons why Democrats have been generous.''
</P>
<P>
   Ronald Burkle, a wealthy donor in California, put it this way in
an interview last winter: ``With Clinton, in 30 seconds I was
connected with him. Gore doesn't connect as easily as Clinton.''
</P>
<P>
   But Roger C. Altman, a former deputy treasury secretary in the
Clinton administration, who now runs an investment firm, said that
Democrats should not be worried. ``The Republican side always out
raises the Democratic side,'' he said. ``Unless the disparity is
historically anomalous _ more than 2-and-a-half to 1 _ I don't
think there's anything particularly noteworthy to that.''
</P>
<P>
   But Torricelli warned that the disparity might be far greater
than that. ``The Democratic Party still has not established a
significant financial base that can always be depended upon,'' he
said. ``The party has succeeded in raising money, but it takes
time, it is not very efficient. The Republican Party has a natural
fund-raising base.''
</P>
<P>
   The concerns about lacking soft money may sound odd given that
the two Democratic candidates have both called on Congress to
eliminate such unregulated contributions. Sen. John McCain of
Arizona has made campaign reform such an issue that he said he
would reject soft money if he won the Republican nomination;
Bradley said he would do so only if his Republican counterpart made
such a move as well.
</P>
<P>
   As the Democrats fret, Mel Sembler, the finance chairman of the
Republican National Committee, said his fund-raising efforts were
moving apace, in large part because party donors think the White
House is within easy reach. ``I get the sense that my contributors
feel they're going to win,'' he said.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
