<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-01-08 15:13 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A0386 &Cx1f; taf-z
u p BC-POLITICAL-BRIEFS-2TAK     01-08 0787
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-POLITICAL-BRIEFS-2TAKES-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
POLITICAL NOTES FROM AROUND THE NATION 
</HEADLINE>
  (bl) 
 By B. DRUMMOND AYRES Jr.  
 &HT;     
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   CRUNCH TIMES FOR BRADLEY
</P>
<P>
   DES MOINES, Iowa _ Bill Bradley summed it up with an apt
metaphor on Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
   ``The full-court press is on,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Indeed.
</P>
<P>
   With less than three weeks to go before Iowa's
first-in-the-nation caucuses on Jan. 24, the former senator from
New Jersey and New York Knicks star has begun to throw money and
political elbows, every which way as he and Vice President Al Gore
tussle over the Democratic presidential nomination.
</P>
<P>
   Though Bradley is essentially locked in a tie with Gore in New
Hampshire, where the first Democratic primary will be held Feb. 1,
he is still struggling to catch up with the vice president in Iowa,
still trailing by about 20 percentage points in the latest poll,
carried out last week by The Des Moines Register, which published
it Saturday.
</P>
<P>
   In his press to close that gap, Bradley this month is dumping
more than $800,000 into a television campaign that is huge by Iowa
standards and that, to take one example, will blitz the
already-bleary-eyed average Iowa viewer with 14 advertisements this
weekend. The senator has also recently extended his string of
campaign offices the entire length and breadth of Iowa, taken up
temporary residence in a hotel here and, more telling, begun to
import volunteer workers from other states to help him turn out
caucus-goers on Jan. 24, turnout being the real key to caucus
success.
</P>
<P>
   Finally, in Iowa, as elsewhere, Bradley has begun to sharpen his
anti-Gore oratory, once limited mostly to wonkish comparisons of
his proposals with those of the vice president. On Friday, for
instance, he called on Gore to muster the courage to propose ``bold
solutions to big problems.''
</P>
<P>
   Will it work? Can Bradley win and add to his momentum heading
for New Hampshire?
</P>
<P>
   He argues that because Gore can easily match him in spending and
has the support of most of Iowa's top Democrats and labor leaders,
with access to the organizing machinery they control, the contest
already is lopsided. So, he contends, as an underdog ``insurgent''
candidate, he need only do ``well,'' not beat Gore outright.
</P>
<P>
   Most political professionals agree. But their definition of
doing well is not his.
</P>
<P>
   They talk of a Gore-Bradley voting split on the order of
55-to-45 percent. Bradley, on the other hand, talks of a 2-to-1
ratio.
</P>
<P>
   If that has a lowering-expectations sound to it, well, this is
Iowa and it's caucus game time again.
</P>
<P>
   FOR BUSH, IT'S ABOUT MEETING EXPECTATIONS
</P>
<P>
   As for the Republican contest in Iowa, it seems rather bland by
comparison. The Register poll published Saturday had Texas Gov.
George W. Bush continuing to hold a comfortable lead of just under
30 points over his only serious challenger, Steve Forbes.
</P>
<P>
   Still, some Bush supporters in Iowa are beginning to worry that
the governor is too comfortably ahead and that he and his handlers
are in danger of becoming complacent about the contest.
</P>
<P>
   They say his current schedule calls for him to spend only about
seven days in the state between now and caucus day, with the rest
of the time spent mainly in New Hampshire, where the Republican
contest in much tighter.
</P>
<P>
   The Bush supporters are not worried that Forbes might overtake
their man in Iowa. But they are concerned about how he might fare
in the expectations game.
</P>
<P>
   Should Forbes narrow the gap somewhat, they say, there would be
damaging talk that the governor did not live up to his advance
billing.
</P>
<P>
   Sen. John McCain of Arizona has chosen not to compete in the
Iowa caucuses but the poll published Saturday showed him in a
virtual tie for third place with Alan Keyes and Gary Bauer, who are
competing.
</P>
<P>
   WALKING THE TALK IN NORTH DAKOTA
</P>
<P>
   Sometimes in a political race, a gimmick will help when name
recognition is a problem. And name recognition was Duane Sand's
problem when he retired from the Navy last week and headed back to
Fargo, N.D., his hometown, to run for the U.S. Senate.
</P>
<P>
   He had been away for 15 years, was a political novice and faced
not only the problem of beating two other contenders for the
Republican Party's nomination but, if successful at that, then
would have to face the veteran Democratic incumbent, Kent Conrad.
</P>
<P>
   What to do?
</P>
<P>
   He would campaign, he announced, by walking across the state,
all 346 miles, from Montana in the west to the Red River in the
east.
</P>
<P>
   In January?
</P>
<P>
   ``I not only talk the talk but walk the walk,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   He starts Monday.
</P>
<P>
   Weather Forecast: High around 30 on Monday, headed down into the
teens by Thursday.
</P>
<P>
   nn
</P>
<P>
   FOR MCCAIN, THE PRESS STOPS SINGING
</P>
<P>
   Sen. John McCain of Arizona can surely take comfort from the way
things are going for him these days in his New Hampshire campaign,
where he leads the Republican field in some polls. But that said,
last week had to have been just about the most uncomfortable for
him, in general, of the campaign season.
</P>
<P>
   For months he had enjoyed a ``good press,'' as the saying goes,
now and again taking a hit, as when Arizona papers stirred some
debate by writing that he had a bad temper, but otherwise receiving
mostly positive coverage.
</P>
<P>
   Too positive, many of his detractors contended, charging that
the press had become blindly enamored of him and his promises to
``talk straight'' and keep special interests at arm's length.
</P>
<P>
   It was the kind of plaint heard in just about every presidential
campaign, justified or not. And it was a good bet, especially if
McCain's poll numbers continued to surge, that sooner or later, the
good press would turn bad, justified or not. It almost always does.
</P>
<P>
   In McCain's case, it came Wednesday. That morning, The Boston
Globe reported that the senator had recently pressed the Federal
Communications Commission to rule on whether a company that had
made a major contribution to his campaign could buy a television
station.
</P>
<P>
   McCain, chairman of the Senate committee that oversees the
F.C.C., said he had asked only that the commission speed up its
decision-making process. At no point, he insisted, had he tried to
tell the commission how to come down on the matter.
</P>
<P>
   No matter.
</P>
<P>
   By the next day, justifiably or not, the story was making bold
headlines in newspapers and newscasts from coast to coast, with the
word ``hypocrite'' prominent in a good many. Editorial writers and
columnists found it rich grist. McCain detractors had a field day.
</P>
<P>
   McCain continued to insist he had done nothing wrong and would
handle the FCC situation in the same manner if he had it to do all
over again. But discussing candidate coverage in general with The
Globe, he lamented philosophically:
</P>
<P>
   ``When there is increased visibility, there's less margin for
error. You could get away with mistakes a month ago that you can't
get away with now. People will be focusing a lot more attention.''
</P>
<P>
   TWISTING INTO EDGE IN ILLINOIS RACE
</P>
<P>
   Since Rep. John Edward Porter, R-Ill., announced he was giving
up his 10th District seat on the state's North Shore, only one
Democrat has expressed interest in replacing him. But on the
Republican side, at least a dozen hopefuls have surfaced.
</P>
<P>
   If all run, the Republican primary could turn into a political
free-for-all and be decided by the slimmest of margins.
</P>
<P>
   Shawn Donnelley, the only woman in the Republican field, has a
plan for achieving that margin _ by working the margins.
</P>
<P>
   The petitions she circulated to get on the primary ballot listed
her name as ``Shawn Donnelley.'' But when the ballot is actually
printed, she wants it to carry her full name, which is Shawn
Margaret Donnelley. sp??
</P>
<P>
   Her reasoning appears to be that ``Shawn Donnelley'' is a
gender-neutral name whereas ``Shawn Margaret Donnelley'' makes it
absolutely clear that she is a women and thus, as she sees it, more
deserving of the support of female voters.
</P>
<P>
   But another Republican hopeful, Andrew Hochberg, a business
executive, objects to the change and has urged election officials
not to sanction it. Illinois law, he argues, requires than the name
on the ballot be the same as the name on the ballot petitions _ no
exceptions.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
