<SLUG> BC-FBN-VIKINGS-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
COWBOYS' SANDERS LOOKS TO FORCE VIKINGS' HAND 
</HEADLINE>
  (mk) 
 By TIMOTHY W. SMITH    
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   The last two times the Dallas Cowboys played the Minnesota
Vikings, injuries reduced Dallas cornerback Deion Sanders to
nothing more than a highly paid, intensely interested bystander.
Vikings receivers Randy Moss and Cris Carter had field days against
the Cowboys' undermanned secondary.
</P>
<P>
   It is a different story this time as the Cowboys (8-8) travel to
Minnesota to take on the Vikings (10-6) in a National Football
Conference wild-card playoff game Sunday afternoon. Sanders is
healthy and eager to go against Moss and Carter, who have combined
for 2,654 yards receiving, the second-highest total in National
Football League history. With Sanders, arguably one of the best
cover cornerbacks in NFL history, it is one of the glamour matchups
of the pro football weekend.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm better this time,'' Sanders said. ``I think it will allow
us to do more things and not just sit back and wait on what they're
going to do. We'll be able to force them into situations. But even
if you had Lester Hayes and Mike Haynes'' _ the former Oakland
Raiders cornerbacks _ ``I don't know if you'd have enough talent to
match up with those guys.''
</P>
<P>
   The Cowboys, who were 1-7 on the road this season, will need all
healthy hands on deck if they are going to beat the Vikings, who
finished the regular season as one of the hottest teams in the NFC.
Dallas is accustomed to entering the playoffs as the NFC East
champion and having at least one playoff game at home. But now, if
the Cowboys are going to make it to the Super Bowl they will have
to do it on the road.
</P>
<P>
   The first step is at the Metrodome in Minneapolis. The Cowboys
are confident they can beat the Vikings there in part because
Sanders is healthy. With his speed, he can control an entire half
of the secondary and limit some of the Vikings' big-play capability
in the passing game.
</P>
<P>
   Sanders was limping with an injured groin and hamstring when the
Cowboys lost to Minnesota, 27-17, on Nov. 8. He missed Minnesota's
46-36 victory on Thanksgiving in 1998 because of an injured big
toe.
</P>
<P>
   Together, Moss and Carter accounted for 65 percent of the
Vikings' total offense and seven touchdowns in those two games
against Dallas. Moss caught three touchdown passes and wound up
with 163 yards, and Carter had seven catches for 135 yards in the
victory last season. Then they combined for 15 catches, three
touchdowns and 207 yards in November.
</P>
<P>
   The other side of Dallas' secondary is just as banged-up as
Sanders was the two previous times. Left cornerback Kevin Smith has
been in and out of the lineup for the last month with a hamstring
injury. His backup, Kevin Mathis, has missed the last two games
with a sprained knee.
</P>
<P>
   Both Smith and Mathis returned to practice last week and will
probably play. In the Nov. 8 game, Vikings quarterback Jeff George
took advantage of Charles Williams, a converted safety who was
filling in for Smith. Most of the big plays to Moss went against
Williams.
</P>
<P>
   Dallas coaches will probably mix their coverages to keep George
guessing. So Sanders, who lines up on the right side, probably
won't be locked on Moss all afternoon. In the Nov. 8 game, Sanders
lined up against Moss 15 times and George threw that way only
twice: Moss had an 8-yard reception and Sanders knocked down a long
pass.
</P>
<P>
   ``Deion's unbelievable,'' George said. ``When he's not healthy
he's unbelievable. Just his presence on the field is unbelievable.
But that doesn't mean you shy away from the guy. We have confidence
in our receivers and our running game.''
</P>
<P>
   The Cowboys are counting on their defensive line to give the
secondary some help. Dallas defensive players believe that if they
can get to George and knock him around, he will become so rattled
that he won't get the ball to his receivers.
</P>
<P>
   On the offensive side of the ball, the Cowboys are hoping that
running back Emmitt Smith will be able to pick up where he left off
in that Nov. 8 game. Smith rushed for 140 yards and two touchdowns
to stake the Cowboys to a 17-0 lead before leaving the game in the
first half with a broken hand. Smith is healthy and is coming off a
122-yard rushing game against the Giants.
</P>
<P>
   If the Cowboys' defensive front can't get to George enough, then
it will be up to Dallas' offense to keep the Vikings' offense off
the field.
</P>
<P>
   ``I wish our offense would let that clock tick down to the last
second before we snap every ball,'' Sanders said, ``because the
more you keep those guys off the field, the less opportunities they
have.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
