u s BC-FBN-SEAHAWKS-NYT &LR;      01-08 0805
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FBN-SEAHAWKS-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
DOLPHINS AND SEAHAWKS: 2 TEAMS WHISTLING PAST THE GRAVEYARD 
</HEADLINE>
  (mk) 
 By CHARLIE NOBLES    
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   If the Miami Dolphins and the Seattle Seahawks are concerned
that they enter their American Football Conference wild-card
playoff game in Seattle on Sunday with zero momentum, they are
concealing it well.
</P>
<P>
   Both losers of five of their last six games, and 9-7 overall,
the teams are talking more like Super Bowl contenders. Never mind
that the Dolphins haven't won a road playoff game in 28 years. Or
that the Seahawks rank a woeful 23rd in the league on both offense
and defense.
</P>
<P>
   ``The answer to our problem is us,'' the veteran Miami defensive
end Trace Armstrong said. ``If you look at the games we've lost,
they've really kind of followed the same theme: turning the ball
over and not getting turnovers. We look at our conference and
there's not that one dominant team. It's a matter of who gets hot,
who doesn't make mistakes.''
</P>
<P>
   The Seahawks have a similar vision.
</P>
<P>
   ``Once you've been invited to the dance, you can take the prom
queen home,'' linebacker Chad Brown said.
</P>
<P>
   Defensive end Phillip Daniels added, ``We're good enough to win
it all.''
</P>
<P>
   The game will be contested in the Kingdome, which figures to be
a significant plus for the Seahawks. It took just 75 minutes for
the team to sell its final 20,000 tickets for the game, and Seattle
is counting on crowd noise to hurt Miami's ability to communicate.
</P>
<P>
   ``It should be absolutely rocking in there,'' coach Mike
Holmgren said. ``Then we have to play up to our fans'
expectations.''
</P>
<P>
   The Seahawks have never lost a home playoff game, but that can
be misleading. They haven't had one since 1984, when most of their
current players were adolescents.
</P>
<P>
   Each team seems to be drawing strength from the other's
perceived weakness.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's not like we're going to a place where the team is a
world-beater with only one loss,'' Miami guard Kevin Donnalley
said. ``It's a team that has had losses like we have. If we can get
back to the way we were playing earlier in the year, we feel real
good about our chances.''
</P>
<P>
   Miami was 8-2 at one point in the season. Of course, so was
Seattle. Eerily, their seasons have nearly mirrored each other.
</P>
<P>
   The difference between them is that the Dolphins' collapse has
been played out amid growing tension between two of the league's
highest-profile individuals, coach Jimmy Johnson, with two Super
Bowl victories from his Dallas tenure, and quarterback Dan Marino,
whose many records include one as the league's career
passing-yardage leader.
</P>
<P>
   Johnson has sought for several seasons now to rein in Marino
from his high-risk passing tendencies. Johnson has been stymied in
large part because of the lack of a suitable running game, but that
has not kept him from making his unhappiness known. The coach is
forever talking these days about how turnovers often lead to
defeat.
</P>
<P>
   Marino has thrown 17 interceptions this season, 12 of them
during the team's 19-turnover siege over the last six games.
Johnson even disclosed a statistic of his own last week. During
Marino's 17-year career, the Dolphins are a lowly 28-46 when Marino
throws at least two interceptions in a game. And under Johnson,
that record is even more stark: 2-13.
</P>
<P>
   That is one reason the Dolphins streamlined their offense during
the week, shaping a more conservative game plan that they hope can
include plenty of running. The key there may well be the rookie
running back J.J. Johnson, who has been hobbled by a right
hamstring pull but is expected to start.
</P>
<P>
   A significant subplot is whether Johnson or Marino, or both,
will retire at season's end. Predictably, neither was forthcoming
heading into the game.
</P>
<P>
   Johnson, in fact, implored the Miami news media ``to put the
soap opera on the back burner for one week'' while the Dolphins try
to refocus against Seattle.
</P>
<P>
   If this should be Marino's final game, it appears that his
teammates will think about it afterward.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't think anyone is thinking about that right now,''
Donnalley said. ``We're just trying to focus on this game, how can
we win this game for this team.''
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile, the Seahawks are hoping that quarterback Jon Kitna
will have running back Ricky Watters to deflect some pressure.
Watters, with 1,210 yards rushing, has been dealing with a sprained
right knee ligament but hopes to play.
</P>
<P>
   ``I've got a lot that's going to be placed on my shoulders, but
I like it that way,'' Watters said. ``I'm going to have to be out
there showing the guys how it's done.''
</P>
<P>
   Watters, in his ninth year, presumably views this game similarly
to the way Marino does. ``If you don't win, you're going to be
watching,'' Watters said. ``And it's this simple: I'd rather keep
playing.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
