<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-EDIT-DIETARY-SUPPLEMENTS-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
EDITORIAL: REGULATING DIETARY SUPPLEMENTS 
</HEADLINE>
  (js) 
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   The New York Times said in an editorial for Sunday, Jan. 9:
</P>
<P>
   The dietary supplement industry, freed from strict regulation by
the 1994 Dietary Supplement Health and Education Act, has made a
vast variety of herbal remedies as readily available on supermarket
shelves as ordinary vitamins. Millions of consumers now take
supplements, like ginkgo, kava and St. John's wort, that were
largely unknown in mainstream markets even a few years ago.
Although some research suggests that some supplements can produce
positive health effects, there have also been cases where people
have been made ill by supplements, or their conditions have become
worse while they tried to use ineffective dietary supplements to
treat a medical disease.
</P>
<P>
   Despite explosive growth in this industry, there is very little
guidance or protection afforded to consumers. The 1994 act severely
limited the ability of the Food and Drug Administration to police
supplements for safety and effectiveness. Now the FDA has made this
situation worse. It will allow supplement makers to make even
broader marketing claims about their products under regulations
that go into effect next month.
</P>
<P>
   Under the act, manufacturers can make claims that their products
affect the ``structure or function'' of the body without having to
go through the strict FDA approval process required of drugs. But
they are not allowed to claim that the products prevent, treat or
cure disease.
</P>
<P>
   In 1998, the FDA proposed regulations to clarify the distinction
between the two types of claims. The proposal stated that while
pregnancy, menopause or general aging are not diseases, certain
conditions associated with those states may be considered diseases,
and products claiming to treat those conditions could therefore be
subject to prior FDA approval. But after enormous opposition from
the supplement industry and consumers, the FDA reversed itself and
decided that common symptoms associated with life stages would not
be considered ``diseases.''
</P>
<P>
   This means that supplement makers will be allowed to claim that
their products can treat hot flashes in menopause, ordinary morning
sickness during pregnancy and even hair loss associated with aging.
Serious or abnormal conditions would still be considered diseases.
But the new regulations give supplement marketers leeway to make
dubious claims and encourage consumers to treat conditions with
products that may be ineffective or, worse, actually harmful. Given
growing use of dietary supplements in this country, it is more
important than ever that Congress tighten the law to allow greater
regulation of this industry.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-01-08-00 1523EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT20000108.0151 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-01-08 15:27 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A0395 &Cx1f; taf-z
u f BC-SNOW-REMOVAL-REAL-NYT     01-08 1102
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SNOW-REMOVAL-REAL-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
EASING REMOVAL OF ICE 
</HEADLINE>
  (js) 
 By JAY ROMANO    
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   Anyone who has been to a hardware store in winter knows that
there are scores of products on the market designed to make ice-
and snow-removal less of a backbreaking chore. But sorting through
the various chemicals, compounds, combinations, concentrations and
price-per-ice-melting-pound computations is better suited to a
chemist with a degree in economics than to a homeowner with an inch
of ice on his driveway.
</P>
<P>
   ``Not all de-icers are created equal,'' said Edward Chouinard,
president of Standard Tar Products, a company based in Milwaukee
that makes Snomelt Instant Ice Melter. ``But virtually all de-icers
work on the same basic principle: They lower the freezing point of
the water produced by the ice they melt.''
</P>
<P>
   Chouinard, whose company manufactures de-icing products used by
homeowners, commercial property managers and state and local
highway departments, explained that while plain water freezes at 32
degrees Fahrenheit, the freezing point of water containing a
de-icing chemical is lower than that _ sometimes much lower.
</P>
<P>
   ``The nice thing about Snomelt is that it's exothermic,''
Chouinard said. ``That means that when you mix it with water, it
creates heat.''
</P>
<P>
   Some de-icers _ for example, sodium chloride, better known as
halite or rock salt _ are endothermic, meaning that they need to
absorb heat from the atmosphere, sunlight or friction from tires to
melt ice or snow. As a result, while rock salt is the least
expensive de-icing agent available _ selling for anywhere from
$2.50 to $4 for a 50-pound bag _ it is only effective at
temperatures above 15 or 20 degrees Fahrenheit.
</P>
<P>
   Products like Snomelt, on the other hand, which is 90 percent to
95 percent calcium chloride and sells for about $15 for a 50-pound
bag, can melt ice or snow at temperatures as low as minus 59
degrees Fahrenheit, depending on the concentration of the chemical
in the solution produced by the melting ice _ a solution that
de-icing experts call brine.
</P>
<P>
   In fact, it is the brine produced by a de-icing product _ rather
than the melting action of the product itself _ that does the work
the homeowner is hoping to avoid.
</P>
<P>
   Rick May, marketing manager for Dow Chemical in Midland, Mich.,
said that most de-icing products work by penetrating the ice,
dissolving into brine and then seeping into the pores of the
concrete under the ice. Once there, the brine breaks the bond
between the ice and the sidewalk, making it easier to remove the
ice.
</P>
<P>
   May added that while calcium chloride can indeed melt ice at
minus 59 degrees Farenheit, that is the ``laboratory limit'' of the
chemical's effectiveness. ``In the real world, its practical
effective temperature is more like minus 28 degrees Fahrenheit,''
he said, adding that the effective temperature of the chemical
decreases because its concentration in the brine becomes lower as
more and more ice melts.
</P>
<P>
   He also explained that since calcium chloride is effective at
such a low temperature, products containing it are less likely to
cause problems on concrete surfaces, which are vulnerable to damage
as a result of being exposed to freeze-thaw cycles.
</P>
<P>
   The damage occurs, he said, when water that has been melted by
the de-icer refreezes because the temperature has dropped below the
level at which the de-icer is effective. When that happens, the
concrete may crack.
</P>
<P>
   When de-icers like plain rock salt are used, May said, the
freezing point of the brine is relatively high _ around 15 degrees
to 20 degrees Fahrenheit _ thereby making it more likely that the
temperature will drop to a point where the melted ice will
refreeze. When a de-icer like calcium chloride is used, on the
other hand, the temperature would have to fall below minus 28
degrees for the ice to refreeze.
</P>
<P>
   ``De-icer damage to concrete is usually not a chemical
reaction,'' May said. In addition to products like calcium chloride
and sodium chloride _ the most and least expensive consumer
de-icing chemicals, respectively _ other de-icers on the market
include potassium chloride, magnesium chloride and urea, as well as
various combinations of some or all of them.
</P>
<P>
   Meltdown Near Zero, for example, a de-icer manufactured by
EnviroTech Services, a company based in Greeley, Colo., contains a
combination of sodium, calcium, potassium and magnesium chlorides.
According to Kenberly Dannatt, a sales assistant for the company,
the product _ which has a dark color to increase its ability to
absorb solar energy, thereby increasing the melting rate _ can work
at temperatures as low as minus 5 degrees Fahrenheit.
</P>
<P>
   Even companies that manufacture rock salt are aware of the
virtues of mixing more potent chemical de-icers in with their salt.
Cargill Salt, a company based in Minneapolis, for example,
manufactures Jiffy Melt, a combination of ordinary rock salt and
magnesium chloride.
</P>
<P>
   ``The advantage of Jiffy Melt is that the salt gives it a high
melting capacity at higher temperatures while the magnesium
chloride allows it to keep working by dropping the freezing point
down to about minus 10 degrees,'' said David Merriweather, director
of quality assurance for the company.
</P>
<P>
   Another de-icer that contains magnesium chloride is Freeze
Fighter, a relatively new product that is intended to prevent snow
or ice from accumulating.
</P>
<P>
   ``Freeze Fighter is something we've been selling to state
highway departments for about 15 years,'' said Robin Reid,
communications specialist for Reilly Industries, an Indianapolis
company that manufactures the product. ``And this year we decided
that it's something we should be offering to homeowners, too.''
</P>
<P>
   Freeze Fighter, which is a liquid, is designed to be applied to
a sidewalk or driveway before or shortly after snow has started to
fall, Ms. Reid said, and should prevent as much as two inches of
snow from accumulating. In other words, she said, if only two
inches of snow falls, none should stick on treated surfaces. ``And
if four inches fall, you should only have two inches to shovel.''
</P>
<P>
   The product, which is applied with a garden sprayer and remains
effective until it is washed away by rain or melting snow, costs
about $9 a gallon _ an amount that will provide coverage of about
2,000 square feet.
</P>
<P>
   ``Freeze Fighter is not just a de-icer, it's an anti-ice and
snow agent,'' Ms. Reid said. ``It allows the homeowner to take a
proactive rather than reactive stance against snow and ice. When
you start seeing flurries, you can get out there and spray.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
