<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BBO-NOTEBOOK-RIVERA-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
RIVERA'S THIRDS COUNT FOR A LOT 
</HEADLINE>
  (With BBO-NOTEBOOK) 
(rk) 
 By BUSTER OLNEY    
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   Short relievers are a relatively new phenomenon in baseball, a
result of the evolution of the manner in which starting pitchers
have been used. It has been only 31 years since the rule for
determining saves was defined. But in the coming season, a
statistical standard seemingly possible only for starters may be
challenged by a reliever.
</P>
<P>
   Mariano Rivera, the New York Yankees' peerless closer, did not
allow a run after July 21 last year, and he will carry a streak of
30 2-3 scoreless innings into this season. That leaves him 28 1-3
innings short of Orel Hershiser's record of 59 innings, set for the
Los Angeles Dodgers in 1988.
</P>
<P>
   Although Rivera's streak has been compiled in bits and pieces of
games, while Hershiser's came with a burst of complete games,
Rivera's streak will be treated the same as Hershiser's in the
record book, according to Seymour Siwoff, president of the Elias
Sports Bureau. Interestingly, however, Hershiser's mark was counted
differently than Rivera's.
</P>
<P>
   When Hershiser broke Don Drysdale's 1968 record of 58 innings,
the common practice was to count innings as a whole. For example,
if Hershiser allowed a run with two outs in the sixth inning, then
he would be credited with pitching five scoreless innings. But
Rivera can not be held to such a stringent standard, Siwoff notes,
because his particular role often calls for him to pitch in thirds
of an inning. If Rivera's streak was counted in the same way as
Hershiser's, would an appearance of one and one-third innings count
as two scoreless innings or one? (If Rivera was credited with a
scoreless inning if he pitched one-third or two-thirds of an
innings in an outing, then his streak of consecutive scoreless
innings would be 33).
</P>
<P>
   ``It's a strange sort of thing in his case,'' Siwoff said on
Friday. ``In fairness to him, you've got to count it the other
way,'' and include one-third or two-thirds of an inning.
</P>
<P>
   A reliever may have built a streak longer than Rivera's, but
Siwoff doesn't know about it; records for consecutive scoreless
innings by a reliever are not maintained. ``If he gets into the
40s,'' Siwoff said, referring to Rivera's count of scoreless
innings, ``that would be something we'd take a look at.''
</P>
<P>
   The Yankees are not sure what their own team record for
consecutive scoreless innings is, for a starter or reliever. Since
1988, the longest scoreless streak by any Yankees pitcher was by
Lee Guetterman, a reliever who threw 29 2-3 consecutive innings
without allowing a run from April 6 to May 24 in 1989. In 1996,
Rivera pitched 26 straight scoreless innings.
</P>
<P>
   Rivera is asked to get anywhere from one to six outs in his
appearances, and so if he does challenge Hershiser's record, his
pursuit will be made slowly and steadily. He needs 28 2-3 innings
of scoreless relief to surpass Hershiser, and last season, he did
not throw his 29th inning until June 26. Going that long without
allowing a run is difficult enough, and power pitchers like Rivera
typically require a few extra weeks to build arm strength and
regain their best fastball.
</P>
<P>
   Hershiser carried his streak of 59 consecutive scoreless innings
into opening day of the 1989 season, and in his first inning of
work, Cincinnati's Todd Benzinger singled home Barry Larkin with
two outs. If Rivera moves closer to Hershiser's mark, does this
mean then that those two outs will be added to Hershiser's record?
</P>
<P>
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
