<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BBO-NOTEBOOK-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
BASEBALL NOTEBOOK 
</HEADLINE>
  (With BBO-NOTEBOOK-RIVERA) 
(rk) 
 By BUSTER OLNEY    
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   HE CAN HIT, BUT ...
</P>
<P>
   Left-handed power hitters who can catch usually generate
exceptional interest on the open market, but with about five weeks
before the start of spring training, the free agent Dave Nilsson
remains unsigned, strangely.
</P>
<P>
   It's not as if Nilsson were coming off a bad year. He hit .309
with 21 homers with the Milwaukee Brewers last season, and he is
healthy enough to be a part-time catcher, as well as play first
base or serve as the designated hitter. He has always been viewed
as a good guy, a positive presence in the clubhouse.
</P>
<P>
   Nilsson initially asked for a three-year deal for $4 million to
$5 million a season, executives say. ``That might be too high for
someone who'll play a lot of first base,'' one American League
official said last week. ``There's a glut of good first basemen.''
</P>
<P>
   Word is, then, that Nilsson _ a native of Australia _ could sign
a huge contract to play in Japan, and then be allowed to play for
his homeland in the 2000 Olympics.
</P>
<P>
   While first base may be a loaded position, there is a general
lack of quality third basemen _ making it odd that there are
several at that position still available.
</P>
<P>
   It has been known since last summer that the Montreal Expos, for
instance, have had designs on shifting Michael Barrett from third
base to his natural position at catcher, but lack a suitable
replacement. What about Ed Sprague, unsigned after hitting 22
homers for Pittsburgh last year? Or Russ Davis, the former Yankees
prospect who was not tendered a contract by Seattle in spite of his
power potential?
</P>
<P>
   There is interest in the remaining pitchers, and now that Aaron
Sele, the best of the free-agent pitchers, signed with Baltimore on
Friday, the others are likely to reach agreements as well. Andy
Benes, for one, signed a three-year, $18 million deal with St.
Louis hours after the Sele announcement. The Cardinals previously
added the pitchers Darryl Kile and Pat Hentgen in trades.
</P>
<P>
   A FAMILIAR ORIOLES ROAD
</P>
<P>
   The addition of Aaron Sele leaves the Orioles almost in the
position they were in a year ago. Their rotation could be among the
best in the American League, with Sele _ a ground-ball pitcher who
should work well in small Camden Yards _ joining Mike Mussina,
Scott Erickson and the talented youngsters Sidney Ponson and Jason
Johnson.
</P>
<P>
   Again, however, starting pitching must drive the Orioles, for
the other elements of the team are questionable, with an unbalanced
and slow lineup, a disparate clubhouse makeup and the same
problematic bullpen. Baltimore's primary goal this off-season was
to improve a bullpen that blew 25 of 58 save chances last year, but
while most of the names have changed, the Orioles' relief corps
could be just as bad.
</P>
<P>
   Chuck McElroy, a left-hander acquired from the Mets for Jesse
Orosco, is a high-ball pitcher totally ill suited for Camden Yards,
and the other left-handed specialist, Buddy Groom, is not exactly
reliable; the Yankees' left-handed-hitting right fielder Paul
O'Neill, for example, has 10 hits in 14 at-bats in his career
(.714) against Groom.
</P>
<P>
   Other teams have tried make-overs as well:
</P>
<P>
   _ The Tampa Bay Devil Rays have added the sluggers Vinny
Castilla and Greg Vaughn to a group that already includes Jose
Canseco and Fred McGriff, giving this team a lineup loaded with
high-strikeout bangers. In other words, they are no closer to
qualifying for a playoff spot, except in fantasy leagues.
</P>
<P>
   _ The Colorado Rockies made the playoffs once in eight years
while fielding a team of heavy hitters who exploited the thin
atmospheric conditions of Denver. So Dan O'Dowd, the team's new
general manager, is trying a different approach, filling his
outfield with speed. That should improve the team's defense, and
its pitching in turn, but until the Rockies figure out a way to
maintain the confidence of young pitchers in such a unusual
environment for baseball, nothing will change.
</P>
<P>
   _ The Houston Astros dealt outfielders Carl Everett, Derek Bell
and the All-Star pitcher Mike Hampton, as they addressed budget
concerns.
</P>
<P>
   _ The Seattle Mariners tried to increase the left-handed
presence in their lineup, adding first baseman John Olerud,
outfielder Stan Javier and second baseman Mark McLemore _ all of
whom can bat left-handed.  &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
