<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-NJ-STARBUCKS-SNUB-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
OUR TOWNS: A DOWNTOWN TOO DECAF FOR STARBUCKS 
</HEADLINE>
  (js) 
 By MATT PURDY    
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   CLIFTON, N.J. _ At first, it doesn't hit you. A stroll down Main
Avenue reveals an ordinary, if aging, suburban downtown with a shoe
repair shop, a couple of dry cleaners, a luncheonette here, a
bakery there, a computer store. But soon you realize something is
amiss. Terribly amiss. Your eyes sweep the streetscape, and you can
hardly believe it. There's no Starbucks.
</P>
<P>
   In its manifest destiny to caffeinate America, Starbucks appears
to have missed downtown Clifton. More curiously, when local
officials and developers recently informed the Seattle-based
company of its apparent oversight and invited them to open a cafe
as part of a renovation project, Starbucks said thanks, but no
thanks.
</P>
<P>
   Clifton became a suburban downtown Starbucks didn't want, and
another front in the emerging class conflict over coffee.
</P>
<P>
   Like other close-in suburbs, Clifton is a crossroads of
industrial grit and middle class comfort. Its face to the world is
a neon clock atop the Tick Tock Diner on Route 3 imploring drivers
to ``Eat Heavy.'' Clifton has its share of commuter subdivisions,
but its downtown sits between Passaic and Paterson, whose South
American, Asian and Middle Eastern immigrants are moving into what
was once a white-ethnic city. Last year, the City Council declared
English the government's official language.
</P>
<P>
   The redevelopment is a bid ``to distinguish ourselves,'' said
Patrick DeLora Jr., president of DeLuxe Cleaners, who heads the
downtown improvement group. ``We're trying to get more of an
upscale image.''
</P>
<P>
   That's why Clifton decided it needed a good $3.30 caramel
macchiato.
</P>
<P>
   But a Starbucks on Main Avenue would violate a largely
unrecognized maxim that all suburban downtowns are divided into two
groups: those with a profusion of expensive coffee places and those
with a profusion of expensive nail salons.
</P>
<P>
   Clifton has many nail shops, three near where developers hoped
Starbucks would sprout. At Choice Nails, Suzanne Garretson had her
hand in a Heat 'N Dry, after having her nails tipped and wrapped
for $45. ``Their coffee is expensive,'' she said of Starbucks.
``You go in, and they say, do you want this one or that one or this
flavor or that flavor, and I am, like, just give me the basic
black.'' Her nails were basic brown.
</P>
<P>
   Starbucks is to basic coffee what tips and wraps are to
straight-up nail polish.
</P>
<P>
   The company's mission is ``inspiring and nurturing the human
spirit,'' said Arthur Rubinfeld, senior vice president for store
development at Starbucks, which has 2,200 stores in North America.
``People connect to coffee,'' he said. ``Coffee is the facilitator,
the glue that holds people together.''
</P>
<P>
   Downtown Clifton is going to have to make do with regular old
paste. While Starbucks has stores in other faded downtowns _ and
its coffee is sold at Barnes &AMP; Noble, including the one on Route 3
_ Rubinfeld said Main Avenue ``didn't have the retail synergy to
merit the investment we make in our stores.''
</P>
<P>
   Somehow, the people of Clifton are holding up. A few were
drowning their sorrows the other day with 85-cent coffee at the
Clifton Spa, a luncheonette with Formica counters and swivel stools
that has found synergy on Main Avenue for 60 years.
</P>
<P>
   ``It is a certain type of person who likes Starbucks,'' said
Albina DeLora, the mother of DeLora, the dry cleaner. She has seen
how the other half drinks at the Starbucks in nearby Montclair.
``They like to sit and read their journals and do their laptops and
have their coffee. You have to have a laptop.''
</P>
<P>
   Rubinfeld says Starbucks has brought people in suburbs together,
declaring, ``We are the front porch of America.''
</P>
<P>
   The Clifton Spa must be the tailgate. ``The backbone of
America,'' Richard Schiro, a security guard, calls it. ``A man
making $300 a week could come in here and feel comfortable. If they
go to Starbucks, they have to first look and see if they can afford
it.''
</P>
<P>
   Not at the Clifton Spa. Scott Reid, the owner, will keep a tab
running for you and, as for nurturing the human spirit, when
there's a rare lull in banter at the counter, the TV in the corner
with rabbit-ear antennae gets pretty good reception.
</P>
<P>
   Oh, yes. Just like at Starbucks, the Spa's customers love the
coffee and, Reid said, ``they squawk about the price.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
