<SLUG> BC-EDWARDS09-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    `Fast Eddie' may be fresh out of luck
 &HT;    By Anne Rochell Konigsmark
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW ORLEANS _ ``Fast Eddie'' has always been a fitting nickname
for Edwin Edwards. The smooth-talking, lady-killing, four-term
former governor of Louisiana has walked _ no, strutted _ out of two
federal racketeering trials a free man.
</P>
<P>
   Monday in a federal court in Baton Rouge, he goes on trial
again, this time with his son Stephen and four other co-defendants.
They are charged with extorting money from the state's casinos and
tampering with the licensing process. There are 28 counts against
Edwards. The former governor, as always, says he is innocent and is
confident a jury will agree.
</P>
<P>
   But something has changed: Observers and even old friends
predict this could be the case that slows him down for good.
</P>
<P>
   ``Edwin Edwards is obviously in a serious situation,'' said Gus
Weill, who was Edwards' political consultant in the 1970s. ``He's
72 years old and he's married to a lovely young woman, and he faces
dying in a federal prison. His son Stephen is also on trial and has
five young children. This is a human tragedy.''
</P>
<P>
   The cause for concern is the federal government's mountain of
evidence, collected during almost three years of investigation.
Prosecutors have tapes _ audio and video _ of Edwards and others
talking in vulgar language about extortion and the ``Louisiana
way'' of doing business. Moreover, several old friends and
potential co-defendants, including San Francisco 49ers owner Eddie
DeBartolo Jr., have pleaded guilty and are helping prosecutors in
exchange for lighter punishments.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's going to be very salacious testimony,'' said John
Maginnis, publisher of the Louisiana Political Fax Weekly. ``When
this thing first started, people were saying, `They'll never
convict him.' Now they're saying, `This time I think they got
him.'''
</P>
<P>
   The allegations stem from events in 1991 _ when Edwards was in
his fourth and final term as governor, and the state legalized
gambling _ and in 1996-97, when Edwards was out of office.
Louisiana limits riverboat casinos to 15. And that turns the gaming
licenses into a valuable and coveted commodity.
</P>
<P>
   Federal prosecutors say Edwards and others took advantage of the
situation and demanded payoffs from casino owners in exchange for
favorable rulings from the state licensing board.
</P>
<P>
   Prosecutors say that in 1996 and '97, when DeBartolo was
applying for the state's 15th and final riverboat casino license,
Edwards and son Stephen repeatedly demanded payoffs ranging from
$10,000 a month to a lump sum of $400,000. Despite being out of
office, Edwards continued to wield awesome power in the state.
</P>
<P>
   And that is just one of several schemes alleged by the
government.
</P>
<P>
   ``Edwards has never faced anything like this,'' Maginnis said.
``And now that he's not governor, people are less afraid of him and
more afraid of the federal government.'' That's why so many old
associates made deals with the prosecution, he said.
</P>
<P>
   Weill agreed.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is the first time he'll be confronted by allies who have
turned against him,'' he said. ``I think this is a whole new ball
game.''
</P>
<P>
   Even if Edwards is acquitted in this trial, which is expected to
last three months, he faces yet another indictment. He and
Insurance Commissioner Jim Brown have been charged with helping the
owner of the failed Cascade Insurance Co. avoid paying millions of
dollars in a legal settlement with the state. In addition, Edwards
is an unindicted co-conspirator in an alleged payoff involving a
New Orleans garbage contract. Former Houston Mayor Fred Hofheinz
and Edwards' close friend Cecil Brown were indicted and have
pleaded innocent.
</P>
<P>
   At Edwards' trials in 1985 and 1986 on federal fraud and
racketeering charges stemming from state hospital licenses, the
case hinged largely on a paper trail. There were no secret tapes or
old friends weaving lurid details of back room deals. Edwards
provided most of the excitement: He taun By Clients of the New York
Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
