<HEADER>
A0404 &Cx1f; tad-z
u p BC-POLITICAL-NOTES09-COX     01-08 0900
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-POLITICAL-NOTES09-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Parties clearly split this time
 &HT;    By Mark Sherman
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ The late George Wallace once complained that there
wasn't ``a dime's worth of difference'' between the Democratic and
Republican parties.
</P>
<P>
   But in the same room on consecutive nights in New Hampshire last
week, the parties' candidates for president showed that Wallace's
lament does not hold in 2000.
</P>
<P>
   You had to strain to hear the word ``tax'' when Democrats Bill
Bradley and Al Gore debated Wednesday. Bradley talked about two
pieces of tax legislation, the most recent of which was 14 years
old.
</P>
<P>
   When the six Republican candidates got together the next night,
taxes were a hot topic.
</P>
<P>
   Defending his $483 billion proposed tax cut, Gov. George W. Bush
of Texas could not think of an occasion where reducing taxes would
not be in order.
</P>
<P>
   ``If there is a recession, it's important to cut the taxes to
make sure our economy grows,'' he said. ``It's also important to
cut the taxes when there's times of plenty, as an insurance policy
against an economic slowdown.'' To some degree, these kind of
differences are to be expected during primary season, when the most
likely voters also are the most ideological.
</P>
<P>
   But, perhaps because the candidates spoke in the same place a
day apart, the differences between the parties seemed especially
clear.
</P>
<P>
   On abortion, Bradley and Gore both mentioned their support for
abortion rights. No Republican favors allowing abortions in any but
the most limited circumstances, and some candidates would appoint
as judges only abortion opponents.
</P>
<P>
   Bradley and Gore advocated allowing gays to serve openly in the
armed forces. All the Republicans criticized that idea. Rutgers
University political scientist Ross Baker said he was struck more
by the Democratic message, which he described as moving to the left
to secure the nomination.
</P>
<P>
   ``Many of us thought that Bill Clinton had rewritten the rule
book in '92 by not only being more centrist, but actually going out
of his way in some instances to stiff a couple of liberal
constituencies,'' Baker said.
</P>
<P>
   Still, he said, the nominees probably will move toward the
center of the political spectrum in the fall. MCCAIN DRAWS FIRE
OVER AID TO DONOR
</P>
<P>
   Sen. John McCain (R-Ariz.) predicted to reporters in New
Hampshire before the holidays that his high-flying campaign
probably would make an ``egregious'' mistake before long.
</P>
<P>
   Last week, his campaign was mostly on the defensive in the first
week back from a holiday break after the Boston Globe reported that
McCain wrote the Federal Communications Commission urging action in
a matter involving Paxson Communications, a major contributor and
supplier of a corporate jet for his campaign use.
</P>
<P>
   In the aftermath, McCain acknowledged that ``we are under a
cloud of suspicion'' because of the vast sums of money in political
campaigns, and he canceled a planned fund-raising event with
Paxson's founder because he feared it would generate more bad
publicity.
</P>
<P>
   But McCain insisted he had done nothing wrong. ``I'd do the same
thing tomorrow,'' McCain said in New Hampshire.
</P>
<P>
   There has been no claim that McCain acted illegally in writing
the FCC and bluntly calling for a decision by Dec. 15 on whether to
approve the purchase of a Pittsburgh television station by Paxson
Communications.
</P>
<P>
   McCain denied any connection between contributions from Paxson
and his action. He said he wrote the letter in his capacity as
chairman of the Senate Commerce Committee, which oversees the FCC.
And, he said, he has frequently clashed with the FCC's slow-moving
bureaucracy. In fact, the complex issue had been pending for more
than two years.
</P>
<P>
   But the harsher criticism of McCain was that he had been shown
to practice the same kind of politics _ acting on behalf of special
interests _ that he rails against at campaign events and is
pledging to eliminate if he is elected president.
</P>
<P>
   In the Paxson matter, McCain received $20,000 from Paxson and
its law firm, Dow, Lohnes &AMP; Albertson, which also represents The
Atlanta Journal-Constitution. He used a Paxson-owned plane the days
before and after his Dec. 10 letter to the FCC.
</P>
<P>
   OUTSPOKEN GORE AIDE RIPS REPUBLICANS ON RACE
</P>
<P>
   Gore came to the defense Friday of Donna Brazile, his
sharp-tongued campaign manager, over her comments about retired
Gen. Colin Powell and Rep. J.C. Watts (R-Okla.).
</P>
<P>
   ``The Republicans bring out Colin Powell and J.C. Watts because
they have no program, no policy,'' she said in a recent interview
with bloomberg.com. ``They play that game because they have no
other game. They have no love and no joy. They'd rather take
pictures with black children than feed them.''
</P>
<P>
   Watts said her comments were ``racist,'' while Powell said he
was ``disappointed and offended.'' Brazile, Powell and Watts are
African-Americans.
</P>
<P>
   Gore said she would continue in her job, even as he praised
Powell as a hero.
</P>
<P>
   Brazile has caused controversy before.In 1988, she quit
Democratic nominee Michael Dukakis' campaign after she told
reporters to check out rumors about President George Bush's
personal life.
</P>
<P>
   For in-depth reporting, opinion and cartoonists, visit the Cox
News Campaign 2000 Web site: http://www.coxnews.com/2000.
</P>
