<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-01-08 15:56 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A0406 &Cx1f; taf-z
u a BC-NY-MARRIAGE-DECLINE-5     01-08 1248
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-NY-MARRIAGE-DECLINE-545&AMP;ADD-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
FEWER NEW YORKERS, PAIRED OFF OR NOT, ARE TYING THE KNOT
</HEADLINE>
   (nk) 
 By JENNIFER STEINHAUER    
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ Marriage rates in New York City are at their lowest
levels since the era when the Bee Gees ruled the airwaves, Farrah
Fawcett sold her own shampoo and the first test-tube baby was born
in England.
</P>
<P>
   Economic incentives that make the single life attractive, a
dearth of twentysomethings and an increased social acceptance of
lives lived under one roof without a certificate are among the
chief reasons for the decline, sociologists say.
</P>
<P>
   The total number of marriages in the city fell 30 percent
between 1997 _ the only year in the last decade when marriage rates
soared _ and last year. The 1997 increase was due largely to
anticipated changes in federal immigration laws that sent thousands
on desperate trips to City Hall in an effort to gain proper legal
status. In the last few years, marriage rates in the city have been
at their lowest level since the late 1970s. In 1997, the rate per
thousand was 9.1; in 1999, it was 7.6, according to preliminary
figures.
</P>
<P>
   The New York statistics mirror a national trend: The rate per
1,000 Americans who married in 1998 was 8.3, the lowest since 1958,
when 8.4 people per 1,000 were wed.
</P>
<P>
   ``The baby boomers basically have all had their initial marriage
by now,'' said Tom Smith, who runs the National Opinion Research
Center at the University of Chicago. ``And we have a relatively
small pool of people in the prime ready-to-get-married age now,''
he added. That age is about 25; the number of births in the United
States declined 16 percent between 1965 and 1975.
</P>
<P>
   Money is a significant factor. Marriage may cause financial
strain for some couples, said Linda Waite, a professor of sociology
at the University of Chicago who recently wrote a book on marriage.
Low-wage earners often find that certain tax credits evaporate with
marriage, and some Medicaid recipients lose their benefits when
they marry someone who works, even at a low-paying job. Among
high-income workers, people bemoan what is known as the marriage
tax.
</P>
<P>
   On the flip side, at least one incentive for marriage _ health
insurance coverage through a spouse _ has waned. Many state
governments and private corporations now offer benefits to domestic
partners, often with very liberal definitions of a couple.
</P>
<P>
   But economic factors and even an increase in cohabitation do not
fully explain the steep downturn, Waite said, ``unless people are
cohabitating permanently, and then what you have is a big change in
the way we relate to each other.''
</P>
<P>
   Ben Speth, 36, who lives in Brooklyn with his girlfriend,
Rebecca Hilton, said that his way of relating pleased him just
fine.
</P>
<P>
   ``I will never be married,'' he said emphatically. ``That
doesn't mean I'll be a bachelor. I don't need the state's
imprimatur. It is enough for me to love and be loved.''
</P>
<P>
   The number of people who choose to live together rather than
marry has exploded in the last few decades. Among Americans born in
the 1970s, about 65 percent say their first live-in partner was not
a spouse. Among people born in the 1940s, the average was closer to
26 percent. Put another way, the number of people now cohabitating
is 7 percent of all American couples; in 1960, the figure was 1
percent, according to figures from the National Opinion Research
Center.
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   Pop culture reinforces the notion: Billy and Georgia, the
married couple in ``Ally McBeal,'' are splitsville. Over in
``Friends,'' Chandler and Monica are living in unwedded bliss, so
far.
</P>
<P>
   New York has always had the reputation of breeding intense
careerists who race from the office to the gym to the bedrooms,
where they scarf down a plate of penne with vodka sauce alone in
front of ``Nightline.'' But people all over the country have chosen
to marry later, if at all, after getting set in their careers.
</P>
<P>
   Cheryl Davis of Houston said that as a child, she always
imagined herself married by the time she was in her 30s. But after
a heartbreak in her mid-20s she turned her attention away from
dating and romance and toward building her career as a corporate
travel planner.
</P>
<P>
   ``My views went a different way,'' said Ms. Davis, now 33. ``I
decided to climb that corporate ladder.'' There were long hours and
lots of overtime. There has also been a boyfriend, whom she kept as
a ``comfort,'' she said, but never considered marrying.
</P>
<P>
   ``I would be disappointed if I never get married,'' Ms. Davis
said. ``But I am an independent person and I absorb a lot of the
family experiences through my own family.''
</P>
<P>
   She is clearly not alone: the number of people who applied for
marriage licenses in Houston last year was 23,987, a 23 percent
decline since 1995.
</P>
<P>
   Andrea McGinty, the chairwoman of It's Just Lunch, a dating
service with offices in 28 cities, said that most New Yorkers who
come to her office were hoping to expand their social circle beyond
clients and co-workers. But marriage is often far from their minds.
</P>
<P>
   ``People are not coming in here saying, `I've got to get
married,' or `My clock is ticking,''' Ms. McGinty said. ``Half of
the city was transplanted here for career reasons, so marriage is
not as big a priority for them as, say, for people in
Indianapolis.''
</P>
<P>
   Nadine Benaderet of Manhattan, a publishing account manager,
says that each decade of her life brings her a new reason for not
focusing on getting married. In her 20s, she was a professional
figure skater, which was all-consuming. ``In my early 30s,'' said
Ms. Benaderet, who is 38, ``I was more concentrated on me and
pulling myself together. I was reading books, doing touch therapy,
healing yoga, things for me. Then my father was sick, so he was the
focus.''
</P>
<P>
   She does not believe that any current relationship will result
in marriage, and that is just fine with her. ``I would like a
partner,'' Ms. Benaderet said, ``but not with the marriage tag.''
</P>
<P>
   Hundreds of studies in recent years have cited the health and
economic benefits of marriage, particularly for men.
</P>
<P>
   ``We have looked at well over 1,000 studies that overwhelmingly
show the strong and consistent relationship between marriage and
well-being,'' said Waite, whose book ``The Case for Marriage'' is
to be published by Doubleday.
</P>
<P>
   In studies, married people demonstrate stronger financial
stability, longer life spans, more active and satisfying sex lives,
less alcohol abuse and more sexual fidelity, Waite said. People who
live together do not rate nearly as high in these categories, she
said, and their relationships do not emulate marriage.
</P>
<P>
   ``Cohabitation is a different bargain than marriage,'' she said.
``Unless couples are engaged, they tend to be much less committed.
They are unlikely to have joint checking accounts. They are much
less likely to be faithful. They spend their leisure time
differently. It is not the same.''
</P>
<P>
   Is there something inherent in the New York dating experience
that prevents marriage? Ms. McGinty, whose dating service puts
people together for a single lunch date, leaving the rest to
nature, tried to put it gently. ``New Yorkers need to understand
that it is a date, not a negotiation, and that we need to bring our
manners with us. This is not an hour to interview someone. Being
able to turn off the workday and use this as personal time would
help.''
</P>
</TEXT>
