<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Hall might be nearing for Morris, Fisk, Perez
 &HT;    By Thomas Stinson
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ The Baseball Writers' Association of America, which
for much of the last decade guarded the gates to Cooperstown as if
protecting the tomb of Abner Doubleday himself, composed itself
last year and waved in a class of three new Hall of Famers last
January.
</P>
<P>
   That largess, which matched the total from the previous three
years, could well be equaled when the Class of 2000 is announced.
Whether the BBWAA remains so magnanimous remains to be seen. It
well could.
</P>
<P>
   A crop of 14 first-year eligibles, led by Jack Morris, joins a
list of 16 holdovers, including Carlton Fisk and long-suffering
Tony Perez, in comprising this year's ballot. While the BBWAA would
be pressed to reach much deeper than those three headliners _ so
sorry, Dale Murphy _ there is another trio banging for admittance.
</P>
<P>
   _ Morris: A five-time All-Star, he won more games than anyone
else in the '80s (162) and while he never won a Cy Young award, he
was in the top 10 seven times. No AL pitcher ever met more
scheduled starts (515) and his 2,478 strikeouts ranks 23rd all
time. He never got close to 300 wins, but his 254 total exceeds
more than half of the 58 pitchers now in the Hall.
</P>
<P>
   _ Fisk: Just 43 votes short (out of 497 ballots) of gaining
admittance in his first year of eligibility last year, Fisk clearly
belongs. Not only did he catch more major league games than anyone
(2,226), only Ty Cobb, Pete Rose and Rick Dempsey matched his 24
seasons as a major league position player. No catcher matched his
376 homers either.
</P>
<P>
   _ Perez: He's been denied eight years but the timing may be
right for a seven-time All-Star who ranks 18th all-time in RBI
(1,652) and is tied for 40th in home runs (379). He missed by 71
votes (14.2 percent of the electorate) last year.
</P>
<P>
   Up the track again is Murphy, a two-time MVP who was fourth
among first-year eligibles in 1999. But Murphy drew just 19.3
percent of the vote when 75 percent is needed, and how he closes
the gap will say much about his chances in subsequent years.
</P>
<P>
   ETC.
</P>
<P>
   Take what you might from the fact that Brian Goldberg, Ken
Griffey Jr.'s agent, just committed his client to filming several
in-uniform ads promoting the 2000 Seattle series. The flurry of
Mariners-Kansas City-Pittsburgh-Cincinnati rumors were made of thin
air. ``In all likelihood, it looks like he'll be back in Seattle,
and Junior's certainly fine with that,'' Goldberg said....
</P>
<P>
   What do Terry Adams, Dan Naulty and Gregg Olson have in common?
They will fill out Los Angeles' bullpen, which needs new meat. In
1999, Dodgers relievers ran up a 4.37 ERA and struck out the fewest
(299) and won the fewest (14) of any NL bullpen.... Cleveland's Jim
Thome wound up leading the league in both walks and strikeouts, a
feat unseen in the AL since Mickey Mantle in 1958....
</P>
<P>
   Tampa Bay's wooing of free agent Aaron Sele compounds the lie
that Devil Rays management told two months ago, when the club vowed
it did not have the money for good talent-hunting. If Sele signs
the $30-million, four-year deal the club pitched him last week,
D-Rays payroll in 2000 will soar from $37 million to somewhere
between $58-60 million.... The New York Yankees have functioned
without a club president since the mid-'80s, which explains the
confusion surrounding Randy Levine's arrival this week. The former
deputy mayor of New York, specially courted and signed by owner
George Steinbrenner, arrives without specified duties, although
since the team faces five possible arbitration cases (shortstop
Derek Jeter, closer Mariano Rivera, pitchers Ramiro Mendoza and
Jason Grimsley and catcher Jorge Posada), that's the logical place
to start. After that? Said a front-office veteran, ``This is a
classic George move.''
</P>
<P>
   2000 HALL OF FAME BALLOT
</P>
