<SLUG> BC-BKN-NOTEBOOK-MAGIC-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
DESPITE EXPECTATIONS, MAGIC IS DOING WELL
</HEADLINE>
   (With BKN-NOTEBOOK) 
(rk) 
 By MIKE WISE    
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   In the Orlando Magic's second game of the season, John Gabriel,
the general manager, watched his work-in-progress commit a string
of turnovers that had him genuinely worried. Standing in the tunnel
area underneath the arena, Gabriel looked toward the bench to see
how his new coach, Glenn ``Doc'' Rivers, was coping.
</P>
<P>
   ``We were throwing the ball out of bounds over and over,''
Gabriel said. ``All the assistants were sitting there, looking so
frustrated and disgusted. Then I looked at Doc. He had his head in
his hands. I realized then: physically, he's not looking sometimes.
That tells you all you need to know about him.''
</P>
<P>
   Intent on getting his players to buy into a system that involves
pushing the ball upcourt at every juncture, Rivers has resorted to
averting his gaze if it will help his team's patience and
perseverance.
</P>
<P>
   Less than halfway through the season, both qualities have
materialized under Rivers, the former Knick courted by many teams
in the off-season to take over their franchise in some manner. What
Orlando has done in less than a year approaches the amazing.
</P>
<P>
   A team predicted to finish in the Atlantic Division cellar _ the
team that traded four of its five starters (Anfernee Hardaway,
Horace Grant, Nick Anderson and Ike Austin) and received a bevy of
journeymen in return _ is pushing for better than a .500 season and
perhaps a playoff berth.
</P>
<P>
   What's more, the Magic is the only team other than the Chicago
Bulls with $10 million or more to offer free agents next summer.
Orlando also has three first-round draft picks, including one from
lottery-bound Golden State that could end up landing the Magic one
of the top three players in the June draft.
</P>
<P>
   Rivers has worked wonders with a collage of players who are not
all-stars. Eleven players on Orlando's roster average more than 15
minutes a game. The point guard Darrell Armstrong and power forward
Bo Outlaw have displayed a work ethic that has caught on.
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile, Hardaway is battling another injury in Phoenix,
Anderson is struggling during his worst season statistically in
Sacramento, and Austin, who played so well for Pat Riley in Miami,
has been benched in Washington. Grant has had a decent season thus
far in Seattle.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think we have to be the poster team for trading a guy a year
early than trading him a year late, when his value completely
falls,'' Gabriel said. ``We've set ourselves up pretty well, we
think. But much of it has been Doc. He talked me into some things I
didn't originally want to do.''
</P>
<P>
   Through a variety of wild trades and minimum-salaried players
signed up for training camp, the Magic at one time this summer had
34 players under contract. Rather than holding onto veterans like
Armen Gilliam, Tim Legler and Terry Davis, Rivers persuaded Gabriel
to keep young, hungry, athletic players like Chucky Atkins, Ben
Wallace and John Amaechi.
</P>
<P>
   ``He told me they would fit better into our style and he was
right,'' Gabriel said. ``I spoke to the fans before our first game
and asked them to be patient, that this isn't what they were used
to. Some people called it a plea. Whatever. I really felt like this
was a year we could rebuild.
</P>
<P>
   ``I looked at the depth-chart board of players in my office. I
asked some of our people, `Tell me in the East who doesn't think
they belong in playoffs.' You don't think Rick Pitino told his
owner they had a chance? You don't think Wes Unseld told Abe Pollin
we'll fill the building? It was so wide open, we just felt a team
of our makeup could play .500 in the conference.''
</P>
<P>
   More than just an uptempo style, Orlando has outworked many
opponents and caught several teams out of shape early in the
season. Shawn Kemp, for example, has been a nonfactor in two games
against Orlando. His burly frame and half-court game have no
purpose against the Magic.
</P>
<P>
   Gabriel gives most of the credit to Rivers. ``I've gained a far
greater respect for one's timing in coaching,'' he said. ``Not
necessarily Doc's, but just the fact when you're committed to a
style, you have to coach that style no matter what.
</P>
<P>
   ``Doc has not done this in a traditional fashion, letting
players make a lot of mistakes and going away from the traditional
NBA rotation of six or seven players. When he's wanted to
overinstruct, yell or pull back the reins, he hasn't. The
boundaries of that style are loose enough where guys are not
inhibited.
</P>
<P>
   ``I thought this was a rebuilding year, but we didn't bottom out
completely. Doc has been the glue in the process.''
</P>
<P>
   Gabriel added: ``One time I asked him about covering his eyes.
He told me, `Gabe, sometimes, I just can't look.' I told him, `Doc,
you're a better man than I am.'''
</P>
<P>
   nn
</P>
