<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Taking note of the NHL Eastern Conference
 &HT;    By Jeff Schultz
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _
</P>
<P>
   FROG-GATE
</P>
<P>
   It hasn't gotten the notoriety of John Rocker's mind melt _ at
least not this side of the Canadian provinces. But Ottawa center
Vaclav Prospal came under verbal fire after calling Montreal
defenseman Patrice Brisebois a ``frog'' _ a long-standing slur
against the French and French Canadians.
</P>
<P>
   It didn't help matters when high-profile agent Rich Winter,
rather than apologize for his client, referred to Brisebois as
``gutless and spineless'' and ``hiding behind his skirt.'' Winter
also said, ``He should have stood up like a real man and settled
this on the ice or in the back lot.''
</P>
<P>
   Yikes. The NHL ordered Prospal to attend diversity training,
which seems to be the in-thing these days. Prospal has apologized
to French Canadians but never mentioned anything about Brisebois.
About the diversity training, he said, ``I'll go to the meeting.
That's all I can say.''
</P>
<P>
   So much for repentance. Brisebois, who has clammed up since
initially complaining about the ``frog'' reference to reporters,
doesn't seem to be getting much sympathy, even from other French
Canadians. Edmonton's Georges Laraque, who is both black and a
Montreal native, said, ``Frog sounds more like a joke. I'm
surprised it's bothering him that much, because lots of French guys
have been called that and nobody complains.''
</P>
<P>
   BRIEFLY ...
</P>
<P>
   Updating the ever-changing prognosis on Florida goalie Trevor
Kidd (dislocated right shoulder): Kidd said he will start skating
next week and hopes to return in a month. So far, no surgery. ``I'm
not facing any shots, and I won't start facing breakaways the first
time I'm on the ice,'' he said. ``But I'm getting a brace next
week, and I'll take it from there.'' ... Pittsburgh general manager
Craig Patrick, when asked if rookie defenseman Andrew Ference might
be spared being reassigned to the minors: ``Anything's possible.
I've seen crazier things happen. Look at the poor guy who got the
flu when Lou Gehrig came in.'' ... Penguins prospect Milan Kraft
had seven goals in seven games and was named the top forward at the
recent World Junior Championships. He played for the Czech
Republic. ``Our plan is to bring him in next year,'' Patrick said.
...
</P>
<P>
   The biggest ovation at this year's All-Star Game in Toronto
figures to be reserved for an assistant coach, not a player.
Philadelphia coach Roger Neilson, who is battling cancer, will be
an assistant for the North American team. He formerly coached the
Leafs. ... Florida was 1-6-2 in its last nine games in California
after a 4-2 loss to Los Angeles on Thursday. ... Tampa Bay ended a
seven-game losing streak with a 3-3 tie in Vancouver. But the
Lightning gave up 36 goals in the seven games and continues to have
problems in goal. The acquisition of Dan Cloutier from the New York
Rangers was central to GM Rick Dudley's move on draft day, but
Cloutier and Kevin Hodson have been equally dreadful. ``(Cloutier)
and I both stink right now _ there's no other way to put it,''
Hodson said. ``We just stink, and there's no excuse for it. We need
to wake up.''
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
