<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-01-08 16:09 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A0411 &Cx1f; tad-z
u s BC-HKN-NHLFEATURE09-COX     01-08 0622
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-HKN-NHLFEATURE09-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Salt Lake is U.S. team's shot to get Games right
 &HT;    By Jeff Schultz
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ Of all the red, white and bruised, Ron Wilson had the
most reason to be bitter. He coached a star-laden team that many,
whether justified or not, projected as a group of gold medalists or
at least finalists.
</P>
<P>
   That same team fizzled, left Japan without gold, silver, bronze
or any other element, and sometime before passing through customs
wrecked a couple of dorm rooms. This was the great Olympic
experience? Fly halfway around the world, lose, then get labeled a
bunch of ``Animal House'' clones? Was that worth a 17-day break in
the NHL schedule?
</P>
<P>
   Yes, Wilson says. The NHL has yet to confirm its participation
in the 2002 Winter Olympics in Salt Lake City, although it appears
a foregone conclusion. It's one thing to put players through a
logistical nightmare in Nagano, Japan, and suffer through unwatched
3 a.m. telecasts back in the U.S. It's another to bypass the chance
for prime-time Games on American soil. Or ice.
</P>
<P>
   ``The NHL belongs in the Olympics,'' said Wilson, the Washington
Capitals coach who was behind the bench in Nagano but has yet to
hear from anybody regarding Salt Lake. ``The best athletes belong
in the Olympics. I don't see that there should be any discussion,
other than making the logistics of it better for all sides. As a
league, we need exposure and the best exposure you can get on an
international basis is the Olympic Games.''
</P>
<P>
   It irritates Wilson that the dorm trashings by undisclosed U.S.
player(s) _ three were reported to have been involved, but Wilson
says it was one _ are repeatedly brought up by the media and casts
all NHL players in an unfavorable light.
</P>
<P>
   ``The dorm thing, when did that happen? After the tournament,''
Wilson said. ``It had nothing to do with the tournament. Who did
it? The U.S. team did it. The Canadians didn't. The Russians
didn't. It came down to one guy doing something stupid. It didn't
come down to 65 NHL players trashing the village. We just paint
everybody with a wide brush, (saying players) didn't really want to
be there. Why? Because one guy got upset and didn't want to be
there and trashed the village. We look for excuses for everything
and there are no excuses. We went, we lost and we lost to the best
player in the world (Czech goalie Dominik Hasek).''
</P>
<P>
   Wilson said U.S. and Canadian hockey fans were right to expect
their countries to win the gold medal, but that those expectations
were a little too optimistic given the circumstances. There was a
reason, he said, that European teams fared better in Nagano.
</P>
<P>
   ``If you're going to have high expectations, you should have
time to prepare,'' Wilson said. ``Personally, I don't know how we
could go about it, unless we had a minicamp at the end of the
summer. At least you could get everybody together and talk about
things before (NHL) teams start their training camps. You'd have to
guess about who would be on the team and pick 25 or 30 guys. But
for the U.S., that's not hard to do. When we won the World Cup we
had three weeks to prepare for it. That's about how long NHL
training camps are. For the Olympics, we had two days.''
</P>
<P>
   Wilson admits Nagano ``was not the Olympic experience you dream
about.'' NHL players and coaches did not march in the Opening or
Closing Ceremonies. Travel was a blur. Salt Lake City would be
better in some ways, the same in others.
</P>
<P>
   As to the U.S.'s gold medal prospects in 2002: ``If we go to
Salt Lake City, we'll probably be one of the favorites again. But
that doesn't guarantee any success.''
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
