 &HT;    Amateur report
 &HT;    By Jeff Schultz
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ The most noteworthy thing to come out of the recent
World Junior Championships was the poor play of Swedish twins
Daniel and Henrik Sedin. They were the No. 2 and No. 3 picks in the
draft by Vancouver in June. The talented Swedish team did not win a
medal; the Czech Republic defeated Russia in the final, the same
result as the 1998 Olympics. Henrik finished first (13) and Daniel
third (10) in scoring in the tournament, yet scouts thought they
didn't stand out as much as expected. However, their performances
are not expected to have much significance. Canucks general manager
Brian Burke, who swung a series of draft-day trades to get into
position to draft the brothers, said: ``It's real simple: We don't
draft players on the basis of one week. Daniel was nursing a bad
leg. A lot of Swedish players didn't play well. From a development
standpoint, as a GM, I don't mind that they've been put in that
crucible. They'll be better pros for it.''
</P>
