<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Taking note of the NHL Western Conference
 &HT;    By Jeff Schultz
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _
</P>
<P>
   TKACHUK CHUCKS IT ALL
</P>
<P>
   The worst-case scenario is being realized in Phoenix. Center
Keith Tkachuk grew so weary of answering questions about his
near-trade to Carolina that he shut it down with the media, but not
before admitting the trade rumors are getting to him.
</P>
<P>
   ``I've been in this organization through a lot of lows,'' he
said. ``And now that I've been a part of building this hockey team,
it's just disappointing to hear you might have been traded. It's
hard to hear that, not to think about it every day you walk into
that rink that someday it could happen.
</P>
<P>
   ``I've got some friends who are helping me out, telling me to
try not to think about it. But it's tough not to think about it. If
I think about it too much, it's going to affect my play and I'll
play bad. But I've been in this league for nine years and I'm going
to try to approach it the best I can. I'm still a Coyote _ for
now.''
</P>
<P>
   Tkachuk missed five consecutive games with back spasms, then was
scoreless and a minus-two at Ottawa on Thursday. Phoenix doesn't
deny the star is being shopped because his salary balloons to $8.3
million next season.
</P>
<P>
   BRIEFLY ...
</P>
<P>
   Whatever happened to Edmonton's Alex Selivanov? After scoring 18
goals in his first 24 games, he went without a goal in the next 16.
``Relax, it's still early,'' he said. ... Phoenix has resumed
negotiations with holdout goalie Nikolai Khabibulin and, should a
deal be struck, likely would move backup Bob Essensa, who was
12-3-2 before suffering a recent groin strain. ... With Rem Murray
back from knee surgery, the Oilers might deal struggling forward
Joseph Beranek, who has only five goals in 37 games. ...
</P>
<P>
   Dallas is unbeaten in 20 straight against Los Angeles (14-0-6).
It's the longest current streak in the league, and one short of the
Stars' franchise record of 21 games, also against the Kings (while
in Minnesota). ... Ziggy Palffy's chronic lower back problems are
starting to become a concern in L.A. Coach Andy Murray said Palffy
isn't risking further damage by playing but added, ``He could use
three months off.'' ... Nashville's unbeaten streak finally ended
at eight games in a loss to Dallas, but GM David Poile said, ``Our
players are starting to believe they belong in this league.'' ...
Despite the streak, the Predators (35 points after 41 games) were
only slightly ahead of last year's midway total (32). ...
</P>
<P>
   Vancouver has won tthree times in the past six weeks (3-12-4)
and general manager Brian Burke is not a happy camper: ``I see a
lot of guys making a lot of money and not playing well.'' Sounds
like somebody is ready for another trade. ... Time for Colorado to
make a move: The Avalanche is 7-1-1 in its last nine home games,
where it plays six of its next seven. ... Detroit is 12-0-1 when
Pat Verbeek gets a point. His reaction? ``Doesn't mean a thing.''
... Red Wings goalie Chris Osgood allowed nine goals in his first
two starts after returning from a broken hand. ``I have difficulty
playing the puck,'' he said. ``I didn't expect to come back as a
world beater.''
</P>
