<SLUG> BC-CLINTON-ABORTION-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
CLINTON URGES DROPPING BAN ON FUNDING OVER ABORTION 
</HEADLINE>
  (js) 
 By MARC LACEY   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ President Clinton said Saturday that he would urge
Congress to reverse course on a law that he reluctantly signed just
months ago that bans U.S. money from going to international
organizations that perform abortions or promote abortion rights.
</P>
<P>
   Congressional Republicans insisted on the abortion language as
part of a spending package eagerly sought by the administration to
free nearly $1 billion that the United States owed to the United
Nations. The White House decision to compromise drew the wrath of
abortion rights advocates.
</P>
<P>
   Reaching out to allies on the issue, Clinton said in his radio
address that he would seek more than $200 million in his fiscal
2001 budget proposal for domestic and international family planning
programs and would urge Congress to end the anti-abortion
restrictions imposed on U.S. funds this fiscal year.
</P>
<P>
   ``I am asking Congress to support these funds, to provide them
without restrictions that hamper the work of family planning
organizations, and even bar them from discussing or debating
reproductive health policies,'' Clinton said.
</P>
<P>
   The president said he would advocate the largest increase in
domestic family planning services in more than two decades, a $35
million increase to boost spending to $274 million. The funds would
be shared by 4,600 clinics and pay for contraceptives, teen-age
pregnancy programs and health screenings, he said.
</P>
<P>
   Overseas, Clinton will propose a $169 million increase, to $541
million, in family planning services and related reproductive
health services. Under the deal to secure U.N. financing, the
administration accepted limits on the current allocation for
overseas family planning. Foreign family planning groups that
provide abortions or lobby for liberalized laws are now ineligible
for U.S. assistance. But Clinton has retained a waiver allowing him
to allocate up to $15 million in American aid to groups that offer
abortions or lobby for them.
</P>
<P>
   He indicated that his approach would best achieve the goal of
both sides of the abortion issue.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-01-08-00 1643EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT20000108.0166 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-01-08 16:48 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A0421 &Cx1f; taf-z
u a BC-IMMIGRANT-LITERATURE-     01-08 0998
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-IMMIGRANT-LITERATURE-ART-2TAKES-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
A NEW IMMIGRANT LITERATURE CONFRONTS THE AMERICAN DREAM 
</HEADLINE>
  (Eds: The title of the book in the 2nd graf is supposed to have a
star between each letter of the first and last names HYMAN KAPLAN.
The symbol is non-transmittable to many newspaper systems.) 
(ART ADV: Photos are being sent to NYT photo clients.
Nonsubscribers can make individual purchase by calling 888-603-1036
or 888-346-9867.) 
(mk) 
 By SUSAN SACHS   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ Once upon a time, the fictional immigrant to New York
City struggled mightily to master the New World and then to
assimilate.
</P>
<P>
   The prototype was the title character of the 1937 Leo C. Rosten
book, ``The Education of HYMAN KAPLAN,'' that indefatigably earnest
student of America who wrestled with the English language and
emerged from the tussle with his personality astonishingly intact.
</P>
<P>
   Who could not marvel at the adaptive abilities of this
Polish-born sweatshop worker to whom the plural of cat was
``Katz,'' the 16th president of the United States was ``Abram
Lincohen,'' and a verbal blunder was ``a sleeping of the tong''?
</P>
<P>
   Now, in a fresh burst of immigrant fiction and memoirs, another
generation of writers is plowing the fertile field where the new
arrival meets the New World. In dozens of books published over the
last decade, these young authors draw on their own experiences to
overturn the classic American tale of the immigrant's metamorphosis
from outsider to mainstream success.
</P>
<P>
   ``They introduce us to a world we should know better,'' said
Gilbert H. Muller, an English professor at La Guardia Community
College in New York who analyzed these writers for his book, ``New
Strangers in Paradise'' (University Press of Kentucky, 1999).
</P>
<P>
   Hyman Kaplan, creature of a more unquestioning time, might still
recognize himself in some of his 1990s literary counterparts, like
Lourdes Puente. A Cuban immigrant in Cristina Garcia's 1992 novel,
``Dreaming in Cuban,'' Lourdes enthusiastically tries to adapt by
embracing the conventions of her new country.
</P>
<P>
   She makes Jell-O molds with miniature marshmallows _ ``food only
people in Ohio eat,'' complains her daughter, Pilar. She never
misses a Thanksgiving Day parade, dreams of a Statue of Liberty
mural to decorate her Brooklyn bakery, and barbecues the family's
dinner whenever she can.
</P>
<P>
   ``Then we sit around behind the warehouse and stare at each
other with nothing to say,'' Pilar says. ``Like this is it? We're
living the American dream?''
</P>
<P>
   The younger woman's lament _ that becoming American is more
complicated for today's immigrants than just learning the language
and embracing the customs _ reverberates through the modern
literature.
</P>
<P>
   Success, the new authors argue through their writing, is no
longer measured in stages of assimilation. Nor is blending with the
white mainstream an option for those of African or Asian descent.
And, with images of real life in the United States part of
ubiquitous world culture, coming to the New World is no longer a
leap into the unknown or a naive quest for a gilded paradise.
</P>
<P>
   While the characters created by the European-born authors in the
first part of the century struggled against the impersonal and
alien pressures of American life, their fictional descendants take
all that for granted. They struggle, but in the more contemporary
sense. They search, as Muller put it, for ``wholeness.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Our world today is much more complicated than it was 100 years
ago,'' he said. ``We are far more mobile. We have more choices. We
slip in and out of various characters. Still, in one way or
another, the promise of America is validated by many of these
writers because their characters either discover themselves or
persist in the attempt.''
</P>
<P>
   The change is evident not only in the way immigrants are
depicted. It is clear from the texture of their experiences.
</P>
<P>
   Immigrants in the early part of the century, for example,
emerged from the dark steerage compartments of crowded ships into
the figurative blue skies of a new life. But, deliberately, no
purging ray of sunshine parts the clouds when a Chinese-born
engineer named Ralph Chang arrives in the United States in the 1991
Gish Jen novel, ``Typical American.'' Instead, New York City is
enveloped in fog. Ralph cannot see a thing.
</P>
<P>
   ``Some of the scenes that are hallmark momentous scenes in the
old literature are typically undermined and played with,'' said Ms.
Jen, who grew up in suburban Scarsdale, N.Y., and plumbs the
tragicomic adjustment of Chinese-American families to the New York
suburbs in her books. ``The earnestness of the earlier writing _
you know, the golden land and all that _ it's hard to write that
with a straight face in the 1990s.''
</P>
<P>
   In her books, the immigrant parents keep a certain distance from
the society around them even as they embrace its opportunities.
When they see something that seems particularly strange or hurtful,
Ralph and his relatives protect themselves by being dismissive.
``Typical American,'' they tell each other with a smug nod.
</P>
<P>
   But their Chinese-American children, born in New York and raised
in its upscale suburbs, eschew protective strategies because they
believe all options are open to them. In ``Mona in the Promised
Land,'' Ms. Jen's 1996 sequel, Ralph's daughter Mona decides to
become Jewish like her best friends in school. In her own quest,
Mona's older sister decides to become even more ethnic than her
parents by making the study of China her life's work.
</P>
<P>
   Their acculturation, in other words, is self-evident.
</P>
<P>
   ``This whole search for identity, this navel-gazing, is very
American,'' Ms. Jen, who is 44 and the daughter of Chinese
immigrants, said in a phone interview from her home in Boston.
``People in China don't talk about their roots. Once you start
thinking about what it means to be Irish-American or
African-American or Chinese-American, then you're American.''
</P>
<P>
   nn
</P>
<P>
   Then again, as she and other authors demonstrate in their
writing, plenty of immigrants today believe they cannot drop the
hyphen in their identities even if they wanted. They have a more
complicated relationship with the American dream than their
forebears had, especially the version that says everyone can
reinvent themselves in the New World.
</P>
<P>
   Irish and German and Italian and Russian immigrants of earlier
years could lose their accents and change their Old World clothing
and habits. They could eventually fit in _ or if they could not,
their children could _ and camouflage their roots.
</P>
<P>
   The literature reflected this: The tension was over how much had
to be sacrificed on the road to Americanization.
</P>
<P>
   In ``The Rise of David Levinsky,'' the 1917 immigrant classic by
Abraham Cahan, the protagonist progressively breaks his religious,
political and family ties and achieves business success. In the
books of Anzia Yezierska, like the overwrought ``Salome of the
Tenements,'' the main characters eagerly liberate themselves by
shedding all vestiges of the past.
</P>
<P>
   No more.
</P>
<P>
   ``I write because it was so painful growing up as an immigrant
and never really feeling I belonged,'' said Meri Nana-Ama Danquah,
an essayist who immigrated from Ghana to the United States with her
parents at the age of 6. ``As an immigrant, if you are of color,
you are marginalized. If you are white, you are pulled into the
mainstream.''
</P>
<P>
   She recently edited a collection of essays called ``Becoming
American,'' to be published in February by Hyperion. In it, 23
immigrant women write of both their disdain for American culture
and their grudging appreciation for the freedoms it grants them.
</P>
<P>
   Ms. Danquah, now 32, said she wanted to give a voice to what she
called ``displaced'' immigrants like herself, who do not fit
familiar American categories.
</P>
<P>
   ``For me, as a black immigrant, there was this assumption or
expectation that I would fit neatly into black America,'' she said.
``I resented the implication that we were the same people, because
we weren't.
</P>
<P>
   Mei Ng, who grew up in Queens, explores the classic literary
theme of estrangement between immigrant parents and their children.
Like other writers of her generation _ she is 33 _ she also expands
it to take in feelings of ethnic and racial alienation.
</P>
<P>
   ``Now I write about what it means to be hyphenated, with one
foot here in a place they wouldn't have me,'' she said. ``America
is a melting pot and all, but people sometimes say in a fit of
annoyance or anger, `Go back where you came from.' And I'm, like,
OK, I'll go back to Queens.''
</P>
<P>
   To survive such blows, some of the modern literary immigrants
develop their own camouflage.
</P>
<P>
   Henry Park, the Korean-American narrator in Chang-rae Lee's 1995
novel ``Native Speaker,'' is a master of disguise in both his
professional and personal lives. Speaking English is presented as
subversive and a method for dissimulation.
</P>
<P>
   Henry is a shadowy industrial spy who helps ruin an
up-and-coming Korean-American politician, thanks to his ability to
slip into a new identity as easily as a silk shirt. He is, perhaps,
the ultimate displaced person, the best proof that assimilation is
an irrelevant theme for many of today's writers.
</P>
<P>
   ``The way my characters think of it, they are part of and
consider themselves part of, what's new in America,'' said Lee, who
is 35 and lives in New Jersey. ``It's not that that's this heroic
stance. It's just that with the new sense of multiculturalism in
this country, people are starting to suggest what being an American
really is.
</P>
<P>
   ``The old immigrant would say, `I'm becoming an American,''' he
continued. ``The new person is now starting out saying, `I am
American.'''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
