</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Being sidelined not easy for Hardaway
 &HT;    By Jeffrey Denberg
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ Having missed 20 games with a jammed right knee
heading into the weekend, Heat guard Tim Hardaway still has no idea
when he will be back.
</P>
<P>
   On Dec. 22, Hardaway told TNT's Craig Sager he would be out
another month, then said later he was joking.
</P>
<P>
   Heat coach Pat Riley will explore trading for another point
guard if Hardaway's condition is still in doubt shortly before the
Feb. 24 trade deadline.
</P>
<P>
   ``We have to know by six weeks, five weeks,'' Riley said. ``By
then, I think we will know whether we have to go in that
direction.''
</P>
<P>
   Is Hardaway confident enough to tell Riley not to pursue outside
options?
</P>
<P>
   ``He has to do whatever makes him feel secure,'' Hardaway said.
``He has to look out for the future. It's just him being cautious.
He's edgy like I'm edgy.''
</P>
<P>
   GUARDING THE PARQUET
</P>
<P>
   The old parquet floor is still costing the Celtics. The wood is
under 24-hour guard and has been insured for $6 million. That led
one employee to crack, ``They ought to consider burning it. They'll
make more money off the insurance than they'll make off selling the
pieces.''
</P>
<P>
   WHAT BIRD WANTS
</P>
<P>
   Larry Bird says he will not coach after this season, but would
consider staying with the Pacers in management. Bird explains,
``It's like coaching. If you have coaches you work well with, it
makes your job a lot easier. It's the same thing in the front
office. If you have people you can't work with, it's a waste of
time. I don't care about running a franchise, talking to agents,
doing contracts. But ...putting the best team together that you
can, that's very appealing.''
</P>
<P>
   NOT SO SURA
</P>
<P>
   Bob Sura has had a particularly bad stretch. He got a double
technical foul (with Ray Allen) for a dust-up in Milwaukee, then
another technical late at Boston for mocking referee Marc Davis
after Davis finally gave him a call. Sura tried to call a timeout
the Cavs didn't have at the end of their loss to Sacramento with
Chris Webber staring in disbelief. Webber never lived down his
brain-lock timeout call in a national championship game at
Michigan.
</P>
<P>
   ``I screwed up,'' Sura said, refusing to hide.
</P>
<P>
   THE NEW VAN GUNDY
</P>
<P>
   Allan Houston scored 26 of his 37 points in a 96-88 victory over
the Celtics in the second half. Performances like that will help
coach Jeff Van Gundy with his New Year's resolution to be more
upbeat. ``This is the new me,'' he said. ``I am not dour. I am
upbeat. I want you guys to document each of my smiles, which will
be aplenty. Losses, wins, they're all the same.''
</P>
<P>
   LAYUPS
</P>
<P>
   Sherman Douglas could be lost to the Nets for the season. The
backup point guard has a lesion on his left ankle that will require
surgery. ... Eddie Jones, who had Olympian aspirations, on Ray
Allen, who got the spot he coveted: ``You know something? I'm
happy. If it had been somebody else, maybe I might be a little
bitter. Because it's Ray, I'm really happy and I don't hold
anything against him.''
</P>
