<SLUG> BC-BKN-NBAFEATURE09-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Shape up, Mavericks
 &HT;    By Curtis Bunn
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ A Dallas Mavericks season-ticket holder who bought the
team last week promised a series of moves that will change the face
of the club. And that face has been pretty ugly lately.
</P>
<P>
   Mark Cuban, a Mavs fan who happens to be the founder of
Broadcast.com, paid Ross Perot Jr. $280 million for the club and
promises to be a proactive owner similar to the Dallas Cowboys'
Jerry Jones.
</P>
<P>
   That means bad news for Don Nelson, the coach and general
manager who has compiled a two-year record of 44-102 going into the
weekend and who has shipped away, among others, Jason Kidd, Jamal
Mashburn, Sam Cassell, Jim Jackson, Chris Gatling, Oliver Miller,
George McCloud, Derek Harper, Samaki Walker and A.C. Green.
</P>
<P>
   In return, the Mavericks got Shawn Bradley, among other busts.
So, Cuban has made it clear Nelson is in the final days of his
coaching career in Dallas and could be bought out of the GM
position, too.
</P>
<P>
   Cuban can afford it. The 41-year-old bachelor with no kids
started his company four years ago. Yahoo bought him out last
summer for $6 billion. He recently purchased a 24,000-square-foot
home for $16 million. Cuban also owns a $40 million jet.
</P>
<P>
   As an owner, he plans to be free with his money a la Portland's
Paul Allen and to form relationships with his players like
Philadelphia's Pat Croce.
</P>
<P>
   As a fan, he has seen the mess that the club has become under
Nelson, who had designated his son, Donn, as his successor at coach
after this season.
</P>
<P>
   Cuban has put the kabosh on that. After meeting with Cuban, the
elder Nelson said, ``It's not going to happen. . ... It's probably
best that (Donn Nelson) get a chance somewhere else.''
</P>
<P>
   Since firing coach Jim Cleamons after one season, Don Nelson has
compiled a .301 winning percentage while securing Dallas' place as
one of the league's worst situations. His courtside conduct also
has drawn unwanted attention. Thursday, he was ejected from a game
engaged in a bumping match with an opposing player _ the Jazz's
Karl Malone.
</P>
<P>
   When Nelson met with Cuban on Wednesday, he came out saying, ``I
feel very secure at this particular time. But if somebody wants to
make a change, then, you know, that's part of life. If I'm part of
the change, I think that's fine, too. If that's best for the
franchise, I'll accept that and go along my way.''
</P>
<P>
   Nelson made similar comments when he coached the Knicks in 1996
and was fired the next day. Cuban is less hesitant to run off
Nelson now because he's not comfortable with bringing in an interim
coach.
</P>
<P>
   Cuban is developing a short list of coaching prospects. He'll
likely add former Mavericks guard Derek Harper to the front-office
staff.
</P>
<P>
   He insisted his primary interest is the team on the court, not
the business side of things as Perot's was. Cuban wants results.
He's seen enough from his baseline seat as a fan to realize the
Nelsons will not get the results he wants. So starts Cuban's NBA
legacy.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
