<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Mourning not 'Zo angry anymore
 &HT;    By Curtis Bunn and Jeffrey Denberg
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ Once, Alonzo Mourning was an NBA pariah, a player the
league least wanted to represent it on a national stage. The Miami
Heat center was a brazen, disobliging bully who seemed to carry and
express perpetual anger.
</P>
<P>
   Over the past few years, the former Georgetown star has had an
ephipany of sorts. He realized that being a jerk took more energy
than being a nice guy. Since then, Mourning's personal growth has
coincided with his professional rise.
</P>
<P>
   And the NBA has taken notice. It could not be more evident than
in USA Basketball's selection of Mourning to the 2000 Sydney
Olympic Games squad.
</P>
<P>
   This for a player who helped personify the anti-American
sentiment in the 1994 World Championships in Toronto when he, among
others, put on a display of sportsmanship that embarrassed the
league.
</P>
<P>
   Mourning also seemed to go out of his way to be a media
adversary, using intimidation tactics when presented with tough
questions.
</P>
<P>
   Now, he's an NBA darling.
</P>
<P>
   ``Alonzo has matured a great deal since then,'' said NBA vice
president Rod Thorn, head of the selection committee. ``I think
he's way beyond that.''
</P>
<P>
   Indeed, Mourning rehabilitated his reputation by abandoning the
us-against-the-world posture and uncovering a well-spoken,
even-tempered gentleman. Since then, he's been the best center in
the Eastern Conference.
</P>
<P>
   ``It is nice for the Olympic committee to put whatever happened
in the past,'' Mourning said. ``I do what I can to better myself.''
</P>
<P>
   GET THIS
</P>
<P>
   The Indiana Pacers are the only team in the NBA with two players
who jumped directly from high schools to the NBA.
</P>
<P>
   Recently, Al Harrington and Jonathan Bender addressed an
Indianapolis public school full of students who wanted to hear
their words of wisdom, which were ... stay in school.
</P>
<P>
   Despite the advice, both players contend they are happy with
their decisions to make the quantum leap.
</P>
<P>
   JUMAINE IN THE HALL
</P>
<P>
   Former Georgia star Jumaine Jones has huge aspirations, but not
even he expected to make the Basketball Hall of Fame as a
Philadelphia 76ers rookie.
</P>
<P>
   But that's what happened. The Sixer played in the last game of
the 1990s and Jones scored the final basket of the1900s _ a 3-point
bank shot.
</P>
<P>
   So, the 76ers were asked to provide Jones' uniform and shoes for
display in the Hall.
</P>
<P>
   ``I wasn't aware they wanted my stuff,'' Jones said, ``but when
they said they did, I said, `Oh, really?' I didn't call for it to
be a bank, but it was.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think anyone on the court would've been likely to make the
last one, but it was me. Good things come to those who wait.''
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
