<SLUG> BC-FBN-JETS-COACH-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
BELICHICK SOLUTION IS PROBABLY CLOSE BY
</HEADLINE>
   (With FBN-LIPSYTE-COLUMN) 
(nk) 
 By GERALD ESKENAZI   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   The feud is taking on proportions worthy of historical
conflicts: Bill Parcells makes a move, Robert K. Kraft summons his
minions in Boston to quell this guy from New Jersey.
</P>
<P>
   But in interviews with people familiar with the latest dispute
between the Jets and the Patriots, it seems clear that this episode
will end with the Jets letting former coach Bill Belichick join the
Patriots _ in exchange for some draft picks.
</P>
<P>
   Here is how it is likely to play out:
</P>
<P>
   Monday, the Jets will give the NFL their reply to Belichick's
claim that the team is preventing him from making a living. NFL
Commissioner Paul Tagliabue will then take another look at the
contract he already has ruled is valid _ and again conclude that
Belichick's services belong to the Jets. At that point, Tagliabue
will sweetly suggest that this can be settled if the two sides use
common sense.
</P>
<P>
   Amid all of this, Parcells is trying to keep together a Jets
team he believed could have made a Super Bowl run in the 1999
season. He knows that if he steps outside the organization for
another head coach, everything is changed. His most likely move is
to appoint Al Groh, the linebackers coach, as the new head coach _
unless the new owner, who is to be announced this month, is happy
only with Parcells as coach.
</P>
<P>
   Kraft, the Patriots' owner, does not want to wait either; he has
already interviewed three candidates for the vacant head coaching
job.
</P>
<P>
   Fairly quickly, then, the Patriots will make an offer to the
Jets.
</P>
<P>
   Still, this could be sticky for a few days. Don't think the Jets
have forgotten that they paid the Patriots handsomely in 1997 to
allow Parcells out of a contract he thought had been in his favor.
Tagliabue arbitrated that dispute and gave the Patriots a total of
four draft picks over three years, including this past season's
first-round selection.
</P>
<P>
   The Jets also gave the Patriots their first- and third-round
draft choices in 1998 as part of their deal to sign running back
Curtis Martin away from New England. In all then, the Jets have
lost six draft picks to New England in three seasons.
Interestingly, none of those has developed into a starter for the
Patriots. Belichick, though, would be the ultimate first-stringer
if Kraft is able to hire him as coach and general manager.
</P>
<P>
   So what is Belichick worth in draft choices? If the Jets were
speaking publicly, they would say ``four draft picks over three
years.''
</P>
<P>
   In New England, though, people are muttering that the Jets
orchestrated all of this. They know that the day the regular season
ended, Parcells notified both Belichick and Jets' president Steve
Gutman he was quitting, a move that made Belichick the Jets' head
coach, since his contract called for his ascension when Parcells
stepped down. The suspicion of those who see this from the
Patriots' point of view is that Parcells had learned that the
Patriots were going to try to hire Belichick. By stepping down
before they could do so, Parcells thought he could keep Belichick.
</P>
<P>
   There are those on the Jets' side who believe that New England
had somehow made it known to Belichick that as soon as Pete Carroll
was dismissed as Patriots coach, Belichick would be offered the
job, along with the general manager's post _ more power than he
would have had with the Jets.
</P>
<P>
   However it happened, Belichick was Jets coach for a day _
shorter than his previous tenure. Remember February 1997? For six
days he was the coach while the Jets were trying to hire Parcells
away from the Patriots by naming him as a ``consultant.'' In theory
he would hang around for a year, until his contract was up, and
then become coach. Soon, though, the Jets parted with the draft
picks that allowed them to make Parcells the head coach
immediately.
</P>
<P>
   Now, three years later, Belichick is trying to reverse the
process, this time contending that his contract with the Jets was
not valid. One of the points his lawyer, Neil Cornrich, makes in
the eight-page grievance he filed with the NFL office is that
Belichick signed it with Jets owner Leon Hess, but that Hess died
shortly after.
</P>
<P>
   ``Does that mean,'' asked a person with knowledge of the
contract, ``that when Leon Hess died all the Jets became free
agents, too?''
</P>
<P>
   There is another twist to this situation. A person familiar with
Belichick's contract contends that the Patriots can make him a
``consultant,'' as the Jets did with Parcells.
</P>
<P>
   According to this scenario, Belichick could be hired by the
Patriots in this vague capacity, but not as a coach or general
manager. The problem with this is that Belichick has three years
remaining on his Jets contract. That is a long time to be the
ruler-in-waiting. In football these days, it is a lifetime.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
