<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-01-08 16:58 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A0428 &Cx1f; taf-z
u a BC-Y2K-SURPLUS-SPAM-NYT &LR;      01-08 0869
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-Y2K-SURPLUS-SPAM-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
PLENTY OF Y2K SUPPLIES READY FOR A REAL DISASTER 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ATTN: N.J., Wash., Calif., Ga.) (js) 
 By TINA KELLEY   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   When New Year's Day arrived with no sign of millennial mayhem, a
lot of people found themselves with more jugs of water and cases of
Dinty Moore stew than they could possibly use in peacetime.
</P>
<P>
   But unwilling to admit defeat _ or embarrassment _ many of those
people say they have no regrets, and are now ready for whatever
sundry disasters _ natural or otherwise they could face between now
and the expiration dates on their dehydrated carrots.
</P>
<P>
   Worried that his water would stop flowing, John Pfuelb, 56, had
dug a six-foot hole in his backyard, in full view of his suburban
neighbors in Clinton, N.J. Now, he said, he has to fill it back in.
He said he devoted an hour a day to his preparations for the
breakdown of the world's computers, even though his family thought
he was nuts.
</P>
<P>
   He also had to put up with teasing from his co-workers, who made
up a mock cover of ``Y2K for Dummies'' with his picture on it.
``The kidding was unbelievable,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   But Pfuelb said he figured that if Fortune 500 companies were
worried enough to spend hundreds of millions of dollars preparing,
his $2,000 investment in supplies and food made sense.
</P>
<P>
   ``There's an old expression: `I'd rather have it and not need
it, than need it and not have it,''' said Pfuelb, an advertising
salesman who works out of his home. ``I thought we were looking at
something kind of serious here, and I don't regret it.''
</P>
<P>
   In retrospect, he said, he learned a lot about food and water
filtration, and has decided that time away from the television
might be good for his family, even if electricity continues to
reach his home.
</P>
<P>
   He figures he will eventually eat three-quarters of the food,
and plans to donate the rest to charity.
</P>
<P>
   J. Candy Arnold, 53, wrote a cookbook, ``Y2Kitchen,'' to help
people prepare for the millennium.
</P>
<P>
   Some people might say the cookbook was out of date as soon as
the clock ticked 12:01 on New Year's morning. But Ms. Arnold thinks
she can still fill a need. The book, which includes recipes for
healthful meals that can be prepared during times of crisis, will
be renamed for use in natural and man-made disasters.
</P>
<P>
   Ms. Arnold, who lives near Seattle, estimated that she spent
$1,500 on her preparations for emergency supplies, including
solar-powered flashlights, radios and lights, two 55-gallon drums
full of water, and a three-month supply of dehydrated and canned
food. She also installed a wood stove in her mobile home.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think I'm an example of a person who hasn't gone
overboard,'' she said, adding that the food and other supplies she
bought could easily be used on camping trips.
</P>
<P>
   If the Internet is any reflection of day-to-day consumer trends,
survival gear can be had cheaply now, for a variety of
nonmillennial purposes. Saturday on eBay, the online auction
service, bidders vied for a Y2K Hand Water Pump, which the seller
said ``would make a nice landscape piece. Easily painted to make it
fit your color scheme.''
</P>
<P>
   A Y2K solar oven, which had attracted no bidders Saturday
afternoon, was called ``great for camping, fishing, outdoor
parties, or just trying it out for fun.''
</P>
<P>
   After the disaster-free arrival of the new year, many of the
well prepared said they considered themselves ready for the the
next catastrophe to come along: a winter storm, hurricane or
earthquake.
</P>
<P>
   Paul Poduska, president of First Millennium, an e-commerce
startup company, had put together an emergency checklist for the
turn of the year, posted at www.baat.com. He has decided to
continue it, modifying it for other kinds of potential disasters.
</P>
<P>
   ``God help California if there were an 8.0 earthquake,'' he
said. ``My house would slide down two blocks. But these things can
be prepared for.''
</P>
<P>
   Debbie Osborne, 29, a public relations executive in Atlanta,
stocked up on imported sauces and other ingredients that she and
her husband rely on for the Mexican dishes they like to eat.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think that it's always wise to take preparations for this,
or for any winter storm that might come along,'' said Ms. Osborne
Saturday, adding that she had no regrets about stocking up.
</P>
<P>
   ``We would certainly do it again,'' she said, ``should we be
around at the next millennium.''
</P>
<P>
   Throughout history, a number of common reactions have been seen
to false apocalyptic prophecies, said David Kessler, executive
administrator for the Center for Millennial Studies at Boston
University. They include simply shifting doomsday back a bit.
</P>
<P>
   ``With Y2K, it would be very difficult to redate,'' Kessler
said. So many people are just redirecting their preparations toward
other disasters.
</P>
<P>
   He harked back to the biblical tale of Jonah, who, after being
swallowed by the whale, emerged to warn Nineveh to change its evil
ways or risk disaster. The citizens repented and nothing terrible
happened.
</P>
<P>
   ``People look at Jonah and say he was wrong, not `Oh, we're so
happy he warned us,' but `He was wrong,''' Kessler said. ``What's
going on in Y2K, you could call it a Nineveh syndrome.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
