<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-OUTDOORS-HUNTING-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
OUTDOORS: THE YIELD OF A GORGE IN NEW HAMPSHIRE 
</HEADLINE>
  (mk) 
 By NELSON BRYANT   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   WENTWORTH LOCATION, N.H. _ ``Come with me to Hellgate Gorge,'' I
said to my companion, Ruth Kirchmeier, and borrowing from
Christopher Marlowe, I continued, ``where we will all the pleasures
prove that hills and valleys, dales and fields, woods or steepy
mountain yields.''
</P>
<P>
   Hellgate Gorge, located on the Dead Diamond River at the north
end of Dartmouth College's Second College Grant _ 27,000 acres of
wilderness _ in the rugged northeast tip of New Hampshire, was
short on dales and fields, but had, I knew, no lack of woods and
steepy mountains, and I believed that Ruth would be pleased by
them, and by the log cabin above the gorge that is always filled
with the moaning of the river as it pours through the gorge,
burnishing and sculpting the ledges.
</P>
<P>
   Ruth acquiesced, although knowing full well that in addition to
my desire for us to spend a little time alone together was my
equally compelling urge to go deer hunting.
</P>
<P>
   The past decade, having become accustomed to venison in the
freezer year-round, whether from Anticosti Island in the Gulf of
St. Lawrence or from the river bottoms and flat agricultural lands
of northern Minnesota, I found myself well into November with no
deer hunts in sight.
</P>
<P>
   Miscalculations and happenstance were responsible for this. I
had planned a hunt with my sons on our newly acquired land in Maine
and had canceled a trip to Minnesota because of that. But a visit
that I made to the Maine holdings during a snowy, wet and cold week
in October revealed that the cavernous lodge on that property
couldn't be adequately heated for winter hunting. Then I came down
with the flu.
</P>
<P>
   My friends, including my brother, each got a deer in Minnesota.
A few weeks later, Ruth and I were on our way to New Hampshire.
</P>
<P>
   There was a trace of snow when we drove up the logging road that
runs for about 11 miles along the Dead Diamond from the Grant's
Gate Camp to Hellgate Gorge. The temperature was in the teens, and
there was ice along the edges of the river and in its oxbows.
</P>
<P>
   At the Gate Camp I had learned from the Grant's caretaker,
Lorraine Turner, that Put Blodgett of Lyme, N.H., had a party of
eight at Merrill Brook cabin, which is about halfway up the road to
Hellgate. Over the years, the Blodgett clan always included Put's
uncle, Pete Blodgett of Dover, Mass. Pete, who hunted the Grant
over a span of more than 70 years, died this summer in his late
90s.
</P>
<P>
   I also learned from the deer log at the Gate Camp that, with
only four more days of the deer season left, 17 deer had been taken
from the Grant since the season opened on Nov. 10.
</P>
<P>
   Ruth and I arrived at the Hellgate Gorge cabin shortly after
noon on Dec. 2 and spent most of the remaining daylight hours
getting our gear inside and setting up camp, lugging water from the
river and kindling a good fire in the wood stove. She immediately
succumbed to the magic of the place and as the light was dying made
a few sketches of the river rushing through the gorge while I
turned on the gas lamps and set about preparing supper.
</P>
<P>
   The weather turned around that night. The temperature rose to
above freezing, and save for brief periods we never saw the sun
again during our remaining three days.
</P>
<P>
   Early on, Put Blodgett and his oldest son, Peter, paid us a
visit. They then departed to hike up to Hellgate and Lamb Valley
Ponds. They were the nonhunting members of their party. Once a
dedicated hunter, Put quit about a decade ago and now gathers
hardwood burls, from which he fashions bowls, and there were
several of them in the back of his pickup. But two members of his
group had already taken deer, his youngest son, Boo, getting a
six-pointer of 140 pounds on Dec. 4 and Dave Clements shooting a
five-pointer of 110 pounds on the same day.
</P>
<P>
   Ruth doesn't hunt, but I took her on a hike to Finnson's Ledge
the following afternoon. I wanted her to see the view over the
river valley from that sheer cliff and reasoned that the two
remaining days would provide ample time for me to get my deer while
she poked about with her sketch pad.
</P>
<P>
   I was wrong. Fog draped the hills and there were times when I
couldn't see 75 yards through the woods. At one point after
wambling through a dense stand of young spruces on my way uphill to
a hardwood ridge, I put up a moose, and the cover was so thick all
that I saw was a big patch of black hide 40 feet away.
</P>
<P>
   Although I encountered no deer, their signs were plentiful. When
we left the Grant, I checked the deer log at the Gate Camp and
learned that the Blodgett party had scored a third time, with Mark
Clements shooting a 10-pointer that weighed 180 pounds.
</P>
<P>
   Put Blodgett later told me that in a last-ditch effort to bag a
deer on the final morning, Mark and his brother Dave were driving
along the logging road between Merrill Brook and Hellgate when they
saw what they first thought was a snag floating down the river. A
few seconds later, they realized that the branches of the snag were
the horns of a splendid buck. It went out of sight around a bend.
They drove downstream to get ahead of the animal. Pressed by the
need for speed, Mark grabbed a single cartridge and his rifle and
ran down through the woods to the river. The big animal had emerged
from the river on the opposite shore and was headed into the woods.
Mark fired his one shot, killing it instantly.
</P>
<P>
   The young men then waded the icy river _ more than waist deep at
that point _fully clothed to get the deer and drove back to Merrill
Brook cabin, where they poured the water out of their boots, dried
their clothes and reveled in their success.
</P>
<P>
   In the decades that I have hunted here I have always scanned the
river and its gravel bars while driving along the logging road, but
the only mammals I have ever spotted were beaver, mink and moose.
Perhaps, I mused, it would be more rewarding to become a hunter of
burls.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
