<DOCTYPE> MISCELLANEOUS TEXT (slug-filter) </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-01-08 17:11 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A0433 &Cx1f; taf-z
u s BC-FBN-NOTEBOOK-1000&AMP;ADD     01-08 1244
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FBN-NOTEBOOK-1000&AMP;ADD-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
WILLIAMS AND SAINTS PLAY THE BLAME GAME 
</HEADLINE>
  (mk) 
 By MIKE FREEMAN   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   New Orleans running back Ricky Williams is considered one of the
most easygoing players in the NFL. But on the telephone last week,
he sounded miserable, even angry. It's understandable. He went
through the Saints' terrible three-victory season. He said he was
treated poorly, at times, by coach Mike Ditka, and it turned out
that his rookie contract with the Saints was so one-sided in favor
of the team that he might try to restructure it.
</P>
<P>
   Ditka traded all of the New Orleans draft choices to get
Williams, but then completely misused the Heisman Trophy winner
once he put on a Saints uniform, so it cannot be said that Williams
was sorry to see the coach fired along with general manager Bill
Kuharich. Indeed, Williams feels change at the top was desperately
needed.
</P>
<P>
   ``This was the worst year of my life in terms of football,''
Williams said. ``I think every player probably felt that way. This
season was a horror story. No question about it.''
</P>
<P>
   Ditka's stint with the Saints will be remembered as one of the
more pathetic in the organization's history, which is rich in bad
times. New Orleans went 3-13 this past season, matching the
second-worst mark in franchise history, and in his three years as
head coach, Ditka was 15-33, including 6-23 in his last 29 games.
Under Ditka, the Saints lost 14 consecutive road games.
</P>
<P>
   No one endured the brunt of the losing like Williams, last
year's first-round pick out of the University of Texas. Ditka
traded the team's eight 1999 draft choices, and the No. 1 and No. 3
picks in 2000, to get Williams. Their relationship started on a
good note, but it became strained in the end, and it was Williams
who began receiving the blame, probably unfairly, for the team's
fortunes.
</P>
<P>
   Williams said fans, teammates and even some coaches and front
office personnel transferred their misery over the losing season to
him, since the franchise had given up so much to get him.
</P>
<P>
   ``I didn't ask coach Ditka to trade all of those picks for me,''
Williams said. ``But I think he blamed me for how bad the season
went. But coach Ditka has to look at himself.''
</P>
<P>
   Toward the end of the season, Ditka publicly admonished Williams
for being overweight and out of shape. ``Once I missed a meeting
and was late for practice one morning,'' Williams said. ``He sat me
down and said I was letting the team down, and also that I did not
want to play hurt.''
</P>
<P>
   Williams added: ``I made some mistakes. And coach Ditka is not
going to like this, but he made mistakes, too, and he treated me
really unfairly. I played hurt most of the year, almost all of the
time. For him to say I didn't was not true. With coach I always
felt like he wanted to overuse me as a way of proving that the
trade was the right thing to do. I wasn't treated like a person. I
was treated like a piece of property.''
</P>
<P>
   Ditka could not be reached for comment but said after his firing
that he understood it. ``You're 3-13, you have the expectations we
do, you bring in Ricky Williams, and it doesn't work out,'' Ditka
said at a brief news conference. ``I mean, we've got to be
realists.''
</P>
<P>
   Williams also expressed resentment over his contract situation.
Williams used an agent inexperienced in making NFL deals, and he
negotiated one of the worst contracts a rookie has signed in 10
years. The main problem with the seven-year, $57.3 million deal is
that much of the money is tied up in practically unreachable
clauses. Williams did receive an $8.84 million signing bonus, but
as the contract now stands he must run for 1,600 yards in each of
the next three seasons _ something that no back in NFL history has
done _ or he will never get most of the $57.3 million.
</P>
<P>
   Williams said many of his teammates resented the fact that he
signed a contract that was so one-sided toward the team. ``I think
a lot of players on the team don't respect me,'' he said. ``It all
started with my contract. It's obvious that because of the problems
with my contract, it hurt my chances of making money. I think a lot
of players looked at me as ignorant or naive.''
</P>
<P>
   Williams said he planned to address the contract with the
Saints, although he would not say exactly how, or if he was
considering hiring a new agent. ``I am definitely going to fix some
things with my deal,'' he said. ``I think the team should fix it,
but I don't know if they will. I'm not going to hold out. But I did
do the contract so I could get on the playing field quickly. The
team took advantage of that.
</P>
<P>
   ``To me, it's sad what happened with my contract. I played
through pain, did the right thing, and I get very little monetarily
for it. There are other players on this team who did not do half of
what I did and got paid a lot more.''
</P>
<P>
   One of Ditka's biggest mistakes was how he used Williams. While
Williams does possess a power running style, he is also a good
receiver out of the backfield, and has enough speed to get outside
on end runs.
</P>
<P>
   At Texas, Williams was the complete back, but in New Orleans,
Ditka mostly ran Williams up the middle, and he was rarely asked to
catch the football. One NFC West defensive coordinator, who twice
drew up game plans against the Saints, said: ``Put Williams on a
team with a coach who knows how to use him, and Williams gets 1,300
or 1,400 yards rushing a season easy. And he wouldn't be hurt as
much.''
</P>
<P>
   Since Williams was mostly pounded up the middle, his body took
the maximum amount of punishment possible, which led to a number of
injuries, including ankle problems. Williams finished with 884
yards rushing and two touchdowns.
</P>
<P>
   ``Mike just saw me as a guy to stuff up the middle down after
down,'' Williams said. ``I was drafted because in college I did
everything. But suddenly here I was being limited.''
</P>
<P>
   There is no question that Williams is still considered a premier
back, and there is speculation that several teams may inquire about
a trade for Williams once the Saints hire a general manager.
</P>
<P>
   But Williams wants to succeed in New Orleans. ``I want to be a
part of turning this thing around,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Shuffling Out of Buffalo?
</P>
<P>
   Only several days before their playoff game at Tennessee,
quarterback Doug Flutie and receiver Andre Reed of the Bills each
voiced displeasure with the organization. Flutie remains angry at
being benched in favor of Rob Johnson, and Reed is bothered by his
diminished role.
</P>
<P>
   Neither player is likely to be back next season, as the Bills
will look to younger players. But Flutie and Reed are only part of
what could be a rapid facelift across pro football.
</P>
<P>
   In one off-season, Barry Sanders could leave Detroit, Jerry Rice
and Steve Young could leave San Francisco, and Miami might trade
Dan Marino.
</P>
<P>
   Griese's Ailment Revealed
</P>
<P>
   One of the most startling physical feats this year was
accomplished quietly by Brian Griese, the Denver Broncos
quarterback who played much of this season even though the
cartilage in his throwing shoulder was basically torn in half.
</P>
<P>
   ``When the surgeon got in there, he said, `Oh, my gosh, I can't
believe this guy played with this,''' said Denver's trainer, Steve
Antonopulos.
</P>
<P>
   Griese is expected to recover from the surgery in several
months. Despite the injury, Griese played better as the season
progressed and he should be the starter next year.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-01-08-00 1711EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
