<SLUG> BC-NY-COMMERCIAL-REAL-1185(3TAKES)-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
REAL ESTATE: FOR NEW YORK LANDLORDS, IT WAS A VERY GOOD YEAR 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ATTN: N.J., Conn.)  (lb) 
 By JOHN HOLUSHA   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ Thomas Falus, president of Cushman &AMP; Wakefield's New
York metropolitan area operations, put it simply: ``1999 was the
best year of the 25-plus years I have been in real estate.''
</P>
<P>
   A booming national economy, a stock market that soared through
the year and the rapid growth of companies related to the Internet
have increased demand for office and retail space in the region,
and the prospect, real estate executives say, is that the good
times will continue.
</P>
<P>
   The average vacancy rate for Class A office properties in
midtown is about 6 percent, with space all but unavailable in some
locations, and average asking rental rates for new leases are close
to $55 a square foot a year.
</P>
<P>
   The figures vary in other parts of the region, but the trend is
the same: there is less space available and what is on the market
is getting steadily more expensive.
</P>
<P>
   Most real estate executives say there is nothing on the horizon
to prevent this year from being as good as the one just past, at
least from the landlords' point of view.
</P>
<P>
   Employment is rising, they note, and there is little risk of
overbuilding, since all the construction projects now under way,
such as the full-block Bear, Stearns headquarters on Madison Avenue
between 46th and 47th streets, and the Reuters building at Seventh
Avenue from 42nd to 43rd streets, had a principal tenant signed up
before a shovel went into the ground.
</P>
<P>
   Construction has begun to pick up again, after falling to nearly
nothing in the mid-1990s. According to Cushman &AMP; Wakefield,
1,477,631 square feet of new office building was completed in 1999
compared to just 112,000 square feet the year before. The big real
estate services company reported that an additional 3,292,689
square feet was under construction during the year, but this is
still small compared with the 9,028,767 completed in 1987.
</P>
<P>
   New construction aside, the search for space is driving some
clients to former industrial properties on Manhattan's far west
side, and others to the waterfront in Jersey City, where developers
cannot build fast enough to satisfy eager clients.
</P>
<P>
   Of course, conditions that favor landlords mean difficult times
for tenants, who find their choices diminished and costs rising.
``There may not be any clouds in the sky for owners, but if you are
a space user there are plenty of clouds and they are dark and
stormy,'' said Michael Cohen, the president of Williams Real Estate
Co., a brokerage concern.
</P>
<P>
   But amid the general ebullience, some real estate executives
warn that history has demonstrated that the industry is cyclical
and what is up now can come down fast.
</P>
<P>
   ``If you look back 50 years in New York real estate, you will
see that the market is an unbroken sine wave with a period of eight
to nine years,'' said Peter Hauspurg, the chairman of Eastern
Consolidated Properties, referring to the up and down nature of the
mathematical expression. ``We are 11 years into the current period,
so something is coming soon. It's different every time, but it will
probably be the equivalent of the savings and loan crisis.''
</P>
<P>
   The insolvency of many savings institutions in the 1980s
prompted the government to dump large amounts of property on the
market, greatly depressing prices. Hauspurg noted that the value of
property in New York fell 60 percent from 1989 to the bottom in
1993 before recovering by last year.
</P>
<P>
   One economic sector that some identify as a possible danger zone
is Internet-related companies, which include those writing software
and offering electronic services, news and advertising. They have
been among the fastest-growing employers in the city, many doubling
in size annually. This has helped lessen New York's traditional
dependence on financial services, which has shown only modest job
growth despite the soaring stock market.
</P>
<P>
   But many of the Internet-related companies are start-ups, with
no current earnings and no prospects of profitability any time
soon. Most are living on funding from venture capitalists or stock
offerings and many are burning through that financing rapidly as
they seek to dominate market segments by growing quickly.
</P>
<P>
   No one is suggesting that the Internet is going away, but some
real estate executives fear that if some prominent companies fail,
markets could sour on the whole industry, cutting off its source of
cash. A rash of bankruptcies could put a lot of office space back
on the market with a depressing effect on rental rates.
</P>
<P>
   ``As we look out for risks in 2000, that is No. 1 on the list,''
said Steve Kohn, a managing director at Sonnenblick-Goldman, a real
estate investment banking company. ``They are not generating their
own cash flow and they are burning through what they have at a fast
rate. Most only have enough cash for 16 to 18 months.''
</P>
<P>
   The large number of Internet-related companies is inflating
demand for professional services as well as building materials and
trades, said Anthony Malkin, president of W&AMP;M Properties, a real
estate management and development company.
</P>
<P>
   ``These guys are spending a lot of on architects, accountants,
lawyers as well as on wiring, hardware and installation,'' he said.
``But it looks as though it is an industry that will have a few
winners and a lot of losers. So when it shakes out, there are going
to be vacancies by the companies themselves and vacancies by the
service providers.''
</P>
<P>
   But others say these companies are occupying space in outlying
areas of Manhattan that are not attractive to mainstream companies.
``They are on the fringe, in Chelsea, Ninth and 10th Avenue and
downtown,'' said Stephen Green, the chairman of S.L. Green Realty,
a real estate investment trust that owns 9 million square feet of
older office space, mostly in midtown.
</P>
<P>
   He acknowledged that Internet companies can be precarious
tenants, since they are dependent on securing outside financing.
``We recognize that if the capital spigot dries up they are not
operationally profitable,'' he said. ``We take some high-tech
tenants, but not many. They are well under 10 percent, probably in
the 5 to 6 percent range.''
</P>
<P>
   Other landlords and property managers also speak of limiting the
concentration of Internet-related companies, but those companies
have certainly become an important factor in some parts of the
city.
</P>
<P>
   According to figures compiled by Insignia/ESG, a real estate
services company, fully one-third of the leases signed last year in
Midtown South were by Internet companies or the telecommunications
firms that support them. But in midtown they only accounted for 4
percent of leases, and were at the 10.5 percent level downtown.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is not a short-term phenomenon, and we are going to have
to learn to deal with it,'' said David Levinson, an executive
managing director of Insignia/ESG. ``Think about the cut-and-sew
operations that used to be in the Garment District. They were not
credit tenants,'' he said, referring to companies with more than
enough financial resources to make lease payments. ``My view is
that we're replacing them with tenants that manufacture software.''
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE _ OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   nn
</P>
<P>
   Regardless of how they are regarded by landlords, these new
companies are preoccupied with growth. Since they need people to
fuel that growth they are willing to do what it takes to find the
space to put those employees.
</P>
<P>
   Doubleclick Inc. and ActBig.com are both Internet-related
companies, but they are at opposite ends of the spectrum.
</P>
<P>
   Doubleclick, which supplies services to advertising agencies and
tracks the effectiveness of advertising, has successfully sold
stock to the public. With financing in hand, its solution to having
people spread over six floors in two buildings in Midtown South was
to move the whole operation to the west side.
</P>
<P>
   The company leased 150,000 square feet at 450 West 33rd St., at
10th Avenue, a property that included the old Sky Rink space on the
top floor. In addition to consolidating all New York employees at
one location, Kevin O'Connor, the chairman of the company, said,
the column-free space was built out to burnish the company's
new-media image.
</P>
<P>
   ActBig.com is a start-up that tries to increase the purchasing
power of consumers by pooling orders electronically. It is in
sublet space in the rear of the third floor of a building at 222
Fifth Ave. between 26th and 27th streets.
</P>
<P>
   Fifteen people are crammed into three small offices, with boxes
piled up between the desks and chairs. Stephen Tsai, the chief
executive, said the critical need was to find more space on terms
that are tolerable to a start-up company that closed its first
round of financing last July 1.
</P>
<P>
   ``We have to map our space needs with our finances,'' Tsai said.
``This is the right space for a start-up, and we need another short
stop until the next round of financing.''
</P>
<P>
   He said that another sublet would avoid draining the company's
capital into the large deposits being demanded by some landlords as
the condition of signing a lease with young companies lacking
established credit. But sublets are hard to find because those who
currently have extra space often decide to keep it for their own
growth.
</P>
<P>
   With the company hiring at the rate of a person a week, finding
more space has become urgent. ``It has become a huge part of my
day-to-day operations,'' Tsai said.
</P>
<P>
   He said that some landlords are seeking to use the shortage of
space as a means of investing in the Internet. ``Some of them want
to use real estate as investment currency,'' Tsai said. ``They will
exchange space for a piece of your company.'' To avoid having to do
this, he said, the company was now willing to sign a lease.
</P>
<P>
   Midtown
</P>
<P>
   Rents Still Rise, Tenants Still Eager
</P>
<P>
   Leonard Stern, the chairman of Hartz Mountain Industries had a
floor come vacant recently in the tower of the lavishly appointed
building the company owns overlooking Central Park at 667 Madison
Ave. at 61st Street.
</P>
<P>
   ``The tenant asked us to take back the space on Monday,'' he
said. The next morning, ``At 8:30 Tuesday, a broker showed up with
a tenant and by 8:40 we shook hands on a 10-year lease at $95 a
square foot for the first five years and $100 a square foot for the
second five years.''
</P>
<P>
   Later in the day another prospective tenant offered $100 a
square foot annually for all 10 years, he said, and later in the
week another offered $110 a square foot for 10 years. Stern said he
was going to stick with the first tenant.
</P>
<P>
   That is the way it was in midtown office market, particularly in
well located buildings with the right amenities. Average annual
asking rents in such buildings are pushing closer to $60 a square
foot, with $70 to $75 a square foot not uncommon, brokers said.
</P>
<P>
   Since most real estate executives say rents over $70 a square
foot financially justifies new construction, some projects are
expected to go forward, although the scarcity of sites suitable for
building is expected to limit their number.
</P>
<P>
   ``New York needs a speculative building or two,'' said Kevin
Haggarty, the executive managing director of Insignia/ESG's capital
advisers group. ``There's nothing to worry about; they would lease
up without trouble. There's not enough sites in the city to
overbuild if we wanted two.''
</P>
<P>
   Stern said rental costs were not a significant factor to the
boutique money management firms that have broken away from the big
Wall Street companies. ``Our floors are 7,700 square feet,'' he
said. ``You can manage $2 billion in that amount of space, so rent
is not an onerous cost for them.''
</P>
<P>
   Downtown
</P>
<P>
   Apartment Developers Think Commercial
</P>
<P>
   Downtown continues to be a lower-cost alternative for companies
reluctant to pay midtown rates. The vacancy rate in Class A
buildings fell to 7.7 percent near the end of the year, while Class
A asking rentals have reached almost $37 a square foot annually.
</P>
<P>
   These rising rents have been changing the plans of property
owners in the area. ``A lot of would-be residential developers are
reconsidering their plans,'' said William Cohen, an executive vice
president of Newmark &AMP; Company Real Estate. In the early part of
the decade, when older office buildings were declared functionally
obsolete and doomed to stand empty, conversion to residences seemed
the only opportunity to realize value from them.
</P>
<P>
   But the rising rental rates _ even Class B buildings can command
$27 a square foot annually _ are changing the economics of those
conversions, he said. ``Residential rents approximate $42 a square
foot, but it costs 40 to 50 percent more to do residential than
commercial,'' Cohen said. ``When you can get $27 a foot with a 3
percent compounded annual escalation, most people are leaning
toward staying commercial.''
</P>
<P>
   One good example of this trend is the building at 48 Wall St.,
the former headquarters of the Bank of New York. ``That building
was held vacant for residential conversion,'' said Michael Cohen of
Williams. ``But it is not being converted. It is going to be used
for offices.''
</P>
<P>
   He said that as demand for office space continues to outstrip
supply this year more of the older buildings concentrated downtown
would become candidates for upgrading for modern tenants.
</P>
<P>
   nn
</P>
<P>
   Building Sales
</P>
<P>
   Prices Recover After Late '98 Decline
</P>
<P>
   Prices of buildings in New York recovered last year, after
declining in late 1998 because of the turmoil in capital markets in
the fall of that year, sales brokers reported.
</P>
<P>
   ``Prices peaked in the summer of 1998 and then fell back,'' said
Warren Heller, managing director of Jones Lang LaSalle's investment
banking group. ``But midtown has recovered back to the highs of the
1980s, although downtown is two years behind.''
</P>
<P>
   He said the outlook for pricing this year is firmly connected to
the direction of rents. ``It is difficult to see any case where
rents do not grow,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   The number of sales fell last year compared to 1998, said
Hauspurg of Eastern Consolidated. ``The number of transactions
declined, although pricing remained strong,'' he said. ``The people
who wanted to be sellers have sold.''
</P>
<P>
   There is plenty of capital available to finance purchases, said
John Lyons, executive managing director of Granite Partners, a real
estate investment banking firm. But, he said, higher prices for
properties have meant lower returns, and some of the money raised
to buy real estate was not invested.
</P>
<P>
   ``In 1999, opportunity funds raised approximately $30 billion to
invest in real estate,'' he said. ``Some of it went overseas, but a
lot of capital stayed on the sidelines.''
</P>
<P>
   He said funds that had returns of 30 percent to 40 percent in
years past were reluctant to invest for a 20 percent return on
their capital. And he said there might be a burst of sales activity
early this year as transactions that were postponed in the fourth
quarter of 1999 for fear of computer problems begin to close.
</P>
<P>
   The Suburbs
</P>
<P>
   New Jersey Market Is the Most Active
</P>
<P>
   The waterfront in Jersey City, N.J., is filling up and brokers
predict that sites well inland from the Hudson River are the next
target for development. Meanwhile, the consolidation of the
pharmaceutical industry in New Jersey is filling up buildings and
causing the start of new projects in Morris and Somerset counties.
</P>
<P>
   New Jersey is the most active market in the metropolitan area,
with some speculative construction under way on Long Island, N.Y.,
and lesser levels of activity in Westchester County, N.Y., and
Fairfield County, Conn.
</P>
<P>
   ``The waterfront will be filled in soon by people moving from
New York,'' said Franklin Speyer, executive director of Cushman &AMP;
Wakefield of Northern New Jersey. ``The demand is double for what
is being planned to be built over the next two years.''
</P>
<P>
   He said that the definition of the waterfront market would
expand, with areas several blocks away from the water becoming
development sites as long as they are conveniently located in
relation to the PATH trains that are the vital link to Manhattan.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're in full development mode,'' said Emanuel Stern, the
president of Hartz Mountain and the son of Leonard. He said the
company is building 70 Hudson St., a 410,000-square-foot
speculative office building in Jersey City and the 205-room TriBeCa
Grand Hotel in Manhattan, and is rebuilding the Chart House
Restaurant at the end of a pier in Weehawken, N.J. It is also, he
said, working on plans for Waverly Yards, a 65-acre mixed-use
development near Newark Airport in New Jersey.
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile, the merger of Hoechst and Rhone-Poulenc to form
Aventis Pharmaceuticals last year is prompting the construction of
two 310,000-square-foot buildings at SJP Properties' Somerset
Corporate Center in Bridgewater, N.J. The first is expected to be
ready for occupancy in the first quarter of 2001 and will be the
company's North American commercial headquarters.
</P>
<P>
   Earlier, Aventis leased 340,000 square feet in SJP's Morris
Corporate Center in Parsippany, N.J., as an interim headquarters.
</P>
<P>
   On Long Island, Reckson Associates Realty Trust is building a
speculative 277,000-square-foot office building in Melville that is
scheduled to be completed this fall. Mitchell Rechler, the co-chief
operating officer of the real estate investment trust, said that
pre-leasing, often a must to get financing in New York City, is
rare on Long Island.
</P>
<P>
   ``We have built over 4 million square feet of property on
speculation,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   The market in Fairfield County in Connecticut remained tight,
with a 10.4 percent vacancy rate at the end of the third quarter.
The vacancy rate in nearby Westchester remained considerably higher
at 16.2 percent, which real estate executives said was the result
of the abandoning of hard-to-divide headquarters buildings by large
corporations.
</P>
<P>
   Retail
</P>
<P>
   Prime-Area Rents Hit New Highs
</P>
<P>
   Rents in prime shopping areas of the city hit new heights last
year, according to Faith Consolo, vice chairman of Garrick-Aug
Associates, a brokerage company specializing in retail properties.
``On Madison Avenue between 57th and 72nd Street, rents went up to
$700 a square foot, and for new properties in 2000 they are asking
$1,000 a square foot,'' she said.
</P>
<P>
   Ms. Consolo said that $100 a square foot was the minimum today
in almost any area of Manhattan, but that some property owners were
in danger of pricing themselves out of the market because retailers
paying high rents have difficulty earning profits.
</P>
<P>
   Alan Victor, an executive vice president of Lansco Corp., said
some retailers have grown resistant to demands for higher rents
from landlords. ``It is getting tougher to make deals,'' he said.
``The market has gotten tighter everywhere on Madison, Fifth Avenue
and SoHo.''
</P>
<P>
   This has led some retailers to move into areas once considered
off the beaten track. ``Chelsea is a big play right now,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Hotels
</P>
<P>
   Occupancy Steady, Room Rates Up
</P>
<P>
   Occupancy rates at New York hotels declined in the first half of
1999 compared with the previous year, but picked up in the second
half to close at 82.4 percent, just a 0.4 percent decline from
1998, according to figures compiled by PricewaterhouseCoopers, the
accounting and consulting firm.
</P>
<P>
   The average daily rate for hotel rooms increased 3.9 percent to
$200.96 during the year, but the increase was well below the 10.6
percent and 11 percent increases in the previous two years.
</P>
<P>
   The highest-priced hotels may see a falloff in occupancy this
year, said Sean Hennessey, director of the firm's New York
hospitality practice. ``At the upper levels,'' he said, ``New York
is priced out of the market for the common guy.'' Average room
rates in the deluxe segment, which includes the Four Seasons and
the Pierre, are $408 a night, he said, while those in the luxury
segment, covering hotels such as the Waldorf and the Plaza, have
been averaging $266 a night.
</P>
<P>
   Several new hotels are scheduled to open this year, including a
Doubletree on 41st Street between Seventh and Eighth avenues, a
Sofitel at 45 West 44th St., and an Embassy Suites in Battery Park
City.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
