<HEADLINE>
TOP STRATEGIST FOR POLICE JOINS FORCE IN BALTIMORE 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ATTN: Md.)  (lb) 
 By WILLIAM K. RASHBAUM   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ Edward Norris, the deputy police commissioner who has
helped oversee New York City's crime-fighting strategies for the
last three and a half years, is leaving his post to take a senior
position with the Baltimore police force, officials said last week.
</P>
<P>
   Norris, who joined the New York Police Department in 1980 and
was appointed to the civilian post of deputy commissioner for
operations in April 1996, will be the No. 2 official in the
Baltimore department, said Marilyn Mode, the deputy commissioner
for public information in the New York department.
</P>
<P>
   He will be replaced by Inspector Garry McCarthy, who commands
the 70th Precinct in Brooklyn, said Police Commissioner Howard
Safir. To hold the title of deputy commissioner for operations,
McCarthy is required to take a leave of absence from the uniformed
service.
</P>
<P>
   Norris' primary responsibilities were advising Safir on
anti-crime strategies and coordinating the program that holds
commanders accountable for crime in their precincts and boroughs.
</P>
<P>
   Last spring, Norris, 40, blamed the news media for a rise in the
city's homicide rate, contending that negative news coverage of the
Police Department had so intimidated officers that they were
reluctant to patrol aggressively and that their reluctance had led
to an increase in killings. Norris singled out the coverage in The
New York Times, although he did not cite specific articles. His
statement was generally viewed as reflecting Safir's sentiments.
</P>
<P>
   Last week, Safir praised Norris, calling him ``a very smart
young strategist who has a real sense of what strategies result in
crime reductions.''
</P>
<P>
   Norris was a protege of Jack Maple, who oversaw the department's
crime strategies until he resigned in April 1996, and Louis
Anemone, the brash former chief of department.
</P>
<P>
   His career took off in 1994, under William Bratton, the police
commissioner at the time. During Bratton's tenure, Norris was
promoted rapidly, jumping three ranks from his position as a
lieutenant commanding a detective squad to deputy inspector in
about three years.
</P>
<P>
   After Safir became police commissioner, he promoted Norris to
deputy chief in 1996 and to deputy commissioner later that year.
Norris' Police Department salary is $126,951.
</P>
<P>
   Norris would not comment, and Baltimore police officials and a
spokesman for Martin O'Malley, the mayor of Baltimore, would not
discuss Norris' new position.
</P>
<P>
   Norris will be chief of department under the new police
commissioner of Baltimore, Ronald Daniel, a department insider who
was named to that post last month and is awaiting confirmation by
the Baltimore City Council.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-01-08-00 1736EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
