<DOCNO> NYT20000108.0181 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-01-08 17:38 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A0442 &Cx1f; taf-z
u s BC-FBN-BILLS-TITANS-NYT &LR;      01-08 0965
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FBN-BILLS-TITANS-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
TITANS SHOCK BILLS, 22-16, ON `MIRACLE' LATERAL 
</HEADLINE>
  (mk) 
 By THOMAS GEORGE   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NASHVILLE, Tenn. _ Time stood still at Adelphia Coliseum
Saturday afternoon. The clock was stuck at the final three seconds
for what seemed like three days. The referee, Phil Luckett, had his
head stuck in a replay booth, a few Buffalo Bills had their worried
heads stuck in their hands and more than a few Tennessee Titans
looked for intervention _ divine, miraculous, lucky or otherwise _
to save their season.
</P>
<P>
   And then it happened.
</P>
<P>
   The most divine, miraculous, lucky play of the season. Luckett
said it was good.
</P>
<P>
   A kickoff gathered by Tennessee with 16 seconds left in the
game, handed to another player, lateraled to another and then
swoosh! A 75-yard kickoff return for a touchdown that counted.
</P>
<P>
   A Tennessee play called Home Run Throwback.
</P>
<P>
   Yes, after Luckett finally trotted back onto the field, the
clock still said 0:03 as he said that the return was indeed good,
that the lateral was legal and that the Titans had won, 22-16,
eliminating the Bills from the playoffs and, finally, turning
history kindly toward the Tennessee franchise.
</P>
<P>
   The Tennessee Titans used to be the Houston Oilers, and in 1993
they lost a playoff game, 41-38, at Buffalo, where the Bills'
staged one of the most dramatic comebacks in the history of pro
football _ a 32-point comeback.
</P>
<P>
   This one was just as sweet for Tennessee (14-3), and especially
for the record crowd of 66,782.
</P>
<P>
   ``I am so proud of our team, our fans, our franchise,''
Tennessee coach Jeff Fisher said. ``This was something special.''
</P>
<P>
   Divine, miraculous and lucky, too.
</P>
<P>
   Buffalo (11-6) entered the fourth quarter trailing by 12-7 and
then scored with 11 minutes 8 seconds to play on Antowain Smith's
1-yard run. Buffalo's 2-point conversion attempt failed, and the
Bills led, 13-12.
</P>
<P>
   But then Tennessee's Al Del Greco kicked a 36-yard field goal
with 1:48 left to give the Titans a 15-13 lead.
</P>
<P>
   No matter. Steve Christie of Buffalo topped that, connecting on
a 41-yard field goal with only 16 seconds left to give Buffalo a
16-15 lead. The Bills certainly looked like winners. What could top
that?
</P>
<P>
   How about a kickoff that was gathered by Lorenzo Neal near the
Tennessee 25 and was then handed to Frank Wycheck? He ran toward
the right side of the field and lateraled the ball back to Kevin
Dyson. Dyson took off with a convoy of blockers and Buffalo was
completely fooled. Dyson ran 75 yards into the end zone and it was
over.
</P>
<P>
   Or was it? Three seconds remained. Instant replay took a look.
Was the lateral legal or was it a forward pass?
</P>
<P>
   Luckett looked.
</P>
<P>
   Divine, miraculous, lucky.
</P>
<P>
   Tennessee moves on.
</P>
<P>
   The teams played through a scoreless first quarter, testing each
other in formation, run schemes, pass protection, blitz packages
and by continually searching for weaknesses. The Tennessee offense
struggled early _ it did not gain a first down until the final
seconds of the quarter. In the quarter, Titans quarterback Steve
McNair was 2 of 7 passing for 11 yards, with 10 of those yards on
one pass. Buffalo managed only three first downs and 51 yards.
</P>
<P>
   With 7:50 left in the first quarter, Tennessee blew the game's
first chance for a score. Jevon Kearse had ripped around right end,
stripped the ball from quarterback Brad Johnson in the pocket and
sacked him. Tennessee linebacker Barron Wortham fell on the ball at
the Buffalo 39. But the Titans offense could move only 3 yards in
three plays, which set up Del Greco's field goal attempt from 43
yards. It sailed wide left.
</P>
<P>
   Kearse decided in the second quarter that what the offenses
could not do, he would do. He would score.
</P>
<P>
   Buffalo began a drive at its 4 with 12:08 left in the half.
Johnson fumbled the snap, tripped on a lineman's leg while running
into the end zone and then found Kearse about to pounce on him near
the back of the end zone. Kearse pounced and the ball fluttered
from Johnson's hands and through the back of the end zone. With
11:19 left, Tennessee gained a 2-0 lead on its first safety since
the franchise's 1979 season.
</P>
<P>
   The only offensive scoring drive of the half ensued.
</P>
<P>
   The Buffalo free kick after the safety was gathered by Titans
returner Derrick Mason, who sped up the middle and through the
heart of the defense for a 42-yard return to the Buffalo 28.
Tennessee's big plays in its five-play drive were Eddie George's
9-yard run around right end to the Buffalo 2 and McNair's 1-yard
no-huddle bootleg scoring run. With 7:55 left in the half,
Tennessee took a 9-0 lead.
</P>
<P>
   Buffalo kept tripping over itself in the first half.
</P>
<P>
   Johnson was poor (5 of 12 for 64 yards) and hurried (five
Tennessee sacks). The Bills rushed for only 30 yards and did not
gain a first down in the second quarter. Buffalo also committed
nine penalties for 44 yards while Tennessee committed none.
</P>
<P>
   The penalties hurt the Bills' chances. Del Greco tried a 45-yard
field goal for Tennessee, which missed left as the first half
expired, but Buffalo was penalized for holding on the play. Del
Greco gained another chance with no time left on the clock and
converted from 40 yards, giving the Titans a 12-0 halftime lead.
</P>
<P>
   For the half, Tennessee led in plays (38-27) and in possession
time (17:18 to 12:42).
</P>
<P>
   Buffalo needed the game to turn: It required a dramatic change.
</P>
<P>
   At the start of the third quarter, Smith dashed 44 yards to the
Titans' 18. Smith later scored on a 4-yard run and suddenly _ no
doubt after a Bills halftime locker room full of introspection and
in-your-face challenges _ Buffalo trailed by just 12-7 three
minutes into the third quarter. And that score held as both teams
entered the fourth quarter.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
