<SLUG> BC-RUN-NEW-BALANCE-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
JACOBS AND CARROLL TOP MILERS
</HEADLINE>
  (nk) 
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ Regina Jacobs of California and Mark Carroll of
Ireland left the Armory Track and Field Center in Upper Manhattan
on Saturday with a lot more money than when they arrived.
</P>
<P>
   Jacobs and Carroll won the women's and men's elite miles in the
New Balance Games _ and the $12,000 each that came with them.
</P>
<P>
   Jacobs, the silver medalist in the 1,500 meters last year at the
world championships, ran a sizzling 4 minutes 21.79 seconds, which
shattered the previous meet record of 4:31.96 set by Sinead
Delahunty last year. Delahunty was second Saturday in 4:30.41.
Jacobs took the lead with three laps to go and ran away from the
field with a 64-second last quarter. Her winning time is the
second-fastest run indoors by an American woman. Mary Slaney has
the fastest time of 4:20.5.
</P>
<P>
   Carroll earned his money the hard way. The 28-year-old
Providence College graduate, captured the men's Elite one-mile run
in a sparkling 3:54.98 Saturday. The victory earned him $10,000 for
breaking the meet record of 3:56.85 and another $2,000 for winning
the race.
</P>
<P>
   Richie Boulet, the defending champion who set the previous
record last year, finished second in the race in 3:57.00 with Paul
McMullen, an Olympian out of Eastern Michigan University, third in
3:57.88.
</P>
</TEXT>
