A0448 &Cx1f; tad-z
u p BC-DEMS-DEBATE09-COX     01-08 0888
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-DEMS-DEBATE09-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Farm policy forms focus of Gore-Bradley debate
 &HT;    By Ken Foskett
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   JOHNSTON, Iowa - In their first Iowa debate of Campaign 2000,
Vice President Al Gore and former New Jersey Sen. Bill Bradley
clashed Saturday over farm policy, Medicare and health insurance
for the nation's uninsured.
</P>
<P>
   The candidates broke no new ground in their 60 minute encounter
and kept a largely civil tone with one another. But the exchange
differed from their debate Wednesday in New Hampshire, where Gore
played the underdog and Bradley appeared more confident.
</P>
<P>
   Buoyed by a new Iowa poll showing him leading Bradley in the
Hawkeye State, Gore took the offensive Saturday on agricultural
policy, a key issue in Iowa and one of Bradley's greatest
weaknesses.
</P>
<P>
   Gore peppered Bradley repeatedly with questions about his votes
against emergency farm aid to Iowa and other Midwestern states in
the 1990s. In an obviously scripted moment, Gore singled out a
member of the studio audience who he said was a family farmer whose
400-acre farm was nearly consumed by floods in 1993.
</P>
<P>
   ``Why did you vote against the disaster relief?'' Gore demanded.
</P>
<P>
   Declining to explain his vote against a 1993 aid package,
Bradley said, ``This is not about the past. This is about the
future.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Well, I can understand why you don't want to talk about the
past,'' Gore retorted.
</P>
<P>
   Bradley ultimately got in the last word on the issue, however,
devoting some of his closing remarks to a broadside against the
Clinton-Gore administration's record in helping family farmers.
</P>
<P>
   ``Al's been hammering on my agriculture votes 15 years ago,''
Bradley said. ``But I would simply ask the family farmers of Iowa
today: Are you better off than you were seven years ago, or do we
need a change?''
</P>
<P>
   Gore also sought to put Bradley on the defensive over Medicare
and health care coverage, charging that Bradley's plan to insure
Americans would leave no money to extend the solvency of Medicare.
</P>
<P>
   Gore has pledged to devote $374 billion over 10 years to help
extend Medicare's solvency from 2015 to 2027. Bradley repeated his
claim that the continuing health of the economy would extend the
insurance program for the elderly without any action now.
</P>
<P>
   On health insurance, Gore charged that Bradley's plan to enroll
uninsured Americans in the federal insurance program for government
workers was insufficient because his proposed subsidy won't cover
most plans.
</P>
<P>
   Bradley has proposed spending $1,200 for each uninsured child
and $1,800 for each uninsured adult living at or near the poverty
level. As he did in the New Hampshire debate Wednesday, Gore
produced a list of federal insurance plans showing that none of the
federal plans offered in Iowa would cover Bradley's subsidies for
adults.
</P>
<P>
   Bradley said his estimate was only a weighted average and that
federally subsidized premiums in some areas would be higher.
</P>
<P>
   ``What we have here is a scare tactic,'' Bradley retorted. ``I
reject that kind of politics.''
</P>
<P>
   The candidates were asked no questions about gays in the
military, which became a flash point in the New Hampshire debate
when Gore suggested that he would make open service for gay and
lesbian military personnel a litmus test for his selection of
members to the joint chiefs of staff.
</P>
<P>
   Gore subsequently backed off those comments, but the spokesman
for the Republican National Committee appeared outside Saturday's
debate to announce that the RNC was purchasing television
advertising time in Iowa and New Hampshire to hammer Gore on the
issue.
</P>
<P>
   A script provided by RNC spokesman Mike Collins features a
picture of Gore and concludes with the line, ``Call Al Gore. Tell
him the only litmus test ought to be patriotism.''
</P>
<P>
   The Democrats' fifth debate of the campaign came as a new poll
here showed Gore holding a solid lead over Bradley in the Hawkeye
State.
</P>
<P>
   A Des Moines Register poll of 501 likely Democratic caucus
participants found Gore holding a 54 percent to 33 percent lead
over Bradley, virtually the same spread as a similar poll taken two
months ago. The poll's margin of error was plus or minus 4.4
percent.
</P>
<P>
   Polls of caucus voters tend to be less reliable than those of
primary voters, but the showing was heartening news for Gore, who
trails Bradley in polls in New Hampshire.
</P>
<P>
   The Iowa caucuses, scheduled for Jan. 24, are the first
presidential preference contest of the 2000 campaign. Although
generally less significant nationally than the New Hampshire
primary a week later, the caucuses are a chance for Bradley to
upset Gore in a state where the institutional backing of the state
party generally gives the incumbent an advantage.
</P>
<P>
   Bradley has poured money and manpower into Iowa, buying up
$800,000 of television advertising before the caucuses, in hopes of
embarrassing Gore with an exceptionally strong showing.
</P>
<P>
   The newspaper's poll, however, indicated that Bradley has a lot
of ground to make up in just 16 days. The poll found that he
trailed Gore among every voting group except college students.
</P>
<P>
   For in-depth reporting, opinion and cartoonists, visit the Cox
News Campaign 2000 Web site: http://www.coxnews.com/2000.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-01-08-00 1743EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
