<DATE_TIME> 2000-01-08 17:44 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A0449 &Cx1f; taf-z
u f BC-CALIF-BIOTECH-REAL-2T     01-08 1027
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CALIF-BIOTECH-REAL-2TAKES-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
REAL ESTATE: A $4-BILLION MIX OF USES IS ON TAP FOR SAN FRANCISCO 
</HEADLINE>
  (js) 
 By MORRIS NEWMAN   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   SAN FRANCISCO _ A 400,000-square-foot university laboratory is
the first building to rise in Mission Bay, the site of a former
rail yard on the city's waterfront that has become San Francisco's
largest redevelopment project.
</P>
<P>
   On a 303-acre site that is now a tangle of unused railroad
tracks, industrial buildings and empty lots just south of the new
San Francisco Giants baseball park, developers plan a
biotechnology-oriented commercial district and a large residential
neighborhood. The centerpiece of the project is a 43-acre
life-sciences campus for the University of California at San
Francisco.
</P>
<P>
   If fully realized, developers say, the 20-year, $4 billion
Mission Bay project will contain 5 million square feet of
commercial space, including office buildings and commercial
laboratory buildings; 2.65 million square feet of university
buildings; 6,000 housing units, and parks and open space.
</P>
<P>
   The primary landowner in the area, Catellus Development Corp. of
San Francisco, the developer for the commercial portion of the
project, donated 30 acres to the university for the new campus,
while the San Francisco Redevelopment Agency donated an additional
13 acres of adjoining land.
</P>
<P>
   Developers and city officials expect the university campus to
serve as a magnet for biotech companies, and the promise of
high-paying technology jobs has made Mission Bay a pet project of
Mayor Willie Brown.
</P>
<P>
   Development officials hope to recreate the synergy between
research institutions and high-tech industry that gave birth to
Silicon Valley, where students and faculty members of Stanford
University in Palo Alto originated hundreds of computer-related
companies. At least 46 biotech companies have already originated at
the University of California campus here, said Bruce Spaulding,
vice chancellor for advancement and planning.
</P>
<P>
   The life sciences campus is expected to attract 31,000 jobs to
Mission Bay, or about 5 percent of the jobs in San Francisco now,
said Amy Neches, senior project manager for the city's
redevelopment agency.
</P>
<P>
   Originally part of San Francisco Bay, the Mission Bay area arose
out of a 19th-century landfill; the area was the city's primary
depository for rubble after the 1906 earthquake.
</P>
<P>
   Starting in the 1920s, the area served as a rail yard for the
city's then-busy harbor. Changes in shipping, notably the rise of
shipping containers, led to the demise of Mission Bay as a cargo
hub in the 1970s.
</P>
<P>
   For nearly 20 years, developers have searched for ways to
redevelop the land in a city where buildable land is scarce.
</P>
<P>
   Even with a steady demand for land, however, city officials and
developers took a decade to agree on a plan. After considerable
controversy about the density of the development and the amount of
public parkland to be developed, the city and county Board of
Supervisors approved a plan in 1991. Soon after, however, the
recession hit California, and the project died.
</P>
<P>
   In the mid-1990s, the future of Mission Bay became linked with
the development plans of the University of California at San
Francisco. At that time, its life sciences division was on the
crowded main campus on Parnassus Avenue, just south of Golden Gate
Park. By the late 1970s, the rapidly expanding university had
already outgrown its campus, but a proposal to build new
laboratories in the neighborhood met with protests and multiple
lawsuits from homeowners.
</P>
<P>
   In 1976, the university agreed to cap the size of the Parnassus
Avenue campus at its existing 3.5 million square feet. Unable to
expand on its central campus, the fast-growing university chose to
decentralize, renting or buying satellite campuses throughout the
city. But that scattering ultimately displeased university
officials, who believed that the ``folks in the disparate sites
didn't feel the sense of community which one expects in an academic
environment,'' Spaulding said.
</P>
<P>
   In the early 1990s, resolved to relocate, the university looked
at 150 sites, many outside the city.
</P>
<P>
   The notion of the university, or even a part of it, leaving the
city alarmed business leaders and government officials, who began
lobbying the university to stay in town.
</P>
<P>
   Nelson Rising, president and chief executive of Catellus, was a
key force behind the university's eventual decision to stay here,
according to Spaulding. ``When Nelson took over as CEO of
Catellus,'' Spaulding said, ``on his very first day he came up to
see me in my office and said, `I want to turn things around.'''
</P>
<P>
   The regents of the University of California approved the Mission
Bay campus in 1997. Last October, construction began on a $143
million laboratory building, one of three that are to make up the
first phase of the university portion of the project. Part of the
financing for the lab buildings comes from a $50 million payment by
Genentech Inc., of South San Francisco, which provided the money as
partial settlement of a patent-infringement lawsuit filed against
the company by the university.
</P>
<P>
   (The university had charged that the company used technology
developed decades earlier at the university; the settlement, in
which Genentech did not admit any wrongdoing, gives the company
naming rights for the building.)
</P>
<P>
   The lab building, designed by SMP/SHG Architects of San
Francisco in association with the Zimmer Gunsul Frasca Partnership
of Portland, Ore., has an entrance facing an eight-acre park, which
is meant to create a campus atmosphere from the start, said William
Diefenbach, a senior vice president of SMP/SHG.
</P>
<P>
   After Catellus persuaded the university to build the campus at
Mission Bay, the developer decided to scrap its approved master
plan and redesign the Mission Bay project, this time as a
technology-related business park surrounding the campus like a
doughnut.
</P>
<P>
   In contrast to earlier plans, which envisioned Mission Bay as
almost a self-contained area within the larger city, the new plan
tries to make it part of the city.
</P>
<P>
</P>
<P>
   The new plan, designed by the architectural firm of Johnson Fain
Partners of Los Angeles, proposes a regular street grid for Mission
Bay, with blocks nearly identical in dimension to those in downtown
San Francisco. William H. Fain Jr., the urban-design principal at
Johnson Fain, said the block size was based on an 1839 surveyor's
map that laid out the first nine blocks of the downtown. The plan
also arranges the streets in a simple grid to allow uninterrupted
waterfront views, a feature missing in earlier plans.
</P>
<P>
   The design of the campus, which was prepared by another firm,
Machado and Silvetti Associates of Boston, conforms to the street
grid pattern.
</P>
<P>
   In addition to its biotech component, Mission Bay will be a
significant housing resource for a city with a severe housing
shortage, said Ms. Neches, the redevelopment official.
</P>
<P>
   In all, 28 percent of the 6,000 housing units will be moderately
priced, she said. Unlike the housing in many other new
developments, the lower-priced apartments and town houses will be
integrated with the market-rate units, she said.
</P>
<P>
   Catellus selected AvalonBay Communities of Alexandria, Va., a
national apartment developer, to build most of the housing. The
city's redevelopment agency plans to start construction this summer
on 90 moderately priced apartments on an acre Catellus donated to
the agency.
</P>
<P>
   In late 2000, Catellus plans to begin work on 160,000 square
feet of retail space, 25,000 square feet of office space and about
500 housing units on a spot the size of a city block, north of the
university campus. At the center of the block will be an
85-foot-wide walkway, or paseo.
</P>
<P>
   To Rising, Mission Bay represents a good example of urban
development: a mixed-use environment that has been designed for
people on foot as much as for those in cars.
</P>
<P>
   The proximity of housing, university and workplace may enable
many people to walk to work _ a rarity in this city of clogged
freeways and far-flung suburbs. ``This is the way we have got to go
in the future,'' he said.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
