<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-NY-GIULIANI-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
NEW YORK MAYOR KEEPS A FIRM HAND ON THROTTLE OF CAMPAIGN 
</HEADLINE>
  (js) 
 By ELISABETH BUMILLER   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ As Mayor Rudolph Giuliani prepares for his annual
State of the City address and luxuriates in the afterglow from the
city's New Year's Eve celebration _ when he gave no fewer than
eight television interviews in one day _ his campaign for U.S.
Senate is at the end of the runway, apparently weighed down with
cash and semiorganized, but ready to fly.
</P>
<P>
   The official line from City Hall remains, amusingly, the same:
The mayor has not yet decided whether he will do Republicans the
favor of taking on Hillary Rodham Clinton, the new Westchester
County resident who is at the White House this weekend packing up
more boxes. Nonetheless, Giuliani essentially outlined his ``City
Hall'' strategy when he told a recent caller to his radio show, ``I
think the best thing for me to do is to do my job the way I've
always done it, and then to try to point out to people why, if they
agree with me, I would be a more effective senator from their point
of view.''
</P>
<P>
   To that end, his Senate exploratory committee, with headquarters
in ramshackle offices in a high-rise on Maiden Lane in Lower
Manhattan, now has seven full-time employees and has taken in more
than $6.6 million in campaign contributions, officials say. Bruce
Teitelbaum, the director of the exploratory committee, who is to be
Giuliani's campaign manager whenever the mayor gets around to
officially announcing, is interviewing for a campaign press
secretary, and has talked to two women, one from Washington, the
other from New York.
</P>
<P>
   A woman is desirable, one adviser close to the mayor said,
because it will be easier for her to criticize Mrs. Clinton.
Teitelbaum's position at the campaign is assured for now; his
lawyer announced last week that, according to federal prosecutors
and the Brooklyn district attorney's office, he is ``presently
neither a target nor a subject'' in the criminal investigation into
the collapse of a Brooklyn building that killed a construction
worker in November.
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile, William D. Powers, the state Republican Party
chairman, is in the early planning stages of a trip he wants
Giuliani to take this spring to the North Country, the counties
north of Albany, as well as other cities upstate _ a reprise of the
mayor's fall travels to endorse local Republicans, whom he had
never bothered with before.
</P>
<P>
   Powers rejected any notion that Giuliani is less than
enthusiastic about the race. ``I think as much as people have asked
me that question, one can only demonstrate by looking at him,''
Powers said last week. ``If somebody is not interested in running
for statewide office, why are they dragging themselves to
Binghamton, Buffalo, Rochester, Syracuse, Albany, Troy and Long
Island?''
</P>
<P>
   Powers also dismissed the talk of a new rift between the state's
frequently warring alpha male Republicans, Giuliani and Gov. George
E. Pataki (although some might call the deceptively relaxed Pataki
a secret alpha male), who incurred the mayor's invective in late
December when he signed a pension bill that the mayor said would
cost the city $100 million.
</P>
<P>
   ``We get off the government page and on the political page,
they're doing fine,'' Powers said, meaning that Pataki is so far
cooperating with Giuliani in his race against Mrs. Clinton. Until
August, Pataki was promoting the candidacy of Rep. Rick Lazio, a
Republican from Long Island, much to the fury of City Hall.
</P>
<P>
   In two polls conducted last month, Giuliani remained slightly
ahead, but with the margin of error he was essentially tied with
Mrs. Clinton. Nonetheless, Mrs. Clinton's support has dropped
significantly since she first announced that she was considering
the race last winter, a time after President Clinton's impeachment
hearings when the public's sympathy for her was enormous. Both
polls, by Quinnipiac College in Hamden, Conn., and Marist College
in Poughkeepsie, N.Y., also showed Giuliani slightly ahead of Mrs.
Clinton among registered white female voters. In addition, the
Marist poll showed that even among Democratic women, Mrs. Clinton's
core constituency, support for her had dropped 20 points from the
beginning to the end of 1999. The mayor's support went up 10 points
in the same period.
</P>
<P>
   In January 1999, the poll reported, 81 percent of the Democratic
women polled supported Mrs. Clinton, compared with 17 percent for
Giuliani. By December, the poll reported, 61 percent of Democratic
women supported Mrs. Clinton, compared with 27 percent for
Giuliani. But the number of polled women in that category was small
_ only 144 in December _ and the margin of sampling error was
large.
</P>
<P>
   Mrs. Clinton's political advisers note that the election is a
long way off, and predict that those women will come back to the
first lady once she settles into her new house in Chappaqua and
begins talking more forcefully about issues like health care and
education. Giuliani's political advisers agree that the election is
a long way off, and are restraining themselves from sounding too
triumphant.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think the manner in which she has engaged has been
frustrating to people,'' said one of Giuliani's senior campaign
officials. ``One day she's here, the next day she's not, one day
she's to the right, one day she's to the left. People were
expecting strong, decisive, independent _ and they're not getting
it.''
</P>
<P>
   Giuliani's political advisers also contend that the mayor could
win the race with as little as 32 percent of the vote in
overwhelmingly Democratic New York City, meaning that the mayor has
to do exceptionally well upstate and in the New York suburbs. So
far, polls show Giuliani running stronger than Republicans
traditionally do in the suburbs _ that is, in Westchester, Nassau,
Suffolk, Orange and Rockland Counties _ but not as strong as
Republicans often do upstate, where the mayor is not as well known.
</P>
<P>
   The Quinnipiac poll, conducted early last month, showed 59
percent of suburban voters favoring Giuliani, compared with 32
percent for Mrs. Clinton. Upstate, the poll showed 47 percent of
voters favoring Giuliani and 38 percent favoring Mrs. Clinton.
(Although the mayor says regularly that he never pays attention to
polls, he often has his advisers call and complain to the pollsters
when he doesn't like the results.)
</P>
<P>
   For now, aides say, Giuliani is entirely focused on his State of
the City speech, in essence his first campaign document of 2000.
The mayor will highlight his accomplishments of 1999, when even
Democrats were grudgingly impressed with how he used his mayoralty
to set the stage for a run for the Senate, particularly in heading
off a transit strike and making sure that Times Square was safe for
New Year's.
</P>
<P>
   Still, his aides say they have no idea when he will officially
announce for the Senate. Powers, who encouraged Giuliani to
announce last year, said the mayor has to say something official by
June, when the state party holds its convention. ``I suppose I can
hold my breath until then,'' Powers said.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
