<DOCNO> NYT20000108.0192 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-01-08 17:48 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A0456 &Cx1f; taf-z
u s BC-BKC-MIAMI-SYRACUSE-NY     01-08 0747
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BKC-MIAMI-SYRACUSE-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
ORANGEMEN RUN INTO NO PROBLEM ON ROAD
</HEADLINE>
   (rk) 
 By CHARLIE NOBLES   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   MIAMI _ Going on the road for the first time this season did not
turn out to be such a problem for the Syracuse Orangemen Saturday.
</P>
<P>
   After fashioning a 10-0 record in the friendly Carrier Dome, the
Orangemen were able to repel a Miami team hungry for
recognition,67-55, at Miami Arena.
</P>
<P>
   It took the senior forward Etan Thomas' block of a Mario Bland
jump shot late in the game to assure the Orangemen's victory. They
led by only five points at the time.
</P>
<P>
   ``I figured we needed to win this game,'' coach Jim Boeheim
said. ``If we lost, all everybody would be writing is how we
couldn't handle playing on the road for the first time.''
</P>
<P>
   Syracuse has its top seven players returning from last season,
Boeheim pointed out, and that unit went 7-2 on the road in Big East
games.
</P>
<P>
   ``We played a real good first half,'' Boeheim said, ``and in the
second half, our offense just went south. And we had too many
turnovers.''
</P>
<P>
   Syracuse shot just 35.7 percent in the second half and had 21
turnovers for the game. But it built such a lead that Miami, now
8-6, could not recover. ``It looked like we forced them out of
their offense in the first half,'' Boeheim said.
</P>
<P>
   It was a different story in the second half, as Miami closed
once to within four points. Still, Damone Brown and Ryan Blackwell,
who tied Jason Hart for top scorer with 14 points each, contributed
mightily through the game's latter stages to help hold off the
hosts.
</P>
<P>
   Syracuse outrebounded Miami, 39-36, and blocked more shots, 5-2,
including two by Thomas. Boeheim went to a spread offense more in
the second half, and he was not pleased with the results. ``It
should be good for us,'' he said. ``Maybe the more we use it, the
better we'll do with it.''
</P>
<P>
   The Orangemen, the Big East's best defensive team thus far with
a 58.1-point average yield coming into the game, put a strong clamp
on Miami's scorers as Syracuse molded what appeared to be a
commanding 36-21 halftime lead.
</P>
<P>
   Miami shot a paltry 8 for 34 from the field, a 23.5 percentage,
as Syracuse moved ahead 11-1 at the game's start and soon had a
15-4 edge. Hart helped the visitors early with a 3-pointer that
opened the game's scoring, another that staked them to a 7-1 lead
and then a driving layup that increased their margin to 10 points.
</P>
<P>
   Even when Syracuse turned the ball over in the next two
possessions _ on bad passes by Brown and guard Tony Bland _ the
Hurricanes could not penetrate its defense.
</P>
<P>
   Miami didn't get its first field goal until 6 minutes 49 seconds
into the game, and then it took a follow-up by Mario Bland after
Elton Tyler's jump shot had been altered by Syracuse's active
defense.
</P>
<P>
   The Hurricanes used four points by James Jones to draw within
16-11, but then Syracuse went on an eight-point run. The substitute
guard Preston Shumpert contributed two free throws and a layup,
while Blackwell had a 3-point play and then a free throw.
</P>
<P>
   A minute later, Blackwell was in the right spot when a rebound
deflected off Thomas' shoulder. He stuffed the ball for a 26-13
lead. The Orangemen's biggest lead of the half was 19 points, after
Hart's steal and layup made it 34-19 with 3:21 left. But then the
visitors went cold. Miami scored six of the half's last eight
points.
</P>
<P>
   Thomas, Syracuse's career blocks leader and top scorer this
season, had a quiet first half. He had four points, four rebounds
and no blocks.
</P>
<P>
   The Hurricanes climbed back in the game early in the second
half, with guard Johnny Hemsley, the team's stop scorer,
contributing eight points in the first 5 minutes. Hemsley, who came
in averaging 19 points a game, had been a miserable 1 for 9 in
field goal attempts in the first half.
</P>
<P>
   Though Hemsley didn't score until 13:38 into the game, his hot
hand early in the second half brought Miami to within 38-34.
Syracuse countered with field goals by Hart and Thomas, but the
hosts closed to within six, backed now by a wildly cheering crowd.
</P>
<P>
   They would not get much closer the rest of the way.
</P>
<P>
   The Orangemen quickly expanded their lead to nine, then after
two free throws by Miami made it 48-41, went on a nine-point run to
put the game away. Brown contributed four of the points, the last
two on a spectacular dunk.
</P>
<P>
   The Hurricanes didn't roll over from there, drawing to within
five, but the issue had been settled.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
