<P>
   CLINTON-MIDEAST _ WASHINGTON _ After years spent trying to end
war in the Middle East, President Clinton has begun preparing
Americans for the price of peace. Any agreement reached among
Israel and its Arab neighbors, in other words, will require
Americans to spend billions of dollars on military, economic and
humanitarian aid. U.S. troops might also be needed as part of a
larger United Nations force to police the peace. Analysts' best
estimates on what Americans should brace for amid Clinton's
full-court press to broker a comprehensive Mideast peace accord
before he leaves office next year. (Deans, Cox News Service).
</P>
<P>
   EDs: MOVED Fri., Jan. 7, in the (i) International and (k)
Commentary categories.
</P>
<P>
   SIERRALEONE _ FREETOWN, Sierra Leone _ When her baby is born,
the teenage girl won't be able to hold it. That's because after the
rebels raped and impregnated her, they hacked off her arms at the
elbow with a machete. If you could see face to face the darkness of
human madness wrought on these people, your heart would ache into
your sleep. I was a Peace Corps volunteer in Sierra Leone from
1962-64, during that nation's heady years of early independence
from Great Britain. I knew these people as kind, loving and
industrious; I never imagined the nightmare that would eat the
nation alive. Nor did I ever expect to return there, especially
after the last decade of coups and fighting. But life has its pulls
and patterns. (Cawood, Dayton Daily News) EDs: MOVED in both (i)
International and (k) Commentary categories.)
</P>
