   WASHINGTON
</P>
<P>
   SCHOOLS-BETTER _ WASHINGTON _ Bucking a national trend of gloom
and doom in discussions of public schools, two Washington-based
education organizations report ``the good news about American
education.'' Comparing the early 1980s with the latest figures from
the 1990s, the Center on Education Policy and American Youth Policy
Forum found dropout rates falling, more students taking tougher
college-prep courses in high school, SAT and ACT scores rising and
public school teachers more likely than private school teachers to
have earned a college degree. (Mollison, Cox News Service).
</P>
