A0462 &Cx1f; taf-z
u p BC-DEMS-DEBATE-630(2TAKE     01-08 0670
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-DEMS-DEBATE-630(2TAKES)-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
GORE ATTACKS BRADLEY ON AGRICULTURE VOTES AND MEDICARE
</HEADLINE>
   (rk) 
 By KATHARINE Q. SEELYE   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   DES MOINES, Iowa _ Setting aside the bitter sarcasm of their
previous encounters, Vice President Al Gore and former Sen. Bill
Bradley Saturday made direct appeals to farmers and senior
citizens, two important voting segments in Iowa, in the first of
their series of debates to be held in this state.
</P>
<P>
   Gore prodded Bradley on several Senate votes that Gore said went
against the interest of agriculture, including those against
ethanol, crop insurance and price supports for farmers. Perhaps
most dramatically, Gore highlighted Bradley's vote against federal
disaster relief for farmers by singling out Chris Peterson, a
farmer in the audience, and describing the 1993 flooding of 300 of
his 400 acres.
</P>
<P>
   Bradley used the question to say that the nation needed real
leadership and a change in its agriculture policy. He noted that
President Franklin D. Roosevelt, who had been criticized as being
bad for farmers, appointed an Iowa farm boy, Henry Wallace, as his
agriculture secretary, implying he would appoint someone of similar
stature in the farming community.
</P>
<P>
   Bradley later asked: ``Are you better off than you were seven
years ago, or do we need to take a step to change?'' The question
served the double purpose of evoking the insurgent spirit of Ronald
Reagan, who used the same thought against President Jimmy Carter in
1980, and highlighting the difficulties faced by farmers in an
otherwise booming economy.
</P>
<P>
   Gore also hammered Bradley on the subject of Medicare. He
faulted Bradley for not offering a proposal to bolster Medicare,
the government health-care program for the elderly, which is
expected to be insolvent by the year 2015. He also asserted that a
proposal by Bradley to expand Medicare's coverage of prescription
drugs would fall well short of helping low-income people. The
elderly represent the largest bloc of voters in the Iowa caucuses.
</P>
<P>
   Gore said of Bradley's lack of urgency about Medicare: ``It kind
of reminds me of the guy who fell out of the 10-story building and,
as he passed the fifth floor, he shouted, `Well, so far, so
good.'''
</P>
<P>
   Bradley, who has invoked Roosevelt in recent weeks as an example
of a president who was able to enact several major programs at
once, said that because the federal surplus has continued to grow,
there would be enough money to establish universal health care and
to preserve Medicare.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think we can do both,'' he said, repeating the phrase for
emphasis.
</P>
<P>
   The two Democratic candidates here under the auspices of Iowa
Public Television just 16 days before voters here attend their
caucuses and begin each party's selection of its presidential
candidates. Gore came into the encounter buoyed by the news
trumpeted in The Des Moines Register Saturday that Gore is leading
Bradley among likely voters here in a new Register poll, 54 percent
to 33 percent.
</P>
<P>
   Gore and Bradley were coming off a particularly edgy debate
Wednesday, and Gore, for one, seemed decidedly determined to shuck
the label of combatant. He resisted opportunities to snipe back at
his opponent, though a couple of times he corrected Bradley and
repeated his message of the last week, that Bradley is too
theoretical and impractical for the rough world of politics.
</P>
<P>
   Bradley's goal was to raise questions about Gore's leadership
qualities and to suggest that he, Bradley, would be the true agent
of change.
</P>
<P>
   On the matter of revamping the campaign finance system, for
instance, he said, ``There is a question here, who's going to
mobilize and get this change? I have put it out there and talked
about it in every meeting I go to, because I believe the American
people have to take over here. I believe the American people, by
voting for me to give me the mandate, will overcome the special
interests in Washington.''
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
</P>
<P>
   He did not raise the matter of gays in the military. The matter
has dogged Gore since their Wednesday debate, when he suggested he
would apply a litmus test to any appointee to the Joint Chiefs of
Staff by requiring that appointee to agree with him that gays
should be allowed to serve openly in the military. Gore backpedaled
from his remarks on Friday, saying he did not mean to suggest that
he would conduct inquiries into the political views of his military
appointees.
</P>
<P>
   In his opening statement, Gore responded to a remark by Bradley
in the previous debate, when he accused the vice president of
having a ``bunker mentality'' after having spent so many years in
Washington.
</P>
<P>
   ``I want to start by telling you what we were doing in that
Washington bunker,'' Gore said. ``We created 20 million new jobs,
cut the welfare rolls in half, passed the toughest gun control in a
generation and created the strongest economy in the history of the
United States of America.
</P>
<P>
   ``Now, we have a fight to continue our future with prosperity,''
he continued. ``I want universal health care, dramatic improvements
in all of our schools and help for farmers. That's not a bunker;
those are the front lines in the fight for our future.''
</P>
<P>
   Bradley used his opening statement to remind his Iowa audience
that he was born and raised in a small Midwestern town in Missouri
just to the south. ``A lot of the small towns that I've gone
through and met people in Iowa remind me of that small town in
Missouri,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   The two candidates were offered opportunities to ask each other
a question, and each used his time to hit at what he considered a
central weakness of his rival.
</P>
<P>
   Bradley, who has run as an outsider, trying to capitalize on
anger toward President Clinton, asked Gore why so many fewer people
trusted government today.
</P>
<P>
   Gore began in a somewhat rambling way, saying that after college
``I thought politics would be the very last thing I ever did with
my life.'' But he was quickly able to find his footing by turning
the question around and re-issuing his challenge to Bradley to
replace campaign commercials with frequent debates. Bradley has
refused the challenge, arguing that he is less known than the vice
president and needs 30-second commercials to get his message out.
</P>
<P>
   ``I know that you have said no, but as they say on that
millionaire show, is that your final answer?'' Gore said.
</P>
<P>
   Bradley replied, ``I think there's another element too, and that
is candidates going out and telling people what they believe, not
thinking polls but telling people what they believe.''
</P>
<P>
   Then in a display of what he could accomplish in a 30-second
commercial, he said: ``And in 30 seconds, you can say a lot. I'm
for a woman's right to choose. I'm for affordable quality health
care accessible to all Americans. I'm for education improvement in
this country. I am for trying to make sure campaign finance reform
is a reality, that working families have a better chance to advance
and that we eliminate child poverty in this country. How's that?''
</P>
<P>
   Given his opportunity to ask Bradley a question, Gore asked a
member of the audience to stand and introduced Peterson, the owner
of a farm that had been devastated in floods in 1993. He then asked
Bradley why he voted in the Senate against a disaster relief bill
that would have helped Peterson.
</P>
<P>
   Bradley sidestepped the question and instead criticized the
Clinton administration's farm policy, saying it had failed to stem
to closing of family farms. ``You know Al, I think that the premise
of your question is wrong,'' Bradley replied. ``This is not about
the past. This is about the future. This is about what we are going
to do to change the agriculture policy we've had over the last
eight to 10 years, during Republicans and Democrats.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
