<P>
   ATTENTION EDITORS: The following photos are part of tonight's
New York Times Photo Package, moving Saturday, 01/08/00. Photo
clients will automatically receive these photos via AP's
PhotoExpress or may download them from either the Wieck Photo
Database in Dallas at 972-392-0888 or from NYTPhotos on Newscom at
305-448-8411. Non-clients can make individual purchases by calling
(888) 603-1036 or 212-556-4204.
</P>
<P>
   (NYT10) RIDGEWOOD, N.J. -- Jan. 8, 2000 --
IMMIGRANT-LITERATURE-3 -- Writer Chang-rae Lee, 35, is a young
author who draws on his own experiences to overturn the classic
American tale of the immigrant's metamorphosis from outsider to
mainstream success. Henry Park, a Korean-American narrator in Lee's
1995 novel ``Native Speaker,'' is a master of disguise in both his
professional and personal lives. Speaking English is presented as
subversive and a method for dissimulation. (Richard Perry/The New
York Times)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT9) NEW YORK -- Jan. 8, 2000 -- NY-DOGS-COOPS-2 -- Michael
Woodruff, a 27-year-old disc jockey and record producer who came to
New York City from Georgia two years ago, with his Jack Russell
terrier, Robert, 4, has had trouble finding dog-friendly buildings
in Manhattan. Now he has spent four months searching for a place to
buy. ``There is such a low percentage of dog-friendly buildings,''
he says. ``It's a real pain.'' (Andrea Mohin/The New York Times)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT8) NEW YORK -- Jan. 8, 2000 -- NY-DOGS-COOPS-1 -- Dr. Susan
Freeman, with Ollie, foreground, and Andrew Kissel, with Bellini.
Dr. Freeman is on a canine interview committee of the co-op board
of her building in Manahttan. The days of whines and noses may be
running out for dog owners hoping to buy a co-op apartment. After
decades of more or less benign acceptance, an increasing number of
buildings are changing their rules to no pets at all, and
particularly to no dogs. Even condominiums, long the bastion of
look-the-other-way boards, have tightened up their pet policies.
(Andrea Mohin/The New York Times)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT7) NEW YORK -- Jan. 8, 2000 -- IMMIGRANT-LITERATURE-2-B&AMP;W --
Leo C. Rosten. in 1969. Once upon a time, the fictional immigrant
to New York City struggled mightily to master the New World and
then to assimilate. The prototype was the title character of the
1937 Leo C. Rosten book, ``The Education of HYMAN KAPLAN,'' that
indefatigably earnest student of America who wrestled with the
English language and emerged from the tussle with his personality
astonishingly intact. (The New York Times)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT6) NEW YORK -- Jan. 8, 2000 -- IMMIGRANT-LITERATURE-1 -- Mei
Ng, 33, who grew up in Queens, explores the classic literary theme
of estrangement between immigrant parents and their children. Like
other writers of her generation she also expands it to take in
feelings of ethnic and racial alienation. ``Now I write about what
it means to be hyphenated, with one foot here in a place they
wouldn't have me,'' says Ng. ``America is a melting pot and all,
but people sometimes say in a fit of annoyance or anger, 'Go back
where you came from.' And I'm, like, OK, I'll go back to Queens.''
(Andrea Mohin/The New York Times)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT5) NORFOLK, Va. -- Jan. 8, 2000 -- CIVILSUPPORT-AGENCY --
Brig. Gen. Bruce M. Lawlor, a one-star Army general, commander of
the Joint Task Force Civil Support, leads an operation that would
respond in the event of a germ or nuclear attack. In the event of
an attack, all of the military's resources, from helicopters and
cargo planes to fleets of trucks, could be used to haul emergency
supplies to devastated cities, but always under the authority of
civilians. Working with civilian agencies, the military would set
up whatever was needed, whether hospitals or decontamination units.
(Shana Raab/The New York Times)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT4) WASHINGTON -- Jan. 8, 2000 -- Y2K-ASSESS -- John
Koskinen, chairman of the President's Council on Year 2000
conversion, was among the experts whose Congressional testimony in
March overestimated the degree of the world's dependence on
computers. Once adjustments were made for technology dependence,
some analysts say, the investment of the United States and other
pacesetters in year 2000 preparations was not that far out of line
with those that started late. (Paul Hosefros/The New York Times)
</P>
