<SLUG> BC-OBIT-WETMORE-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
JAMES WETMORE, 84, EPISCOPAL SUFFRAGAN BISHOP 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ATTN: Pa., R.I., Canada)  (lb) 
 By WOLFGANG SAXON   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ Bishop James Stuart Wetmore, the longest-serving
suffragan bishop of the Episcopal Diocese of New York and a staunch
advocate of ecumenism, died Dec. 28 at the Lutheran Care Center in
Poughkeepsie. A resident of Millbrook, he was 84.
</P>
<P>
   He suffered a long illness, the diocesan office at the Cathedral
Church of St. John the Divine reported.
</P>
<P>
   Elected by a diocesan convention of priests and laity, he served
as the bishop's principal aide from 1960 until his retirement in
1987. His duties as suffragan were whatever the head of the New
York diocese assigned him, and Wetmore's most visible presence was
in the Episcopal efforts toward cooperation with other churches and
faiths.
</P>
<P>
   Thus, in 1968, he became the first non-Catholic to preach from
the pulpit of St. Patrick's Cathedral, seat of the Roman Catholic
archbishop of New York. He served as chairman of the diocesan
Ecumenical Commission from 1969 to 1988.
</P>
<P>
   He headed the group that founded the Council of the Churches of
the City of New York in 1960 and served as a council director from
1962 until his death. He was a past president of the Episcopal
Housing Corp. and vice president of the Seamen's Church Institute,
and until his death he was president of St. Peter's School in
Poughkeepsie.
</P>
<P>
   Born in Hampton, New Brunswick, Canada, he graduated in 1938
from Kings College in Halifax, Nova Scotia, where he received a
licentiate in theology the following year. He was ordained a deacon
in 1938 and a priest in 1939.
</P>
<P>
   He came to New York in 1953 to direct the Department of
Christian Education of the Diocese of New York. He held the
director's post until his election as bishop suffragan.
</P>
<P>
   He served in the North American section of Christian education
for the World Council of Churches from 1954 to 1964. In the 1960s
he also was a trustee of St. Hilda and St. Hugh's School in
Morningside Heights.
</P>
<P>
   Wetmore is survived by his wife of 59 years, Francis Howard
Robinson Wetmore; three daughters, Nancy Faulds of Putnam Valley,
Mary Bohun of Cortland Manor and Jane Robin Gulotta of New Paltz;
two sons, Charles of Bethlehem, Pa., and Stuart of Warwick, R.I.;
11 grandchildren, and two great-grandchildren.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-01-08-00 1812EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT20000108.0202 </DOCNO>
