<DATE_TIME> 2000-01-08 19:14 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A0470 &Cx1f; tad-z
u a BC-FLAGMARCH09-COX     01-08 1063
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FLAGMARCH09-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Confederate flag supporters wage war in S.C.
 &HT;    By Chris Burritt
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   COLUMBIA, S.C. _ Confederate flag supporters declared political
war Saturday on both the NAACP and South Carolina legislators who
back the group's campaign to remove the divisive banner from atop
the Statehouse.
</P>
<P>
   ''If any House or Senate members vote to bring down this flag,
will you work to destroy them?'' yelled Ron Wilson, lieutenant
commander in chief of the Sons of Confederate Veterans in South
Carolina.
</P>
<P>
   ''Yes!'' shouted back several thousand flag-wavers, crowding the
Statehouse grounds against the backdrop of a huge Confederate flag
flowing down the Capitol steps.
</P>
<P>
   Officials of the Sons of Confederate Veterans, the South
Carolina Heritage Commission and other groups announced plans for a
lobbying campaign aimed at pressuring state legislators to keep the
flag ''flying permanently'' over the Capitol.
</P>
<P>
   A newly formed ''Keep it Flying'' political action committee
will rally support with statewide commercials, field director Jim
Freeman said. It also will campaign for sympathetic candidates in
state elections.
</P>
<P>
   The efforts aim to counteract the National Association for the
Advancement of Colored People's tourism boycott of South Carolina
and its threat to impose other economic sanctions against the state
until legislators vote to remove the flag.
</P>
<P>
   Five miles away from Saturday's rally, officials with the state
NAACP planned a parade and rally scheduled for Martin Luther King
Jr. Day on Jan. 17. The officials discussed intensifying the
group's sanctions aimed at pressuring
</P>
<P>
   legislators to vote to remove the flag, but they weren't
prepared to announce further steps, said state NAACP executive
director Dwight James.
</P>
<P>
   ''There is a clear right side in this debate,'' said James,
reiterating the NAACP's view that the Rebel flag is an insulting
symbol of slavery. ''I clearly believe the flag has no legitimate
place on the Statehouse grounds.'' In Saturday's chill, the flag
dominated the grounds. Thousands fluttered in the breeze, flying
atop poles that supporters hoisted and waved when speakers defended
the flag as honoring the 26,000 Confederates who died fighting for
South Carolina.
</P>
<P>
   Bolstered by Confederate banners and bumper stickers and the
banner emblazoned on hats, shirts, belts and socks, flag supporters
relished attacking their foes.
</P>
<P>
   ''I can tell you they picked the wrong state this time,'' Wilson
said.
</P>
<P>
   As for legislators who side with flag opponents, Wilson said,
''We will take them out.''
</P>
<P>
   The General Assembly convenes Tuesday, with wrangling over
whether to move the flag threatening to overshadow other business,
House and Senate leaders have warned.
</P>
<P>
   Although South Carolina's flag supporters have been gathering
momentum in recent years, claiming partial credit for Gov. David
Beasley's surprising defeat in 1998, this weekend's rally is the
biggest show of force yet in defense of the flag.
</P>
<P>
   The rectangular Union Jack, a red flag with a blue X studded
with white stars, has flown atop the Capitol since 1962, when
legislators raised it as part of the Civil War centennial.
</P>
<P>
   ''It is going to stay right there; it ought to stay right
there,'' said Conrad Mizzell, 49, of Marietta, Ga., wearing a black
feather in his gray cap. ''It is a living monument of the boys who
died.''
</P>
<P>
   Flanked by Confederate monuments, the Statehouse has become a
symbolic setting for the latest showdown over the Rebel banner. Its
granite walls are still marred by Union shells fired in 1864.
Occupying Columbia, Gen. William Sherman's troops burned the
building.
</P>
<P>
   But it survived, and 136 years later it is the last Statehouse
in the South to fly the Confederate flag. The state flags of
Georgia and Mississippi incorporate the symbol.
</P>
<P>
   Flag supporters gathered in Columbia warned that, if it falls in
South Carolina, opponents will target the Georgia and Mississippi
flags.
</P>
<P>
   ''I think this can only steamroll into something else,'' said
Stan Dilcher, 39, of Marietta. He was one of several hundred
Georgians who traveled to Columbia for what many view as a pivotal
defense of Confederate history, which they claim has been unfairly
labeled as racist for the past 30 years.
</P>
<P>
   ''If the Confederate flag comes down, the truth of Confederate
history will be lost to political correctness,'' said the Rev.
Bobby Eubanks, presenting a statement from ministers defending as
''noble Christians'' Confederate officers such as Gen. Robert E.
Lee and Stonewall Jackson.
</P>
<P>
   ''May the South rise again to tell the truth ...'' Eubanks
shouted as the crowd drowned him out.
</P>
<P>
   Many among the estimated 6,000 flag supporters wore uniforms of
Confederate gray. Women wore hoop skirts, some in black mourning
dresses, and children wore bonnets and floppy hats.
</P>
<P>
   The celebration started at Elmwood Cemetery, where a regimental
band from Georgia played ''Dixie'' following a roll call of the
Confederate dead buried on a hillside.
</P>
<P>
   Gray smoke rose from musket fire, starting the mile-long march
through downtown Columbia to the Capitol lawn, a river of red,
white and blue.
</P>
<P>
   Starting from the rear, marchers cut loose with high-pitched
Rebel yells, which others repeated all the way to the front of the
parade. As they neared the tall granite monument honoring the
Confederate dead, on the Capitol grounds, the singing of ''Dixie''
and other songs grew louder.
</P>
<P>
   Several black people who watched the parade defended the group's
right to assemble, but they disagreed with their mission.
</P>
<P>
   ''You've still got people, no matter how much they smile at you,
who hate black people,'' said Janice Hallman, 38, standing on Main
Street with her 3-year-old son, Michael. ''If you went to their
house, right now, they'd probably tell you to go through the back
door.''
</P>
<P>
   ''The Old South is gone; it is not coming back,'' said David
Smith, 49. ''This is the last symbol of the Old South. Until it
comes down, we will not go forward.''
</P>
<P>
   Holding a hand-drawn sign reading ''Worship God! Not Flag,'' the
Rev. Louis Rivers, 46, said, ''I think we are spending too much
time on this flag, both black and white, and not enough on the
moral issues on which this country was founded.''
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
