u s BC-FBN-DOLPHINS09-COX     01-08 0929
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FBN-DOLPHINS09-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Marino: `I'm not done'
 &HT;    By Karen Rosen
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   SEATTLE _ A football institution will call it quits today.
</P>
<P>
   That would be the Kingdome, not Dan Marino. The Seahawks'
stadium will close its doors if Seattle loses, but the Miami
quarterback has given no indication that his career will end with
the Dolphins' season.
</P>
<P>
   As critics clamor for the 38-year-old Marino to be benched in
the first round of the AFC playoffs, coach Jimmy Johnson has said
Dan's the man. That's quite an endorsement, because their
relationship, which was already strained, has worsened with
Marino's declining performance on the field.
</P>
<P>
   ``Dan is our starting quarterback,'' Johnson said. ``Let's put
the soap opera on the back burner for a week.''
</P>
<P>
   But it still simmers. It seems fairly certain that either Marino
or Johnson will be with Miami next year, but not both.
</P>
<P>
   Anticipating that last week would be Marino's last, Dolphins
owner Wayne Huizenga flew Marino's family to Washington in a
private jet. Miami lost 21-10 for a 9-7 record but already knew it
would be in the playoffs because Seattle lost earlier in the day.
The owner has said he wants to be involved in any management
decision about Marino, who is immensely popular with Miami fans.
</P>
<P>
   ``The last few years, when the season's over, I see what's gone
on in the year and how I feel,'' said Marino, the NFL's all-time
leading passer who went over the 60,000-yard mark this season.
``Right now my focus is more on, `Let's go to Seattle and win this
game.'''
</P>
<P>
   Marino bristles at retirement talk.
</P>
<P>
   ``I've been answering this question, and I'm tired of answering
it,'' said Marino, who missed five weeks with a pinched nerve in
his neck and has a 1-5 record since returning at Thanksgiving.
``You never know when your last game is going to be. ... Who knows
what the future holds?''
</P>
<P>
   Before Christmas, Marino let off some steam, and some people
read between the lines that he wanted an 18th season.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm not done,'' Marino said. ``The people who know football
understand that. This is my job, and I take great pride in what I
do. To hear people say I'm finished, well, I don't let that kind of
criticism bother me. I'm past that.''
</P>
<P>
   Marino will take a pared-down offense into today's game, hoping
to cut down on turnovers. He has thrown 17 interceptions this year
and only 12 touchdown passes. Marino's decision-making has been
questioned as often as his arm strength, which was affected by the
pinched nerve.
</P>
<P>
   The Pittsburgh native has looked mechanical while his
quarterback rating plummeted to 69.1, second-worst among starters.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're looking at the things Dan is most comfortable using, and
that's what we're going to concentrate on,'' Johnson said.
</P>
<P>
   What Miami needs is a solid running game, which has been
lacking.
</P>
<P>
   ``The running game has been a problem for the Miami Dolphins for
20 years,'' Johnson said. ``It's not like it's all of a sudden
cropped up this year.''
</P>
<P>
   But in the past, Marino could carry the team. The future Hall of
Famer's biography and stats fill 47 pages of the Dolphins media
guide.
</P>
<P>
   Before he was injured, he was the AFC player of the week in the
first and fifth weeks of the season. He took himself out of the
Oct. 17 game against New England in the first quarter because he
didn't have enough strength in his throwing arm. The weakness
resulted from the pinched nerve the week before at Indianapolis,
when he led the team to a last-minute victory.
</P>
<P>
   Backup Damon Huard came in against the Patriots to engineer a
31-30 victory, then helped the Dolphins win four of their next five
games. When Marino returned against Dallas, he threw five
interceptions in a 20-0 loss.
</P>
<P>
   ``I probably rushed Dan back into the lineup,'' Johnson said.
``He was rusty, so we turned the ball over a bunch, even though we
played pretty good defense. We lost the next game against (the
Colts), and since that time our confidence has been shaken, and
that's really been a problem.''
</P>
<P>
   Johnson said that despite Huard's success, ``I think it's best
for us to go with Dan right now. I think Dan is our best chance to
win. I would anticipate that we would stay with him throughout the
game.''
</P>
<P>
   He played down talk of a feud, in which they supposedly barely
speak.
</P>
<P>
   ``Dan and I have a great relationship,'' Johnson said. ``We have
respect for each other. We keep getting questions about our
relationship. I don't think that has affected either one of us.''
</P>
<P>
   Marino said ``The press made a much bigger deal out of
everything than there really is. I've said all along (that) Coach
Johnson is the head coach of the team and I'm the quarterback. I
have to do my job.''
</P>
<P>
   And after nine operations, two bad knees and some pain remaining
in his neck, he still thinks that he can get the job done. If
Marino wins one more game, he ties John Elway for most games won in
a career with 148.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm proud of my consistency factor over 17 years,'' said
Marino, who in June signed a two-year extension through 2001. ``The
games I've started, the team was able to rely on me every week. I
felt like I always played my position at a very high level. What's
disappointing is not being able to win a Super Bowl.''
</P>
<P>
   As the father of five prepares for his 17th playoff game in his
17th season, he said he just wants to take advantage of the chance
to play.
</P>
<P>
   ``You never know,'' Marino said, ``when it might be your last
opportunity.''
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
