<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FBN-COWBOYS09-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Vikings focused on Cowboys first
 &HT;    By Curtis Bunn
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ The pictures of a team in despair remain imbedded in
the minds of the Minnesota Vikings. The most lucent might be
Randall Cunningham.
</P>
<P>
   After Morten Andersen kicked the overtime field goal in the
Metrodome to win the NFC Championship, the Falcons hysterically
celebrated their berth in the Super Bowl.
</P>
<P>
   Cunningham, on his knees, pounded the turf with both hands, just
as Moses did in ``The Ten Commandments'' after his trooops drowned.
</P>
<P>
   Such images, the Vikings insist, serve as motivation as they
begin their quest to make amends for last year's devastating
failure. Redemption starts this afternoon against the Dallas
Cowboys.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're more focused this year than last year,'' receiver Randy
Moss said. ``When Atlanta came in here, there was a lot of hype
being talked, and even though we didn't say it, I think we bought
into the hype. Guys talking about what we're going to do when we
get to Miami, things like that.''
</P>
<P>
   No such discussions have taken place among the Vikings this
time. When the Falcons brought Minnesota to its knees, the Vikings
learned a painful lesson about overconfidence. Sufficiently
humbled, their outlook is specfic.
</P>
<P>
   ``Now,'' Moss said, ``we're just talking about, `Let's get to
the Super Bowl.' We're not talking about how we're going to get
there, where we're going to party, we're going to do this or we're
going to do that. We're just talking about going through the
playoffs and just win and hope we go to the Super Bowl.''
</P>
<P>
   Although they do not have the best record in the NFC, as they
did last year, the Vikings consider themselves the class of the
conference. Cunningham has been replaced by former Falcon Jeff
George, and Minnesota has responded with eight wins in its past 10
games.
</P>
<P>
   The offense is not as explosive as the record-setting unit of
last season, but it remains one of the most feared in the NFL. And
so, Moss, for one, believes the Vikings' promise is limitless.
</P>
<P>
   ``We should be 16-0,'' the brash receiver said. ``We can't
really be satisfied with what we've done so far. Everybody's goal
is the Super Bowl. Simple as that. If we don't get there, it'll
just be a big disappointment for the second year in a row. But if
we get there, we'll make a lot of things happen.''
</P>
<P>
   Cunningham could not make it happen for the Minnesota offense as
he did in 1998, but George has. George waited patiently and,
significantly, without disruption. When coach Dennis Green pulled
the plug on Cunningham, George injected some power into a
high-voltage unit.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're peaking at the right time,'' George said.
</P>
<P>
   But it does not mean they've reached maximum efficiency. Moss
said last year's loss prevents any contentment. The Vikings have
the physical talent to prevail. Defensively, John Randle moved back
to defensive tackle and has solidified that unit.
</P>
<P>
   ``We still have some things we have to work on,'' veteran Chirs
Doleman said. ``We're not a complete package. But guys have been
working hard. Right now, it's just starting to show up.''
</P>
<P>
   After last year, it's more about the way they approach the
prospects than anything else, according to Moss.
</P>
<P>
   ``As far as our momentum and the desire and being hungry to go
out there and fight for a championship, I don't think we're there
yet,'' Moss said. ``It's about how bad we want it.''
</P>
<P>
   Moss said he wants it so much that he'll take the responsibility
as the team's leader. It's very likely that the Cowboys' Deion
Sanders will defend against him today in a highly anticipated
glamour matchup.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think I'm prepared for it,'' said Moss, who had a
team-record 1,413 yards this season. ``Hopefully, they'll continue
to ride my shoulders all the way to the Super Bowl, man. I think
I'm just going to have to take that challenge and meet it.''
</P>
<P>
   The biggest challenge could be George's. His playoff experience
is nominal, and his reputation for having blow-up games is
solidified. That's why it's important for the Vikings to establish
a sound running game with Robert Smith.
</P>
<P>
   ``Being able to run is something you have to do in the
playoffs,'' George said.
</P>
<P>
   If the Vikings do as they believe they should, and run to the
Super Bowl, George returns to Atlanta as something many Falcon fans
thought he never would be: a winner.
</P>
<P>
   ``I can't think of a better scenario,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
