u s BC-FBN-AFC-NOTES09-COX     01-08 0610
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FBN-AFC-NOTES09-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Several key calls go against Buffalo
 &HT;    By Mark Schlabach
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   NASHVILLE, Tenn. _ The NFL brought back instant replay this
season so officials wouldn't blow critical plays in big games.
</P>
<P>
   Well, it doesn't get any bigger than the playoffs, but officials
may have dropped the ball in Saturday's AFC wild-card game at
Adelphia Coliseum.
</P>
<P>
   Besides Kevin Dyson's disputed 75-yard kickoff return, which
lifted the Titans to a 22-16 victory against the Bills, there also
were two other controversial plays.
</P>
<P>
   With the Bills trailing 9-0 late in the second quarter, Buffalo
quarterback Rob Johnson appeared to complete a long pass to rookie
Peerless Price down the right sideline.
</P>
<P>
   But line judge Byron Boston ruled that Price bobbled the ball
before falling out of bounds. Boston, father of Arizona Cardinals
receiver David Boston, is the official who was accused of nepotism
earlier this season by Washington receiver Michael Westbrook.
</P>
<P>
   This call didn't help the Cardinals, but it certainly hurt the
Bills.
</P>
<P>
   Television replays appeared to show that Price made the catch,
which would have given Buffalo a first down in Titans' territory
with 1:53 left in the half.
</P>
<P>
   But because Boston said Price bobbled the ball, replay official
Bob Boylston wasn't allowed to review the play under replay rules.
</P>
<P>
   ``In the first half, they wouldn't even review Peerless'
catch,'' Johnson said. ``He caught that ball, but I really can't
say where he was at.''
</P>
<P>
   The Bills were forced to punt, giving the Titans possession at
their 22-yard line.
</P>
<P>
   On the fifth play of the drive, Tennessee faced third-and-10 at
its 33. Titans quarterback Steve McNair faked a handoff and ran
around right end, gaining 9 yards before he was pulled down by
safety Henry Jones.
</P>
<P>
   Officials ruled that McNair was less than 1 yard short of a
first down. But after a replay delay of more than five minutes, the
ball was moved up a few inches, giving Tennessee a first down.
</P>
<P>
   Six plays later, the Titans took a 12-0 lead on Al Del Greco's
40-yard field goal as time expired in the half.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is why the system doesn't work,'' Bills general manager
John Butler said.
</P>
<P>
   SHOELESS JOHNSON
</P>
<P>
   Buffalo was forced to line up for Steve Christie's 41-yard field
goal with 16 seconds left, instead of taking a couple of shots at
the end zone. Christie made the kick, which gave the Bills a 16-15
lead.
</P>
<P>
   Two plays earlier, Buffalo had first-and-10 at the Tennessee 35.
Johnson ran around left end for a 3-yard gain, but Titans defensive
tackle John Thornton pulled off the quarterback's right shoe.
</P>
<P>
   The Bills were out of timeouts, so Johnson didn't have enough
time to put the shoe back on. On second down, Johnson completed a
9-yard pass to Price for a first down _ while wearing only one
shoe.
</P>
<P>
   ``We didn't have any timeouts. Our quarterback didn't have a
shoe,'' Bills coach Wade Phillips said. ``We decided we need to go
ahead and kick the field goal because we had a chance to win the
game. I didn't want to risk him slipping or something like that.''
</P>
<P>
   REED'S FAREWELL?
</P>
<P>
   Bills receiver Andre Reed, who criticized the team and
quarterback Doug Flutie last week, finished the game without a
catch. Reed has been critical of his lack of involvement on offense
this season, his 15th with Buffalo.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'd love to come back here next year,'' Reed said. ``I don't
know if that's going to happen. Right now, I don't know whether I'm
a part of this team in the future. It sure didn't look like it
today.''
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
