<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-01-08 19:51 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A0476 &Cx1f; ttx-z
r s BC-FBN-GALLOWAY-COLUMN-T     01-08 0839
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FBN-GALLOWAY-COLUMN-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
DEFEAT TODAY WOULD LEAVE BLAME SQUARELY WITH GAILEY
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By RANDY GALLOWAY 
c.1999 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Chan Gailey has heard no glowing endorsements lately from the
owner. Gailey doesn't know about his job security status after
today.
</P>
<P>
   Let the Cowboys lose, even as a seven-point 'dog to the
Minnesota Vikings, and Jerry Jones' verdict could follow a natural
course, based on already a disappointing 8-8 regular season.
</P>
<P>
   Does Gailey think about his neck being on the line today? That
the wild-card round of the playoffs could push him into the
coaching no-no land of the fired?
</P>
<P>
   ``Does it ever enter my mind? Sure,'' answered Gailey. ``But is
it anything more than a passing thought? No.
</P>
<P>
   ``If I'm dwelling on that, then I'm not preparing properly for
Minnesota. I would never allow that to happen.''
</P>
<P>
   With Gailey, you can believe every word of the above. He is,
without question, the good soldier, the good company man, the
zoned-in-tuned-out-on-distractions kind of coach that every
football boss will kill for.
</P>
<P>
   Gailey does not put his private thoughts _ pro or con _ on the
street. Nor does he put ``any'' company business on the street.
Gailey is not nearly as boring as his public perception _ what he
says to the media is exactly what he wants you to know about the
Cowboys or about Chan Gailey. Nothing.
</P>
<P>
   All of this makes Gailey the perfect coach to work under the
large shadow Jones want to cast. Except ...
</P>
<P>
   The results aren't there. Gailey's offensive philosophy has come
under question, and rightfully so. He was hired two years ago to
put points on the board. Then there's the seasonlong disaster with
penalties. It has been a team consumed by yellow hankies. This is a
direct reflection on the head coach. So is the 8-8 record.
</P>
<P>
   Therefore, the public criticism of Gailey has reached the
immense stage.
</P>
<P>
   ``To say you don't hear it and it doesn't affect you a little
bit would be a lie,'' he replied. ``But again, if I let it get to
me personally, then it impacts my job. My responsibility is to not
get caught up in the other stuff.''
</P>
<P>
   Coaching the Cowboys may be the hardest job in sports. The
spotlight is large and the expectations can be unreasonable, based
on the talent available. For example, some of the same media types
who in August were writing off the Cowboys as a .500 team are now
calling for Gailey's head. With a .500 record.
</P>
<P>
   Jones is certainly among those who allows expectations to exceed
football reality. But what owner doesn't? Jones, however, has gone
public lately with a demand from Gailey for a change in offensive
philosophy, an indication the owner was blaming the coach. And also
an indication the owner is now meddling in football.
</P>
<P>
   Voices inside Valley Ranch say Gailey brought this meddling on
himself with an unwillingness to listen to offensive coaching staff
members who suggested ideas different from the head coach.
</P>
<P>
   ``Hard-headed'' is the criticism.
</P>
<P>
   ``There is a certain amount of truth to that,'' said Gailey,
``but also some untruth. I believe in listening, and in using new
ideas as long as they stay with the parameters of the base offense.
</P>
<P>
   ``But if those ideas get too far out there, then you would be
changing everything, including blocking schemes. I don't think you
can go that far.''
</P>
<P>
   For obvious reasons, quarterback Troy Aikman has a strong
presence in all things having to do with the Cowboys' offense.
There have been constant theories from many, including Fox analyst
Terry Bradshaw, that the Gailey offense is not best-suited for
Aikman's talents.
</P>
<P>
   To shorten a long football explanation, Aikman is considered an
aggressive, go-right-after-a-defense kind of quarterback, using
downfield slant patterns and 15- to 20-yard ``outs.'' Gailey's
offense is more about deception, or ``trick 'em.''
</P>
<P>
   By the way, Gailey disgrees with that definition of his
offensive system. But while many have blamed Aikman's troubles this
season on his distrust of young receivers, that may be untrue.
Could it be he is struggling with the Gailey offense?
</P>
<P>
   ``Troy and I have talked about it, and shared ideas,'' said
Gailey. ``But there hasn't been any indication of a strong
displeasure on his part.''
</P>
<P>
   Aikman agrees with that, or at least he does in talking to the
media.
</P>
<P>
   Whatever the case, Jones hired Gailey two years ago after Jones
said he had carefully studied the offensive system Gailey would
bring to Dallas. Jerry called this offense a perfect fit for
Aikman. If it's not, then blame Jones.
</P>
<P>
   But, of course, if there's a loss today to the Vikings, Jerry's
blame will point elsewhere. Like right to Gailey.
</P>
<P>
   What about the notion Gailey already has made up his mind to
resign after this season, no matter what happens today in
Minnesota?
</P>
<P>
   ``It's one of those things that will cross your mind, but I'd
never do it,'' he said. ``I'm not going to quit.''
</P>
<P>
   So does it come down to win or be fired? Maybe. Probably. Stay
tuned.
nn
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
