</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FBN-BILLS-TITANS09-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Disputed play lifts Titans in a stunner
 &HT;    By Mark Schlabach
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   NASHVILLE, Tenn. _ So much for the Immaculate Reception.
</P>
<P>
   Titans receiver Kevin Dyson's 75-yard kickoff return for a
touchdown, which stunned the Buffalo Bills 22-16 in Saturday's AFC
wild-card game, may be remembered as the most disputed play in NFL
history.
</P>
<P>
   Just call it the Immaculate Deception.
</P>
<P>
   Dyson, a late substitute on the play, caught a lateral pass from
tight end Frank Wycheck, then ran down the left sideline behind a
wall of blockers, reaching the end zone for the game-winning score
with only three seconds left.
</P>
<P>
   ``We believe in miracles,'' Titans safety Blaine Bishop said.
``This is something special. It is unbelievable.''
</P>
<P>
   The victory sends Tennessee into next week's divisional
playoffs. If Seattle beats Miami in today's other AFC wild-card
game, the Titans will travel to Jacksonville. If the Dolphins win,
the Titans will play at Indianapolis.
</P>
<P>
   It took a miracle _ and inconclusive video evidence _ to keep
Tennessee alive in the march to Super Bowl XXXIV in Atlanta.
</P>
<P>
   ``It wasn't in the hands of the officials,'' Titans coach Jeff
Fisher said. ``It was higher up.''
</P>
<P>
   Indeed, for a few anxious moments, replay official Bob Boylston,
who sits above the field in the instant-replay booth, was deciding
the outcome of the game.
</P>
<P>
   Boylston and referee Phil Luckett reviewed Dyson's return,
questioning whether Wycheck's throw was a lateral. If Wycheck's
pass was thrown forward, it was illegal.
</P>
<P>
   But when Luckett returned to the field from behind the Titans'
bench, he announced the throw was legal, sending the record crowd
of 66,782 fans into delirium.
</P>
<P>
   ``The line judge's initial ruling was that it was not a forward
pass,'' Luckett said. ``We went to the instant replay. Taking from
where the pass left (Wycheck's) hand right on that yard line, the
receiver catches it right there on that yard line. It did not
appear to be a forward pass, therefore it is not a foul.''
</P>
<P>
   But the Bills were crying foul.
</P>
<P>
   ``I hope those referees that called this game never work another
one,'' Buffalo linebacker Gabe Northern said, ``because they'll do
something like that to somebody else.''
</P>
<P>
   Said Buffalo defensive end Marcellus Wiley: ``If I was sitting
in the Titans locker room, I'd by saying I'm lucky. It's one thing
to be opportunistic and fortunate, but that was just given to
them.''
</P>
<P>
   Buffalo, which had trailed the entire game, took a 16-15 lead on
kicker Steve Christie's 41-yard field goal with 16 seconds left.
</P>
<P>
   Titans fullback Lorenzo Neal fielded the ensuing kickoff in a
group of Tennessee players and then handed the ball off to Wycheck
near the 25-yard line.
</P>
<P>
   Wycheck took two steps, then threw the ball toward the left
sideline to Dyson, who took a step back.
</P>
<P>
   ``It worked to perfection,'' Wycheck said of the play, called
``Home Run Throwback.'' ``It was like being a little kid again,
drawing something up in the dirt and then going out and doing it,''
Wycheck said.
</P>
<P>
   Dyson, a second-year pro from Utah, was near the 25-yard line
when Wycheck threw. Whether he was in front of or behind the line
will be debated forever.
</P>
<P>
   ``I saw Frank catch the ball,'' Dyson said. ``I wasn't supposed
to catch the lateral. It was supposed to be (receiver Isaac Byrd).
I made sure I got behind (Wycheck). I took one hard step out to
make sure it was a lateral. I was sure.''
</P>
<P>
   The play recalled another memorable playoff play in 1972.
Pittsburgh defeated Oakland in the first round when Franco Harris
caught a deflected pass from Terry Bradshaw for the decisive
touchdown in the final seconds. It went down in NFL history as the
Immaculate Reception.
</P>
<P>
   It was the first touchdown on a kickoff return for the Titans
since 1988, when they were the Houston Oilers, and the first
kickoff return ever for Dyson, who was replacing two other players
slated for that job on the play.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's crazy,'' Christie said. ``I can't believe it. They had a
wall of blockers, and I knew I couldn't get to him. When I saw
that, my heart started to sink.
</P>
<P>
   ``I knew there was no way anyone was going to get him.''
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
