<SLUG> BC-FBN-NFC-NOTES09-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Several 'Skins to miss Bucs matchup
 &HT;    By Matt Winkeljohn
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   LANDOVER, Md. _ The Redskins had no trouble beating the Lions
Saturday afternoon.
</P>
<P>
   Next Saturday's divisional playoff game at Tampa Bay figures to
be a much different story, especially if running back Stephen Davis
and two of his offensive linemen miss the game.
</P>
<P>
   The Redskins are certain to be without left tackle Andy Heck,
who tore a hamstring in the first quarter at FedEx Field. He was
replaced by fifth-year pro Kip Vickers.
</P>
<P>
   Davis sprained his right knee in the second quarter, after
rushing for 119 yards and two touchdowns on his first 15 carries.
</P>
<P>
   On a 1-yard run, Davis got leg-whipped by Lions free safety Mark
Carrier, and then middle linebacker Stephen Boyd rolled across him.
</P>
<P>
   In the third quarter, with the Redskins leading 27-0, Boyd
intercepted a Brad Johnson pass, and as Boyd returned it, Detroit
Pro Bowl defensive end Robert Porcher went after Johnson.
</P>
<P>
   They got in a scrap, and as they grappled to the earth referee
Bob McElwee got knocked down.
</P>
<P>
   As several players from both sides went at it, Washington Pro
Bowl right guard Tre Johnson swang his right arm like an axe, and
whacked back judge Bill Leavy in the process.
</P>
<P>
   That got him ejected, and it could earn him a suspension by the
NFL office for next week.
</P>
<P>
   HIGH COMEDY
</P>
<P>
   It would be a tough call deciding who had a tougher go of it
Saturday, the Lions or the officiating crew.
</P>
<P>
   With 9:57 left in the third quarter, McElwee's microphone got
stuck in the ``on'' position, and people in the stadium and Shirley
Povich press box were privy to about four minutes of unusual
conversation.
</P>
<P>
   Usually, the microphone is turned on only when the referee is
announcing a penalty, ruling or key substitution.
</P>
<P>
   At one point, McElwee and head linesman Terry Gierke were
discussing the fight, and unbeknownst to McElwee, everybody was
listening _ and laughing.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't have the number of the guy,'' McElwee said. ``Then, we
got this clown (Johnson).''
</P>
<P>
   Somebody on the sideline ran on the field and told McElwee his
mike was stuck on. He said, ``OK,'' but the fiasco continued.
</P>
<P>
   He got ticked.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is ridiculous,'' he said, with 7:25 left in the period.
``I can't work ...''
</P>
<P>
   The problem was soon fixed.
</P>
<P>
   SERIOUS BUSINESS
</P>
<P>
   FedEx Field was sold out, and in fact fans seeking season
tickets _ and the playoff ticket privileges that come with them _
spend years on a waiting list before qualifying to buy season
tickets.
</P>
<P>
   It was hard to tell the game was soldout, though, as officials
estimated some 10,000 fans were delayed because there was a suicide
attempt on nearby Wilson Bridge, over the Potomac River.
</P>
<P>
   Traffic was halted both ways.
</P>
<P>
   EXTRA POINTS
</P>
<P>
   A pair of Georgia natives helped the Redskins. Rookie cornerback
Champ Bailey, Washington's first-round draft choice out of the
University of Georgia, and a native of Folkston, Ga., had an
interception in the first quarter. That led to the first of two
first-half field goals by kicker Brett Conway, who was a soccer
star seven years ago at Parkview High School in Lilburn.... On
Vickers' first play, he threw the key block, on Detroit defensive
end Tracy Scroggins, to spring Davis on a franchise-record 58-yard
run off left tackle. That tied the 58-yard run by former Washington
running back Timmy Smith in Super Bowl XXII for the longest in
Redskins' post-season history.... The Lions had fits with crowd
noise Saturday, much as the Redskins had problems with crowd noise
in the SilverDome when they lost 33-17 at Detroit Dec. 5. In that
game, nine of Washington's 14 penalties were on the offensive line,
either holding, or jumping offsides. The Lions held or jumped
offsides six times in the first three quarters Saturday....
Attendance was announced at 79,411, a Redskins record, but there
were never that many fans in the house.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
