<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-REEVES-COLUMN-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
MAVS' OWNER-TO-BE NEEDS TO KISS NELLIE ADIOS
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By JIM REEVES 
c.1999 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   FORT WORTH _ When Mark Cuban phoned the house to introduce
himself Thursday _ an unprecedented move by a sports owner in more
than 30 years of sports coverage in this area _ my first thought
was that he'd somehow made a mistake and was about to yell at me
for that morning's column.
</P>
<P>
   You know, the one where colleague Randy Galloway welcomed the
Mavericks' new ``Yahoo'' to town. It dang sure wouldn't be the
first time Galloway got me into trouble.
</P>
<P>
   My second thought was that this was probably the first
billionaire who'd ever called just to say hello, a suspicion
confirmed by a quick scan of Caller ID. Nope, no other billionaires
on there.
</P>
<P>
   No question about it, Cuban is an original.
</P>
<P>
   He just wanted to say hello and invite me to the Mavericks Club
before the Mavs' game with Utah on Thursday night to have a cold
one. I was on the list with a number of local media wags. I
couldn't make it, but Cuban obviously knows the way to a sports
writer's heart.
</P>
<P>
   And if he overpaid for the Mavs, who cares? It's his money. Easy
come, easy go.
</P>
<P>
   But I just can't help offering one piece of advice: Kiss Nellie
goodbye and be done with it.
</P>
<P>
   Don't repeat the mistake the Mavs made when they hired Jim
Cleamons as coach, ``then'' Don Nelson as GM. If Nelson isn't going
to be the long-term general manager here, then get rid of him, hire
a capable new man and let him hire the coach. That way you get a
tandem on the same page with, hopefully, the same philosophies.
</P>
<P>
   Allowing Nelson, who will happily pad his bank account at the
Mavs' expense as long as they let him, to bring in a new coach
would be a disaster. In fact, if Nelson's going to stick around,
I'd keep him as coach and hire a new GM to run the team. It's his
decisions and judgment as a general manager that should get Nelson
fired, not his coaching.
</P>
<P>
   Naturally, Cuban didn't exactly ask for the advice when he
phoned but hey, it's no problem. What are friends for?  &LR; subheds:A
TIDY PROFIT  &LR; body:Mark Cuban will make some of the Mavs' wealthy
investors even richer once his offer to buy the club is approved by
the NBA. One minority stockholder who invested about $1.5 million,
for instance, will walk away with a cool $8.5 million off this
deal.
</P>
<P>
   But not everyone will take the money and run. Don Carter, the
team's original owner, still holds just over 4 percent of the club.
He could take Cuban's check for almost $10 million and walk, but he
has advised the team's new owner-to-be that he intends to hold onto
his stock.
</P>
<P>
   Maybe Carter figures Cuban will make him even more money in the
long run. Or maybe his Mavs' ties just run too deep.  &LR; subheds:WHEN
HE SPEAKS ...  &LR; body:Rafael Palmeiro is emerging as the Rangers'
vocal leader and conscience, unafraid to speak his mind for what he
feels is best for the team. Not only was he pushing hard for the
Rangers to re-sign pitcher Aaron Sele to the end but he said of the
Todd Zeile situation: ``I'm not sure what happened. But one thing I
can say, if we were going to sign him, we should have signed him
sooner. I'm not sure what approach they took but the same thing
happened in Baltimore with me. I said all along I wanted to remain
in Baltimore and the earlier they try to sign me, the better chance
they had. I told \Rowner Peter\S Angelos that but he waited and
waited and I ended up back here with the Rangers.''
</P>
<P>
   Are you listening, Doug Melvin? There's something wrong when
Sele winds up signing with a team that has a state income tax for
just $1 million more over four years than what the Rangers were
offering. Either his agent messed up badly (not out of the
question) or the GM did. How about it?  &LR; subheds:LINEUP CONCERNS
 &LR; body:There's no question that the Rangers' lineup, as it currently
stacks up, presents some major concerns. Melvin is worried about
the overall on-base percentage of the team (Palmeiro and Rusty
Greer are the only ones with decent numbers in that category) and
manager Johnny Oates is concerned about who will protect Palmeiro
in the middle of the order. One solution could be to bat Palmeiro
third and Ivan Rodriguez fourth.
</P>
<P>
   Greer is willing to bat leadoff, and the Rangers like the fact
that he collects a lot of doubles and has a high on-base
percentage. But he doesn't want to bat leadoff against
right-handers, then drop to the middle of the order when Chad
Curtis bats leadoff against left-handers.
</P>
<P>
   One solution to the leadoff situation is to play Curtis every
day against both LHP and RHP and trade Lee Stevens. But Melvin said
he doesn't want to do that after losing both Juan Gonzalez and
Zeile in the off-season.
</P>
<P>
   What the Rangers need is for either Ruben Mateo, Gabe Kapler or
Mike Lamb to have a breakthrough season and become a force in the
fifth spot in the batting order.  &LR; subheds:FAMILIAR ACE  &LR; body:Kenny
Rogers still believes he can be a No. 1 pitcher and is willing to
take that role and match up with other teams' aces.
</P>
<P>
   ``I got a chance to beat them more than anybody,'' Rogers said,
which may tell you all you need to know about the Rangers'
rotation.  &LR; subheds:CALL HIM MACK OSTRICH  &LR; body:Talk about burying
your head and hiding, Texas coach Mack Brown did just that
regarding the suspensions of four players before the Cotton Bowl.
Brown adamantly refused to provide details of the suspensions,
hiding behind the Buckley Amendment, which protects the release of
information regarding students (UT is currently embroiled in two
lawsuits for just such violations). Keeping the lid on so tight
only fueled more speculation and rumor. Both teams were given
random drug tests before the game, in accordance with NCAA rules.
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile, all-Big 12 receiver Kwame Cavil has announced he'll
move on to the NFL after setting school records for receptions and
yards (1,188) as a junior.
</P>
<P>
   Word on the street in Austin is that the other two underclassmen
involved, defensive end J.J. Kelly and reserve linebacker Jamal
Joyner, may not be back for spring drills and could transfer
elsewhere.
</P>
<P>
   At his news conference Thursday, Cavil wished the Longhorns
luck, and said he ``honestly believe they will make a run at a
national championship in the very near future.'' Come again? Since
the Cotton Bowl this team has lost its leading TD scorer (Chris
Robertson), its record-setting receiver (Cavil) and its
record-setting quarterback (Major Applewhite) to major knee
surgery.
</P>
<P>
   Not exactly the best way to kick off a national championship
run.  &LR; subheds:FRAN THE MAN  &LR; body:Interesting, isn't it, that of the
four schools TCU head coach Dennis Franchione can opt out of his
contract for should they come calling, two _ Notre Dame and Arizona
State _ could be in big trouble next year. New coach kind of
trouble.
</P>
<P>
   You don't think Fran would be a huge hit at Notre Dame, do you?
Keep an eye on this situation.  &LR; subheds:AUTHOR! AUTHOR!  &LR; body:Just
when Jim Dent, author of ``The Junction Boys,'' has landed himself
a real job again _ sports columnist at the ``San Antonio
Express-News'' _ comes word that he's also landed a contract to
write a book about Oklahoma's 47-game winning streak under Bud
Wilkinson from 1954-57.  &LR; subheds:KLIF MASSACRE  &LR; body:Norm Hitzges'
run at KLIF/AM 570 ended almost exactly 15 years to the day he
started his morning sports talk show there on Jan. 8, 1985. His
departure _ his last show is Tuesday morning _ leaves WBAP's Randy
Galloway with the longest running sports talk show at the same
venue. Galloway has been at WBAP for 15 years, too, but started
there shortly after Hitzges, who is moving into the 10 a.m.-noon
slot on KTCK/AM 1310, arrived at KLIF.
</P>
<P>
   The KLIF move away from sports _ the station terminated Hitzges'
partner, Leon Simon and evening sports talk hosts Wally Lynn and
Mike Fisher _ wasn't totally unexpected. The station has not been
doing well in the ratings for some time and there was concern that
its sports shows were competing against those of sister station
KTCK, three floors down in the same building. Rumors had abounded
for the past couple of years that changes were being considered.
</P>
<P>
   Dropping sports talk, however, is not good for the consumer, any
more than the death of the ``Dallas Times Herald'' was good for the
newspaper business. We're never better off when our options are
narrowed and competition is limited.
</P>
<P>
   Lynn and Fisher say they intend to start up some sort of sports
talk show over the Internet through connections with Mark Cuban's
Broadcast.com. Simon hasn't indicated whether he'll attempt to stay
in the radio business. \Ntagtop:Jim Reeves, (817) 390-7760
\Ntagbottom:revo\Nstar-telegram.com
</P>
<P>
   &LR; subheds:REVO'S RIMSHOTS  &LR; agatea: YAKETTY YAK: With Norm Hitzges
moving from KLIF to KTCK, you think this means The Ticket is going
back to sports talk?
</P>
<P>
   YANKEE BEATER? He failed miserably trying to pitch for the
Yankees in the playoffs two years ago. He walked in the winning run
in the deciding game while pitching for the Mets against the Braves
last October. Surely the Rangers aren't trying to tell us that the
man they expect to make the difference next October, in front of
60,000 screaming lunatics at Yankee Stadium, is Kenny Rogers. Are
they?
</P>
<P>
   SOMETHING'S ROTTEN SOMEWHERE: The Rangers wanted Aaron Sele and
Todd Zeile back next season. Instead, when state income taxes are
figured in, both will make less money playing next year somewhere
besides Texas. Maybe Doug Melvin needs to try a different mouthwash
or deodorant or something.
</P>
<P>
   OFF HIS ROCKER: So baseball wants John Rocker to undergo
psychological testing after his ridiculous statements in ``Sports
Illustrated'' a few weeks ago. Gee, can we get Albert Belle and
Kevin Brown on that list, too? And can I volunteer for the job? I
think I can get a rubber stamp made up that says ``Idiot'` without
too much trouble.
</P>
<P>
   CALL IT CHARACTER: Philadelphia guard Allen Iverson is
complaining that he was left off the U.S. Olympic basketball team
because of his image. Gee, you think so? Maybe he should have
thought of that when he was cultivating his ``bad boy'' image.
</P>
