<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-01-08 20:16 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A0482 &Cx1f; taf-z
u s BC-FBN-TITANS-BILLS-NYT &LR;      01-08 0912
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FBN-TITANS-BILLS-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
TITANS BEAT BILLS, 22-16  
 (HLW) 
</HEADLINE>
   By THOMAS GEORGE   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NASHVILLE, Tenn. _ The play was the most familiar and folksy of
backyard, old-school calls _ the old across-the-field lateral on a
kickoff with 16 seconds remaining _ and it left the Buffalo Bills
in shambles and lifted the Tennessee Titans to a dramatic,
thumping, 22-16 wild-card playoff victory before 66,782 fans on
Saturday at Adelphia Coliseum.
</P>
<P>
   Many who saw it still cannot believe it.
</P>
<P>
   ``What a play!'' said Tennessee's Bruce Matthews.
</P>
<P>
   What a game. What a show. What victory. What a loss.
</P>
<P>
   ``What can you say?'' asked Tennessee's Eddie George.
</P>
<P>
   Plenty.
</P>
<P>
   Tennessee won the game with three seconds left on a 75-yard
kickoff return for a touchdown by receiver Kevin Dyson. In a fourth
quarter that featured four lead changes, Tennessee thought it had
the game won when it kicked a 36-yard field goal with 1 minute 48
seconds left to lead by 15-13. Buffalo thought it had it won when
Steve Christie made a 41-yard field goal with 16 seconds left to
lead by 16-15.
</P>
<P>
   But then Christie kicked off, Lorenzo Neal gathered the short
boot near the Tennessee 25, ran toward his right and then handed
the ball off to teammate Frank Wycheck. Wycheck, a tight end, spun
and threw the ball across the field to Dyson. Dyson caught the low
toss and took off down the left sideline with a convoy of blockers.
Buffalo was completely fooled, its players a few steps behind
Dyson, and he raced 75 yards into the end zone. The play took 13
seconds, but the big question _ did Wycheck throw a forward pass to
Dyson? _ would be answered by instant replay.
</P>
<P>
   Referee Phil Luckett studied the play at his sideline replay
booth while players and coaches from both teams stood and paced on
the field, waiting. The clock said :03. It seemed as if Luckett was
taking three days to decide.
</P>
<P>
   What would he rule?
</P>
<P>
   ``I was talking to No. 25 on their team while we waited,'' said
the Titans' Anthony Dorsett of Buffalo's Donovan Greer. ``We both
were saying: `This is crazy. What if it's our way? What if its your
way?' Nobody knew what to expect.''
</P>
<P>
   The Bills' owner, Ralph Wilson, said he did.
</P>
<P>
   ``When it went from the replay booth into the hands of the
officials on the field, I knew we were through _ and you can print
that,'' Wilson said.
</P>
<P>
   Luckett finally appeared and said the play stood as called.
Touchdown.
</P>
<P>
   Tennessee (14-3) wins. Buffalo (11-6) loses. Tennessee marches
on in the playoffs. The Buffalo season is finished.
</P>
<P>
   Luckett is no stranger to controversy. In 1998, he was involved
in two decisions that accelerated the return of instant replay this
season _ the botched overtime coin toss between the Lions and
Steelerson Thanksgiving and the phantom Vinny Testaverde touchdown
against Seattle.
</P>
<P>
   He explained: ``The line judge's initial ruling was that it was
not a forward pass. We went to the instant replay. Taking from
where the pass left the passer's hand right on that yard line, the
receiver catches it right there on that yard line. It did not
appear to be a forward pass, therefore there is not a foul.''
</P>
<P>
   Luckett said the key in his ruling is not where the players
involved in the lateral were standing but the points from where the
ball was thrown to where it was touched. It was a lateral, he said.
Case closed. Game over.
</P>
<P>
   That was not good enough for Buffalo.
</P>
<P>
   ``Everybody knew that was illegal _ it was a forward pass,''
said cornerback Thomas Smith.
</P>
<P>
   ``They know they didn't beat us; we beat them,'' said defensive
lineman Marcellus Wiley. ``We didn't lose; we just got taken. I
could be fined next week. But thanks to this mess, we don't play
next week, either.''
</P>
<P>
   The Tennessee sideline had a different perspective. ``I saw no
flags and that's when I celebrated,'' quarterback Steve McNair
said.
</P>
<P>
   ``What a beautiful thing!'' Neal said.
</P>
<P>
   Stunned and stung. That was the Bills.
</P>
<P>
   ``I hate leaving things to chance and we did that the whole
day,'' said defensive end Bruce Smith. ``That being said, it's sad
to have a game come down to the officials _ and that's  &UR; with &LR; 
instant replay.''
</P>
<P>
   ``It's just not real,'' Wiley said. ``That ball was thrown
forward. I'm depressed. I wish Tennessee the best. I wish them the
worst.''
</P>
<P>
   Tennessee led by 12-0 at halftime. Buffalo needed a swift
momentum change and got it in the third quarter when it scored on
an Antowain Smith 4-yard run fewer than three minutes into the
second half. The Buffalo defense shut out Tennessee in the third
quarter, so Buffalo entered the final 15 minutes trailing by 12-7.
</P>
<P>
   And then it swiped the lead. And lost it. And grabbed it back
again. And then lost it for good.
</P>
<P>
   ``I've seen a lot of them, but I haven't seen one like that
before,'' Wade Phillips, Buffalo's head coach, said of the final
play. ``I thought we played well enough to win. We had a heck of a
year. It's a shame it had to end this way because I though we
outplayed them, especially in the second half when we settled
down.''
</P>
<P>
   A lateral. On a kickoff. The winning touchdown on a play called
Homerun Throwback.
</P>
<P>
   ``There's something to be said about destiny and belief and
expectation,'' said Jeff Fisher, the Tennessee head coach. ``We say
those things all year. We had them even when things looked gloomy.
My heart goes out to the other locker room right now, but our
players and our fans, they deserve this.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
