r s BC-HKN-NHL-REPORT-TEX     01-08 1275
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-HKN-NHL-REPORT-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
STICKS NO PROBLEM, BUT WORDS SEEM TO BE
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By JENNIFER FLOYD 
c.1999 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   ``Congress shall make no law respecting an establishment of
religion, or prohibiting the free exercise thereof; OR ABRIDGING
THE FREEDOM OF SPEECH, or of the press; or of the right of the
people peaceably to assemble, and to petition the government for a
redress of grievances.''
</P>
<P>
   Congress doesn't have to. The NHL, just like Major League
Baseball, will.
</P>
<P>
   Maybe, you've heard that NHL commissioner Gary Bettman insisted
Ottawa Senators forward Vaclav Prospal attend sensitivity training
because during a game he called Montreal Canadiens defenseman
Patrice Brisebois, a  &LR; %!&AMP; frog.
</P>
<P>
   The problem? The word frog.
</P>
<P>
   It's considered a racial slur by some French Canadians, as
volatile as the N-word is to most black Americans. In
precedent-setting decisions, the NHL has suspended players in the
past for use of the N-word toward black players.
</P>
<P>
   First things first, Prospal shouldn't have said it. Just as
there shouldn't be any racist or sexist comments in any workplace.
Just as there shouldn't be breast cancer. Just as athletes
shouldn't make more than teachers.
</P>
<P>
   Unfortunately, the world isn't perfect, and sometimes people say
things that aren't nice.
</P>
<P>
   But what we are forgetting is that, unlike cancer or salary
inequity, these are just words. Their ability to hurt comes only
from the credence we give to the person saying them.
</P>
<P>
   Racial slurs, sexist comments, they reflect poorly on the person
using them, not the person or persons whom they are about. Yet,
every time we react to the rantings of a person like Atlanta Braves
pitcher John Rocker or a slur by Prospal we do just that.
</P>
<P>
   What the NHL and Major League Baseball should do, not that
either asked, is ignore the words. What the Prospals and Rockers of
the world will find is while the Constitution protects their right
to say whatever they want, it says nothing about the public's
reaction.
</P>
<P>
   Public and not-so-public opinion, and there are a lot of French
Canadians in the NHL, are a lot more persuasive than some
$100-an-hour class on being sensitive. Many have suggested that
Brisebois should've just turned around and slashed Prospal. End of
problem.
</P>
<P>
   Deliver a stick to the face. Two minutes in the penalty box.
</P>
<P>
   Say something mean. It's off to New York for sensitivity
training.
</P>
<P>
   And does the NHL really expect us to believe that racial slurs
are more dangerous than the kind of stick work that goes on during
the course of your average NHL game?
</P>
<P>
   Obviously, yes.
</P>
<P>
   Well, at least, the NHL hasn't totally discounted the whole
Constitution thing. They like that Second Amendment.
</P>
<P>
   ``A well-regulated militia, being necessary to the security of a
free state, THE RIGHT OF THE PEOPLE TO KEEP AND BEAR ARMS, shall
not be infringed.''
</P>
<P>
   Sticks and stones may break players' bones, but according to the
NHL, it's words that really hurt.
Shawn Baldwin A little more offense would make a great sport even
better, says Pittsburgh Penguins legend Mario Lemieux.
A hero of the game predicts a bright future for hockey Pittsburgh
Penguins legend Mario Lemieux nabbed just about every award
possible while playing hockey.
</P>
<P>
   Stanley Cups, Hart Trophies, you name it. He won it.
</P>
<P>
   Lemieux, along with Lou Vairo, director of special projects for
U.S.A. Hockey, and Penguins general manager Craig Patrick, added
another honor to his packed resume. All were recipients of this
year's Lester Patrick Trophy for outstanding service to hockey in
the United States.
</P>
<P>
   ``I have won a few awards in my career throughout my career on
the ice, but this one is very special since I have been on the
business side for a few months now,'' Lemieux said. ``So I am very
excited about it.''
</P>
<P>
   For what feat did he owe the pleasure of this award?
</P>
<P>
   Nothing short of the tiny task of saving hockey in Pittsburgh.
When he bought the team, they were broke and U-Haul looked to be
the next call. Now, they are once again Lemieux's Penguins. Only,
he has a receipt to prove it.
</P>
<P>
   So where does he see hockey heading now?
</P>
<P>
   ``In the near future, this could be the most exciting game in
the world, and from my perspective I feel that it is right now,''
Lemieux said. ``But we can always improve our game by, what I have
been preaching for the last five or six years, having more offense
in the game; letting our star players display their talent to their
full potential.''
</P>
<P>
   It's one thing when your random, average NHL players say that
there is too much clutching and grabbing. It's quite another when
Mario Lemieux says it. After all, part of the reason he chose to
retire when he did was he didn't like the direction the game was
headed.
</P>
<P>
   He says it's getting better. He says it needs to get even
better.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think we have to do a better job as a league to protect our
star players and to promote them, like they did in basketball with
Michael Jordan and the way they do it in football with the
quarterbacks and the receivers,'' Lemieux said. ``They protect the
offense and the players that sell their game and it only makes
sense.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think we have to do a better job as owners and GMs and
players to realize that; and if we do, I think hockey is going to
be much better in the future.''
</P>
<P>
   For what he has done and he continues to do for hockey in the
states, there can never been enough awards for Mario Lemieux.
\Nsubheds:around the east If his chemotherapy treatments go well,
Philadelphia Flyers coach Roger Neilson will be in Toronto for
All-Star weekend.
</P>
<P>
   Neilson has been selected as an assistant to Maple Leafs coach
Pat Quinn on the North American All-Star squad. A week later,
Neilson is scheduled to have a bone marrow stem cell transplant,
sidelining him for at least six weeks. He has a leukemia-like
cancer that attacks plasma in bone marrow, generating malignant
blood cells.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's been a long time since I've been there \Rto All-Star
weekend\S, so I'm excited about it,'' Neilson said. ``If everything
the doctor says is right and if it continues this way, I'm planning
on going.''
</P>
<P>
   So, Carolina owner Peter Karmanos said he doesn't want to
contribute to escalating salaries in the NHL. That's why he isn't
caving into salary demands of restricted free agent Keith Primeau
and why he supposedly nixed a trade of Primeau for Coyotes forward
Keith Tkachuk. Tkachuk's $8.3 million contract next season is
``stupid,'' he says.
</P>
<P>
   So, why did he sign Detroit forward Sergei Fedorov to an offer
sheet worth $12 million for less than a half of a season that the
Red Wings were forced to match?
</P>
<P>
   \Nsubheds:Around the West How often is it that you hear the
general manager of a team sounding like the fans on talk radio?
</P>
<P>
   Just listen to Vancouver Canucks GM Brian Burke:
</P>
<P>
   ``I put the blame on the players,'' Burke told the ``Vancouver
Province''. ``I see a lot of guys making a lot of money and not
playing well.''
</P>
<P>
   Nashville goalie Tomas Vokoun was demoted not once, but twice,
to the Predators' minor-league affiliate in Milwaukee. Let's just
say the demotions got his attention.
</P>
<P>
   He was 0-8-1 with a 3.54 goals-against average before getting
demoted.
</P>
<P>
   He is 4-1-1 since his return, the lone loss in that stretch
coming against the Stars.
</P>
<P>
   ``Well, it's just like the beginning of the season,'' Vokoun
told the ``Nashville Tennessean''. ``If someone had told me I
wasn't going to get my first win for a couple of months, I'd have
said: `You're crazy.' You never know what is going to happen, and
that's the beauty of the game.''
</P>
<P>
</P>
