<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BKN-MAVERICKS-OWNER-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
WITH NEW OWNER, MAVERICKS HOPE THE DOMINOES FALL FOR THE GOOD
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By DWAIN PRICE 
c.1999 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   DALLAS _ The theory goes that a new owner will bring in a new
president, who will go find a new general manager, who will hire a
new coach, who will draft new players.
</P>
<P>
   It's all still theory for Mavericks owner-in-waiting Mark Cuban,
but one of the most memorable weeks in the team's 20-year history
ended with everyone _ management, coaches, players, fans, the NBA _
wondering if Cuban will make the dominoes fall in the coming
months.
</P>
<P>
   Cuban admits he is too busy delighting in his latest trinket _
the pending purchase of the Mavericks for $280 million _ to rock
anybody's world just yet. ``I don't want to blow this thing up,''
he said. ``I don't know enough about the NBA business to just come
in here and make a lot of changes.''
</P>
<P>
   Even outgoing Mavericks owner Ross Perot Jr. said changes are
inevitable, especially for an organization that posted the worst
winning percentage in all of professional sports during the 1990s.
The potential for change is part of the buzz Cuban, 41, has
generated, a buzz not heard from the Mavericks since the 1980s,
when the franchise was battling the Los Angeles Lakers for Western
Conference supremacy.
</P>
<P>
   ``How exciting would it be to hit the winning jumper in the NCAA
basketball tournament?'' Cuban said. ``That's not even half as
excited as I am now.''
</P>
<P>
   Cuban will benefit from the NBA's new television contract
starting next season and a new arena, the American Airlines Center,
in 2001. The team's roster also includes at least two players,
guard Michael Finley and forward Dirk Nowitzki, other NBA teams
covet.
</P>
<P>
   It will be up to Cuban to put the pieces together, including a
team president, general manager, coach and players _ even new
uniforms.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think he's going to be a fabulous owner,'' said Terdema
Ussery, the Mavericks' president and chief executive officer.
``He's a guy who is going to bring a lot of innovative ideas into
this business that's going to benefit not only us, the Dallas
Mavericks, but the whole league.
</P>
<P>
   ``He has incredible energy, and he has a laser focus on the
things that he turns his attention to. He has infused the
organization with a mission and a passion to succeed.''
</P>
<P>
   Ussery and coach/general manager Don Nelson will have two years
remaining on their contract after this season. For now, Cuban said
Nelson will be the team's GM next season. However, Nelson said this
week neither he nor his son Donnie, an assistant, will coach the
Mavericks next season.
</P>
<P>
   One possible coaching candidate might be Isiah Thomas, a star at
Indiana University, where Cuban went to college. As GM, Thomas
helped the Toronto Raptors acquire a talent base that once included
Damon Stoudamire, Marcus Camby, John Wallace and Walt Williams, and
currently includes Tracy McGrady and Doug Christie. The Raptors, an
expansion team in 1995, came within one victory of reaching the
playoffs last season.
</P>
<P>
   Thomas is commissioner of the Continental Basketball
Association, a sort of minor league for the NBA.
</P>
<P>
   ``My dream is just like every other CBA player's dream, and
that's to get back in the NBA,'' Thomas said. ``If it's the right
situation with the right people, yeah, I'm interested in coaching
because I love basketball.''
</P>
<P>
   In addition to assembling a management team, Cuban knows his
mission to bring an NBA championship to Dallas also includes
acquiring quality players. He said he will spare no expense to add
players like Tim Duncan and Grant Hill, who become free agents this
summer.
</P>
<P>
   Several Mavericks might be playing their last season with the
team, including forward Gary Trent, who could opt to become a free
agent this summer.
</P>
<P>
   When asked about center Shawn Bradley during a radio interview
this week, Cuban referred to him as ``Stone Cold Shawn Bradley.''
Bradley, whom Nelson acquired from New Jersey in a nine-player deal
in 1997, has one year left on an eight-year contract that pays him
$44.2 million.
</P>
<P>
   Also this week, Nelson said on his radio show that he might have
overpaid injured point guard Steve Nash, whom Nelson signed to a
six-year, $33 million contract last year before Nash became a free
agent.
</P>
<P>
   Sacramento Kings general manager Jerry Reynolds said if he were
running the Mavericks, he would make Finley and Nowitzki
``untouchable'' and start dealing from there.
</P>
<P>
   ``You've got two big-time talents there in Finley and
Nowitzki,'' Reynolds said. ``Both are all-star caliber players _
Finley already and Nowitzki later.
</P>
<P>
   ``Those are two guys you wouldn't, under any circumstance,
consider trading.''
</P>
<P>
   Reynolds transformed the Kings from paupers into one of the
NBA's regal young teams by drafting Jason Williams in 1998 and
trading for Chris Webber and Vlade Divac, all within a span of
three months.
</P>
<P>
   The Kings also have new owners in Gavin Maloof, 42, and his
brother Joe, 43. They have the same gold standard and come from the
same generation as Cuban.
</P>
<P>
   ``Our owners are really fans of the game, are very positive, and
they have fun with it,'' Reynolds said. ``The fact that the guys
like the NBA as a fan before they bought the team is neat in
itself.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's been a real honeymoon. I've been here a long time. This
makes me look forward to waking up _ other than the fact that I
ain't dead.''
</P>
<P>
   Cuban, who made $1.5 billion when he sold his Internet company,
Broadcast.com, has been trying to learn as much as he can about the
Mavericks' business side. From his baseline seats as a
season-ticket holder since 1994, he knows what's wrong with the
product on the court.
</P>
<P>
   ``One of the biggest problems the Mavs have is getting people
into the arena,'' Cuban said. ``A part of that is they don't
communicate.
</P>
<P>
   ``But I'm just a fan of the game, and I hope it turns around
quickly now that I'm a huge part of it.''
</P>
<P>
   The dominoes are now in his hands.
nn
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
