<HEADLINE>
TONY PEREZ DESERVES A SPOT IN THE HALL OF FAME
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By SIMON GONZALEZ 
c.1999 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Carlton Fisk's dramatic home run is part of baseball lore.
</P>
<P>
   The Red Sox catcher frantically waved his arms, imploring to
ball to stay fair. It did, hitting the foul pole atop the Green
Monster in Fenway Park, giving his team a victory over the
Cincinnati Reds in Game 6 of the 1975 World Series, ending one of
the greatest baseball games ever played.
</P>
<P>
   Does anyone remember that Tony Perez hit a home run the next
day? He did, and while it wasn't as dramatic as Fisk's it was
equally as important.
</P>
<P>
   The Red Sox led Game 7, 3-0, when Perez came up against Bill Lee
in the sixth inning with a runner on base. Perez timed Lee's
blooper pitch perfectly and sent it soaring over the net above the
Green Monster for a two-run shot that propelled the Reds to a 4-3
victory and the World Series title.
</P>
<P>
   In a microcosm, that's the story of Perez's career.
</P>
<P>
   He almost single-handedly won Game 5 against the Red Sox,
hitting two home runs and driving in six runs in a 6-2 victory. The
Reds wouldn't win Game 7 without his home run off Lee. But the
indelible memory of the '75 Series is Fisk's arm-waving home run to
win Game 6 in the 12th inning.
</P>
<P>
   Just as Perez's vital contributions were overshadowed by Fisk in
the World Series, so it was on his own team. Think of the Big Red
Machine, and the first names likely to come to mind are Johnny
Bench, Joe Morgan and Pete Rose.
</P>
<P>
   Perez, though, was just as important a cog in one of the best
teams of all time.
</P>
<P>
   He was the cleanup hitter, the clutch hitter, the quietly
efficient RBI machine. He drove in at least 90 runs for 11
consecutive seasons, in 1967-77 (although the last one came with
the Expos). He topped the century mark seven times, with a high of
129 in 1970.
</P>
<P>
   He finished his career with 1,652 RBI, 18th in major-league
history, to go along with a .279 batting average and 379 home runs.
</P>
<P>
   The Hall of Fame balloting will be announced Tuesday. Bench
already is in. So is Morgan. Rose would be if not for his lifetime
ban. Fisk, who fell 43 votes short last year in his first year of
eligibility, will get in this time.
</P>
<P>
   This is Perez's ninth time on the ballot, his ninth chance. It's
time for him to emerge from the shadows and take his place among
baseball's best.
Catch as catch can Carlton Fisk will get in this year. Deservedly
so. After all, he is the major-league record holder for games
played (2,226) and home runs (351) by a catcher.
</P>
<P>
   But what about Gary Carter? He remains a long shot, despite very
similar career numbers.
</P>
<P>
   Fisk played 24 seasons, 11 with the Red Sox and 13 with the
White Sox. He was an 11-time All-Star.
</P>
<P>
   Carter played 19 seasons, 12 with the Expos, five with the Mets
and one each with the Giants and Dodgers. He also was an 11-time
All-Star and twice was MVP of the mid-season classic.
</P>
<P>
   Carter was the superior defensive player, winning three Gold
Gloves to Fisk's one and setting major-league records for putouts
and chances.
</P>
<P>
   Carter also was at least Fisk's equal with the bat. He had nine
seasons with 20 or more home runs; Fisk had eight. Carter had four
seasons of 100 or more RBI, including a league-leading 106 in 1984.
Fisk had two.
</P>
<P>
   Fisk's career edge in home runs (376-324) and RBI (1,330-1,225)
are functions of longevity, not superior skills.
</P>
<P>
   So what's the difference between the two? Fisk's extra five
seasons, certainly. And of course that arm-waving home run,
although Carter also was part of a dramatic postseason moment. The
Mets were down to their last out in Game 6 of the '86 Series
against the Red Sox when Carter singled, starting the three-run
rally that culminated with Mookie Wilson's ground ball trickling
through Bill Buckner's legs.
</P>
<P>
   Otherwise, Carter holds his own.
</P>
<P>
   So if Fisk deserves to be in the Hall _ and he does _ so does
Carter. Back for more Dwight Gooden once was the best pitcher in
baseball. He's still only 35, two years younger than Roger Clemens.
That's why he keeps getting chances, despite mediocre records and
high earned-run averages the past few seasons.
</P>
<P>
   The latest chance comes courtesy of the Astros. They gave Gooden
a minor-league contract, but he's a candidate for a spot in the
rotation behind Jose Lima, Shane Reynolds, Scott Elarton and Chris
Holt.
</P>
<P>
   It would be one of the best stories of the year if Gooden could
regain his old form, but that's about as big a long shot as the
Royals and Twins battling for the American League Central title.
</P>
<P>
   Gooden hasn't been the same since his once promising career was
sidetracked by drug problems. Since missing all of the '95 season
because of a suspension, he is 31-22 with a 4.94 ERA, including 3-4
with a 6.26 ERA in 26 games (22 starts) for the Indians last year.
Best of the best ``The Sporting News'' polled 20 top baseball
executives and asked them to name the top five players in the game.
</P>
<P>
   According to the poll, Mariners shortstop Alex Rodriguez is the
best player. Rodriguez received 77 points, four more than teammate
Ken Griffey Jr., although Griffey had eight first-place votes, two
more than Rodriguez.
</P>
<P>
   The rest of the list, with vote totals: Pedro Martinez, 52;
Nomar Garciaparra, 21; Derek Jeter, 16; Ivan Rodriguez, 14; Larry
Walker, 10; Sammy Sosa and Manny Ramirez, 6; Vladimir Guerrero and
Chipper Jones, 5; Roberto Alomar 4; Barry Bonds, Mark McGwire and
Randy Johnson 3; Bernie Williams and Jeff Bagwell, 1.
</P>
<P>
   It's interesting to note that the highest ranking player from
the National League was Walker, who came in 7th. Right choice,
wrong choice More evidence that Rangers GM Doug Melvin made the
right choice in signing Kenny Rogers to a three-year, $22.5 million
deal: Rogers allowed opponents an OPS (on-base percentage plus
slugging average) last year of .730. That was just a shade higher
than Chuck Finley (.716), who received a three-year, $27 million
deal from the Indians. It was much better than the .802 of Aaron
Sele.
</P>
<P>
   Sele, by the way, erred in turning down the Rangers' four-year,
$28 million deal. He agreed to a four-year, $29 million contract
with the Orioles, but he would have netted more by staying in Texas
because of the lack of a state income tax. Hot stove embers Houston
has talked about sending Moises Alou to the Pirates for Jason
Schmidt or Francisco Cordova, but Alou would have to waive a
no-trade clause. That would leave the increasingly emasculated
Astros with an outfield of Roger Cedeno in center and youngsters
Richard Hidalgo, Daryle Ward and Lance Berkman battling for the two
corner positions.
</P>
<P>
   The Royals want to sign free agent Ricky Bottalico to replace
the retired Jeff Montgomery as their closer.
</P>
<P>
   The A's offered prospects Adam Piatt, Brett Laxton and Mario
Encarnacion for Angels center fielder Jim Edmonds. With the Angels
dragging their feet, the Angels dangling the same package for Twins
ace Brad Radke.
</P>
<P>
   The Braves will take a close look at 19-year-old shortstop
Rafael Furcal in spring training. The phenom hit .322 and stole 96
bases at the Class-A level, and if he isn't overmatched, the job
could be his. If he is, the Braves will look at Blue Jays shortstop
Alex Gonzalez, who is on the trading block.
</P>
<P>
   With Aaron Sele and Andy Benes agreeing to deals Friday, Omar
Olivares could be the next free agent pitcher to sign. The Rockies
are interested.
</P>
<P>
   The Pirates are looking for a closer and might trade Al Martin
to the Mariners for Jose Mesa or Jose Paniagua.
nn
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
