<HEADLINE>
CONNECTICUT BEATS TENNESSEE, 74-67  
 (HLW) 
</HEADLINE>
   By JUDY BATTISTA   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   KNOXVILLE, Tenn. _ Sue Bird remembers sitting behind the
Connecticut bench last year, her left knee still in a cast,
watching Tennessee wrench the No.1 ranking and a 54-game home
winning streak away from the Huskies in Storrs. The guard from
Syosset, N.Y., squirmed then, the discomfort of her surgically
repaired knee compounded by the knowledge that the Huskies were
losing in large part because she was not on the court.
</P>
<P>
   Saturday, Bird, now a sophomore and the starting point guard,
was on the court for the intense rematch, weaving the Huskies
around and through Tennessee's pressure defense, screaming
instructions over the din in the raucous Thompson-Boling Arena and
hitting a stream of big shots in the second half to lead No.1
Connecticut to a 74-67 victory over the No.2 Lady Vols that not
only handed Tennessee its second home loss of the season but also
solidified the Huskies' dominance of women's basketball.
</P>
<P>
   It is still early January, but Connecticut has already beaten
the No.14, No.6, No.3 and now the No.2 teams in the nation, and an
enormous part of their supremacy is Bird's presence.
</P>
<P>
   ``She really took over the game for us,'' UConn's Shea Ralph
said of her teammate's play in front of 20,789. ``She did it almost
single-handedly. Their pressure defense is the best part of their
game and she not only handled it but made big shots.''
</P>
<P>
   Bird, who has averaged 10 points per game this season, finished
with a career high 25 points on 8-of-10 shooting and also had 4
steals. During the most critical stretch of the game, after
Tennessee had used a ratcheted up press to whittle a 13-point
Connecticut lead to just 5 points, Bird scored 8 consecutive
points, including two 3-pointers that opened the Huskies' lead back
to 11 points with 5 minutes 57 seconds remaining. With the lead
again down to 5 with 1:10 left, she hit both ends of a one-and-one
to solidify the lead. As the final second ticked off the clock,
Bird flung the ball in the air, an exultation for which she had
waited a year.
</P>
<P>
   ``Last year, I wasn't in very many games, especially big ones,''
said Bird, who started the first eight games of the season before
tearing the anterior cruciate ligament in her left knee. ``I was
dying to be out there. It's really hard to sit there and know
there's nothing you can do. It's a helpless feeling. I'm not saying
if I were playing we would have won. But it was killing me to be
sitting behind the bench. Because of that experience, I value each
game much more. You have to play every game like it's your last
because it could be.''
</P>
<P>
   Connecticut Coach Geno Auriemma teases that Bird, who went to
Christ the King High School in Queens County, N.Y., may technically
be one of the fabled group of New York point guards, but that she
really grew up on the not-at-all mean streets of Syosset where
``the last thing that was stolen was the newspaper off the porch,''
Auriemma says. But Bird, who has the face of Snow White and the
giggle of a cheerleader, also has the same toughness _ if more
well-concealed _ that the top scorers Ralph and Svetlana Abrosimova
possess, Auriemma says, and she controlled Connecticut in one of
the best _ and most highly anticipated _ game on the women's
schedule this season. The Huskies did not trail after the first
five minutes of the game.
</P>
<P>
   Connecticut's pressure defense was superb and rattled the Lady
Vols, particularly point guard Kristen Clement, who finished with
seven turnovers and no points. Connecticut thrived on those
turnovers with its speedy transition offense, scoring 21 points off
turnovers. Auriemma said he did not try to focus his game plan on
slowing Clement, but instead wanted to limit how many times Tamika
Catchings, one of Tennessee's All-Americans, touched the ball.
</P>
<P>
   The plan worked. Connecticut packed in its defense and
Catchings, the forward who was the team's leading scorer averaging
16.2 points entering the game, took just nine shots and scored just
8 points, forcing Tennessee to rely on center Michelle Snow (21
points) and guard Semeka Randall (20 points) almost exclusively.
Connecticut led by 43-37 at the half but Tennessee's haplessness
was encapsulated in the opening moments of the second half. With
the Tennessee fans standing and clapping in anticipation of the
Volunteers' first points, Connecticut reeled off 7 points in a row
on their first three possessions. It was a deficit that sent
Tennessee into a hole from which they would never fully recover.
</P>
<P>
   ``We played on our heels,'' Summitt said. ``We didn't get back
in transition. They were more aggressive, more confident, more
mentally tough. We were very tentative in the beginning of both
halves.''
</P>
<P>
   These two teams _ the premier teams in the game today _ will
meet again Feb. 2 in Storrs and then, perhaps, again sometime late
in the post-season tournament in March. Auriemma thinks he sees a
pattern in games like this. Saturday, the pattern was a pretty one
for the Huskies.
</P>
<P>
   ``There is so much pressure on your best players _ Shea, Svet,
Tamika, Semeka _ in games like this and they feel it,'' Auriemma
said. ``Usually somebody else steps up and that was Sue. Today, we
got more from our other guys than they got. That's why we won.''
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
