<SLUG> BC-DONORS-MCCAIN-BOS </SLUG>
  
 MCCAIN WROTE LETTERS on behalf of donors 
(For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By ANNE E. KORNBLUT AND WALTER V. ROBINSON  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ Senator John McCain raised about $80,000 from
broadcast and telecommunications companies in four instances
shortly before or soon after he interceded on their behalf with
federal regulators in 1998 and 1999, according to campaign records
reviewed Saturday.
</P>
<P>
   Aides released about 500 letters that McCain has written as
chairman of the Senate Commerce Committee since 1997, with little
evidence that many of them had involved major contributors to his
campaign. And McCain, who was campaigning in South Carolina
Saturday, said his only interest was to protect consumers.
</P>
<P>
   But in several cases, according to federal campaign finance
records that were matched against the letters, the correspondence
to the Federal Communications Commission, which his committee
oversees, coincided with substantial fund-raising efforts by the
companies that stood to benefit from his letters.
</P>
<P>
   In one case, officials of BellSouth Corp. donated $16,750 to the
Arizona senator at a fund-raiser on May 6, 1998. Four months later,
McCain asked the FCC in a letter to give ``serious consideration''
to allowing BellSouth to enter the long-distance market.
</P>
<P>
   Although McCain has long favored the so-called Baby Bells, he
also wrote to the FCC on behalf of AT&AMP;T, Sprint, and MCI Worldcom
in June 1998. Two weeks later, Sprint officers donated $2,000. In
October, 1998, McCain raised another $25,800 from AT&AMP;T officials at
a fund-raiser.
</P>
<P>
   McCain, who has built his campaign around denunciations of
special interest money and power in Washington, was put on the
defensive last week, when The Boston Globe reported that he
interceded last month with the FCC on behalf of Paxson
Communications, which owns or operates 73 television stations.
McCain's letter-writing began soon after the company helped him
raise $20,000, and in a period when he was using Paxson's corporate
jet.
</P>
<P>
   After the report last week, McCain canceled a fund-raiser that
Paxson's chairman, Lowell Paxson, was to have held for him Saturday
in Florida, an event that had been expected to raise $50,000.
</P>
<P>
   The Globe also reported last week that McCain last May rebuked
the FCC for bias against two Baby Bells, SBC Communications and
Ameritech, which were seeking FCC permission to merge. Just before
that May 12 letter, officials of the two companies contributed or
solicited donations of about $120,000 to McCain's campaign.
</P>
<P>
   The letters made public Saturday also include an April 1999
letter McCain wrote to the FCC on Ameritech. That was just after
the company's chairman at the time, Richard Notebaert, a friend of
McCain's, cohosted a Chicago fund-raiser for McCain.
</P>
<P>
   Dan Schnur, the McCain campaign's communications director,
acknowledged Saturday that McCain's contributors get access to him,
but not preferential treatment. ``Big- money contributors to both
parties get access that other people don't,'' Schnur said. But, he
said, McCain ``and the people who work for him do their level best
to make sure those contributors are not given different
treatment.''
</P>
<P>
   During his campaign, McCain has criticized the campaign finance
system, saying that it leaves influential lawmakers like himself
beholden to business interests that provide the funds.
</P>
<P>
   Though McCain has said he too is a victim of the system, his
rhetoric often suggests that he himself has been scrupulous in not
taking actions that benefit campaign donors.
</P>
<P>
   The campaign records examined Saturday include funds that McCain
raised for his presidential campaign during the first three
quarters of 1999, and funds donated to his 1998 Senate reelection
camapaign. In 1998, McCain faced only token opposition, and was
able to transfer about half the $4 million he raised to his
presidential campaign.
</P>
<P>
   Officials of BellSouth are among his largest contributors. In
1999 officials of BellSouth, a regional Bell operating company,
have contributed nearly $30,000 to McCain's presidential campaign.
</P>
<P>
   BellSouth wanted entry into the lucrative long-distance
business, and petitioned the FCC to that end. The FCC was then
required to judge whether there was enough competition in the local
market to warrant their entry into long distance. McCain wrote two
letters _ one on March 6, 1998, and the other on Sept. 15, 1998 _
arguing that wireless service should be taken into account as
competition.
</P>
<P>
   The $16,750 fund-raising event was on May 6, 1998.
</P>
<P>
   In the September letter, McCain said: ``I encourage you to give
serious consideration to whether PCS is providing competition to
the local exchange market.'' He said the FCC ``should be focused on
implementing the Telecommunications Act to encourage competition,
not maintain the status quo.''
</P>
<P>
   ``He wrote to the commission to express his view as to the
law,'' said Mark Buse, the Commerce Committee staff director. ``The
FCC ignored this, and denied BellSouth's petition in 1998 to get
into the long-distance business.''
</P>
<P>
   Echostar chairman Charles W. Ergen has long sought permission to
broadcast the network affiliate programming into homes. But the
company was stymied by a 1998 court case. McCain wrote a letter on
Aug. 19, 1998, to the FCC chairman, William E. Kennard, in order to
``raise our concerns'' over the case.
</P>
<P>
   McCain wrote that the case _ which led to a ruling in favor of
the networks and against the satellite companies _ ``threatens to
undermine the progress we have made in promoting competition.''
</P>
<P>
   Kennard replied that he essentially agreed. Correspondence led
to the Satellite Home Viewers Act, passed last fall.
</P>
<P>
   ``Echostar and DirecTV did both come in and meet the chairman,''
Buse said. ``They did not ask him to do anything specific.''
</P>
<P>
   AT&AMP;T and its major long-distance competitors had a far different
concern, according to Buse _ the so-called ``Gore tax'' on
long-distance carriers. The money goes to the installation of the
Internet in classrooms and libraries.
</P>
<P>
   The big three long-distance carriers wanted to be able to
itemize this tax on phone bills, so customers would know this was a
federal imposition rather than a rate increase by the phone
companies. The FCC wanted the companies to bury the tax in the
bill.
</P>
<P>
   McCain wrote a letter on June 2, 1998, on behalf of the
long-distance carriers arguing that ``consumers have an absolute
right to know how much their bills are going up and why their bills
are going up.''
</P>
<P>
   But, Buse said, ``None of these companies came to us on this
subject.''
</P>
<P>
   In the end, the amount of the tax was lower than people had
expected. But most companies are still unable to itemize it the way
they had wanted.
</P>
<P>
   The AT&AMP;T fund-raiser was held on Oct. 13, 1998. It netted
McCain's campaign $25,800.
</P>
<P>
   McCain has consistently said, as he did again Saturday, that his
only goal has been to prod the FCC, which often moves slowly, to
take action. And he has also insisted that there has been no
connection between the fund-raising and any action he has taken as
the Commerce Committee chairman.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
