<SLUG> BC-CHECHNYA-GENERALS-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
KREMLIN PLAYS DOWN MILITARY SHAKEUP
</HEADLINE>
  (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By BRIAN WHITMORE  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   MOSCOW _ Insisting nothing has changed in its military campaign
against separatist rebels, the Kremlin  &UR; yesterday &LR;  played down a
shakeup among its top field generals in Chechnya.
</P>
<P>
   Acting President Vladimir V. Putin also cited concern for
civilians and the weekend's Orthodox Christian and Muslim holidays
as reasons for the announcement Friday of a temporary halt in the
bombardment of Chechnya's capital, Grozny.
</P>
<P>
   Despite the announcement, television stations in Russia reported
fighting and artillery strikes  &UR; yesterday &LR;  on the outskirts of
Grozny.
</P>
<P>
   As officials scrambled to explain away the command shakeup,
military analysts said the reason was simple: Russian forces have
lost the initiative to the outnumbered but determined Chechen
rebels. After easily winning control of northern Chechnya, Russian
forces have been bogged down for weeks on the outskirts of Grozny
and desperately need to regroup, they said.
</P>
<P>
   Putin told reporters the removal Friday of his top two generals
in Chechnya _ Lieutenant General Gennady Troshev, who commanded
forces in eastern Chechnya, and Major General Vladimir Shamanov,
who led troops on the west _ was not a reflection on their
performance.
</P>
<P>
   ``Russia doesn't throw away such generals as Troshev and
Shamanov. There has been no replacement and no replacement has been
planned. It is a technical question,'' Putin said early  &UR; yesterday &LR; 
 &UR; morning  &LR; after leaving an Orthodox Christmas Divine Liturgy. He
gave no further details.
</P>
<P>
   Putin's statement went against the Defense Ministry announcement
naming new leaders. Troshev's replacement, Sergei Makarov, told NTV
television that Troshev had been given a promotion and would serve
as deputy head of the Northern Caucasus military district.
</P>
<P>
   Putin also offered various reasons for the bombing halt,
including respect for the Orthodox Christmas and for Muslims who
were celebrating the end of the fasting month of Ramadan. Another
reason, according to Putin, was concern for the civilians trapped
in Grozny.
</P>
<P>
   ``We will not forget that and we will respect the feelings of
believers,'' Putin said.
</P>
<P>
   The Kremlin leader also repeated accusations that Chechen rebels
had blown up containers of toxic chemicals as a means of defense.
Putin said that in such circumstances, artillery attacks and
airstrikes against Grozny ``are not safe for the civilian
population.''
</P>
<P>
   Pavel Felgenhauer, a Moscow-based defense analyst, said Russia's
bombing pause was unrelated to humanitarian or religious concerns.
</P>
<P>
   ``The Russian forces are losing the initiative and the Chechens
are effectively counterattacking. Russian troops are bogged down
and the reserves are depleted, and they need to regroup,''
Felgenhauer said.
</P>
<P>
   He added that while the rotation of field generals is often
routine, the timing of the reshuffle, made after Russian troops
have been stuck in Grozny's outskirts for weeks, looked suspicious.
</P>
<P>
   ``Much of the situation is due to the bad work of the generals
in the field, who have split the troops into many small units that
cannot help each other,'' Felgenhauer said, adding that the shakeup
may be a prelude to a change in tactics.
</P>
<P>
   The Kremlin launched its military assault on Chechnya in late
September after a series of apartment bombings that killed hundreds
of people in Russian cities. Authorities blamed Chechen rebels for
the bombings. The rebels contend they were not involved in the
attacks.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
