<HEADER>
A0490 &Cx1f; ttc-z
r s BC-BKN-NBA-COLUMN-LADN     01-08 0972
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BKN-NBA-COLUMN-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
IT'S TIME FOR WORST TO PONDER WHO'S BEST
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By SCOTT WOLF  
 c.2000 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOS ANGELES _ It's clear the Lakers and Blazers are the top two
teams in the NBA, but it's even clearer the Bulls, Warriors,
Grizzlies, Mavericks and Wizards are the worst.
</P>
<P>
   With that in mind, scouts for those teams have begun to get
serious, flying to as many college basketball conference games as
possible to see how players react in pressure situations.
</P>
<P>
   But that doesn't mean these teams don't already have their cheat
sheets handy with a list of their top 10 prospects.
</P>
<P>
   So, here's a sneak peek at the top 10, if the draft were held
today:
</P>
<P>
   Kenyon Martin, power forward, 6-8, 230, Cincinnati, Sr.: Thebest
senior in the draft, and perhaps best player. Martin has great
shot-blocking ability, can score facing the basket and has shown
this season he can hit a jump shot.
</P>
<P>
   Chris Mihm, center, 7-0, 262, Texas, Jr.: The top true center
prospect in the country, he has the defensive skills to be an
impact player and has an underrated perimeter game. All he lacks is
maturity, which might come if he stays in school for his senior
year.
</P>
<P>
   Quentin Richardson, shooting guard, 6-6, 215, DePaul, So.: He
was a projected lottery pick after his freshman season, and has
made it known he will not be back next year. He can rebound as well
as any guard in college basketball, although his outside shot is
still under review.
</P>
<P>
   Terence Morris, small forward, 6-9, 205, Maryland, Jr.: Needs to
bulk up, but makes everyone's top-10 list. He's a scorer and
leader, and has that wonderful ``upside'' NBA experts seek.
</P>
<P>
   Loren Woods, center, 7-1, 225, Arizona, Jr.: After sitting out
last season, the Wake Forest transfer has returned with a
vengeance. He could be joined by teammate Michael Wright in the
lottery.
</P>
<P>
   Hanno Mottola, power forward, 6-10, 245, Utah, Sr.: He's as
likely to shoot a 3-pointer as grab a rebound inside. Scouts love
to compare him to former Ute Keith Van Horn, minus all the
preseason hype.
</P>
<P>
   DerMarr Johnson, small forward, 6-9, 200, Cincinnati, Fr.: He's
played only a handful of games, but has been so dominant in the
Bearcats' preseason schedule that he zoomed up the charts. He can
shoot, run and rebound with grace.
</P>
<P>
   Stromile Swift, power forward, 6-9, 235, Louisiana State, So.:
There's a reason Louisiana State got off to a 12-0 start, and it
wasn't just a soft schedule. How he fares in the SEC will determine
if this early projection holds.
</P>
<P>
   Joel Przybilla, center, 7-1, 260, Minnesota, So.: A still-raw
prospect, his shot-blocking ability alone is expected to make him a
top-10 pick, if he chooses to come out this season.
</P>
<P>
   Chris Porter, small forward, 6-7, 218, Auburn, Sr.: He started
out as a preseason choice for player of the year, but his stock has
dropped because of poor shooting and questions about effort.
</P>
<P>
   Deals, deals, deals: The Sixers' latest target is Phoenix
forward Tom Gugliotta, who survived his recent encounter with an
herbal supplement. Philadelphia is believed to have suggested Larry
Hughes andMatt Geiger as compensation.
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile, Washington is trying to figure out what to do with
disgruntled center Ike Austin, provided coach Gar Heard doesn't get
fired first.
</P>
<P>
   The Wizards have offered Austin to Milwaukee for Tim Thomas and
Robert Traylor. The Lakers have also reportedly expressed interest
in Austin.
</P>
<P>
   The Knicks continue to fruitlessly offer Kurt Thomas and Charlie
Ward for Glen Rice.
</P>
<P>
   The Jazz has dangled Jacque Vaughn and Howard Eisley to Indiana
for Chris Mullin and Portland for Detlef Schrempf. The Blazers
don't want to deal Schrempf, but he's become frustrated over a lack
playing time. Just like the other six players on Mike Dunleavy's
bench.
</P>
<P>
   Mr. Doubletalk: If you want to know why New Jersey players
couldn't stand former coach John Calipari, listen to him speak out
of both sides of his mouth, regarding his desire to return to
college coaching instead of the hectic pace of the NBA.
</P>
<P>
   ``A good college situation, I'd be interested,'' Calipari said.
``A good pro situation, I'd have to be interested.''
</P>
<P>
   Calipari has already interviewed with the University of Memphis.
</P>
<P>
   Don't call me coach: One of the most outlandish cases of
nepotism quietly dissolved in Dallas this week, when coach Don
Nelson said his son, Donnie, would not take over the team next
season.
</P>
<P>
   A case of Nelson Sr. coming to his senses? Hardly. He just
realized that with new owner Mark Cuban taking over the team, he
wouldn't have the power to make such a decision anymore.
</P>
<P>
   ``In retrospect, that was obviously a mistake,'' Donnie Nelson
said. ``Butpeople who really know me know that titles are not a big
thing to me. I've said it a gazillion times and I'm getting tired
of saying it.''
</P>
<P>
   Genius at work: Sacramento point guard Jason Williams continues
to demonstrate why he can confound and astound simultaneously.
</P>
<P>
   He made 2 of 14 shots in the first 40 minutes against Cleveland
on Tuesday, then hit three straight 3-point shots in 90 seconds to
lead the Kings to a victory.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm going to miss shots,'' Williams said. ``But you miss 100
percent of the shots you don't take. So I'm just going to keep
jacking them up there until they go in.''
</P>
<P>
   To weave or not to weave: After Orlando's Ben Wallace switched
his hairstyle from cornrows to an Afro, the Magic went 7-3.
Teammates asked Wallace to retain the Afro, and the team conducted
an online poll. More than 60 percent of the fans also asked for the
Afro.
</P>
<P>
   Historic moment: Sixers rookie Jumaine Jones scored the last
basket of the millennium on a 25-footer with 3.6 seconds left. In
case you're wondering, the NBA intends to place his jersey in the
Hall of Fame.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
