<HEADER>
A0492 &Cx1f; taf-z
u s BC-FBN-LIONS-REDSKINS-NY     01-08 1060
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FBN-LIONS-REDSKINS-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
REDSKINS BEAT LIONS, 27-13  
 (HLW) 
</HEADLINE>
   By MIKE FREEMAN   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   LANDOVER, Md. _ Unfortunately for the National Football League,
the best action during Washington's 27-13 rout of the Detroit Lions
during a National Conference wild-card game Saturday occurred in
the third quarter, in a World Wrestling Federation smackdown type
of scrum between Redskins and Lions players. It led to the ejection
of a key offensive lineman, to an official getting punched in the
back of the head and to an embarrassing situation in which the
microphone of Referee Bob McElwee remained stuck on and he could be
heard referring to one of the fighting players as a ``clown.''
</P>
<P>
   The game itself was a blowout early. The Redskins scored 27
consecutive points, thanks mainly to running back Stephen Davis,
who torched the Lions before leaving the game in the first half
with what team officials described as a mild injury to his right
knee.
</P>
<P>
   Davis used both cutback and power running to finish with 15
carries for 119 yards and 2 touchdowns in less than two quarters.
One of Davis' runs was spectacular. It occurred in the first
quarter when he sprinted up the middle, was surrounded by three
Lions defensive backs, and outran them all for a 58-yard gain. It
tied running back Tim Smith's run in Super Bowl XXII as the longest
run in Washington's postseason history. Before that run, Davis had
a 1-yard touchdown score.
</P>
<P>
   The Redskins will travel to Tampa Bay for a second-round playoff
game next Saturday.
</P>
<P>
   The Lions scored five minutes into the fourth period on Ron
Rice's 94-year fumble return and then got their lone offensive
touchdown as time ran out on Gus Frerotte's 5-yard pass to Ron
Rivers.
</P>
<P>
   About the only bad news for Washington was the loss of its
starting left tackle, Andy Heck, who tore his hamstring. He is out
for the remainder of the season.
</P>
<P>
   The game featured one of the most bizarre moments of the season.
Washington led by 27-0 midway through the third quarter when
Redskins quarterback Brad Johnson and Lions defensive end Robert
Porcher got into a nasty bout. Johnson, who weighs about 60 pounds
less than Porcher, flipped the hulking defensive end like a
hamburger, and the two fought on the ground while officials tried
to break it up.
</P>
<P>
   Then other players got in on the action. One was Redskins
offensive lineman Tre Johnson, who threw a punch at an unidentified
Lions player, but missed, and hit the back judge, Bill Leavy, in
the back of the head. Leavy slowly walked away from the crowd of
players, looking slightly stunned. Johnson was tossed from the game
and will very likely be fined by the league in the coming weeks.
There is also the chance that he could be suspended for the
Redskins' next playoff game.
</P>
<P>
   But the weirdness was not over. Brad Johnson, after finally
being separated from Porcher, raised his hands triumphantly, as if
he were Ali after beating Frazier. Then Johnson added to his
pyrotechnics by doing a Hulk Hogan type of pose, as the record
crowd of 79,411 cheered.
</P>
<P>
   As this was happening, McElwee, during a television timeout,
started describing in detail what happened in the fight to another
official. Only McElwee seemed unaware his microphone was stuck
open, and he called Tre Johnson a ``clown.'' McElwee's microphone
remained on for much of the third quarter.
</P>
<P>
   But by then the game was long over. There has not been any doubt
about the talent of Washington's offense _ only St. Louis scored
more points than the Redskins did this season. Washington has been
able to destroy most defenses, using a steady running attack from
Davis, and a passing game headed by Johnson, one of the more
accurate throwers in the league.
</P>
<P>
   The problem for Washington has been its defense. The unit has
improved its play slightly in the last eight games of the regular
season, but for Washington to have any chance to advance deep into
the playoffs, it needs to play even better.
</P>
<P>
   Detroit was not expected to give the Redskins much of a game,
despite the fact the Lions beat Washington in the regular season,
ending an 18-game Redskins winning streak against them. Still,
Detroit lost its final four games of the season, backing into the
playoffs.
</P>
<P>
   The Lions, 8-8 during the season, had other omens to deal with
as well. The Lions are now 0-20 on the road against the Redskins
since that franchise moved to Washington in 1937, and continued a
league tradition of no team .500 or below ever winning a playoff
game.
</P>
<P>
   Washington's defense played one of its better games of the
season. On the first play from scrimmage, Frerotte was sacked by
linebacker Greg Jones. Frerotte was jumpy for much of the first
half. He was Washington's quarterback until the Redskins released
him after the 1998 season after trading for Johnson.
</P>
<P>
   Frerotte had a poor game until it didn't matter. Some of his
passes were uncatchable, except the one right into the hands of the
Redskins rookie cornerback Champ Bailey for an interception in the
first quarter. Frerotte finished 21 for 46 for 251 yards and 2
interceptions and was sacked five times.
</P>
<P>
   The rest of the Lions were equally neurotic, and terrible. The
team had six penalties in the first quarter and three false starts
after two. Lions safety Allen Aldridge was called for
unsportsmanlike conduct after going to the head of Johnson.
</P>
<P>
   The Redskins, scoring five of the first six times they had the
ball, took advantage of the numerous Detroit mistakes, and rode the
back of Davis, who has deceptive cat-like moves for someone who is
234 pounds, and can run up the middle with power.
</P>
<P>
   After his first touchdown, Davis smacked the Lions in the teeth
again, running for a 4-yard score. The Redskins later added two
Brett Conway field goals of 33 and 23 yards and a Johnson-to-Albert
Connell 30-yard pass for a 27-0 halftime lead.
</P>
<P>
   Late in the first half, Washington got a scare when Davis had
his right leg caught in an awkward position after players from both
teams went scrambling for a loose ball. It looked like it could be
a terrible injury until the Redskins announced that Davis had a
mild sprain of his right knee.
</P>
<P>
   After lying on the ground for several minutes, Davis got up and
ran off the field to the sideline. If the score was not so
lopsided, he would have probably returned.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-01-08-00 2033EST &QL; 
