<DATE_TIME> 2000-01-08 20:37 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A0493 &Cx1f; taf-z
u s BC-BKC-MIAMI-SYRACUSE-NY     01-08 0623
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BKC-MIAMI-SYRACUSE-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SYRACUSE BEATS MIAMI, 67-55  
 (HLW) 
</HEADLINE>
   By CHARLIE NOBLES   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   MIAMI _ University of Miami basketball fans heckled the senior
forward Etan Thomas of Syracuse throughout Saturday's Big East
game. But by the end, Thomas had won over the hecklers and the
undefeated Orangemen had won again.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's funny,'' Thomas said following Syracuse's 67-55 victory
before 3,511 at Miami Arena. ``After the game, they started talking
about me coming down to play for the Miami Heat. I guess I got
their respect.''
</P>
<P>
   Thomas, Syracuse's career leader in blocked shots and its top
scorer this season, had a rather quiet game by his standards. He
made 5 of 7 field-goal attempts along the way to 12 points and
managed a team-leading 11 rebounds and 2 blocks.
</P>
<P>
   But it was Thomas' block of Mario Bland's shot with 19 seconds
left that sealed the victory, Syracuse's 11th straight and second
in the Big East. Miami trailed by just 5 points at the time.
</P>
<P>
   ``We had the shots _ they just didn't go,'' said Bland, Miami's
center, after his team shot a season-low 31.3 percent from the
field, its worst since February 1996 against Syracuse. ``They won,
but in my opinion, they shouldn't have.''
</P>
<P>
   Actually, going on the road for the first time this season did
not turn out to be so taxing for the Orangemen. After fashioning a
10-0 start in the Carrier Dome, they were able to put
recognition-hungry Miami on its heels early and hold on.
</P>
<P>
   ``I figured we needed to win this game,'' Syracuse Coach Jim
Boeheim said. ``If we lost, all everybody would be writing is how
we couldn't handle playing on the road for the first time. It's a
good thing we won.''
</P>
<P>
   Being able to win on the road was not much of a concern, though,
Boeheim said. Syracuse has its top seven players returning from a
team that went 7-2 on the road in Big East games last season.
</P>
<P>
   ``We played a real good first half,'' Boeheim said, ``and in the
second half, our offense just went south. And we had too many
turnovers.''
</P>
<P>
   Syracuse shot just 35.7 percent in the second half and had 21
turnovers for the game. But it built such a lead _ 17 points late
in the first half _ that Miami (8-6, 1-1 Big East) could not
recover. ``It looked like we forced them out of their offense in
the first half,'' Boeheim said.
</P>
<P>
   It was a different story in the second half, as Miami closed
once to 4 points. Still, the senior forwards Damone Brown and Ryan
Blackwell contributed mightily through the game's late stages. They
accounted for 15 of Syracuse's final 21 points and wound up with 14
each.
</P>
<P>
   Boeheim went to a spread offense more in the second half in
trying to protect a lead, and he was not pleased with the results,
citing his team's poor shooting percentage.
</P>
<P>
   But one big shot that fell came from Jason Hart, a senior guard
who also had 14 points. Miami had moved within 38-34 with 13
minutes 35 seconds to play when Hart sank a 3-pointer to complete a
13-2 run.
</P>
<P>
   ``I knew it was going to go in,'' Hart said. ``We've got three
guys who know how high the stakes are every night. We know what to
do to close out games.''
</P>
<P>
   The Orangemen, the Big East's best defensive team with a
58.1-point-against average coming into Saturday, put strong clamps
on Miami's scorers in molding a commanding 36-21 halftime lead.
Miami shot a paltry 8 for 34 from the field, 23.5 percent, as
Syracuse moved ahead by 11-1 at the game's start and soon had a
15-4 edge.
</P>
<P>
   ``They needed a wake-up call at halftime,'' Thomas said. ``And
it looks like they got it.''
</P>
<P>
   Indeed, the Hurricanes climbed back in the game early in the
second half, with guard Johnny Hemsley contributing 8 points in the
first five minutes.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
