<HEADER>
A0494 &Cx1f; kan-z
r v BC-BC-KAN-BUDGET-KAN &LR;      01-08 0613
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BC-KAN-BUDGET-KAN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
   
<TEXT>
<P>
   The Kansas City Star plans to move the following stories for use
by clients of the NYTimes News Service for AMs and PMs of Sunday,
January 09. If you have any questions, please call Patricia Hardin
on the Star's News Desk at (816) 234-4753.
FISHER-COLUMN -- Near midnight a week ago Friday, as clocks moved
toward the year 2000, a goodly number of Plato's 75 residents
gathered at the gazebo on the south side of Missouri 32.
</P>
<P>
   A bonfire provided light and some warmth. The Bank of Plato
across the road was serving coffee, hot chocolate and snacks. The
crowd was festive.
</P>
<P>
   Just after midnight _ 12:00:01 a.m. to be exact _ the crowd
cheered. At that moment Plato, founded in 1858 deep in the Ozarks
and unaccountably named for the Greek philosopher, became an
incorporated village.
</P>
<P>
   By JIM FISHER. 29 inches.
</P>
<P>
   BANKRUPTCIES-GAMBLING -- Cathy, a 34-year-old saleswoman in
Kansas City, had several platinum cards as proof of her good
credit.
</P>
<P>
   Then she started gambling at area riverboats.
</P>
<P>
   She'd bet a few hundred dollars in cash. When she lost that,
she'd get cash advances on her credit cards at the casinos'
customer service counters.
</P>
<P>
   ``It made me sick, but the more sick it made me, the more I
would go back,'' she said. ``They weren't going to beat me; I was
going to beat them. But they won.''
</P>
<P>
   She gambled away an estimated $10,000 to $20,000 between 1996
and 1998. In late 1998, faced with credit card debts of more than
$45,000, she declared personal bankruptcy.
</P>
<P>
   She's not alone. Bankruptcies citing gambling debts as a
contributing factor have jumped since the riverboats entered the
Kansas City market in mid-1994.
</P>
<P>
   By JOYCE SMITH. 67 inches.
</P>
<P>
   SUMMER-BASKETBALL -- One of the most successful high school
basketball coaches in the country, Raytown South's Bud Lathrop,
feels a bit lonely these days.
</P>
<P>
   It used to be that when Lathrop had a top prospect, college
coaches would flock to his gym on recruiting trips.
</P>
<P>
   ``Ted Owens, Digger Phelps, Nolan Richardson all have come
through here,'' Lathrop said. But, he said, college coaches don't
come around as much now.
</P>
<P>
   The reason: Summer basketball. College coaches now do much of
their recruiting during the summer _ at games, tournaments and
camps completely unrelated to the athletes' high schools. Some
athletes are playing more games for their summer league teams than
for their schools.
</P>
<P>
   Issues surrounding summer leagues are at the heart of a federal
grand jury probe that has sidelined three university basketball
players from Kansas City. The players _ Kareem Rush, JaRon Rush and
Andre Williams _ all have reportedly acknowledged receiving
payments or benefits from their former summer league coach, a
Kansas City businessman or a Los Angeles sports agent.
</P>
<P>
   The grand jury is exploring whether somebody paid amateur
athletes to play basketball, thereby endangering their eligibility
and potentially defrauding federally funded universities.
</P>
<P>
   But the grand jury isn't alone in looking at summer basketball.
</P>
<P>
   This week in San Diego the NCAA will discuss changes to
basketball recruiting rules to limit the influence of summer
coaches.
</P>
<P>
   By MARK MORRIS, KATIE FUNK and HOWARD RICHMAN. 55 inches.
</P>
<P>
   DEBATE-DEMOCRATS (JOHNSTON, Iowa) -- In an hour of polite
slights and digs at nuanced policy differences, Al Gore and Bill
Bradley demonstrated Saturday that they mostly agreed on
government's role in this new century.
</P>
<P>
   Yet the men also showed how starkly their campaigns and
characters differ in manner and mode.
</P>
<P>
   By STEVE KRASKE and SCOTT CANON. 32 inches.
</P>
