<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-KC-FISHER-COLUMN-KAN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
WITH FOCUS ON NEW YEAR, TOWN GRABS ATTENTION WITH INCORPORATION 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By JIM FISHER  
 c. 1999 Kansas City Star   PLATO, Mo. _ Near midnight a week ago
Friday, as clocks moved toward the year 2000, a goodly number of
Plato's 75 residents gathered at the gazebo on the south side of
Missouri 32.
<TEXT>
<P>
   A bonfire provided light and some warmth. The Bank of Plato
across the road was serving coffee, hot chocolate and snacks. The
crowd was festive.
</P>
<P>
   Just after midnight _ 12:00:01 a.m. to be exact _ the crowd
cheered. At that moment Plato, founded in 1858 deep in the Ozarks
and unaccountably named for the Greek philosopher, became an
incorporated village.
</P>
<P>
   The timing _ one second after midnight _ was a outright gambit
to grab media coverage. Plato _ bonfire, snacks and cheering _
would be one of those good-news stories. It would be the first new
town in Missouri in the year 2000 and, likely as not, the newest
incorporated entity in the nation in a new millennium.
</P>
<P>
   ``I know, I know,'' said Lyle Adcock, president of the bank.
``Some people say the millennium doesn't start until 2001. But give
us a break. We were having a good time.''
</P>
<P>
   Still, there was a serious underpinning to what happened here.
</P>
<P>
   Plato, like every other place, is looking for money,
specifically state and federal grants and loans to build sewers,
improve its all-but-nonexistent infrastructure and treat
wastewater. Now, instead of going hat in hand to the township or
county and asking for the little money those bodies have,
incorporation allows Plato to be a player on its own.
</P>
<P>
   The incorporation takes in 220 acres in and around town. For the
first time, a village board of trustees can pass ordinances and
establish zoning regulations. In short, setting a house trailer
willy-nilly is likely a thing of the past.
</P>
<P>
   Plato's incorporation was not a rarity. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   John Ballard of Ashland, Mo., a former governmental affairs
specialist with the Missouri Cooperative Extension Service who now
does small-town strategy consulting, says that each year about a
dozen towns _ most in the eastern part of the state _ incorporate.
Another recent incorporation was Irena in Worth County.
</P>
<P>
   Incorporation, said Ballard, gets the bureaucrats' attention.
</P>
<P>
   ``Plato can now go to the government on its own and get grants,
loans and all kinds of expertise,'' he said. ``The days of having a
bake sale for town improvements are gone. They're just too
expensive, and things like sewers and water systems have gotten too
complicated.''
</P>
<P>
   Bob Biram, a village trustee, said: ``This sounds crazy, but
we've got to get a handle on our growth. We should have done this
years and years ago.''
</P>
<P>
   Growth and Plato would seem antonyms. Tucked in the northwest
corner of Texas County, the community is much like it was a century
ago.
</P>
<P>
   There's a smattering of houses, the bank, a school, a cafe, a
post office, a store and a gas station. The streets are unpaved
except for the highway, which until the 1950s was a gravel trace
through the hills.
</P>
<P>
   Until a couple of years ago, Cecil Benson, now in his 90s and in
a rest home, charged a single dollar for a haircut here.
</P>
<P>
   Plato on the surface seems untouched _ where farmers and
cattlemen come to drink morning coffee and the only traffic
problems come when school starts or lets out. A Springfield
newspaper a few years ago termed it ``The Town That Time Forgot.''
</P>
<P>
   Yet there have been stirrings. Roughly 1,000 homes have hooked
onto the water system in the past couple of years. The bank, once
said to be the smallest in the United States, has seen its assets
grow from $3 million in 1991 to $14 million today.
</P>
<P>
   Off the road and out of sight are acreages holding new,
six-figure houses that would meld seamlessly into tonier parts of
St. Louis and Kansas City. And the school now has 600 students in
kindergarten through 12th grade.
</P>
<P>
   Adcock said Plato was becoming _ of all things _ a bedroom
community.
</P>
<P>
   ``Draw a circle around Plato and you come up with six fair-sized
towns or cities all within about 30 miles,'' he said. ``Mountain
Grove, Hartville, Lebanon, Waynesville, Licking and Houston. Those
towns have jobs. Professional people. Factories. And, of course, up
at Fort Leonard Wood, the military.''
</P>
<P>
   Adcock said the conventional wisdom had been that only big
cities are subject to people heading out to the countryside for a
quieter, allegedly safer and less harried life. Not so, he said.
There's sprawl here also.
</P>
<P>
   ``Take Licking,'' he said. ``It has a new prison. People will
have good state jobs with benefits. And I guarantee you that some
of them will start looking around first thing for some acreage.
What I'm seeing as a banker in the past few years is a lot less
materialism. A lot less desire for `stuff.' People want to be out
in the country. Some of them will be coming our way.''
</P>
<P>
   Ballard said the nature of commuting had been redefined with
dependable cars, better tires, cell phones and essentially cheap
fuel.
</P>
<P>
   ``Now you see commutes that you would have shook your head at 20
years ago,'' he said. ``Sixty, 70 miles one way is nothing
anymore.''
</P>
<P>
   Willia ``Tiny'' Duncan, who sells real estate a dozen miles
north of here at Evening Shade, said eight housing developments,
most with an acre or more per dwelling, had sprung up in the area
in recent years.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're at the back gate of Fort Leonard,'' she said. ``You hear
of the military downsizing. But the fort's grown with the new
engineers school. The tour of duty is five years, plenty of time to
buy a house. And the retirees _ they look at this country and
figure they can't do any better than here _ cost of living, space,
taxes.''
</P>
<P>
   Duncan is helping with a petition drive to incorporate Evening
Shade. Like Plato, Evening Shade's overriding challenge is sewers
and wastewater.
</P>
<P>
   Clyde McWilliams, soon to be 88, who lives in the country north
of Plato, said he was pleased with the incorporation. But he said,
grinning, that he would be seeing fewer of his Plato friends.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm an old-timer,'' he said. ``I try to stay out of `town'
much as I can.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
