<HEADLINE>
THE SIX DEGREES OF DON NELSON: THERE'S NO ESCAPING THE DON
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By RICHIE WHITT 
c.1999 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Slide over, Kevin Bacon, it's time you share the epicenter of
the universe ...
</P>
<P>
   1. Bacon starred in ``Wild Things'' with Matt Dillon.
</P>
<P>
   2. Dillon appeared in ``Malcolm X'' with Spike Lee.
</P>
<P>
   3. Lee directed ``He Got Game'' starring Ray Allen.
</P>
<P>
   4. Allen plays for the Milwaukee Bucks, coached by George Karl.
</P>
<P>
   5. Karl was head coach for the Golden State Warriors in '88,
under a GM named Don Nelson.
</P>
<P>
   Translation: As difficult as it is to watch a movie without
connections to Bacon, it's going to be equally impossible for
prospective Mavericks owner Mark Cuban to hire a coach completely
clean of Nelson's greasy fingerprints.
</P>
<P>
   Nelson is no longer the NBA's best coach, but he's certainly the
best connected.
</P>
<P>
   It's Bacon whose bevy of movies and often convoluted traces to
other actors has spawned a Web site, a book, a board game and a
nationwide cult-fad called the ``Six Degrees of Kevin Bacon.'' But
_ given that even Bacon can be saddled with a Nellie Number (5) _
it's Nelson who has developed connections to be undisputed
epicenter of basketball coaching.
</P>
<P>
   Nelson, in fact, is the Kevin Bacon of basketball. Or is Bacon
merely the Nellie of Hollywood?
</P>
<P>
   Like Bacon, Nelson's career is more about quantity than quality,
with too much ``Footloose'' and not enough ``A Few Good Men''. Both
are active (Bacon has starred in 35 movies since debuting in
``Animal House'' in '78; Nelson has 895 coaching victories in 21
years). Both are decorated (Bacon earned a Golden Globe award for
his role in ``The River Wild''; Nelson was named one of the NBA's
Top 10 Greatest Coaches). Both are innovative (Bacon's sadistic
scientist role in ``Flatliners''; Nelson's introduction of quirky
lineups, point forwards and trapping defenses).
</P>
<P>
   Most of all, however, both are very, very well connected in
their industry.
</P>
<P>
   Based on the ``Six Degrees of Separation'' theory that posits we
are all connected by six or fewer stages of circumstance or
acquaintance, Pennsylvania college students armed with free time
and cheap whiskey researched that everyone from Marlon Brando, to
Queen Latifah, to Bob Barker, to O.J. Simpson and even Liberace
could be connected to Bacon. In fact, according to a University of
Virginia computer program dubbed ``The Oracle of Bacon,'' he has
six-step links to 240,000 actors and actresses with the exception
of Lassie.
</P>
<P>
   Almost as eerie is Nelson, who has forged more organized labor
connections than John Gotti during his coaching stints in Milwaukee
('76-87), Golden State ('89-95), New York ('95-96) and Dallas
('97-present). His far-reaching tentacles grew over an
unprecedented 38 years in the NBA, earning him five titles as a
player with the Celtics, three coach of the year awards and
participation in more than 3,000 games, second only to Atlanta's
Lenny Wilkens.
</P>
<P>
   Of the league's 28 other head coaches, 20 of them can be linked
to Nelson in two moves or less.
</P>
<P>
   For example, Dan Issel of the Nuggets has a Nellie Number of 2.
An assistant on Issel's staff is John Lucas, who played for Nelson
in Milwaukee in '87. Also a 2 is Lakers coach Phil Jackson, who
recently hired assistant Jim Cleamons, whom Nelson fired in Dallas
two years ago.
</P>
<P>
   Eight coaches are direct branches off the Nelson coaching tree,
including the Bucks' George Karl (head coach for '88 Warriors under
GM Nelson), the Knicks' Jeff Van Gundy (assistant with the '95
Knicks under head coach Nelson) and the Blazers' Mike Dunleavy
(played on '85 Bucks coached by Nelson.
</P>
<P>
   The NBA's coaching fraternity is so Nellie-knit, in fact, that
only four are more than three separations from Nelson. The New
Jersey Nets' Don Casey is the farthest removed, taking six steps:
1. Casey was an assistant on '98 Nets under head coach John
Calipari. 2. Calipari is an assistant on '00 Sixers under head
coach Larry Brown. 3. Brown coached '94 Pacers with assistant Gar
Heard. 4. Heard was an assistant with '98 Pistons under head coach
Alvin Gentry. 5. Gentry was an assistant on '91 Clippers under head
coach Mike Schuler. 6. Schuler was an assistant with '86 Bucks
under a head coach named Don Nelson.
</P>
<P>
   When it comes to roots, there is no Whoa! in Nellie.
</P>
<P>
   It's been easy to trace him _ to everyone from Ozzie and Harriet
to Bugs Bunny (1. Bugs starred in ``Space Jam'' with Shawn Bradley.
2. Bradley was acquired by the Mavericks in a trade made by
Nelson.) Now, it's time to replace him.
</P>
<P>
   Since Nelson will not return to the bench, the Mavericks will
have a new coach next season. And since the new coach probably will
not be a one-step move like son, Donnie, it could be as complicated
as a four-step connection like Jerry Sloan. Whatever the case,
chances are the ``Six Degrees of Separation from Nellie'' will
provide at least a bitter Nelson aftertaste to the flavor of his
successor.
</P>
<P>
   Wonder if Bacon is available?
chart \Nsubheds:SIX DEGREES OF SEPARATION FROM NELLIE
\Nagatea:Given Don Nelson's 44-104 record in Dallas, the Mavericks'
league-high streak of 10 consecutive nonplayoff seasons and their
epitaph as ``Worst Professional Sports Franchise of the '90s,''
logic would dictate hiring a successor with a high Nellie Number
next season. But, given the fact seemingly all NBA coaching careers
run through him at some point, finding the missing link in the
Nelson chain won't be easy.
</P>
<P>
   A look at the league's 28 other head coaches and their Nellie
Numbers: \Nsubheds:1 \Nagatea:Paul Silas, Hornets: 1. Played on '76
Celtics with Nelson. George Karl, Bucks: 1. Head coach for '88
Warriors under GM Nelson. Jeff Van Gundy, Knicks: 1. Assistant with
'95 Knicks under head coach Nelson. Gregg Popovich, Spurs: 1.
Assistant with '93 Warriors under head coach Nelson. Paul Westphal,
Sonics: 1. Played on '74 Celtics with Nelson. Scott Skiles, Suns:
1. Played on '87 Bucks coached by Nelson. Mike Dunleavy, Blazers:
1. Played on '85 Bucks coached by Nelson. Garry St. Jean, Warriors:
1. Assistant on '89 Warriors under head coach Nelson.
</P>
<P>
   2 Alvin Gentry, Pistons: 1. Assistant with '91 Clippers under
head coach Mike Schuler. 2. Schuler was an assistant with '86 Bucks
under head coach Nelson. Chris Ford, Clippers: 1. Assistant with
'83 Celtics under head coach K.C. Jones. 2. Jones was an assistant
with '77 Bucks under head coach Nelson. Lionel Hollins, Grizzlies:
1. Assistant with '92 Suns under head coach Paul Westphal. 2.
