<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BKN-NBA-REPORT-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
VINCE CARTER DESERVED OLYMPIC STRIPES
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By DWAIN PRICE 
c.1999 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Anyone who voted against Toronto's Vince Carter being on the
2000 U.S. Olympic basketball team ought to never vote for anything
else for the rest of their lives.
</P>
<P>
   How anyone could exclude the game's greatest showman is beyond
me. But the nine-person USA Basketball selection committee voted,
6-3, to have Milwaukee's Ray Allen in the Olympic Games rather than
Carter.
</P>
<P>
   Carter is one of the reasons why the NBA went to great lengths
to change the rules during the off-season. He is Mr. Excitement,
able to put goosebumps on even the most casual basketball fan.
</P>
<P>
   We, as sportswriters, are often fans of the sports we cover. We
get in free and have some pretty good seats. But we're there
because we love the game. We're there because we also love to be
entertained by players like Carter.
</P>
<P>
   Truth be told, we all rush home to see ESPN SportsCenter to
watch highlights of Carter soaring through the air. Why he won't be
able to soar through the air while representing our country in the
Olympics does nothing but cheat basketball fans all over the world.
</P>
<P>
   ``We are all fans at heart,'' said Isiah Thomas, a 12-time
all-star named to the 1980 U.S. Olympic team that boycotted the
Moscow Summer Games. ``And at the end of the day you want to be
able to sit down at home and eat some popcorn and a hotdog, get
something to drink, and watch the game and maybe somebody will make
you go oooh and aaah.
</P>
<P>
   ``Clearly, when you look at Vince Carter, if he's not the best
two-guard that's playing right now, then he's got to be the second-
or third-best behind Kobe Bryant and Allan Houston. I don't know
what the people were looking at.''
</P>
<P>
   Like the movie he stars in, Ray Allen's got game, but his is
below the rim where most of us fat-belly folks play.
</P>
<P>
   ``Ray is really good, but it's hard to put Ray Allen ahead of
Vince Carter,'' said Sacramento Kings general manager Jerry
Reynolds. ``Vince is about flash, youth and excitement.''
</P>
<P>
   Apparently, the USA Basketball selection committee wanted to
pick someone who would accept 12th-man status. Hey, I think Chuck
Nevitt or Bruno Sundov might relish such a role.
</P>
<P>
   At least real basketball fans know the score. They continue to
pour in more votes for Carter _ almost a million _ than any other
player for the Feb. 13 NBA All-Star Game.
</P>
<P>
   Mavericks fans are still buzzing about the spectacular four-dunk
display Carter put on at Reunion Arena on Dec. 30. Thomas saw it,
too, from his home.
</P>
<P>
   ``He did a real 360-degree dunk,'' Thomas raved. ``Most players
do a 180. But that was a real 360.''
</P>
<P>
   Raptors general manager Glen Grunwald said hes very disappointed
Carter was left off the Olympic squad.
</P>
<P>
   ``He deserves to be on the team,'' Grunwald said. ``He's one of
the best players in the world right now.''
</P>
<P>
   Perhaps someone should have slipped a reminder to the USA
Basketball selection committee.
</P>
<P>
   &LR; subheds:AROUND THE EAST  &LR; agatea:The return of New Jersey Nets
forward Jayson Williams has been pushed back another six-to-eight
weeks.
</P>
<P>
   Williams was hoping to start practicing this past week, but his
leg is just too weak.
</P>
<P>
   ``He has a significant strength deficiency in the surgically
repaired leg, so it would be foolhardy, if not irresponsible, to
allow him to practice,'' Nets GM John Nash said. ``As a result,
we're just going to work on strengthening the leg in order to allow
him to play at a later date.''
</P>
<P>
   Now what's Isaiah Rider up to? He has been suspended twice by
the Atlanta Hawks, and now has the gall to think the Hawks will
re-sign him when he becomes a free agent after this season.
</P>
<P>
   ``I hope they want me,'' Rider said. ``It's a great situation.
They let me do my thing on the court.''
</P>
<P>
   Chicago Bulls forward Toni Kukoc is back, and that could be bad
news for the Mavericks.
</P>
<P>
   Kukoc had been out since the fourth game of the season with back
spasms. The poor Bulls have doubled their win total _ from two to
four _ since Kukoc returned this past week.
</P>
<P>
   Through Friday, the Mavericks were only four games ahead of the
Bulls, who have the worst record in the NBA.
</P>
<P>
   Miami is 12-6 with Mavericks castoff Anthony Carter starting at
point guard in place of the injured Tim Hardaway.
</P>
<P>
   &LR; subheds:AROUND THE WEST  &LR; agatea:The Minnesota Timberwovles
followed an eight-game losing streak by winning eight of their next
nine games, including Thursday's 98-96 victory against Portland.
</P>
<P>
   By the way, a Timberwolves executive denied a published report
that they're trying to trade Terrell Brandon to the New York Knicks
for Kurt Thomas, Chris Childs and John Wallace.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're not in waste management,'' the executive said.
</P>
<P>
   Just call the Vancouver Grizzlies road warriors.
</P>
<P>
   After going 3-52 in their previous 55 road games, the Grizzlies
have now won three of their past 12 road games. That includes
breaking a 30-game road losing streak in Dallas, and winning the
second game played in Miami's brand new AmericanAirlines Arena this
past Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
   Los Angeles Lakers center Shaquille O'Neal averages 34 points
and 16 rebounds in his last six games and is the leading candidate
to win this year's most valuable player award.
</P>
<P>
   The contract for Denver Nuggets point guard Nick Van Exel is $77
million for five years. Five years are guaranteed for $50.5
million, with years six and seven guaranteed if he meets certain
incentives.
</P>
<P>
   &LR; subheds:SPOTLIGHT ON Malone stands his ground In his 14-plus
seasons in the NBA, perennial Utah Jazz all-star forward Karl
Malone thought he had seen it all.
</P>
<P>
   But when Mavericks coach/gerneral manager Don Nelson bumped him
in the chest Thursday night during a scene worthy of professional
wrestling, Malone couldn't believe his eyes.
</P>
<P>
   ``When I'm out there playing a game, whether you like the way I
play or not, I think you're totally out of line to get in a
player's face like that,'' Malone said. ``I have the utmost respect
for every coach because of their position.
</P>
<P>
   ``But I think it's a fine line that you don't cross, and I think
\RNelson\S crossed that line and I have no respect for that in this
game. He was up in my face. You don't go and pick an argument with
a player. I don't appreciate it at all.''
</P>
<P>
   Nelson, who was fined $10,000 and suspended by the NBA from last
night's game against Atlanta, said he was merely defending his
players.
</P>
<P>
   Malone defended the rough way he attacks the basket, with his
knee out high. One of those high knees caught Mavericks center
Shawn Bradley squarely in the stomach, prompting Nelson to blow his
stack.
</P>
<P>
   ``When I'm going to the basket, how many guys are really trying
to block my shots, or how many guys are really fouling me hard?''
Malone asked. ``I've played this game for 15 years, and I know when
a guy is going to block my shot and when he's going to commit a
hard foul.
</P>
<P>
   ``That's how I go to the hole, and I'm going to go to the hole
like that until I walk away from this game. I go hard.''
</P>
<P>
   Malone, 36, who said he doesn't know when he'll retire, said
Nelson is the first coach to bump him.
</P>
<P>
   ``I have nothing to apologize for and I will not apologize to
anybody for anything,'' said Malone, who was fined $10,000 by the
NBA for the incident. ``If my kids were watching that and they ask
me what happened when this old man walked up to me in my face, I'm
going to say he was out of hand.
</P>
<P>
   ``When you're on the court, you defend your territory. And no
one has a right to come out there, especially off the bench as a
coach and do anything like that.''
nn
</P>
</TEXT>
