<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-01-08 21:17 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A0500 &Cx1f; ttx-z
r s BC-FBN-COWBOYS-VIKINGS-T     01-08 0999
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FBN-COWBOYS-VIKINGS-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
COWBOYS SHOULD TOSS CONSERVATIVE GAME PLAN AND AIR IT OUT AGAINST
VIKINGS
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By RAY BUCK 
c.1999 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   MINNEAPOLIS _ Conventional wisdom screams for the Cowboys to
avoid getting into a shootout with the Minnesota Vikings today.
</P>
<P>
   But conventional wisdom, in this instance, may be a blueprint
for narrow defeat. And the Cowboys are interested in more than
keeping it close.
</P>
<P>
   As a seven-point underdog against the Vikings, the Cowboys take
a seven-game road losing streak into this NFC wild-card game at the
Metrodome.
</P>
<P>
   One thing the Cowboys learned from their Monday night loss
inside this building Nov. 8 is that no lead _ even a 17-0 lead _ is
safe against the Vikings because the Minnesota offense most likely
will find the end zone a few times.
</P>
<P>
   Minnesota set an NFL record last season by scoring 558 points.
This season, the Vikings scored 399 points.
</P>
<P>
   The Vikings have averaged 29.8 points per game the past two
seasons. By comparison, the Cowboys have scored 29 or more points
only 10 times in 33 games during the same two seasons. This
includes a scant three times in 1999 and none since beating
Washington, 38-20, nearly 21/2 months ago.
</P>
<P>
   In their Nov. 8 meeting, the Cowboys (albeit they lost Emmitt
Smith to a broken hand and Troy Aikman to a concussion) blew a 17-0
lead as the Vikings ran off 27 unanswered points.
</P>
<P>
   Vikings quarterback Jeff George threw three touchdown passes
that night: two to Randy Moss, including a 47-yarder, and one to
Cris Carter.
</P>
<P>
   Whether they like it or not, the Cowboys are going to have to
throw downfield with Troy Aikman looking for Raghib Ismail on the
slant or Jason Tucker on the deep post or Chris Brazzell on the
``go'' route.
</P>
<P>
   All this, of course, must be set up by the play-action pass. And
the play-action pass must gain its credibility from a successful
running game.
</P>
<P>
   Smith rushed for 140 yards and two touchdowns before breaking
his right hand with six minutes remaining in the first half Nov. 8.
He has some unfinished business ahead of him today.
</P>
<P>
   So does the entire Cowboys offense.
</P>
<P>
   Coach Chan Gailey was asked this week about ``shortening'' the
game _ thereby keeping Moss &AMP; Co. off the field as much as possible
_ by controlling the ball, staying in the huddle an extra couple of
seconds, maybe using long snap counts, etc.
</P>
<P>
   ``Sure we want to keep the score down ... when the ``Vikings''
have the ball,'' said Gailey, who wouldn't tip his hand on exact
offensive strategy, except to say that he is less interested in how
the Cowboys score than he is in how much.
</P>
<P>
   ``If it takes two minutes \Rto score\S ... fine. Just score,''
Gailey emphasized.
</P>
<P>
   No one around Valley Ranch this week has been naive enough to
think that the Vikings can be shut out, or even shut down.
</P>
<P>
   In their last two games against the Cowboys (Nov. 8 game and
1998 Thanksgiving Day), the Vikings have 779 total yards, 73 points
and two victories.
</P>
<P>
   Moss and Carter have combined for 25 catches for 505 yards and
seven touchdowns in those two games.
</P>
<P>
   The Cowboys, meanwhile, have 841 total yards, 53 points and two
losses to show for those two games.
</P>
<P>
   The biggest difference between these two offenses (and, to some
extent, these two teams overall) is that the Vikings do a better
job of finishing.
</P>
<P>
   The Vikings have won eight of their past 10 games, averaging
27.9 points per game. The Cowboys have lost six of their past 10
games, including two of their past three, averaging 24.3 points per
game during the last 21/2 months of the season.
</P>
<P>
   That's about the difference of a missed field goal per game.
</P>
<P>
   Speaking of Richie Cunningham, the Cowboys now have a field-goal
kicker Gailey can trust. Eddie Murray, 43, who last kicked for
these Vikings in '97 before coming out of retirement last month,
has made 7 of 9 field-goal attempts, including his past five.
</P>
<P>
   Of course, the Cowboys being able to score touchdowns rather
than field goals and being able to run off some clock in the
process of scoring points are factors in which team wins or loses
today.
</P>
<P>
   What we know is that the Vikings need to be outscored.
</P>
<P>
   They will score points, and they can do it by striking quickly
or putting together long drives.
</P>
<P>
   With George capable of seeing the whole field, and with Moss,
Carter and Jake Reed all running through the Cowboys' secondary,
the Vikings are able to attack deep as well as keep opposing
defenders honest by working the underneath routes.
</P>
<P>
   ``You can't sit back there and rot ... not against these guys,''
said Cowboys free safety George Teague. ``Our philosophy each week
is to make the other team go the hard way, make 'em go on 10- or
11-play drives. We feel most teams, eventually, will make a
mistake.
</P>
<P>
   ``But the Vikings are smart enough to see if you're playing deep
just to \Rprevent\S giving up the deep ball,'' Teague explained.
``So at some point, you've got to make a play back there.''
</P>
<P>
   No team turned the ball over more than the Vikings in 1999 _ 40
times (21 interceptions, 19 fumbles), tied with Arizona for the
NFL's worst.
</P>
<P>
   The Cowboys need turnovers to get Moss, Carter, et al., off the
field.
</P>
<P>
   And put the ball in the hands of Aikman and Smith. Because what
the Cowboys know is this:
</P>
<P>
   Last month, Kansas City's Elvis Grbac was able to get the Chiefs
not only into a shootout with the Vikings, but was able to win it,
31-28. If Grbac can do that, then why not Aikman?
</P>
<P>
   In late November, San Diego's Jim Harbaugh and Kenny Bynum
pushed the Vikings to the brink while getting the Chargers involved
in a high-scoring affair (35-27 loss for the Chargers). If Harbaugh
and Bynum can do that, then why not Aikman and Smith?
</P>
<P>
   In both cases, the Chiefs and Chargers went against conventional
wisdom, which should tell the underdog Cowboys that they might want
to find the nearest window inside the Metrodome today.
</P>
<P>
   And give conventional wisdom a toss.
nn
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
