<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FBN-VIKINGS-PLAYMAKERS-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
VIKINGS' PLAYMAKERS POSE SERIOUS CHALLENGE FOR COWBOYS
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By CLARENCE E. HILL JR. 
c.1999 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   In the hip-hop world that is the NFL 2000, there are two types
of creatures: players and player haters.
</P>
<P>
   No team fields more players (read: playmakers) than the
shot-calling Minnesota Vikings (10-6), who play the 8-8 Cowboys in
today's NFC wild-card game in Minneapolis.
</P>
<P>
   Cris Carter and Randy Moss are the second-most-productive
pass-catching duo in league history. Running back Robert Smith can
score from anywhere on the field, and quarterback Jeff George's
right arm has few equals.
</P>
<P>
   ``They already have Carter and Moss, and now Robert Smith is
back,'' Cowboys cornerback Kevin Smith lamented. ``It's not even
fair.''
</P>
<P>
   Fair or not, ready or not...
</P>
<P>
   The Cowboys, who were the original players in their title years,
have been given their charge for today's game: Be player haters or
get played.
</P>
<P>
   The Vikings and their playmakers have been held to less than 20
points only three times in the past two seasons _ and they scored
17 in each of those games.
</P>
<P>
   Moss, who set a rookie record with 17 receiving touchdowns last
season, did anything but slump, catching more passes for more
yardage. Despite facing defenses designed to stop him, Moss caught
80 passes for an NFC-high 1,413 yards. He scored 12 touchdowns.
</P>
<P>
   Carter, fourth in the NFL in career receptions, caught 90 passes
for 1,241 yards and 13 touchdowns this season, improving in each
category over 1998. Moss and Carter came within 41 yards of the
record for a receiving duo in a season, set by Miami's Mark Duper
and Mark Clayton in 1984.
</P>
<P>
   The Vikings used a lot of three-receiver sets last season with
Jake Reed. In 1999, they thrived with more two-receiver formations,
and Carter credits his improvement to that and Moss' presence.
</P>
<P>
   ``Playing opposite Randy at the X-receiver spot that Michael
Irvin played so well is better for my style,'' Carter said.
</P>
<P>
   He said the early-season quarterback change _ from Randall
Cunningham to George _ was a key factor as well. George has the
third-highest quarterback rating in the league.
</P>
<P>
   ``Jeff gets me the ball more and allows me to do things I like
in the offense,'' Carter said. ``They try to get me the ball
more.''
</P>
<P>
   The Vikings turned to George after Cunningham struggled during a
2-4 start. George _ signed as a free agent in the off-season after
stints in Indianapolis, Atlanta and Oakland _ led Minnesota to an
8-2 record the rest of the way. He passed for 2,816 yards and 23
touchdowns.
</P>
<P>
   Now, the Cowboys will try to contain the Vikings. The defensive
line will try to rattle George with pressure to take the heat off
the secondary, which is healthier than it has been in weeks.
</P>
<P>
   Cornerback Deion Sanders, who was hobbled during the first
meeting between the two teams Nov. 8 with groin and hamstring
strains, said he's as injury-free as he has been in two years.
</P>
<P>
   Cornerback Kevin Smith, who missed the past three games with a
strained hamstring, might start, and nickel cornerback Kevin
Mathis, who missed the past month with a sprained knee, is expected
to play.
</P>
<P>
   ``Even if you had Lester Hayes and Mike Haynes, I don't know if
you have enough talent to make up for those two guys,'' Sanders
said. ``But I'm better this time. I think it will allow us to do
more things and not just sit back and wait on what they are going
to do. We are going to have some fun out there.''
</P>
<P>
   But as Kevin Smith said earlier, the addition of Robert Smith to
the Vikings' offense is ``unfair.'' Smith rushed for 1,015 yards _
including a 70-yard touchdown run two weeks ago _ despite missing
three games with a hernia.
</P>
<P>
   ``This guy can take the ball to the house,'' Cowboys defensive
coach Dave Campo said. ``It's like picking your poison. You are not
going to stop them. So it will be a chess game out there. Where are
we at? What are they tempted to do? What do we need to do to slow
them down? They have outstanding receivers, a great running back
and an outstanding quarterback. You can put them all together,
shake them around and see what's the best way to get the job
done.'' Added Sanders: ``I wish our offense would let the clock
tick down to the last second before every snap. Because the more
you keep those guys off the field the less opportunities they
have.''
nn
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
