<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FBN-NFL-PARITY-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
NFL BECOMES A PARODY OF PARITY
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By CHAREAN WILLIAMS 
c.1999 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   The NFL playoffs have turned into a lottery. Go ahead, pick a
team. Any team.
</P>
<P>
   The St. Louis Rams? The Jacksonville Jaguars? The Indianapolis
Colts? The Minnesota Vikings?
</P>
<P>
   Nobody is playing favorites.
</P>
<P>
   In the NFC, the fifth-seeded Cowboys (8-8) might have as good a
chance as the top-seeded St. Louis Rams (13-3). Of the six teams in
the NFC playoffs, the Cowboys have the only quarterback who has won
a playoff game. The Rams, whose opponents combined for an NFL-worst
93-163 record, have only 12 players with playoff experience.
</P>
<P>
   In the AFC, the second-seeded Indianapolis Colts (13-3) have the
same record as the fourth-seeded Tennessee Titans (13-3). And the
Titans, who have won four in a row, sport the longest winning
streak of the 12 playoff teams.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think it's wide-open,'' Cowboys cornerback Deion Sanders
said. ``I think anybody could win it. There's a movie out right now
called /Any Given Sunday''.''
</P>
<P>
   The only given this postseason is that there are none.
</P>
<P>
   In NFL history, five wild-card teams have reached the Super
Bowl. The 1980 Oakland Raiders and the 1997 Denver Broncos are the
only wild-card teams to win a championship.
</P>
<P>
   However, jokers are wild this postseason.
</P>
<P>
   Most Las Vegas oddsmakers like the Rams to win Super Bowl XXXIV,
but even the Cowboys are given a prayer.
</P>
<P>
   ``Once you've been invited to the dance, you can take the prom
queen home,'' Seattle Seahawks linebacker Chad Brown said. ``You're
in the dance. Everybody has a chance.''
</P>
<P>
   Most of the Super Bowl contenders entered the playoffs doing the
moonwalk.
</P>
<P>
   Only three postseason qualifiers ended the regular season with
at least three consecutive victories. The Miami Dolphins went 2-6
in the second half of the season. The Cowboys are 4-6 in their past
10 games. The Seattle Seahawks have lost five of six. The Detroit
Lions ended the regular season with a four-game losing streak.
</P>
<P>
   The Super Bowl Shuffle began yesterday, and until the music
stops Jan. 30 in Atlanta, this postseason promises to play out at
78 rpm.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't know if the word is `watered down' or not, but there's
not a great or dominant team out there,'' FOX-TV analyst John
Madden said. ``In that, there's no real givens where you can say,
`This is a team that is going to the Super Bowl and win the Super
Bowl.' Therefore, it's wide-open. As a football purist and
traditionalist, I really don't like it. I don't think that that's
good.
</P>
<P>
   ``But I think because of that, this has been one of the most
interesting years. Not a good year. Not a talented year. But an
interesting year. I think that's going to carry through the
playoffs. I don't think there's going to be great football, but I
think they're going to be interesting games.''
</P>
<P>
   Parity has become parody.
</P>
<P>
   The NFL brags that for the first time in history four teams
finished with 13 or more victories, but the league declined to
publicize the fact that a record nine teams finished .500. The
previous high was six in 1974 and '83.
</P>
<P>
   The Lions and the Cowboys both got in this postseason tournament
despite going .500. Before this season, only three 8-8 teams ever
had secured postseason berths.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's not a very good year for the NFC,'' New York Giants
quarterback Kerry Collins said. ``I don't know what the explanation
is for it. I don't know if these things go in cycles or what, but
... there are a lot of football teams that obviously didn't play
the way they wanted to play all season and their record shows it.''
</P>
<P>
   Jacksonville was the only one of the six division winners from
last season to repeat, and seven of the 12 playoff teams from 1998
failed to qualify this season. Three of those teams _ the New York
Jets, the New England Patriots and the Green Bay Packers _ lost
their head coaches last week.
</P>
<P>
   The other five division winners this season finished at .500 or
below a year ago. The Colts established the biggest turnaround in
NFL history, going from 3-13 to 13-3. The Rams finished 4-12 a year
ago, and the Redskins were 6-10.
</P>
<P>
   ``There's so little difference between the top teams and the
bottom teams,'' said Coach Dan Reeves, whose Atlanta Falcons went
from 7-9 in 1997 to 14-2 and the NFC title last season to 5-11 this
season. ``I think our season last year gave everybody hope that you
can go from a real poor football team to a real good football team
in one year. Or vice versa.''
</P>
<P>
   There are two things missing from the playoffs this year: the
San Francisco 49ers and the Green Bay Packers.
</P>
<P>
   From 1966-98, the Cowboys, the 49ers and the Packers had 54
playoff appearances, 17 Super Bowl appearances and 13 Super Bowl
titles. The league's three premier teams have missed the playoffs
in the same season only once.
</P>
<P>
   But Green Bay and San Francisco are home this postseason, and
the Cowboys barely survived the cut.
</P>
<P>
   ``I look at this thing as the salary cap finally coming home,''
FOX-TV analyst Cris Collinsworth said. ``We saw immediately when
free agency and the salary cap were put into place that teams like
Dallas and San Francisco were able to buy their way around it, but
now they're having to pay that price. And the teams that weren't
able to do that big up-front spending all of a sudden are getting
closer.''
</P>
<P>
   Minnesota Vikings receiver Cris Carter took offense earlier this
week when asked about the ``mediocrity'' in the NFL this season. He
said that is an inaccurate perception based on down years by the
Cowboys, San Francisco, Green Bay and Denver.
</P>
<P>
   ``If you look at the emergence of St. Louis and Indianapolis,
they are very good football teams _ in any year,'' Carter said.
``You can make yourself think that they wouldn't be good teams if
it was another year, but that's not true.''
</P>
<P>
   But not everyone is picking the Rams or the Colts to end up
meeting in the Super Bowl. For perhaps the first time in history,
these playoffs are missing a prohibitive Super Bowl favorite.
</P>
<P>
   ``Everyone says they like parity, but in reality, everybody
likes the dominant team,'' Buccaneers coach Tony Dungy said. ``Then
you can root against them. Or if it happens to be your team, then
you're happy. I think sports has always flourished with the
dominant team, and I think that's the way most fans deep down
inside would like it.''
</P>
<P>
   Although everyone is meeting in the middle, someone has to come
out on top. Which team that will be is anyone's guess.
</P>
<P>
   ``It appears to be anyone's race,'' Cowboys quarterback Troy
Aikman said. ``I don't think anyone looks at it and says, `This is
definitely the team. If they don't make it, something is clearly
wrong.' You've got a lot of teams that are pretty much lumped in
there together. A lot of different people are going to have a lot
of different opinions \Rabout who is going to win it\S.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-01-08-00 2118EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
