<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SUMMER-BASKETBALL-2ND </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SUMMER BASKETBALL PROGRAMS ARE SURROUNDED BY CORRUPTION 
</HEADLINE>
 TAKE-KAN   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By MARK MORRIS, KATIE FUNK and HOWARD RICHMAN  
 c. 2000 Kansas City Star  
<TEXT>
<P>
   According to a fall 1998 survey by the National Association of
Basketball Coaches, 70 percent of Division I college basketball
coaches support summer recruiting.
</P>
<P>
   However, at its meeting this week, the NCAA will consider
competing proposals to either limit the summer recruiting period
from 24 to 14 days, or to eliminate it entirely. All the proposals
are aimed at limiting the influence of summer-league coaches and
agents.
</P>
<P>
   Proposals also would require closer monitoring and greater
financial disclosure of events where coaches are permitted to
recruit.
</P>
<P>
   Michael A. Tranghese, commissioner of the Big East Conference,
isn't convinced the NCAA can stop the problems.
</P>
<P>
   ``I believe the problems are larger than us,'' he said. ``How do
I, as a commissioner, deal with an agent who's talking to a kid in
the ninth grade? I think the problem is societal. It pains me to
say that.''
</P>
<P>
   KU men's basketball head coach Roy Williams agrees there are no
easy answers.
</P>
<P>
   ``We can't cure college basketball's problems by cutting out
summer recruiting,'' Williams said. ``Some people think the abuses
would stop if college coaches stopped going to the summer
tournaments. But think back to when you were 16. If somebody
offered me a trip to Las Vegas when I was 16, would I worry about
whether the coaches were there. No, I'd take the trip.''
</P>
<P>
   Williams still is concerned, however, and said parents should
keep control of the recruiting pressures.
</P>
<P>
   ``I've always said the best decisions are made when the
youngster makes the decision with guidance from the parents,'' he
said.
</P>
<P>
   ``When you get somebody from the outside, it's unusual to have
someone whose only concern is what's best for the youngster.''
</P>
<P>
   Kenneth Shaw, chancellor of Syracuse University, was chairman of
the NCAA's Division I basketball task force. He favors any proposal
that will make recruiters deal more directly with high school
coaches.
</P>
<P>
   ``We'd like to believe that the high school coaches have not
only the student's athletic progress in mind, but also their
academic and social progress,'' Shaw said. ``That's what they're
there for. They're educators.''
</P>
<P>
   The NCAA also is seeking greater cooperation with shoe
companies, whose money often drives the frenzy of summer
basketball. Sonny Vaccaro, who deals with coaches for Adidas,
acknowledged his company's role in the process. But his solution is
novel and unlikely.
</P>
<P>
   ``Do not allow any company affiliated with athletic situations _
Gatorade, shoe companies _ to give any money to anybody at the
amateur level,'' Vaccaro said. ``We sponsor teams because we want
to see the best kids at our tournaments. When the corporations give
money, they expect results.''
</P>
<P>
   Vaccaro is not willing to leave the court to the competition.
</P>
<P>
   ``Then Nike will own everything,'' he said. ``If one person
owned everything ... could you imagine the corruption then?''
</P>
<P>
   Further down the basketball food chain, high school coaches and
players try to deal with a flawed system that isn't all bad, they
said.
</P>
<P>
   ``There are real good AAU coaches and a lot with poor
characters,'' said Rick Zych, boys basketball coach at Bishop Miege
High School. ``I've been around some of the coaches who believe
that grades and hard work are important. But for the most part, AAU
coaches only care about the basketball player. The high school
coaches see the kids daily, can talk about work habits, know how
the kid performs academically.''
</P>
<P>
   But Piggie defends the summer leagues, saying they keep some
youths who might otherwise be on the streets out of trouble.
</P>
<P>
   ``I get blasted for trying to help these kids,'' Piggie said,
``and that's not fair. I'm trying to help these kids for life.
</P>
<P>
   ``The AAU atmosphere these kids face is like NBA or college
atmosphere. They travel, and they play against the best kids in the
country. There's a lot of pressure to perform, but it lets you know
where your game really is at.''
</P>
<P>
   Lathrop, who has won more than 800 games in his 41 years as
coach, said summer basketball wasn't a true gauge of a player's
ability.
</P>
<P>
   ``How can a college coach judge kids in those games? Those games
are like a gym class,'' Lathrop said. ``They just run up and down
the floor, and whoever has the ball shoots it.''
</P>
<P>
   Kenny Oliver, a Raytown South junior with dreams of playing
big-time college ball, has decided not to play summer basketball,
as he has in past summers.
</P>
<P>
   It isn't that the system is rocked with scandal. It just doesn't
meet his needs, he said.
</P>
<P>
   Oliver said: ``I'd rather go to the gym and shoot 500 times
instead of shooting 10 times in an AAU game.''
</P>
<P>
   (30)
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-01-08-00 2130EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT20000108.0236 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-01-08 21:31 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A0508 &Cx1f; kan-z
r s BC-SUMMER-BASKETBALL-2TA     01-08 1089
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SUMMER-BASKETBALL-2TAKES-KAN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SUMMER BASKETBALL PROGRAMS ARE SURROUNDED BY CORRUPTION 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By MARK MORRIS, KATIE FUNK and HOWARD RICHMAN  
 c. 2000 Kansas City Star  
<TEXT>
<P>
   KANSAS CITY, Mo. _ One of the most successful high school
basketball coaches in the country, Raytown (Mo.) South's Bud
Lathrop, feels a bit lonely these days.
</P>
<P>
   It used to be that when Lathrop had a top prospect, college
coaches would flock to his gym on recruiting trips.
</P>
<P>
   ``Ted Owens, Digger Phelps, Nolan Richardson all have come
through here,'' Lathrop said. But college coaches don't come around
as much now, he said.
</P>
<P>
   The reason is summer basketball. College coaches now do much of
their recruiting during the summer _ at games, tournaments and
camps unrelated to the athletes' high schools. Some athletes are
playing more games for their summer-league teams than for their
high schools.
</P>
<P>
   Issues surrounding summer leagues are at the heart of a federal
grand jury probe that has sidelined three university basketball
players from Kansas City. The players _ Kareem Rush, JaRon Rush and
Andre Williams _ all have reportedly acknowledged receiving
payments or benefits from their former summer-league coach, a
Kansas City businessman or a Los Angeles sports agent.
</P>
<P>
   The grand jury is exploring whether amateur athletes were paid
to play basketball, thereby endangering their eligibility and
potentially defrauding federally funded universities.
</P>
<P>
   But the grand jury isn't alone in looking at summer basketball
programs.
</P>
<P>
   This week in San Diego the National Collegiate Athletic
Association will discuss changes to basketball recruiting rules to
limit the influence of summer coaches.
</P>
<P>
   ``Many of these individuals operate in a structure devoid of any
accountability,'' an NCAA task force reported last summer.
</P>
<P>
   Summer basketball tournaments _ often held by the Amateur
Athletic Union _ have been around for decades. The teams, organized
independently, can be sponsored by corporations or charitable
groups, which often pay for travel, uniforms and shoes.
</P>
<P>
   Coaches engaged by the sponsors recruit players and run the
teams. The best players move to premier teams, hoping that head
college coaches, with more time in the summer to travel, will be
able to evaluate them.
</P>
<P>
   According to a new basketball book, Sole Influence: Basketball,
Corporate Greed and the Corruption of America's Youth, real money
began to flow into youth basketball in 1996. That year,
Philadelphia's Kobe Bryant became the first academically qualified
player to turn pro after high school, noted the book's authors, Dan
Wetzel of Basketball Times and Don Yaeger of Sports Illustrated.
</P>
<P>
   Firms such as Nike and Adidas pour millions of dollars into
traveling teams of high school all-stars and flashy camps where top
prospects dunk in front of college recruiters. Professional sports
agents also have begun attending the camps.
</P>
<P>
   The coaches of those all-star teams sometimes receive lucrative
consulting contracts with the shoe companies. Former Kansas City
coach Myron Piggie, for whom the Rush brothers and Williams played
while in high school, received a consulting contract that he said
was worth $50,000 a year to tout Nike products and take his team to
summer tournaments.
</P>
<P>
   As for the players, University of Kansas basketball player Drew
Gooden put it frankly: They get free gear, clothes and shoes.
``Things like that corrupt a kid's mind,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Shoe company spokesmen say their only interest is to market
their products and provide opportunities to high school athletes.
</P>
<P>
   Piggie said that he only gave his players legitimate expense
money on trips, which is permitted by NCAA rules, and that he had
done nothing wrong.
</P>
<P>
   Kansas State Vice President Robert Krause, who oversees the
day-to-day operations of the school's athletic programs, said the
system could wreck an athlete's attitude about academics.
</P>
<P>
   ``It conditions kids to come to the university just for the
sport,'' Krause said. ``The kids are brought into the farm system
with the expectation that they're doing it for a career in the
sport and not for an education.''
</P>
<P>
   Greg Gurley, a former star player at Shawnee Mission South who
later played at Kansas, remembers summer ball during a simpler
time, the late 1980s and early 1990s.
</P>
<P>
   ``We had a team, the KC Wildcats, and we played in places like
Las Vegas and Los Angeles,'' said Gurley, 27, who led Shawnee
Mission South to an undefeated state championship in the 1989-1990
basketball season. ``We had to raise money to go on trips, maybe
$2,000 to $3,000 every summer for each of us. There were no
improprieties going on with us. We got our money by selling yellow
trash bags, candy bars, lollipops, anything we could. I'd mow
lawns.''
</P>
<P>
   Rockhurst High School coach Mark Nusbaum says he can tell when
players have adopted the summer basketball mentality _ they expect
to be wined and dined.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's almost tough for players to come back (to high school
basketball) after playing in the summer,'' Nusbaum said. ``We've
got freshmen who've been to Orlando. They come back here, and where
do we go? Leavenworth. These kids have had the best uniforms, best
warmups, they're given travel bags, shoes. ... They come back and
say, `We have to wear these uniforms?' They wonder why they have to
stay at the Motel 6 and not the Ritz.''
</P>
<P>
   Though summer teams often are tagged with the ``AAU'' label,
that organization's executive director cautions that the Amateur
Athletic Union only organizes the tournaments.
</P>
<P>
   ``The AAU does not have teams,'' Bobby Dodd said. ``We do not
pay bills. We do not select coaches.''
</P>
<P>
   Stung by criticism that Piggie, convicted of a felony, was
coaching teams in AAU-sponsored tournaments, Dodd said the
organization adopted rules about a year ago requiring coaches to
disclose their criminal records before they can participate.
</P>
<P>
   ``The responsibility for appropriate adults working in youth
programs lies with the parents and guardians,'' Dodd said. ``They
are the ones who are there day to day.''
</P>
<P>
   While much of the current attention is focused on the college
men's game, Pam DeCosta, the KU women's assistant coach in charge
of recruiting, said problems on the women's side weren't far
behind.
</P>
<P>
   ``I would love it if you could go out and wouldn't have to talk
to the AAU coaches,'' she said. ``I think it's going to get a
little bit dirtier. ... The men's (game) is crazy and we follow
suit.''
</P>
<P>
   (more)
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
