<SLUG> BC-RAC-SANTAANITA-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SWEPT OVERBOARD WINS AT SANTA ANITA
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By FRANK C. GIRARDOT  
 San Gabriel Valley Tribune  
<TEXT>
<P>
   ARCADIA, Calif. _ For a horse that didn't run his race, Swept
Overboard finished Saturday's $100,000 Grade III San Miguel Stakes
in style, winning the 6 furlong sprint and beating favorite Forest
Camp by the slimmest of margins.
</P>
<P>
   The race, considered the first test for West Coast
three-year-olds who hope to run in the Santa Anita and Kentucky
derbies, featured a group of owners and trainers who had never won
it.
</P>
<P>
   On the other hand, winning jockey Eddie Delahoussaye made his
fifth trip to the winner's circle in the San Miguel. That makes him
the event's all-time leading rider.
</P>
<P>
   Swept Overboard, who looked to be the early speed of the field,
came from the back of the pack and won a stretch duel with Forest
Camp. Trained by John Shirreffs, Swept Overboard covered the 6
furlongs in 1:08.99.
</P>
<P>
   ``Today he broke real slow,'' Delahoussaye said. It was a real
tough fight for the last 100 yards.''
</P>
<P>
   Delahoussaye said the pre-race instructions He received from
Shirreffs were helpful.
</P>
<P>
   ``He told me to let the horse do what he wants,'' Delahoussaye
said. ''
</P>
<P>
   In order to be considered a hopeful for either the Santa Anita
or Kentucky Derby, Swept Overboard will have to prove He can run
well at a distance of a mile or greater. All his previous races
have been six furlongs or less.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is a big step for him,'' said Shirreffs. We'll let the
horse dictate where He wants to go, not where we want to put him.
</P>
<P>
   ``There's only one way you can find out,'' he said. ``That's
when you run.''
</P>
<P>
   As for Forest Camp, his finish was the second big disappointment
for the horse in recent months. Although He won the Grade II Del
Mar Futurity back in September, the Bob Baffert-trained Forest Camp
finished sixth in the Breeder's Cup Juvenile in November. ``What
are you going to do?'' Baffert asked. ``He drew the rail and when
you are down on the inside you have to use them a little more. You
have to be just a little more than the best from the one-hole.''
</P>
<P>
   McCarron saved his comments for Delahoussaye.
</P>
<P>
   ``I can't believe Eddie D. outrode me again,'' He said. ``This
was a good start for the year.''
</P>
<P>
   While Swept Overboard's future is somewhat uncertain, Baffert
has already set his sights on Forest Camp's next race.
</P>
<P>
   ``We'll try the San Vicente,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   __The stable run by Santa Anita owner Frank Stronach had a
winner on the dirt course in Saturday's third race. That winner was
Luftikus, ridden by Kent Desormeaux.
</P>
<P>
   The win was Desormeaux's second of the afternoon. His first came
aboard Stabilizer in the second. Both helped Desormeaux maintain
his lead as Santa Anita's top jockey in 2000.
</P>
<P>
   __Stronach's plans for Santa Anita rennovation became a bit
clearer this week. The Arcadia City Planning Commission has sent a
letter to homeowners living within 1000 feet of the track detailing
some of Stronach's ideas. The letter advises that there will be an
open public meeting on Jan. 25 at City Hall.
</P>
<P>
   Stronach is asking to city to allow his FrontRunner restaurant
to remain open until 1:30 p.m. seven days a week for satellite
wagering and unspecified other activities. Current city code only
permits late operation on Friday and Saturday night.
</P>
<P>
   Track management is also asking permission to leave the big
screen television on the infield turned on until 1:30 p.m. All the
better to see those simulcast races.
</P>
<P>
   __The Board of Stewards fined jockey David Flores $100 Saturday
for ``reporting late to the padock.''
</P>
<P>
   No further details of the incident were disclosed.
</P>
<P>
   __A 66-year-old jockey will tempt fate Thursday in part of an
attempt to make history.
</P>
<P>
   Jockey Ray York, a fixture of the Southern California racing
scene for six decades, will ride Culebra in Thursday's seventh
race. Doing so will make him (according to the flacks at Santa
Anita) the first jockey to ever ride in seven decades.
</P>
<P>
   York's first professional mount came in June 1949. He won his
first race a month later. York's last ride was in 1992 at Bay
Meadows in Northern California.
</P>
<P>
   In between He won 3,082 races; one of those was the 1954
Kentucky Derby aboard Determine.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
