<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-DEBATE-DEMOCRATS-KAN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
GORE AND BRADLEY SPAR OVER FAMILIAR ISSUES 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By STEVE KRASKE and SCOTT CANON  
 c. 2000 Kansas City Star   JOHNSTON, Iowa _ In an hour of polite
slights and digs at nuanced policy differences, Al Gore and Bill
Bradley demonstrated Saturday that they mostly agreed on
government's role in the final year of the 20th century.
<TEXT>
<P>
   Yet the men also showed how their campaigns and characters
differ in manner and mode.
</P>
<P>
   Asked how to end school violence, for instance, the vice
president wonkishly rattled off a list of programs from income tax
credits to drug enforcement that could ``give our children a
feeling that their life has meaning.''
</P>
<P>
   More professorially, the former senator from New Jersey spoke in
bigger, if less specific, terms and settled on the need for ``a new
ethic of responsibility.''
</P>
<P>
   Throughout their debate, much of it spent sparring over how best
to save Medicaid and Medicare, the Democratic rivals made clear
their differences in style. Gore was full of details. Bradley was
big on vision.
</P>
<P>
   Gore seized on that theme to close the afternoon face-off. The
presidency is not ``an academic exercise or a seminar on
theories,'' he said, poking at Bradley's deep-thinking ways. ``I
think the presidency has to be a day-to-day, resolute fight for the
American people.''
</P>
<P>
   Bradley, in turn, said the presidency was about leadership.
Although he didn't use terms like the ``Great Society,'' he lauded
Lyndon Johnson as a bold leader willing to tackle America's most
intractable problems.
</P>
<P>
   ``What leadership is about, I believe, is taking a national
problem _ health care, education _ and turning it into a public
issue and then engaging the idealism of the American people in
order to make something happen,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   That, Bradley added, is what President Franklin Roosevelt did in
the 1930s with Social Security.
</P>
<P>
   ``They didn't say, `Well, we're going to cover 20 percent of the
people and see how it works out,' '' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Held just 16 days before the Jan. 24 caucuses _ the first major
event in a speeded-up primary season _ Saturday's debate came as
Bradley seeks to wrestle the Democratic nomination away from a
sitting vice president. The Republican candidates will next debate
in Iowa on Saturday.
</P>
<P>
   A poll released Saturday in The Des Moines Register suggested
that Gore had managed to halt Bradley's advance in Iowa. In June,
Gore towered over Bradley by being favored by 64 percent of
Democrats to Bradley's 24 percent. By November, Bradley had climbed
to 32 percent and Gore had fallen to 54 percent. The poll of 501
likely Democratic caucus participants released in Saturday's paper
showed the numbers essentially stuck: Gore 54 percent, Bradley 33
percent.
</P>
<P>
   On the Republican side, Texas Gov. George W. Bush continued to
pace the field with 45 percent support. Publisher Steve Forbes was
in second place with 18 percent.
</P>
<P>
   Saturday's forum found the candidates treading on familiar
ground. Bradley advocated the more sweeping changes in health care
and gun control, while Gore insisted that Bradley's initiatives
could exhaust the country's newfound budget surplus.
</P>
<P>
   Gore's preparation for the debate was pointed and precise,
seemingly scripted.
</P>
<P>
   When Gore and Bradley disagreed over how much the premiums for
Bradley's replacement health insurance program for Medicaid would
run, Gore presented debate moderator Dennis Ryerson with a list of
insurance companies in the state _ none of which, the vice
president said, would meet Bradley's price. When Gore wanted to
make a point about education, he asked a first-grade teacher
planted in the audience to stand up.
</P>
<P>
   And when he wanted to argue that Bradley is a late arrival to
the cause of family farming, he asked a hog farmer to rise to his
feet while wondering aloud why Bradley had voted against aid to
help rural Iowa recover from the flood of 1993.
</P>
<P>
   For this, Bradley seemed ready.
</P>
<P>
   ``The premise of your question is wrong,'' he said. ``This
(campaign) is not about the past. This is about the future.'' And
then later in the debate: ``I would simply ask the family farmer of
Iowa, `Are you better off now than you were seven years ago?' ... I
will not rest until rural America and urban America move ahead.''
</P>
<P>
   As they have in other forums, the two clashed on health care, an
issue of growing concern in Iowa because of its older-than-average
population. Bradley's plan would devote $65 billion yearly toward
overhauling Medicare and Medicaid in an effort to insure nearly
every American. Gore wants a phased-in transition to programs that
would cover more people, but not the universal coverage Bradley
envisions. Gore says Bradley's plan is too expensive. Bradley
complains Gore's doesn't do enough to deal with a serious problem.
</P>
<P>
   The two were questioned by senior citizen Margaret Rooney about
which candidate's plan would help her most with her soaring
prescription drug costs. Rooney said her bills topped $5,600 a
year.
</P>
<P>
   Bradley said his plan would wind up covering about $2,100 of the
woman's costs. Gore never said exactly what his plan would cover,
although Bradley's campaign calculated afterward that under Gore's
plan Rooney would pay more than $4,900.
</P>
<P>
   But Gore pointed to a broader question. He charged that Bradley
failed to spend more money on Medicare, which Gore said was
destined to go bankrupt in 2015 ``unless we start acting to save it
now.'' Even Sen. John McCain, a Republican presidential candidate
from Arizona, calls for spending more on Medicare, the vice
president said.
</P>
<P>
   Bradley countered that the program was on sound financial
footing until 2015.
</P>
<P>
   ``The vice president said that I was prepared to let Medicare
go. Absolutely not,'' Bradley said. ``I replace Medicare, not
neglect it.''
</P>
<P>
   Moving to campaign reform, Gore repeated his challenge to
Bradley that the two drop all television advertising in at least
one state to demonstrate their commitment to changing the election
system. Gore would replace the ads with more one-on-one debates in
that state.
</P>
<P>
   Noting that Bradley has refused such overtures before, Gore
picked up a line from the show ``Who Wants to Be a Millionaire?''
and asked Bradley: ``Is that your final answer?''
</P>
<P>
   Bradley seemed unmoved and once again refused to go along with
Gore's proposal. Campaigns can communicate a lot of information in
30 seconds, he said. Later, Bradley noted that Gore had supported
campaign reform for two decades.
</P>
<P>
   ``Well, nothing's happened. ... The administration hasn't
submitted a campaign reform bill,'' Bradley said.
</P>
<P>
   (30)
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
