<SLUG> BC-BBO-BBNOTES-PROSPECTS-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
LOOK OUT BELOW FOR SOX PROSPECTS 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By GORDON EDES  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   The Internet has been buzzing with tales of a hot Red Sox
prospect down in Mexico by the name of Melville Stakes.
</P>
<P>
   Haven't heard of him? The story, as spread in cyberspace, is
that Stakes is a 6-foot-4-inch, 215-pounder from Rutland, Vt., an
18-year-old switch hitter who in 57 games in Mexico this winter hit
52 home runs, stole 46 bases, batted .391, and drove in 127 runs.
His performance may have slipped Peter Gammons's notice, but the
word on the Web is that Sox general manager Dan Duquette was
thinking of having the kid go straight from Sonora to the big
leagues.
</P>
<P>
   Oh, and he pitches, too.
</P>
<P>
   The answer to every Red Sox fan's dream?
</P>
<P>
   Sadly, as Baseball America was only too glad to point out in
response to one naive inquiry, Melville Stakes is a fantasy, sprung
from the same fictional origins that some years ago gave us Sidd
Finch, the mythical hurler from the Himalayas. Nice try, but
someone smelled a rat in Rutland.
</P>
<P>
   There is, however, a true story out of Mexico that should fire
the imagination of any Sox fan who last summer embraced the ballad
of the Belleville Basher, Brian Daubach, as unlikely a hero as the
Sox have had in many years.
</P>
<P>
   And unlike Melville Stakes, Morgan Burkhart exists, though
whether he is for real may not be known until he shows up at
training camp in Fort Myers this spring.
</P>
<P>
   Burkhart, a 27-year-old switch-hitting first baseman, last week
was named Most Valuable Player of the Mexican winter league after
leading the circuit with 55 RBIs in 67 games. He also hit 18 home
runs, began the season with a 19-game hitting streak, and according
to the Sox became the first player in Mexican League history to
homer from both sides of the plate in the same game.
</P>
<P>
   This, after a season in which he hit .363 with 23 home runs and
67 RBIs in just 68 games for Single A Sarasota in the Florida State
League, then was promoted to Double A Trenton, where he hit another
12 home runs and drove in 41 runs in another 66 games.
</P>
<P>
   Add them up _ Sarasota, Trenton, and Navajoa in the Mexican
League _ and you've got a player who in a year's span has hit 53
home runs and knocked in 163 runs in 201 games.
</P>
<P>
   Who is this guy? Even the Sox, who signed him last winter,
weren't quite sure. They misspelled his name in the team's media
guide.
</P>
<P>
   But the Burkhart believers know their man, who grew up in
suburban St. Louis _ on the other side of the Mississippi River
from Daubach _ went undrafted despite leading Central Missouri
State to a Division 2 title, then was working construction in a
warehouse until his baseball career was revived.
</P>
<P>
   ``He's the greatest hitter I've ever been around,'' said John
Cate, who managed Burkhart in the four years he spent playing for
the Richmond Roosters in the independent Frontier League.
</P>
<P>
   Cate is a longtime Indiana high school baseball coach who never
had heard of Burkhart until he ran into a Central Missouri coach at
a baseball clinic in Chicago who offered an unsolicited rave of a
player who hit .391 his last year in college.
</P>
<P>
   Why no interest from the big boys?
</P>
<P>
   ``Those so-called scout cards,'' said Cate, whose disdain was
evident over the telephone. ``He didn't fit any of their
categories. Scouts don't want to admit mistakes. They'd say, `We
like him but we don't have a place for him.' Or, `He's too short.'
Or, `He doesn't have a position.' ''
</P>
<P>
   Burkhart is short, for a first baseman. He's listed as 5-10,
though he's got Popeye forearms, according to Cate.
</P>
<P>
   ``Remember Hack Wilson?'' said Frontier League commissioner Bill
(Not the Spaceman) Lee, invoking the name of the Hall of Fame Cubs
outfielder who was 5-6 but still holds the record for RBIs in a
season with 190. ``He's got arms like Hack Wilson.''
</P>
<P>
   In Burkhart's first season with Richmond, he finished runner-up
in MVP voting. The next three years, he won the award. His last
season there, he hit a league-record .404, with 36 home runs and 98
RBIs.
</P>
<P>
   ``He could have run for mayor and won,'' Lee said. ``He put our
league on the map. And in four years, he didn't miss a game. He
played through everything. He just loves the game.''
</P>
<P>
   Burkhart was paid $600 his first season with Richmond, $750 the
second. That was increased to $1,100 his last two seasons, plus all
the free luncheons he could attend in Richmond, where Rooster
players lived with host families.
</P>
<P>
   One night, playing in Johnstown, Pa., Burkhart was 5 for 5 when
he came up to the plate for a sixth at-bat and was intentionally
walked. The fans booed. Another night, at home, he came up with the
bases loaded in the bottom of the ninth and was given another
intentional walk.
</P>
<P>
   ``He has an unbelievable knowledge of the strike zone, and is
the most disciplined hitter I've ever seen,'' Cate said. ``Every
year we thought he wouldn't be coming back, but every year no one
signed him.''
</P>
<P>
   Even if he'd wanted to return for a fifth season, he couldn't.
He was too old for the Frontier League, which stipulates that a
player can't turn 27 before June 1 of a given season.
</P>
<P>
   Finally, the Sox came calling. Farm boss Kent Qualls offered
Burkhart a job last winter, and the kid hasn't stopped playing
since. Last week, with Navajoa in the playoffs, Burkhart hit two
home runs in the first game.
</P>
<P>
   Duquette said he hasn't decided whether Burkhart will be invited
to big-league camp as a nonroster player.
</P>
<P>
   ``Why not?'' Cate said. ``What do the Red Sox have to lose?''
</P>
<P>
   The Frontier League has yet to send an alumnus to the big
leagues, unlike independent circuits like the Northern League,
which can boast of such grads as Braves pitcher Kevin Millwood and
Rangers reliever Jeff Zimmerman, among others.
</P>
<P>
   ``Will Morgan make it?'' Cate said. ``I don't know, but it would
not surprise me if he gets the chance?''
</P>
<P>
   A better idea on Rocker
</P>
<P>
   As well-intentioned as they may have been, the great minds who
decided that Braves pitcher John Rocker should undergo a
psychological evaluation for his offensive blathering in a magazine
interview made a big mistake. What Rocker's rants conveyed in a
public context sadly didn't stray far from opinions aired in
private, not only in clubhouses, but in boardrooms, bedrooms, and,
yes, even some newspaper offices. There's a difference between
crazy and stupid, and it smacks too much of knee-jerk political
correctness to haul Rocker before a shrink. There may be an
epidemic of ignorance in this country _ and again, it's not limited
to ballplayers _ but it's not a question of mental competence, a
deprived childhood, or a conflicted sense of self. It's about
educating a person to their blind prejudices and hateful invective.
Braves boss Stan Kasten had the right idea when he suggested that
the next time the Braves visit New York, he take Rocker to the
Statue of Liberty. But Kasten, and Major League Baseball, and the
Players' Association shouldn't stop there. Rocker would have been
better served by doing what pitcher John Burkett did when he was
with the Florida Marlins and visited an AIDS hospice in Miami
Beach, while dressed in full uniform. Or by spending an afternoon
riding the No. 7 train with an immigrant son or daughter of this
country, then going to the job and later home with that person, who
has never had luxury of big-league meal money, never mind a
million-dollar salary. Send Rocker to a city school to speak to
kids who weren't blessed with a 95-mile-an-hour fastball but have
dreams every big as his. Rocker, like so many athletes _ like so
many of us _ has been insulated for too long from the real world. A
counseling session won't break through that cocoon. Having some
real contact with the very people Rocker ripped would be far more
useful. And Rocker will endure no greater punishment than what he
is sure to face within the walls of a multicultural Braves
clubhouse, and in stadiums filled with folks who will let him know
in unmistakable terms how wrong he was . . . Remember Carl Everett,
the center fielder who is supposed to be a new centerpiece in the
Sox' lineup this season? Well, Everett is finally going to get
around to coming to Boston on Thursday for an introductory press
conference, his first public appearance since the Sox acquired him
from Houston. There were the typical excuses made for Everett's
unavailability _ his wife had a baby, it was the holidays, etc. _
but somehow Jose Offerman made it here last December after he
signed, and Pedro Martinez flew up from the Dominican Republic
twice in a month's time after he came in a trade, then signed a new
deal. So the tolerance for Everett's no-show is odd for a club
charging its fans as much as $45 per game. By the way, Duquette
said Friday that he has yet to talk about a multiyear deal for
Everett with agent Larry Reynolds, who is also scheduled to come to
town this week . . . Duquette, incidentally, went to Sox doctors
Bill Morgan and Arthur Pappas for surgery to repair the torn thumb
ligament he suffered in a recent skiing accident. And Tom Gordon
would probably like to know that Duquette said it's not true that
Sox CEO John Harrington threatened to void his contract if he went
to someone other than a Sox doc.
</P>
<P>
   One-way tickets
</P>
<P>
   Dernell Stenson, the Sox first-base prospect, came home from the
Dominican Republic for the holidays and elected not to go back and
finish the winter league season there. Yes, the Sox would have
liked him to do so _ Duquette said it would have been good for him
to experience the intensity of the Dominican playoffs _ but you're
inviting only misery if you force a kid to stay in a place so
different from home if he doesn't want to be there. Third base
prospect Wilton Veras also dropped off the roster of his Dominican
team, Escogido, for whom he was batting just .214, and is working
out at the Sox academy in the island nation. A lack of playing time
is the reason given for Veras's decision . . . After signing Jeff
Fassero, the Sox never made another pitch for Doc Gooden, who last
week signed a minor league deal with Houston that includes a
$500,000 base salary and incentives that could make the package
worth as much as $2 million. Duquette said he still hopes to add
another pitcher, and mentioned Canton's Bobby Witt as still under
consideration . . . A man of his word: Duquette said there is no
language in Sunny Kim's contract that would keep him from being
traded, but because of Kim's strong desire to pitch in Fenway Park,
and his promise as a prospect, Duquette won't deal the young Korean
righthander, who probably will pitch in Pawtucket this season . . .
PawSox tickets are now on sale by phone (401-724-7300), fax
(401-724-2140) or online (www.pawsox.com), with walkup sales
beginning Feb. 5. The best news? Top seat is still just 7 bucks . .
. Inky, Dinky, Doo: The independent Nashua Pride signed Pete
Incaviglia, who spent most of last season recovering from rotator
cuff surgery. Inky, 35, has played for six big-league teams and now
joins Daddy Butch Hobson in Nashua.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-01-08-00 2157EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
