<HEADER>
A0513 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u s BC-BKN-NBANOTES-STJEAN-B     01-08 1812
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BKN-NBANOTES-STJEAN-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
ST. JEAN IS GOLDEN STATE WORRIER 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By PETER MAY  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   So, coach, how's it going?
</P>
<P>
   ``It hasn't been fun,'' Garry St. Jean said. ``It's been hard.
Real hard.''
</P>
<P>
   No kidding. St. Jean certainly hasn't had any fun the last
couple of weeks. He has gone from hesitant executioner _
terminating P.J. Carlesimo _ to hesitant overseer _ replacing
Carlesimo _ of one of the NBA's historically hapless franchises,
the Golden State Warriors. He has yet to win a game in his second
coaching incarnation, something that could change with a long
homestand and some equally inept opponents coming into Beirut by
the Bay.
</P>
<P>
   But St. Jean also knows the painful reality: He has no chance to
right the ship, assuming it hasn't been sinking from the start. Ask
him what he needs, other than healthy players, and St. Jean says,
``Training camp. The only problem with that is that everyone else
has played 30 games.''
</P>
<P>
   Or, as Suns senior executive vice president Cotton Fitzsimmons
said, ``It's just about impossible, coming into a situation like
that. You try to make it as easy as possible. You try to eliminate
the chaos. But there's no way. You need practice time. There isn't
any. I had the same thing happen when I replaced Paul Westphal. You
just can't do it. You have to do things piecemeal and that's never
good enough.''
</P>
<P>
   The Warriors thought they had a chance to be decent this season,
perhaps doing what Denver is now doing. Instead, they've been
awful. They've been decimated by injuries; St. Jean said that at
least three of the Warriors' projected top eight have been out for
every game (John Starks, Chris Mills, and Terry Cummings are the
current invalids). Then owner Chris Cohan decided to jettison
Carlesimo _ who was twisting in the wind anyway _ and had St. Jean,
who was brought in after P.J., deliver the word to a guy he never
hired in the first place.
</P>
<P>
   Said Fitzsimmons, ``They do things backwards out there.''
</P>
<P>
   St. Jean called the move ``the hardest thing I've ever done. I
don't want to do it again. Ever.'' He knew Carlesimo wasn't
succeeding. He also knew it wasn't for lack of trying.
</P>
<P>
   ``P.J. was in a no-win situation,'' Fitzsimmons said. ``I talked
to my son, Gary (the Warriors' assistant general manager) and told
him, `You've got a bad team.' And I know from bad teams. I always
started with them.''
</P>
<P>
   There are a couple of untouchables on the roster: Erick Dampier
and Antawn Jamison. Dampier just returned this week after missing
the first two months of the season. Their own first-round draft
pick in 2000 _ which could be a top three pick _ is headed to
Orlando, the last of the three first-rounders Don Nelson sent to
the Magic along with Penny Hardaway to get Chris Webber.
</P>
<P>
   The Warriors are still paying for the sins of St. Jean and, more
incredibly, of his predecessors. Saint undoubtedly would like to
have back the trade with Toronto, in which he sent draftee Vince
Carter and cash to the Raptors for Jamison. Recent draftees include
Adonal Foyle, Todd Fuller, and Joe Smith. Only Foyle is still
there. Fuller, taken ahead of Kobe Bryant, is in Charlotte. Smith,
taken first overall in 1995, was traded to Philadelphia for two
players (Clarence Weatherspoon and Jim Jackson) who left Golden
State high and dry as free agents. We haven't even gotten to
Latrell Sprewell. Or Donyell Marshall.
</P>
<P>
   The Warriors just completed a winless swing through the East,
finishing it off with a 75-point, 30-percent-shooting gem in
Cleveland. They've lost eight straight and have fewer wins than any
other team but Chicago. Cotton Fitzsimmons is right. They are a bad
team. Now it's St. Jean's turn to try to get blood out of a stone.
He's been around long enough to know that that equation doesn't
work.
</P>
<P>
   Dee's knees
</P>
<P>
   Dee Brown is back home in Orlando and could find out Monday what
the rest of his season will be like. Brown's left knee is bothering
him again and he has had two opinions: one from the Raptors,
suggesting rehab, the other from an independent source, suggesting
surgery. A third opinion is due from an Orlando specialist. Brown
is frustrated and would not return until March if he has another
operation. Left unsaid is that he's a free agent and not in
Toronto's future plans. Brown already has arthroscopic surgery on
the knee prior to the season. He apparently came back too soon,
because it's gotten worse, not better . . . Stephon Marbury told
reporters this past week that he has absolutely no regrets about
leaving the Timberwolves. ``When you have regrets, it's like
cancer,'' he said. ``People don't understand, and they still don't
understand because they choose not to, that I didn't leave
Minnesota because of basketball. It goes beyond basketball. I have
a life. I'm still a human being. I still have to live there and
wake up to snow every day and freezing weather. I loved playing
basketball there. If people got it wrong, so be it.'' . . .
Speaking of the Wolves, they have done a 180 from their December
funk, and one of the reasons is the insertion of Malik Sealy into
the starting lineup at shooting guard. ``He probably merited it
sooner,'' said Wolves boss Kevin McHale. ``All year long, he's been
one of our more consistent players. Lately, he's been ultra
consistent.'' The Wolves' comeback win at home Thursday over
Portland was their eighth in nine games. They beat San Antonio and
the Trail Blazers in the space of 48 hours. After a quick Eastern
swing this weekend (Detroit, Philly), they face home
character-builders this week against Miami, the Lakers, and, ahem,
the Celtics (Thursday). McHale thinks the team has snapped out of
its swoon, which saw the Wolves lose eight in a row. ``It was
ugly,'' he said. ``But those guys got their rear ends chewed out a
lot by me and the coaching staff and no one pointed fingers. At the
end of it, I think we've got guys with good character. I still
don't know how good we'll be. But I do know we have good guys. But
this has been a strange year. There's one team doing well, the
Lakers, and everyone else is ebbing and flowing. We were on a
serious ebb there for a while.'' . . . No sooner had Nelson met
with new Dallas owner-to-be Mark Cuban than he said that his son
was not in line to succeed him and never really had been. Huh? ``I
tried to convince him to stay here,'' said Fitzsimmons. The younger
Nelson was a Phoenix assistant before joining his father in Dallas
as the heir apparent. ``If he had stayed here,'' Fitzsimmons said,
``he'd probably be the coach now.'' Big Nellie, meanwhile, should
take his money and go back to Maui, although he is pledging to
stick around for another year in the front office, not his strong
suit. Does he really not know that it hasn't worked in Dallas?
Cuban looks like either a terrific, enthusiastic,
willing-to-do-whatever-it-takes owner or a meddlesome, John Y.
Brown-in-waiting. ``This is exactly the kind of owner the league
needs,'' Big Nellie said, referring to Cuban's deep pockets.
However, Cuban is also an unabashed Mavericks fan _ there
apparently are still a few _ and pledges to be hands-on, never a
good sign.
</P>
<P>
   Fashion statement
</P>
<P>
   Albert White of the CBA's Sioux Falls Sky Force made the mistake
recently of wearing sweats when the team was out in the public eye.
For that transgression, he was suspended one game. The CBA, under
new boss Isiah Thomas, has instituted a dress code and already has
fined and suspended several players and one coach. Players and
coaches are expected to wear a coat, shirt, slacks, and shoes (no
sneakers or sandals) when travelling. (The exception is when they
travel by bus.) Several members of Dennis Johnson's La Crosse
Bobcats were fined for violating the code and Grand Rapids coach
Mark Hughes was even suspended a game because several of his
players were deemed to be sartorially incomplete . . . The always
intrepid Craig Sager of TBS/TNT fame tried to get Karl Malone this
past week to plug the Jazz' game Monday night with San Antonio (on
TBS). Malone wouldn't bite, mainly because the Jazz had games with
Dallas and Houston before the Spurs and couldn't afford to overlook
either one. Sager tried again. No luck. He stopped there, before he
Jim Grayed the whole thing. Well, when the Spurs do play the Jazz,
it will be only the third time this season that San Antonio has
played one of the other Big Three in the West. The Spurs still have
yet to face Portland and have played the Lakers only once . . .
Speaking of Malone, he demonstrated again on Thursday why he's an
annual first-team selection to the All-Interview squad. He went
chest to chest with Nelson during the Utah victory over the Mavs.
It didn't get to fisticuffs, but it took a few seconds before the
two were separated. Nelson wound up with a one-game suspension and
fine for bumping a ref before the Malone contretemps. Malone would
not reveal what the two said, but added, ``I was taught to respect
my elders. But Granddaddy always said if a person gets out of line,
you gotta put him in his place. There is a fine line you don't
cross and he crossed it. I think he's a little overmatched in this
one.'' Also in that game, Shawn Bradley was called for a technical
after getting kicked in the stomach on one of Malone's trademark
``kick jumpers.'' Bradley crumpled to the floor in pain. Said the
Mailman, ``When a Volkswagen hits an 18-wheeler, what's the result
going to be?'' Utah, by the way, had just beaten Charlotte the
night before and is 6-0 in the second game of back-to-backers. Not
bad for an allegedly actuarially-challenged squad . . . McHale on
Shaquille O'Neal: ``He's playing the way the Lakers hoped he would
and everyone else was afraid he would.'' . . . The Hornets,
struggling out West without Eddie Jones, activated the NBA steals
leader last week. But it was a formality. League rules stipulate
that a team can't carry 11 players for more than two weeks. So
Jones was activated, but he's unlikely to return until the Hornets
come back East this week. Eldridge Recasner, injured in the
preseason car accident with Derrick Coleman, may be ready to play
next month . . . Game of the Week: Lakers at Indiana on Friday.
They are the only two teams right now who, as McHale might say, are
flowing rather than ebbing . . . Denver's Dan Issel accused Jerry
Sloan of trying to run up the score in a Utah blowout last week.
Sloan, as you might suspect, didn't take kindly to the comments and
shot back that he was upset when Issel walked out on the Nuggets.
Knicks coach Jeff Van Gundy, meanwhile, said he couldn't conceive
of a situation in the NBA where a team intentionally ran up the
score. ``If you get beat by 50,'' he said, ``it's your own fault.
It's not the job of the opponent to make it look better for you.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
