</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SPT-HOLLEY-COLUMN-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
FINALLY LETTING DOWN HIS HAIR 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By MICHAEL HOLLEY  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Note to reader: I am selling out. Every other columnist in this
section has written a story similar to the following one. Me? I
used to be the last holdout on the sports block. Not anymore; I
have sold out. What will I do next, get a haircut?
</P>
<P>
   A few items to discuss with the Sports Barber . . .
</P>
<P>
   --The Buffalo Bills, losers of four Super Bowls, didn't simply
blow a playoff game to Tennessee on an unlikely lateral Saturday.
They also granted clemency to Bill Buckner, Chris Webber (circa
1993), Greg Norman, and the Atlanta Braves of the 1990s.
</P>
<P>
   --OK, let's be honest. Who rooted hardest for the Titans: you,
the Tennessee fans, or Doug Flutie?
</P>
<P>
   --If you believe that Pete Carroll was too soft with the
Patriots, you'll understand why Bob Kraft likes Bill Belichick.
According to former Browns center Mike Baab, this is what the coach
told the Browns during his first team meeting: ``I've worked too
long and too hard for this chance to let you guys (expletive) it up
for me.''
</P>
<P>
   --Actually, Coach Belichick doesn't bother me. Coach/General
Manager Belichick is a near obscenity. It's too bad he has such
disdain for the media because he has a lot to share: He has visited
prisons, accompanied police on drug raids, observed surgeons at
work, jammed to the Allmans, and, the toughest job of all, served
as sports editor of the Annapolis (Md.) High yearbook.
</P>
<P>
   --The myth is that the people of Cleveland hated Belichick for
waiving an ineffective Bernie Kosar. Not quite. They hated him for
waiving Kosar when Todd Philcox was his only healthy quarterback.
</P>
<P>
   --Antoine Walker hasn't been dancing much lately. He says he'll
do it more when the Celtics go over .500. Seriously.
</P>
<P>
   --If I had to vote this morning for NBA Coach of the Year, my
choice would be Orlando's Doc Rivers. The Magic began Saturady
night with 16 wins, or about 13 more than anyone expected at this
point.
</P>
<P>
   --A couple of months ago, I went to see ``Pokemon: The First
Movie'' with my 6-year-old nephew, Justin. His immediate review was
that it was OK, but a little confusing. I reminded Justin of this
two weeks ago and he said, basically, that he meant it when he said
it. Hey, Rick Pitino, are you moonlighting as a kindergarten
teacher?
</P>
<P>
   --``Hurricane,'' which is the story of boxer Rubin Carter, has a
little too much Hollywood in it but Denzel Washington _ the best in
the business _ saves it.
</P>
<P>
   --Ty Law, when asked to compare the coaching skills of Carroll
and Bill Parcells: ``Hell, that's like comparing Michael Jordan to
Latrell Sprewell.''
</P>
<P>
   --My name is Bob Kraft. The first, second, and third thing I do
this morning is phone Joe Gibbs and convince him to come out of
retirement. I sell him on the resurgent NASCAR scene in New
Hampshire. I tell him he can sign Mark Martin or Jeff Gordon to the
practice squad if he wants. Anything.
</P>
<P>
   --I'd take Gibbs over even Parcells and Bill Walsh.
</P>
<P>
   --I think Shaquille O'Neal is underrated. Yep. Underrated. What
can't he do? You say free throws. Bill Russell shot 56 percent for
his career from the line and Wilt Chamberlain finished at 47
percent. O'Neal came into this season at 53 percent. He also has
career averages of 27 points and 12 rebounds. As much as he gets to
the line, he actually gets fouled twice as often as that. But it's
rarely called because he is so strong and it's not so obvious that
he has been whacked. Plus, look at how Penny Hardaway, Dennis
Scott, and Nick Anderson have performed with Shaq no longer in
their lives.
</P>
<P>
   --Another reason Boston sports fans are praised for their
knowledge: Reader Doug Bishop wrote that Jordan and William
Shakespeare had more than artistic brilliance in common. Both,
Bishop said, retired at the top of their games.
</P>
<P>
   --John Rocker did more damage with his mouth than Sprewell ever
did with his hands. So why have Time magazine and the Wall Street
Journal been so quiet with their commentaries? You may recall that
Time referred to Sprewell as a ``corn-rowed punk'' when he choked
P.J. Carlesimo. The Journal had a headline that read ``Jail
Sprewell.'' No such words about Rocker.
</P>
<P>
   --If I had three sports wishes, one of them would be access to
Rocker's voice mail. We have heard from those who have condemned
the Braves pitcher for his ignorant remarks, but I'd feel more
comfortable if I knew the names of his supporters.
</P>
<P>
   --So, if Kraft does eventually interview Marty Schottenheimer, I
hope he asks about Mike Junkin. When he was in Cleveland,
Schottenheimer traded up to the draft's top five to select Duke
linebacker Junkin, who was, of course, a bust. Really, when was the
last time you heard of someone trading up to draft a Duke football
player?
</P>
<P>
   --Once a year, I think every NFL coach should be allowed to pick
his favorite entertainer, author, or orator to speak on his behalf
at a press conference. Imagine how J.D. Salinger would respond (as
Holden Caulfield) when asked if Carroll's Patriots quit on him in a
time of war: ``I don't know too much about it myself, but I do know
it would drive me crazy if I had to be in the Army and be with a
bunch of guys like this. I was in the Boy Scouts once, for about a
week, and I couldn't even stand looking at the guy's neck in front
of me . . . I swear, if there's another war, they better just take
me out and stick me in front of a firing squad. I wouldn't
object.''
</P>
<P>
   --The Celtics have a head-shaving promotion Monday at the
FleetCenter. I'm thinking about it.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
