<SLUG> BC-BKW-UCONN-TENNESSEE-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
HUSKIES PULL RANK 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By SUSAN BICKELHAUPT  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   KNOXVILLE, Tenn. _ The couple hundred University of Connecticut
fans, barely visible in the sea of orange, and barely audible among
23,385 at Thompson-Boling Arena, had a lot to cheer about after the
game as they stood up in their nosebleed seats and chanted,
``UConn, UConn, UConn.''
</P>
<P>
   The No. 1 women's basketball team in the country defeated No. 2
Tennessee, 74-67, to hold onto its perfect record of 12-0.
Tennessee fell to 11-3.
</P>
<P>
   Connecticut point guard Sue Bird, who tore her anterior cruciate
ligament last year and saw action in just eight games, led the
Huskies with 25 points, whie Svetlana Abrosimova added 14 and Shea
Ralph 13.
</P>
<P>
   When the players were introduced, the Tennessee fans cheered
lustily for Semeke Randall, though it sounded like boos. Boo is a
nickname she picked up last year when the Lady Vols played UConn at
Storrs, Conn.
</P>
<P>
   Randall and Abrosimova had fought for a loose ball in that game
and Randall had gained possession. Thereafter, she was booed by the
UConn crowd every time she touched the ball. Tennessee won the
game, which made the booing much easier for Randall to take.
</P>
<P>
   ``So thanks to Connecticut, that's my nickname,'' she said.
``But I guess I'm carrying it with class.''
</P>
<P>
   Randall laughed off insinuations that there might still be bad
blood between she and Abrosimova.
</P>
<P>
   ``There are no hard feelings, I think she's a great player,''
Randall said, adding that the altercation was not surprising during
a hard-fought game.
</P>
<P>
   ``She wants to win, I want to win,'' Randall said. ``It's
emotional.''
</P>
<P>
   Tennessee coach Pat Summitt was correct when she predicted the
game would look more like a track meet than basketball.
</P>
<P>
   Both teams were hustling, not just to score, but to deny
opponents the ball as each team committed 12 first-half turnovers.
</P>
<P>
   UConn had the early upper hand at 20-13, but Tennessee went on a
run to go ahead, at 24-20.
</P>
<P>
   But UConn capitalized on its eight first-half steals (three by
freshman Kennitra Johnson and two by Bird), to pull back in front.
</P>
<P>
   The Huskies shot 56 percent (18 for 32) from the floor in the
half, while Tennessee made just 12 of its 30 field goal attempts.
</P>
<P>
   As a result, UConn went to the locker room up, 43-37.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-01-08-00 2201EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
