<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BKC-BC-PROVIDENCE-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
BC SLIPS PAST PROVIDENCE 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By MICHAEL VEGA  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   BC67Providence62
</P>
<P>
   Al Skinner had watched his Boston College men's basketball team
endure an extended stretch of scattershot play.
</P>
<P>
   With 2:45 remaining in Saturday's Big East opener against
Providence, the Eagles had rallied from a 57-47 deficit with a 10-0
run over a span of 2 minutes 22 seconds, forcing the Friars to
commit three turnovers that resulted in 6 points.
</P>
<P>
   It was precisely that kind of effort that helped Skinner remain
composed during the final 2 1/2 minutes _ when the game got truly
frenzied and the teams traded three consecutive 3-pointers and five
turnovers _ of BC's 67-62 victory over the Friars before a
breathless Conte Forum crowd of 5,486.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's funny, but at that point in time I felt a lot more
comfortable,'' Skinner said, after his Eagles improved to 9-4
overall. ``In all honesty, I thought the pressure was on them,
because if we did the right things defensively then they would have
to make some tough shots.
</P>
<P>
   ``So my urgency was when we were down and we were struggling and
making mistakes. Once we got the lead, I really settled down. I
felt a lot better with a 1-point lead than I did being down by 1
point.''
</P>
<P>
   Freshman guard Troy Bell, who was the only Eagle to score in
double figures, came within one missed free throw of tying his
career high (29 against UMass Dec. 4). Bell hit 8 of 17 shots,
including 4 of 8 from 3-point range, and was 8 of 11 from the foul
line. He outscored the rest of BC's starters, who combined to score
20 points by going 5 for 21 from the field (1 for 7 on 3-pointers)
and 9 for 12 from the line.
</P>
<P>
   Kenny Walls had 9 points, including a pair of free throws that
tied it, 57-57, with 2:45 to go, Jonathan Beerbohm chipped in 8
points and three rebounds, and 6-foot-8-inch freshman power forward
Uka Agbai, whose hustle didn't show in the box score, loomed large
with his play against Providence's 7-2 center Karim Shabazz (15
points, 16 rebounds), with 3 points, 6 rebounds, 5 blocked shots,
and 2 steals.
</P>
<P>
   ``I just try to play hard all the time,'' said Agbai. ``They
call me the Garbage Man because I do all the dirty work. I just try
my best and do whatever it takes to win. Even though it doesn't
show up on the stats, it doesn't bother me too much.''
</P>
<P>
   Asked about fronting Shabazz, who was his counselor two summers
ago at an ABCD basketball camp, Agbai said, ``I do look up to him.
I wish I was 7-2 _ and hopefully I get to be 7-2 _ but I had to
play as if I was 7-2 just like he was.''
</P>
<P>
   The Friars, who led, 30-29, at halftime, outshot (44 percent to
35.7 percent) and outrebounded (41 to 30) the Eagles, but were
outscored, 20-5, over the final 5:07. Providence committed eight of
its 26 turnovers during that stretch, including five in the final
1:12, and took only 10 trips to the foul line all afternoon,
compared with 29 for BC.
</P>
<P>
   ``We put them on the foul line and we turned it over when it
counted,'' said Providence coach Tim Welsh, whose team fell to 8-7
overall, 1-1 in the conference. ``And that was the game right
there.''
</P>
<P>
   After Walls capped BC's 10-0 comeback with his tying free
throws, Bell engaged Providence's Donta Wade in a 3-point
tete-a-tete when he knocked down a trey from the top of the key to
give BC a 60-59 lead with 1:46 left. Wade answered with a
line-drive three to give the Friars a 62-60 edge, but Bell gave BC
the lead for good with another trifecta, this one from the corner
in front of the Eagles' bench with 1:18 left.
</P>
<P>
   ``I heard everybody screaming `No!' but I felt like we just
needed something,'' said Bell. ``I knew I was feeling all right,
and so I just took it and knocked it down _ luckily.''
</P>
<P>
   Xavier Singletary made it a 64-62 lead by hitting the first of
two free throws and Bell, who scored 13 points in the final 3:03,
three of his four foul shots over the final 17.9 to ice it.
</P>
<P>
   ``What it says is that this team understands winning and it's
important to them,'' said Skinner, whose team plays its first
conference road game Wednesday night at Notre Dame. ``Even though
we didn't necessarily play well, even on the offensive end, we
still understand winning and we understand the extra hustle that
you need to win.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
