<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SAIL-AMERICACUP-CONNER-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
TEAM CONNER AWAITS RULING 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By TONY CHAMBERLAIN  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   AUCKLAND, New Zealand _ The fate of Stars &AMP; Stripes hung over
the dockside compound of Team Dennis Conner Saturday awaiting a
series of formal hearings and recommendations that could knock Team
Dennis Conner back a point or more in the standings, or in the most
extreme judgment, throw the San Diego cup veteran out of the
regatta.
</P>
<P>
   Long after racing ended Saturday night, an arbitration panel was
sending its findings to a jury. At question is what, if any, action
to take against Stars &AMP; Stripes in wake of findings that the
midnight blue IACC 75-footer sailed the first race of the current
Louis Vuitton semifinals with an illegal rudder.
</P>
<P>
   According to the written Cup protocol, a boat must manufacture
any appendages either in its home country or in the host country,
which is New Zealand.
</P>
<P>
   But Team Dennis Conner had a rudder built in Australia, which
could leave them vulnerable to some penalty.
</P>
<P>
   While that storm swirled around the dockside offices all
weekend, out on the water things did not look much brighter for
Stars &AMP; Stripes, since a light air pattern put the boat built for
high winds and rougher water at a distinct disadvantage.
</P>
<P>
   AmericaOne, Paul Cayard's San Francisco-leading team, trounced
Stars &AMP; Stripes, first by winning the start and getting the first
windshift, then by a show of blazing straight line speed that left
Stars &AMP; Stripes well off the pace.
</P>
<P>
   And heading into Saturday's races, the pattern of high pressure
and light air seems to be locked in over Auckland _ great news for
the thousands of boaters and vacationers in the height of their
summer _ bad news for Stars &AMP; Stripes, which was racing Nippon
Sunday.
</P>
<P>
   But ashore, the Team DC heavies were fighting back.
</P>
<P>
   ``Any suggestion that Team Dennis Conner would be excluded would
be silly,'' said skipper Ken Read. ``It's not even an option. It's
not even worth talking about. It's just all crazy.''
</P>
<P>
   Read said that the rudder, which was designed by US designers
and made from materials sent from the US, was built in Australia
only in the interest of time.
</P>
<P>
   ``Our whole team believes everything we have done is 100 percent
OK,'' said Read, a 36-year-old Newport, R.I., native, and former
J-24 world champion.
</P>
<P>
   Stars &AMP; Stripes team members concede dockside politics of this
kind are ``distracting'' and can get in the way of a team's sailing
focus. In 1992 when they were competing in the finals of the Louis
Vuitton Cup against Italy, New Zealand faced charges of rigging an
illegal bowsprit. New Zealand admits the controversy was so
distracting it was a large part of its poor performance against the
winning Italian team, Il Moro de Venezia.
</P>
<P>
   Stars &AMP; Stripes team members say they are pleased at least to
see their controversy go before an arbitration panel, rather than
the summary judgment of a jury.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is what an arbitration panel is for,'' said Read, ``to
construe what is a pretty vague document at times.''
</P>
<P>
   At question before that panel is whether precedent has been
established to weaken the nationality clause of the protocol.
Specifically, argued Stars &AMP; Stripes tactician Tom Whidden, the
case of Italy's Azurra and France's French Kis which in 1986 had
keels built by a German manufacturer.
</P>
<P>
   Also cited was the most famous such controversy that arose when
in 1983 Australia II was charged with using a revolutionary keel
built in part in Holland.
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile, Stars &AMP; Stripes has watched the ascendancy of an old
rival, Paul Cayard's AmericaOne take the lead on the board at 4-1
before Saturday's races. Stars &AMP; Stripes is 3-1.
</P>
<P>
   To our readers: Because New Zealand is 18 hours ahead of US East
Coast time, all action takes place a day ahead (i.e. a Sunday noon
race there is taking place Saturday evening here). To avoid
confusion, all time references in America's Cup stories will
reflect when the events took place according to Eastern Standard
Time.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
