<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-OLY-OLYNOTES-USSOCCER-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
WOMEN WANT US SOCCER TO KICK IN MORE MONEY 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By JOHN POWERS  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Though strikes/walkouts/boycotts have become a ritual whenever
US Soccer and its elite players wrangle over a new deal, the
ongoing tiff with the women's team is decidedly different.
</P>
<P>
   Until they had filled every stadium from the Meadowlands to the
Rose Bowl during last summer's World Cup, the women had to swallow
the dictum that they deserved less money because they generated
less money. Now, after two World Cup titles, an Olympic gold medal,
all those sellouts, and a prodigious amount of pre-Cup promotional
work, the women feel they've earned the respect that comes with
more money. What they want is a reported top-end $5,000 per month
and $2,000 a game, compared with the $3,150 and $250 they made
before the Cup.
</P>
<P>
   ``We have always lived up to our end of the bargain,'' Brandi
Chastain tells the world on her AthleteDirect.com Web site.
``Knocked on doors, pounded the pavement, run clinics, and signed
unlimited autographs for the good of the game.''
</P>
<P>
   So Chastain and her teammates, who will be the core of this
summer's Olympic team, are skipping the Australia Cup while US
Soccer sends a JV made up of present and former collegians and high
schoolers. Not that there has been a dropoff on the scoreboard. The
B team waxed the Czechs, 8-1, in their opener Down Under.
</P>
<P>
   Why not Iverson?
</P>
<P>
   Why isn't the NBA's leading scorer on the US Olympic men's
basketball team? Because the selectors wanted a shooting guard, so
they bypassed Allen Iverson for Milwaukee bombardier Ray Allen.
Actually, Iverson was all but out of the running when the committee
chose five guards (Tim Hardaway, Allan Houston, Jason Kidd, Gary
Payton, Steve Smith) last year. His name barely came up during last
week's vote, when Grant Hill and Alonzo Mourning were also added to
the roster. The only decision was whether to choose Allen or
Toronto forward Vince Carter, who is leading the All-Star
balloting. Allen got the nod because he's more experienced and more
likely to accept 12th-man status . . . With Kara Wolters added last
week, just one spot remains on the US women's team. It could be
determined this week after the selectors chat by conference call.
After running roughshod (as in 11-1) over a dozen college
varsities, the Americans are off to Europe to face the Polish and
Slovak national squads and club teams . . . Though the
International Olympic Committee made a big deal out of adding 15
``active'' (as in recent) athletes as members, they're really just
temps. Unlike the incumbents, who can be reelected until they reach
70, the athletes have to step down after eight years. And while
they're nominated by their peers, they still have to be approved by
an IOC selection committee, the executive board, and the full body
. . . As expected (though originally denied), the IOC has moved
next month's board meeting from the United States to the other side
of the world to avoid any FBI agents who might pepper members with
questions about the Salt Lake bidding scandal. Instead of Colorado
Springs, the Lords will convene in Sydney.
</P>
<P>
   Beating the odds
</P>
<P>
   US pairs skater Paul Binnebose, who nearly died last autumn
after fracturing his skull in a fall during practice, could be back
on the ice later this month, if only for a reentry spin. Binnebose
lost 50 pounds and developed heart and lung infections while he was
bedridden for two months. ``At one point, we said all we want is
for him just to live,'' says coach Ron Ludington . . . Missing from
the US skating championships yet again will be Nicole Bobek, who
missed last month's sectionals with the flu and was denied a
medical waiver to Nationals. Bobek, who was kept out last year by a
pelvic ailment, says she'll still stay eligible for another shot at
Olympus . . . Both the men's and women's world skating champions
were knocked off at the recent Russian nationals. Alexei Yagudin
was beaten by 17-year-old Evgeni Plushenko, and Irina Slutskaya
took down Maria Butyrskaya . . . Back on the beam after imploding
at trials and missing the last US Olympic team is 17-year-old Apolo
Anton Ohno, who recently became the youngest short-track
speedskater to win an overall World Cup event title. Ohno ranked
fifth in the global standings at the holiday break. South Korea's
Kim Dong Sung leads the men's list, Bulgaria's Evgenia Radanova the
women's . . . Nice effort by the US men's hockey team, which lost
the bronze medal to the Canadians in a shootout at the world junior
championships after finishing eighth last time. It was the best
showing since 1993 for the Americans. The unheralded Czechs stung
the Russians for the gold.
</P>
<P>
   Tripped up
</P>
<P>
   Who would pay anybody to land the world Nordic skiing
championships? The Finns, who paid for the Croats and Belarussians
to go to New Zealand and (they hoped) vote for Lahti as next year's
host. Lahti got the bid, but Finnish police are investigating
whether the free trips amounted to a bribe . . . Lake Placid's new
combined luge-bobsled-skeleton run should be open by month's end,
in time for next month's inaugural winter Goodwill Games. Price of
the state-of-the-art venue is $24 million, more than double what
the individual runs cost when they were built for the 1980 Games .
. . New US women's gymnastics team coordinator Bela Karolyi was
underwhelmed by the physical condition of the several dozen Olympic
hopefuls who turned up for last month's one-day camp in Tulsa. ``To
be honest, I was not pleased,'' he says. ``The shape wasn't the one
that is required for a team that wants to be at the top standard.''
Karolyi will convene the group again next weekend and cut the list
in half before the next of his monthly camps. ``I hope they're
going to be in much better physical shape _ and ready,'' he says.
Among the hopefuls are three of the ``Magnificent Seven'' who won
gold in Atlanta: Dominique Moceanu, Amy Chow, and Jaycie Phelps.
</P>
<P>
   Off target
</P>
<P>
   Latest cheating scandal comes in archery (yes, archery), with
Shane Parker getting booted off the US Olympic team and suspended a
year for firing two extra arrows after he'd missed the target twice
at last year's trials. Taking his place is 44-year-old Butch
Johnson of Woodstock, Conn., who'll be making his third trip to the
Games . . . Jim Pedro of Lawrence, the newly-crowned world champ,
leads the list of fighters just named to the US Olympic judo team,
which gets to send a full roster to Sydney. Joe Felton, the former
Detroit Lion from Fall River, will also make the team if he
outpoints Martin Boonzaayer by April . . . USA Track and Field
types are crossing their fingers and hoping that the wrong person
doesn't win next month's Olympic women's marathon trials in South
Carolina. If the victor hasn't met the ``A'' standard of 2:33 (and
only Libbie Hickman and Kristy Johnston have, so far), the
Americans will get to send only one runner to Sydney, even if
others have gone sub-2:33. The men, who haven't settled on
selection procedures, would have the same problem at their May
trials. Only David Morris and Joe LeMay have met the ``A'' standard
of 2:14.
</P>
<P>
   Out of the pool
</P>
<P>
   Another setback for gold-medal swimmer Amy Van Dyken, who had
surgery last week to remove scar tissue from the surgery she had
two years ago after tearing her rotator cuff in the weight room. If
all goes well, she figures to be back in the pool by March, five
months before the US Olympic trials . . . With Mike Gebhardt
nailing down a Mistral spot at the recent world championships, the
US sailing team has qualified for all but one of the 11 Olympic
events at Sydney. They'll get a final shot at the Finn class in
England in June . . . Why are the US Olympic boxing trials being
held seven months before the Games? Because victors now have to
earn the right to compete in Sydney at a series of regional
qualifiers in the spring. Only 54 boxers from the hemisphere (not
counting Cubans, who get to send a full team) will earn slots. So
it's possible that one or more Americans could make the team and
still stay home . . . Coincidence or karma? Six years to the day
after her henchmen kneecapped Nancy Kerrigan, Tonya Harding skidded
off an icy road last week and put her pickup into a ditch.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
