<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-01-08 22:10 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A0616 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u s BC-BOX-BOXNOTE-FRANCIS-B     01-08 1985
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BOX-BOXNOTE-FRANCIS-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
FRANCIS AN ALMOST UNKNOWN SOLDIER 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By RON BORGES  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Riddick Bowe joined the Marine Corps after fighting Andrew
Golota twice. Julius Francis opted for the British Army even before
he has fought Mike Tyson once.
</P>
<P>
   The little-known British heavyweight champion, who is scheduled
to fight Tyson Jan. 29 in Manchester, England, ``joined'' the
British Army Wednesday so he could be free to train at the barracks
gym at Aldershot and live in the sergeant's mess there, according
to Frank Maloney, Francis's manager. Those claims are somewhat in
doubt, and exactly how it will help Francis stay upright against
Tyson is anyone's guess, but if it works, heavyweights all over
America will be driving to Parris Island with their trainers in the
back seat. That is the nature of sport: Success breeds imitation
almost without fail.
</P>
<P>
   ``I am going to lock myself away and mentally focus my body and
my mind and be away from the media,'' Francis said by phone from
England.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's nice to get all the attention, but when it comes down to
fight night, I have to be mentally and physically focused. There is
no way I can do that in the gym in London I use with the media
attention this fight has attracted.''
</P>
<P>
   Since it will be Tyson's first European appearance and the fight
sold out in less than two days, Francis may have a point, although
the smart money is betting he'll have more trouble keeping his eyes
focused after he takes Tyson's first punch than he'll have trying
to keep himself focused in the weeks leading up to the fight.
</P>
<P>
   A prohibitive underdog with a long record _ only some of which
was produced in the boxing ring _ the former street tough and
prison inmate had a rather succinct analysis of what his most
dangerous punch will be.
</P>
<P>
   ``The one that lands,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Good point, but when a 35-year-old fighter sporting a 21-7
record and only 11 knockouts walks out of the darkness talking
about beating up Tyson, it is difficult not to laugh even after
acknowledging that this newest version of Tyson is a shadow of what
he once was.
</P>
<P>
   Francis understands the skepticism about him because of the fact
that he was an unranked fighter and unknown commodity until he was
plucked from obscurity by Tyson's handlers for this match. Yet he
insists, ``I have just done what people have not expected me to do.
I have seen guys crumble against Tyson. He has _ or had _ an aura
of invincibility, but it's been broken. Evander Holyfield broke it.
When James ``Buster'' Douglas wiped the floor with him, the bubble
was burst.
</P>
<P>
   ``A man is a man. Whatever they say about Tyson, he is human. He
bleeds. He feels pain.
</P>
<P>
   ``Tyson is fighting for his life. That's the same way I'm
approaching this fight. I set my sights and have always set my
sights further than what anybody else has seen them. I definitely
see this fight as a steppingstone.''
</P>
<P>
   As Julius Francis seems likely to soon learn, he isn't the only
one.
</P>
<P>
   Short jabs
</P>
<P>
   Johnny Tapia should be applauded, and not merely for his
comeback fight this weekend against World Boxing Organization
bantamweight champion Jorge Eliecer Julio at The Pit in
Albuquerque. The fight is likely to be sold out, but Tapia
suggested to the promoter and the local police that two $30 tickets
be given to anyone agreeing to take a gun off the streets. Thus
far, more than 60 guns have been traded in, many of them illegals.
Tapia's mother was murdered when he was a boy, which scarred him
deeply and led to many of his outside-the-ring problems. Now he is
trying to help prevent young people in Albuquerque from going
through the hell he once faced. ``Before New Year's Eve, I got 57
guns off the street,'' Tapia said. ``The title don't mean nothing
to life. There's six bullets to a gun. You know how many lives were
saved just on New Year's Eve? That's a beautiful thing.'' So are
Tapia's efforts . . . Word in the cable industry is that promoters
Don King and Dan Goossen are back trying to make a David Reid-Felix
Trinidad fight for March 4. That was the original date of the fight
before complications arose over Reid's contract with HBO. Those now
appear solved because Goossen's suit against Time-Warner is going
away, but rival promoter Bob Arum has been holding that date for a
pay-per-view bout headlining bantamweight champion Paulie Ayala and
he wants to stick to it . . . Lou Duva is suing International
Boxing Federation 154-pound champion Fernando Vargas for what he
claims is the portion of Vargas's last purse he's owed. Duva no
longer trains Vargas but retains a share of his management
contract. Word is Main Events, which promotes Vargas, told the
champion to pay Duva but he refused. Duva and his son and daughter
have also filed suit against Kathy Duva, Lou's daughter-in-law, as
a result of the still unsettled breakup of what was once the family
boxing business . . . Meanwhile, Lou and his son and daughter are
back in the promotional saddle, having formed a new promotional
company called Duva Boxing. Duva's lawyers had to talk him out of
calling it Duva's Main Events, which should come as no surprise to
anyone who knows the feisty Duva. Their first promotion under the
new Duva banner will be Jan. 28 at The Ruins in New Orleans with
Harrah's casino as co-promoter. The main event pits super
middleweights Thomas Tate and Syd Vanderpool. Also on the card will
be undefeated heavyweight Clifford Etienne, who is 12-0 with nine
KOs. Known as the Black Rhino, he has thus far shown noticeable
punching power, and trainer Don Turner is convinced he will one day
be heavyweight champion. Maybe so, but it's a long walk from Baton
Rouge to the big time . . . Undefeated WBO super middleweight
champion Joe Calzaghe has this view of challenger David Starie.
``Starie's a good challenger, but there's no way he'll win,'' said
Calzaghe (27-0, 23 KOs). ``I have more knockouts than he has
fights.'' Starie (22-1, 16 KOs) is the British and Commonwealth
champion . . . Here's how sad it can get in boxing. Former
heavyweight champion Michael Moorer was sued by his 79-year-old
grandfather, who introduced him to boxing. Henry Smith originally
was seeking 25 percent of Moorer's past earnings, or $6.9 million.
A contract was produced with a handwritten addendum saying Smith
would get 5 percent of Moorer's income during his days fighting out
of the Kronk Gym. He did receive $64,850 and another $20,000 in
hotel room expenses, plane tickets, fight tickets, and meals,
according to John Davimos, Moorer's manager.
</P>
<P>
   Around and around
</P>
<P>
   Trainer Teddy Atlas appears to be ready to train Junior Jones
for his upcoming fight with Prince Naseem Hamed. Both Jones and
manager Gary Gittleson approached Atlas about preparing the former
world champion for what is likely to be his last shot at the
big-time. Atlas has yet to formally agree because of his reluctance
to return to the corner with anyone who isn't fully committed to
winning, but it is expected he will begin working with Jones next
week at Marciano's Gym in New Jersey if Jones can convince him he's
ready to follow the plan Atlas lays out. Atlas will quickly decide
after those opening training sessions whether he will stay the
course based on how Jones's preparation is going . . . Atlas
continues to train only one fighter while working as boxing's top
analyst on ESPN2's ``Friday Night Fights.'' That is undefeated
Elvir Muriqui, the Kosov Kid, who is back home now but returns to
begin training soon. Muriqui will soon make an appearance on an
ESPN show with Atlas doing a boxing first: He will work the corner
with a live microphone, thus becoming the first man to serve as
cornerman and commentator in the same fight . . . The Miami Herald
reported that former super middleweight Sanderline Williams claims
he was offered $30,000 to take a dive against Roberto Duran ``in
the early 1990s.'' Williams claims the offer was made in a
restaurant near Cleveland, but the fight never took place. Williams
once served as Duran's sparring partner, and his former manager,
John Giachetti, said his fighter was offered $30,000 to fight Duran
but not to lose to him. Promoter Mike Acri, who was handling Duran
at the time, said he never even offered Williams the fight. ``For
what?'' Acri said . . . Sad to report that 38-year-old attorney
Jacqueline Frazier-Lyde, the daughter of Joe Frazier, will fight in
Scranton, Pa., Feb. 8 for $25,000. The mother of three supposedly
is preparing to challenge Laila Ali, 21-year-old daughter of
Muhammad Ali. The plan is for her to fight Ali in September, the
25th anniversary of the Thrilla in Manila. Frazier's first fight is
on the undercard of an IBF light heavyweight title fight between
champion Salvatore Di Salvatore and undefeated Chris Mills (18-0) .
. . Over and over people predict the death of boxing, and it proves
again and again that no sporting event fascinates like a big fight.
An entertainment trade magazine recently listed 1999's top box
office events. First was the Christmas show at Radio City Music
Hall, grossing more than $54 million for 208 performances. Next was
the Lewis-Holyfield rematch, which grossed nearly $17 million at
the Thomas and Mack Center in Las Vegas. That's nearly a third as
much money for one night as Radio City did for its 208 Christmas
shows. The Holyfield-Lewis gate was nearly twice as much as the
third-place finisher, David Copperfield's magic shows, which
grossed $8.6 million . . . Golota will undergo an arthroscopy on
his right knee as a result of the car accident he was involved in
recently in Iowa. His companion died in the accident but Golota
received only minor injuries, including a sprained medial
collateral ligament and a torn medial meniscus . . . To make your
plans early for this year's International Boxing Hall of Fame
induction weekend June 8-11, call Ed Brophy at 315-697-7095 . . .
HBO's spring dance card has rapidly filled up with a strong first
quarter headlined by a April 29 heavyweight title fight between
undisputed champion Lennox Lewis and undefeated challenger Michael
Grant.
</P>
<P>
   Local bleatings
</P>
<P>
   John Ruiz's shot at the world heavyweight title is off until
November, and his chance to solidify his No. 1 ranking with the WBC
by fighting No. 2 contender Grant disappeared with it. So where
does that leave the Chelsea fighter? Manager Norman Stone is hoping
for a boxoff for both the WBC's and WBA's No. 1 rankings against
three-time world champion Holyfield. Holyfield is third in the WBC
and second in the WBA, having been moved ahead of Ruiz by the
latter organization. Stone is hoping King can make that match, with
the winner guaranteed a title fight in July. HBO Sports president
Seth Abraham said if Ruiz were to get that fight and win ``he would
have tremendous leverage in any negotiations with either Grant or
Lennox for a title fight. He would be the underdog, but it's a
gamble worth him taking.'' Stone said he would also ask the WBC to
reaffirm Ruiz's No. 1 ranking because he had made his best effort
to make an elimination bout with Grant and was denied. ``Johnny did
something unprecedented,'' said Tony Cardinale, lawyer for both
Stone and Ruiz. ``He was willing to risk the mandatory title shot
and his No. 1 ranking against the No. 2 contender.'' Stone will try
to force the WBA to declare its title vacant when Lewis fights
Grant April 29 because, by contract, he was supposed to defend it
against the sanctioning body's top contender, Henry Akinwande, or
the next-highest available contender if Akinwande was is not
available. If that's done, Ruiz and Holyfield would fight for the
WBA title. Failing that, they hope to force the boxoff with
Holyfield that would bring Ruiz over a $1 million payday and set
him up for a big-money title shot with the Grant-Lewis winner.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-01-08-00 2210EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
