<DOCTYPE> MISCELLANEOUS TEXT (slug-filter) </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-01-08 22:10 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A0617 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u s BC-GLF-GOLFNOTES-DUVAL-B     01-08 1992
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-GLF-GOLFNOTES-DUVAL-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
DUVAL IS LEANING INTO IT 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By JIM McCABE  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Usually, all Tiger Woods has to do is show up and he's the
story. But at last weekend's Williams World Challenge in Arizona, a
charity event that was billed as Woods's invitational, the
spotlight instead belonged to David Duval.
</P>
<P>
   And for good reason.
</P>
<P>
   The man who for a short time last year replaced Woods as the
world's top-ranked player made observers stop and take notice. Not
because of 300-yard drives; Duval does that routinely. Not because
of wedges that would have settled into thimbles from 100 yards;
again, that's ho-hum for Duval. No, what people noticed was the
physique. Duval has obviously made a commitment to better health
and it's apparent that he isn't about to sit back while Woods races
into the stratosphere without him.
</P>
<P>
   Though his playing weight is still 190 pounds, Duval has
distributed it better. He is leaner, less bulky in the midsection,
and seemingly stronger. But he is no more revealing about himself,
shrugging off inquiries about his new look.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's no secret,'' he told reporters in Hawaii, where he is the
defender at this weekend's Mercedes Championship. ``Go work hard
and eat well, and that will happen.''
</P>
<P>
   Duval didn't say so, but it's probably no conincidence that he
took this approach after watching Woods put up a dominating
performance in 1999 that left everyone else playing for second
place. In the process, people stopped talking exclusively about
Woods's eye-opening length and marveled, too, at his physical shape
and it wasn't long before it was publicized how hard the phenom
worked out.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's difficult to compete against players who are so much
stronger than you are,'' said Woods, who has gained 22 pounds since
breaking into pro golf as a 158-pounder in 1996. ``You just need to
get stronger to keep up.''
</P>
<P>
   What remains to be seen is whether Duval's new approach to
physical conditioning will help him keep up with Woods. Even though
he has turned the ripe old age of 24, Woods has no intention of
releasing his grip on the pro golf world.
</P>
<P>
   It's still his, but it should be fun watching him trying to keep
it.
</P>
<P>
   Changing his clothes
</P>
<P>
   Jesper Parnevik has heard the jokes about his attire (he wore
bright red pants in the opening round of the Mercedes
Championship), but the Swede has always insisted that he's in style
_ European style, which he insists blazes the way. Perhaps he is
correct, because Duval has ended his association with Tommy
Hilfiger and signed on with Mossimo, a California-based clothing
company known for its European style. Duval unveiled the new look _
all black and nowhere as loose-fitting as the traditional golf
fashion _ during the Williams World Challenge, but it remains to be
seen whether the untucked shirttail is part of the new style . . .
Another change that keen golf fans will take note of in 2000 (and
we're not talking Woods's bag being emblazoned with Buick or Vijay
Singh's switch from Wilson to Cleveland irons) is the much-heralded
Callaway golf ball, which has been one of the great industry
secrets in recent years. The ball is ready (reporters made note of
Rocco Mediate and Brian Henninger heading out for practice rounds
at the Mercedes Championship armed with black pens to cover the
logo) but won't officially be introduced until the PGA Merchandise
Show in early February . . . Had enough of polls? Here's one that
proves how nonsensical they are, and why we should hope that it's
another thousand years before we have to suffer more of them.
PGATour.com and GolfWeb asked readers to select the golfers of the
millennium, and 5,207 votes later, the list was a joke. Rightfully,
Jack Nicklaus was first, but get a load of these placings: Payne
Stewart sixth, Fred Couples seventh, Greg Norman ninth, Sergio
Garcia 12th. Sergio Garcia! Ahead of Tom Watson and Lee Trevino?
One amazing golf shot that produces a second-place finish in the
PGA outweighs 14 major championships? Please. Where is Harry
Vardon? Gene Sarazen? Walter Hagen? Billy Casper? One look at the
list should have produced laughter, then editors should have showed
sanity and not published it. Given the voters' leanings, I'm
stunned that Celine Dion, Kevin Costner, and Michael Jordan weren't
there . . . Of the 31 eligible players, only Jose Maria Olazabal
chose not to take part in the Mercedes . . . Olazabal was an easy
choice for the Ben Hogan Award, given by members of the Golf
Writers Association to a player who continues to be active in golf
despite a physical handicap or serious illness. The GWAA also voted
Nancy Lopez the William D. Richardson Award for consistent
contributions to the game . . . Remember the woman who stripped
down to her underwear and ran onto the 18th green to plant a kiss
on Woods at the British Open last July? She was fined $400 by a
judge in Arbroath, Scotland, this past week, but outside the court
Yvonne Robb could not promise to behave at the 2000 event at St.
Andrews. ``I'm going to have to surprise you,'' she said . . .
Pampered members of the American PGA Tour hopefully appreciate what
they have. If not, please point out to them that this weekend in
Australia, the 2000 SmokeFree Victorian Open is featuring a
$100,000 purse, of which $18,000 goes to the winner.
</P>
<P>
   Honorable mention
</P>
<P>
   An evening to honor golf champions of 1999 was held at Wellesley
CC Wednesday, with the highlight being Player of the Year honors
presented to Jim Salinetti of Stockbridge GC (MGA) and Melanie
Curtin of Presidents GC in Quincy (WGAM). Salinetti, a senior at
the University of Rhode Island, earned the prestigious award for
the second time, thanks in large part to a dominating performance
to win last summer's State Amateur at Kittansett (he also completed
the State Am/POY perfecta in 1997) but perhaps a more treasured
victory came late in the summer at Blue Hill CC when Dick Salinetti
birdied the par-5 18th to nail down the Father and Son
Championship. ``I had to talk him into hitting the 7-wood,'' said
Jim with a laugh, nodding to the man who taught him this game he
now plays so well, ``but he hit the most awesome shot (to 5 feet)
I've ever seen.'' For Curtin, 28, it culminated a rather incredible
rise to the top of the local women's golf scene as she just started
playing the game five years ago. The Weymouth native was an avid
tennis player, earning a scholarship to Jacksonville University,
but she made the transition to golf quite smoothly. So well, in
fact, that she will pursue it professionally, having earned full
exempt status on the Futures Tour. Curtin will head to Florida
later this month to work on her game as she chases a dream that she
hopes will lead to a career on the LPGA. Curtin's many friends and
supporters are having a fund-raiser on her behalf Jan. 21 at the
Weymouth Elks Club. The donation is $60; for information, call
Patty Buck (617-325-0156), Peter Hess (617-770-2746), or Lisa
Kennedy (781-740-8358) . . . One player who knows about being
player of the year is Geoff Sisk of Marshfield. The two-time State
Open champion is a few weeks away from a trip to Florida, where he
will prepare to return to the BUY.com Tour (formerly Nike Tour) in
hopes of earning his way back to the big leagues. He was on the PGA
Tour in 1999, but his rookie campaign was disappointing, filled
with mistakes, inconsistent play, and indifferent travel plans. He
finished 198th on the money list, then failed at the second stage
of Q School. ``I played in every Monday pro-am I could play in,''
said Sisk, who has enough status that he hopes to get into at least
the first five stops on the BUY.com Tour. From there, if he plays
well, he is confident the remainder of the season will take care of
itself. ``They're not beating me, I'm beating myself,'' he said.
``The window of opportunity is starting to close, but until I can
say I've played my best and been beaten, I'm going to try.'' Sisk
will again be joined by his good friends on the minor league
circuit, as Kevin Johnson of Pembroke and Fran Quinn of
Northborough are fully exempt . . . There are details to be worked
out, but the MGA deserves a round of applause by beginning the new
year with a bold step that can only bring hundreds more players
into competition they normally wouldn't be eligible for. A state
net team championship will make its debut in 2000, with qualifying
rounds leading to a final, most likely in October. As the level of
play has improved dramatically and entries have exploded, the MGA
has, like most golf associations, been forced to set a minimum
handicap requirement. That, unfortunately, has left a lot of
willing enthusiasts on the sideline . . . He was honored for his
1999 Mid-Amateur championship, but Frank Vana Jr. of Marlborough CC
received a second tribute Wednesday, a rather unexpected nod as MGA
Golfer of the Decade. His Player of the Year points from 1990-99
totalled 3,991, a thousand more than runner-up (and his State
Four-ball partner) Jack Kearney of Elmcrest. Quite a tribute to
this consistent standout, though what should be noted is that Frank
Vana Sr. should thus be called Caddie of the Decade, for he has
been there nearly every step of the way. After Vana and Kearney,
the top 10 rounds out with James Driscoll of Charles River, Joe
Keller of Oyster Harbors, Jon Fasick of New England CC, Jim
Ruschioni of Oak Hill, Justin Peters of Pembroke, Steven Tasho of
Thorny Lea, Salinetti, and Brendan Hester of Pleasant Valley . . .
Brian Connor, a Walpole native who attended Xaverian Brothers High
School and Boston College, has been named director of marketing for
the TPC course that is being built in Norton. The land will be
cleared this spring and the Arnold Palmer-designed course is
scheduled for completion in 2002 . . . Four Massachusetts golf
shops _ The International in Bolton, Stow Acres CC, Edwin Watts in
Hanover, and Joe and Leigh's Discount Pro Shop at Pine Oaks in
Easton _ were included in the Top 100 across the country as voted
by Golf Shop Operations, a subsidiary of Golf Digest . . .
Children's educational and recreational programs throughout the
Mashpee area received $34,000 in grants from the Paul and Phyllis
Fireman Charitable Foundation and the Willowbend Children's Charity
. . . Chances are you will never meet Jenny Ritchie of New Zealand,
but you may want to raise a toast for her remarkable luck last
weekend. The 51-year-old ended the century with a hole-in-one Dec.
31, then began the next one with another ace less than 24 hours
later . . . Sad passings to report: Don Carner, who married Jo Ann
Gunderson in 1963 and operated a par 3 course in Seekonk before
they set out on a long and successful LPGA Tour journey, died at 84
after a long battle with Parkinson's; Gary Adams, who in the mid
'70s wanted to design a metal wood to please driving range owners
but ended up revolutionizing the golf industry, died at 56; and
Australia's most beloved amateur, Doug Bachli, who defeated
American Bill Campbell at Muirfield in 1954 to capture the British
Amateur, died at 77 . . . But no loss is as painful as that which
strikes closest to the heart, which is why the death of colleague
Robin Romano, 45, is nearly unbearable. She advised, encouraged,
and never stopped being the best friend one could ever have been
blessed with. When the topic was golf there was no one I enjoyed
talking with more than she, and I don't know of many people who
played the game _ or lived life _ more passionately. On the first
tee of the first round we ever played together, I took note that
she marched to the white tees, from where I hit. Three holes later,
to make things more fair, I suggested she move to the blue and I
move to the red. She laughed (though I was serious; oh, how she
could play), and it is the memory of that laugh that I will cherish
forever.
</P>
</TEXT>
