<HEADLINE>
BU ROLLS PAST NORTHEASTERN 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By FRANK DELL'APA  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   The Boston University and Northeastern men's basketball teams
had much in common before confronting each other Saturday at Case
Gym. Both teams had two victories, against the same opponents, and
four successive defeats in seasons that appeared to be going
nowhere.
</P>
<P>
   But the Terriers set themselves apart in this game. They
dictated the tempo from the start, reacted efficiently to
Northeastern's pressing tactics, and maintained their composure in
a 62-45 victory before an announced crowd of 467. Neither team
appears capable of competing for the America East title, but BU
(3-10, 2-3) at least separated itself from the bottom teams.
</P>
<P>
   ``Northeastern is always one of our biggest rivals,'' BU's Mike
Costello (12 points) said. ``We play with their guys in summer and
we know each other well. We were real excited for this game after a
couple tough road trips and we were ready to play. We had a good
game plan. We knew we had to stop them on the outside, take care of
the ball against their pressing and trapping.''
</P>
<P>
   BU scored 14 of the game's first 16 points. The Huskies closed
to within 21-12 on Jean Bain's jumper with 10:03 left in the first
half. But the Terriers soon pulled away, stretching their advantage
to 48-21 on a Nacho Rodriguez inside move midway through the second
half.
</P>
<P>
   ``I told them that losing is OK as long as you give all your
effort,'' said Northeastern coach Rudy Keeling. ``This result is
regrettable but we still have a lot of games left, so let's go from
here.''
</P>
<P>
   NU (2-10, 1-3) put Marcus Blossom at point guard in place of
Bain, but the move failed to bring cohesion to the team. Whether
Blossom will continue in the role against Towson Friday will be
determined by midweek, Keeling said.
</P>
<P>
   BU, which has suffered four defeats by 20 or more points, seemed
unaccustomed to being in position to dominate an opponent. But the
Terriers adjusted to their status and eventually seemed to thrive
on their good fortune.
</P>
<P>
   ``I expected it to be a close game,'' said BU coach Dennis
Wolff. ``We had good focus to begin the game and played
unselfishly, particularly at the beginning of the game.
</P>
<P>
   ``This was a good win for us and now we have to build on it and
beat Liberty Tuesday (at BU). We found open guys and they made
shots. And if you make open shots everything is a little easier.''
</P>
<P>
   Costello and Jean Avebe, BU's only seniors, ignited the
Terriers' early run, scoring 11 of the team's first 14 points.
</P>
<P>
   ``You look at the ages of our players and you've just got to be
patient with them,'' Wolff said. ``We've had two or three chances
to win games. We've played hard but we just ran out of gas against
Hofstra (a 74-46 loss Jan. 2). This is a good group and they want
to win.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
