<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BKC-UMASS-FORDHAM-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
UMASS ROUTS FORDHAM 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By JOE BURRIS  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   AMHERST _ Most of the fans at the Mullins Center stuck around
after Saturday's contest was over. When the University of
Massachusetts Minutemen packed up and headed off the court after
their 82-52 triumph over Atlantic 10 foe Fordham, the faithful gave
them a rousing ovation and didn't stop clapping until the home team
was out of view.
</P>
<P>
   There is joy again is Western Massachusetts. The much-maligned
Minutemen, facing what some had coined a must-win situation, staged
arguably their most significant triumph of the year _ holding the
A-10's highest-scoring team 28 points below its average while
scoring the third-most points they've tallied all season.
</P>
<P>
   Even UMass coach Bruiser Flint was seen smiling. His team
improved to 7-7 overall, 1-1 in league play, and snapped a
three-game losing streak. Due to a break in the schedule, Flint's
team has one week to savor the triumph, and the coach hopes it help
the Minutemen turn their season around.
</P>
<P>
   ``We've been up and down, up and down, but I keep saying that
there's a lot of basketball left to play,'' said Flint, whose team
held the Rams to 21 first-half points, a low for any UMass opponent
this season.
</P>
<P>
   Monty Mack had a game-high 22 points and Chris Kirkland added 21
points and five steals for the Minutemen, who avoided starting 0-2
in A-10 play for the first time since 1988-89.
</P>
<P>
   The UMass players credited a team meeting Friday with the
improved performance.
</P>
<P>
   ``We played with a sense of urgency,'' said guard Shannon Crooks
(10 points, 4 steals, 2 blocks). ``We told each other, `We're not
going to lose this game, no matter what.' This is the best feeling
I've felt all year.''
</P>
<P>
   The Minutemen still shot poorly (40 percent) from the floor, but
you would never know it from their output.
</P>
<P>
   Trailing, 6-3, early, UMass used a full-court press to force
steals and gain transition buckets en route to a 15-0 run and 18-6
lead with 11:02 left in the first half.
</P>
<P>
   Fordham cut the lead to 18-11, but the Minutemen, who have have
had trouble maintaining large leads, regrouped for a 31-21 edge at
intermission.
</P>
<P>
   The closest Fordham came in the second half was 32-23 with 19:31
left on a jumper by Teremun Johnson. As they did in the first half,
the Minutemen went on a 15-0 burst to lead, 47-23, with 14:48
remaining.
</P>
<P>
   ``We were into this game early,'' said Fordham coach Bob Hill.
``I thought we had a decent presence defensively. But when they
started to press we lost our composure. They had a nice little run
that got them control of the game and in the process it became an
up-and-down game and they were just jumping over us.''
</P>
<P>
   Bevon Robin led Fordham with 13 points but made just 2 of 8
shots from the floor. The Rams (7-7, 0-2) shot 30 percent from the
floor, including 27 percent in the second half.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think we can beat teams shooting 40 percent if we don't
shoot in the 30s,'' said Flint, whose team outscored Fordham, 32-6,
on the fast break.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
----- &QC; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Flint said junior college transfer guard JoVann Johnson has yet
to return to school since telling the coach about a death in his
family during the Christmas break.
</P>
<P>
   ``I call him every day and leave messages, and I haven't heard
from him,'' said Flint about the player he recruited to help the
team's outside shooting woes. ``The thing is, his teammates call
him, too, because they're concerned about him.''
</P>
</TEXT>
