<HEADER>
A0643 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u s BC-HKN-NHLNOTES-FANKHOUS     01-08 2681
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-HKN-NHLNOTES-FANKHOUSER-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
ATLANTA IS FANKHOUSER'S BEST STOP 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By KEVIN PAUL DUPONT  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Scott Fankhouser, last seen around here as UMass-Lowell's No. 1
netminder, now holds down that same job for the Atlanta Thrashers.
That's as of today. To start the season, he held that title for the
Greenville Grrrowl in the East Coast Hockey League. A few weeks
later, he was the top puckstopper for the Orlando Solar Bears in
the IHL.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm starting to learn with pro hockey,'' said Fankhouser,
``you've just got to make the most of your breaks. I realize, hey,
I could be back in the East Coast League next week. You've just got
to hope you find a niche and play it.''
</P>
<P>
   Unlike most young netminders in the league, the 24-year-old
Fankhouser prefers the old-time standup style of puckstopping. He
doesn't have that Dominik Hasek flop-around style, or the
much-copied Patrick Roy butterfly style.
</P>
<P>
   ``If I start flying around out there, I'll get beat,'' said
Fankhouser, who signed with Atlanta as a free agent last summer,
after going 16-14-0 with UMass-Lowell last season. ``I'll go out
and handle the puck some _ because that helps your defense _ but
otherwise I stay in there and stay up straight, just kind of let
the puck hit me.''
</P>
<P>
   As a kid in Littleton, Colo., Fankhouser was a Rockies fan, but
it was Oiler goalie Grant Fuhr, the Hall of Famer-to-be, who caught
his attention. To this day, he keeps an Oiler pennant, signed by
Fuhr, hanging in his room back in Littleton.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't play like him, not by any stretch of the
imagination,'' said Fankhouser, who was in net for a win over the
Capitals Thursday night, lifting his record to 2-2-1 with a
sparkling .913 save percentage. ``Grant made those big, quick,
flamboyant saves. That's not me. I'm more the Kirk McLean style.
But I just loved the way Grant played. He was by far the most
exciting goalie to watch, I think.''
</P>
<P>
   Originally drafted by St. Louis, the 6-foot-2-inch Fankhouser
was never signed by the Blues and ultimately caught on with the
Thrashers as a free agent, getting a three-way deal that guaranteed
him only $18,000 to play in Greenville. After quickly moving up to
Orlando after going 6-1 with the Grrrowl, he got the call to
Atlanta after only one start with the Solar Bears.
</P>
<P>
   ``We had some injuries,'' said Atlanta general manager Don
Waddell, ``and to be honest, the closest I figured Scott would get
to NHL ice would be to drink out of the water bottle.''
</P>
<P>
   Now, after a couple of weeks of observing Fankhouser's steady
play, Waddell is more impressed with each of his starts.
</P>
<P>
   ``He's just so cool, calm, and collected,'' said Waddell. ``He
doesn't scramble or panic. He took over in a game against the
Flyers and stopped (Eric) Lindros on a breakaway.''
</P>
<P>
   In about a month, top netminder Damian Rhodes will be off the
injured list. Rhodes and Norm Maracle have been considered the
short- and long-term solutions in the Atlanta net, but Fankhouser
has upset that equation with his steady hand and confidence.
</P>
<P>
   ``We want to be careful,'' said Waddell. ``There's no question
he has a future in the NHL. Does that future have to be now? Not
necessarily. We've all seen goalies, like Jim Carey, who get
everyone caught up and then see it disappear. We're an expansion
team and we're not trying to do our best for today _ we're trying
to do what will be best for the next 10 years.''
</P>
<P>
   But Waddell is well aware of the impact winning can have on an
expansion city. With Fankhouser's win over Washington, the
Thrashers were on a two-game winning streak.
</P>
<P>
   ``Heck,'' he said, ``if we ever won three in a row, half the
city would be out getting their fingers fit for Stanley Cup rings.
And you know what, I might be one of 'em.''
</P>
<P>
   A primo rumor
</P>
<P>
   While Jason Allison's one-year contract extension was being
tidied up Thursday, a rumor making its way around the league had
the Bruins shoring up their sagging center spot with a trade that
would see netminder Byron Dafoe dealt to the Carolina Hurricanes
for free agent holdout Keith Primeau.
</P>
<P>
   ``That's definitely news to us,'' said Todd Reynolds, the former
Northeastern netminder who is one of Primeau's agents. ``We haven't
heard Boston before, but it wouldn't surprise me if something
happened soon, and it wouldn't surprise me if he went to a club no
one's talked about much, and that it happens overnight.''
</P>
<P>
   Reports in the last few weeks had the 28-year-old Primeau
landing in New York (Rangers), Philadelphia, and Phoenix. Just
before New Year's, Phoenix reportedly was prepared to swap Keith
Tkachuk to Carolina, with the 6-foot-4-inch, 210-pound Primeau
agreeing to a four-year deal worth slightly more than $4 million a
year. That was until Hurricanes owner Peter Karmanos took a harder
look at Tkachuk's deal, which calls for the former BU forward to
earn in excess of $8 million next season.
</P>
<P>
   ``Keith Tkachuk,'' said Karmanos, who never verified that the
offer was on the table, ``has a stupid contract.''
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile, the powerful Primeau bounces back and forth between
his family in suburban Raleigh and regular workouts in Ontario.
Last week, he was back in North Carolina, while the Hurricanes were
picking up 2 points on Causeway Street. He was Carolina's top point
producer last season, with 30 goals and 62 points _ production that
would have ranked third on the Bruins in 1998-99.
</P>
<P>
   ``A number of teams have expressed interest in Keith,'' said
Reynolds, confirming the three aforementioned clubs. ``Los Angeles
and St. Louis made some inquiries, too, but we haven't heard from
Boston.''
</P>
<P>
   It would be highly unlikely for Boston to swap for a such a
high-priced free agent without first talking to his
representatives.
</P>
<P>
   Would such a deal make sense for the Bruins? In many ways, yes.
</P>
<P>
   For the better part of six weeks, it has been a struggling,
unentertaining club; witness Thursday night's debacle at the hands
of the Hurricanes. As of Friday morning, only five of the 15 clubs
in the Eastern Conference had fewer victories than Boston. Clearly,
it's a team in need of an impact center. Primeau would bring speed,
size, strength, and some pop to the position. If his hands were on
a par with the rest of his game, he would be a 100-point scorer. He
never has shown that kind of touch in the NHL.
</P>
<P>
   Dafoe held out for a month at the start of the season, finally
agreeing to a three-year pact worth $9.45 million (less the month
of lost wages). He has since struggled to regain his 32-23-11 form
of last season, a result of his own lackluster performance as well
as the club's inability to pressure the offensive net and score
goals.
</P>
<P>
   If Dafoe were dealt for Primeau, who at $4 million-plus per year
would be at the high end of Boston's payroll, the Bruins then would
bring up Providence's John Grahame, the 24-year-old netminder who
filled in so admirably during much of Dafoe's holdout. The Boston
net would be entrusted to the combination of Grahame and Rob
Tallas.
</P>
<P>
   Remember, the Bruins and Hurricanes share a significant piece of
trading history, dating back almost five years. On Aug. 26, 1994,
the Bruins, unwilling to pay Glen Wesley some $5 million over three
years, first signed the free agent defenseman and then traded him
to Hartford (soon to be Carolina) for three-first round draft picks
that turned out to be Kyle McLaren, Jonathan Aitken, and Sergei
Samsonov.
</P>
<P>
   These old houses
</P>
<P>
   Word out of Toronto last week was that Maple Leaf Gardens, now
69 years old, likely will be converted from hockey shrine to
condominiums. If a plan is approved soon, remodeling could begin
late this year. In Buffalo, the latest working plan for the
now-defunct Aud is for it to become a transportation hub for buses,
trolleys, cabs, perhaps trains. Here in the Hub? In the next month
or two, look for Delaware North officials finally to choose a
developer _ it's down to two proposals _ and construction to follow
on a $500 million build-up (roughly three times the cost of the
Vault) that will include hotel and retail space. When the two-acre
project is complete, the Vault's front door, masked anyway all
these years by the Central Artery, essentially will be shifted
toward Causeway Street, where all the new construction will act as
an enticing welcome mat. The last brick of the old Garden was
hauled away in October 1998 . . . The Buffalo News, in its Jan. 1
edition, named Lou Jacobs among the city's top 10 business
personalities of the 20th century. Jacobs, father of the
concessions company that became Delaware North Companies Inc., is
remembered for this quote: ``Wherever a crowd gathers, a lot of
people will get hungry.'' Not quite, ``We'll sell no wine before
it's time,'' but wouldn't Jacobs's words look marvelous over the
concession stands at the Vault? . . . Columbus, ready to enter the
league this fall, hasn't settled on a coach yet. Blue Jackets GM
Doug MacLean no doubt will wait at least until late this season,
giving him the advantage of factoring in the handful of coaches
who'll be whacked over the next four months . . . Closing in on
Terry Sawchuk's league-record 447 career victories, Roy recently
began reading a biography on the legendary, complex great. ``One of
the great things about all this is that the closer I get to the
record,'' Roy told the Calgary Sun last week, ``there will be more
and more things written and said about Terry Sawchuk. People will
sort of rediscover him.'' The 34-year-old Roy began the season with
412 regular-season wins. His 110 postseason triumphs more than
double the 54 won by Sawchuk. Only 40 when he died on May 31, 1970,
Sawchuk succumbed to a blood clot related to his fall over a
barbecue pit during a tussle with Ranger teammate Ron Stewart . . .
His days of line changes behind him, Wayne Gretzky now writes lines
as a newspaper columnist in Canada's National Post (think the
National Enquirer could land Wade Boggs?). The Great One's vision
of the future includes European-based clubs. ``Absolutely,''
Gretzky wrote recently. ``The reason is simple _ television and
travel _ and one day we'll see teams in places like Sweden and
Finland and Germany and probably even London. Maybe they'll have an
interlocking schedule, maybe two leagues would play for another
trophy, the World Cup, after the Stanley Cup.'' . . . The Canadian
government hasn't announced a formal plan of tax relief for its NHL
clubs, but it appears each of the six teams will be handed $5
million a year through 2004 (the end of the NHL's collective
bargaining agreement) to make it easier to compete with US-based
squads. Canada's NBA and Major League Baseball teams will want the
same handouts, of course, and then other privately-owned
enterprises will raise their hands, too. Sounds like a nightmare
that only secession to the US can end. Better yet, how about IPO
Canada, enabling every American to own a share of the provinces? .
. . Lightning GM Rick Dudley on junior star Jay Bouwmeester, the
16-year-old Canadian blue liner who wowed everyone at the recent
World Junior championships: ``I didn't see Lindros play at the same
age, but I've never seen a 16-year-old play like that.''
Bouwmeester isn't available until the 2002 draft . . . Bruins
play-by-play guy Dale Arnold picked up an A in lip reading Thursday
night, relating to viewers that Bruins coach Pat Burns said, ``It
doesn't matter,'' to Kerry Fraser as the referee tried to explain
why he awarded Carolina's sixth goal _ on a play Fraser initially
blew dead. Burns indeed was right _ the Bruins were toast well
before then _ but it was a shocking moment in Boston sports,
emphasized all the more by the TV cameras, to see the coach of the
never-say-die Bruins so casually admit the obvious.
</P>
<P>
   Learning curve
</P>
<P>
   Only the day before he drilled home career goals Nos. 600 and
601, Brett Hull longed for the day when the league would relax its
limitations on curved stickblades, noting that goalies had plenty
of protection (``You couldn't hurt 'em with a cannon.''). Bruins
Hall of Fame netminder Gerry Cheevers isn't so sure today's
shooters would find the banana blades of old to their liking.
``Overall, I think you'd see the skill level drop for a lot of
forwards,'' said Cheevers, who lived through the era of the bowed
blade. ``It takes away a lot of backhand passes and backhand shots
_ now I'm talking about guys who had ridiculous curves. Some of
them, once they had it on their backhand, you wouldn't have to
worry about a thing, it actually helped you as a goalie. On the
same hand, it did make just average shooters very dangerous. It
gave their shots dip, speed, and the trickiest part of all was that
you didn't know where it was going.'' . . . First the Senators'
Vaclav Prospal calls Patrice Brisebois a ``(expletive) frog,''
denigrating Brisebois's French-Canadian heritage, then issues a
public apology, but pointedly omits Brisebois. Prospal instead made
a blanket apology to all French-Canadians and then added, ``But I
never will apologize to the one Frenchman who caused all this
controversy. That's my statement and I'll stick to it.'' Hey, OK,
nothing like a small man with an even smaller sense of diplomacy.
Let's do everything we can to find this guy a summer home next to
John Rocker's place. Later in the week, Prospal's agent, Rich
Winter, came out firing at Brisebois, labeling the Canadiens
defenseman ``gutless and spineless'' and saying he was ``hiding
behind his skirt.'' . . . If Ray Bourque calls it quits this
spring, as many expect, he will have played at least one
regular-season NHL game in no fewer than 53 rinks. Funkiest of the
bunch, without question, had to be the tiny Stampede, home to the
Calgary Flames during construction of the Saddledome. The benches
were so small that players had to sit glee-club style on two tiers
and the boards so high that ex-Bruin Bobby Lalonde could skate by,
his head barely visible above the rail. Bourque got in one game at
the old Detroit Olympia in a 6-3 loss to the Wings on Dec. 1, 1979
_ just 11 days before the Joe opened for business . . . Just back
with the Kings after hernia surgery, ex-Bruin Jozef Stumpel is out
again, this time with a wrenched knee . . . Almost seven years
after the Bruins made him the No. 25 pick overall in the '93 draft,
Kevyn Adams, now in his fourth year of pro hockey, looks as if he's
caught on as a regular with the Maple Leafs. The job: fourth-line
in-your-face pest, a la Tyson Nash in St. Louis (last seen getting
pummeled by Joe Murphy). ``I guess that's a good thing,'' the 6-1,
195-pound Adams told the Toronto Star. ``If the other guys are mad
at me, then maybe I'm doing something right.'' Lowballed by the
Bruins, Adams never signed in Boston and was one of three
consecutive first-rounders _ along with Dmitri Kvartalnov ('92) and
Evgeny Ryabchikov (21) _ who stunted the club's growth in the '90s
. . . The Blackhawks have adopted a playoff approach for home
games, retreating to a downtown hotel for R&AMP;R after day-of-game
skates at the United Center. Who knows if it will translate to
extra points in the standings, but their hotel points will get a
huge boost. It's somewhat reminiscent of the day Mike Milbury, then
coach of the Bruins, bused his boys to cheap digs on Route 1 prior
to Game 5 of a playoff series with the Canadiens in '91. Milbury
then: ``I don't know what went on in every room _ but my room was
quiet.'' The cheap digs did the trick: The Bruins dumped the Habs,
4-1, the next night and went on to win the series . . . Old friend
Rosie Ruzicka, front and center during the Czech Republic's
gold-medal win at the Japan Olympics, retired from the Czech Elite
League Tuesday, hindered by a groin problem. ``No one ever scored
as many goals on me as he did,'' said countryman Hasek. Added
fellow Czech Jaromir Jagr: ``Rosie's been my idol since pee-wee
hockey.'' To see him leave, said Jagr, was like watching Gretzky
retire. Wonder where Rosie keeps that Channel 38 Seventh Player
trophy.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
