<SLUG> BC-BKN-CELTICS-ANDERSON-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
ANDERSON OFF TO HEALTHY START 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By PETER MAY  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   CHICAGO _ Kenny Anderson wanted this year to be different. So
far, it has been. The wins haven't come as often as he'd like, but
the injuries are another story. For the most part, they've stayed
away.
</P>
<P>
   Anderson's health and fragility were hot topics at the start of
the season. Could he sustain a full season under Rick Pitino? The
signs weren't good. In his 1 1/2 years in Boston, he had missed 28
games because of various ailments.
</P>
<P>
   There's still a lot left of this season, but Anderson started
Saturday night for the 32d time. As they might say in Foxboro, he
hasn't missed a snap.
</P>
<P>
   Anderson worked out hard over the summer, hiring a track coach
in Atlanta to work on his legs and stamina. Once the season
started, he hired a personal chef and is more diligent than ever in
taking care of his body. It shows.
</P>
<P>
   ``All I can do is prepare myself not to get hurt,'' he said
before Saturday's game with the Bulls. ``I'm doing more lifting.
I'm taking care of my body. Year by year, I think I'm getting wiser
in that regard.''
</P>
<P>
   Pitino, who has publicly pleaded for Anderson to be in great
shape, said the point guard was arguably the team's MVP _ not
exactly a coveted honor at this point _ earlier in the week. His
numbers aren't necessarily eye-popping, but what sticks out are his
shooting _ 46 percent, which would be a career high _ and a nearly
3-1 assist to turnover ratio.
</P>
<P>
   And the 32 starts in 32 games. ``I was watching some interviews
on TV with older players,'' Anderson said, ``and I watched them
talk about what they did in the twilight of their careers. They
talked about taking care of their bodies.
</P>
<P>
   ``I understand that there are injuries that you can't prevent.
If someone bumps you, or you come down wrong on someone's foot and
sprain an ankle, those kinds of things. But you can take care of
your body to help with other things.''
</P>
<P>
   Anderson, 29, has had two minor scrapes already this season. He
lasted only 11 minutes in the Celtics' sixth game of the season,
sustaining a hip pointer against the Pistons.
</P>
<P>
   Ironically, the team had signed Doug Overton two days earlier in
the event Anderson got hurt. But he was back in the starting lineup
two nights later against the Knicks.
</P>
<P>
   The other brush came last Tuesday in New York, when he strained
his left hamstring against the Knicks. He tried to play with the
injury in the second half, but clearly was hobbled. Luckily, the
Celtics had two days off and he was ready to play Friday. He had 12
points, 7 assists and 3 steals in 34 minutes against the Kings.
</P>
<P>
   ``I've been lucky so far,'' he said. ``I just hope it stays this
way.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
