<DOCTYPE> MISCELLANEOUS TEXT (slug-filter) </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-01-08 22:15 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A0697 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u s BC-FBN-NFLNOTES-BELICHIC     01-08 3246
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FBN-NFLNOTES-BELICHICK-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
BELICHICK'S SANITY IS MADDENING 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By RON BORGES  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   The only lunatics around the NFL at the moment are the ones
whispering that Bill Belichick may have ruined his career by
refusing to accept a bad job under worse circumstances last week.
</P>
<P>
   The NFL is a place where lunatics abound. Many of them are paid
handsomely for their antisocial tendencies, especially when acted
out on what is regarded by many as the holiest day of the week.
Belichick is not among them.
</P>
<P>
   The shame this week does not belong to him for following his
heart (and, to be honest, probably his accountant) and deciding not
to succeed the NFL's version of Bigfoot on the Giants Stadium
sideline. The shame belongs to people such as Jets president Steve
Gutman, who suggested that Belichick was in some sort of ``inner
turmoil'' because he decided he didn't want to follow Bill
Parcells, perhaps the greatest football coach of his time, as head
coach of a team with an aging and infirm starting quarterback, a
$10 million salary cap overrun, and an ownership situation that
will change radically between now and September.
</P>
<P>
   If that decision makes Belichick look like a troubled man, then
pro football and society could use a few more like him.
</P>
<P>
   Belichick has been accused of accepting a $1 million ``bonus''
for not interviewing for jobs in Chicago and Kansas City a year
ago. Both Gutman and Parcells know that is not what happened. They
know the money was a salary increase given him by a kindly man
named Leon Hess and that Belichick earned that money this past
season, paycheck by paycheck, just as they know that after the deal
was done, Belichick spoke with both Mark Hatley of Chicago and Carl
Peterson of Kansas City before they went in other directions.
</P>
<P>
   Certainly, one could call Belichick disloyal or disingenuous for
promising to follow Parcells and then getting cold feet.
</P>
<P>
   Then again, you could argue, as I would, that not taking the
Jets job may have been the sanest thing Belichick has done since
the day he first decided to ruin his life by turning it over to the
NFL's debilitating demands.
</P>
<P>
   The life of an NFL coach, in particular an assistant coach, is
not what it appears from the outside. Trust me, it's better than
working for a living in the real world because, as my old man used
to say, it's indoor work most of the time with no heavy lifting.
It's not putting roofs on houses in February as my father did for
nearly 50 years. It's not making other people's beds or cleaning
their laundry or picking up their mess as my mother had to do for
too many years. It's not real work at all, not in the
back-breaking, mind-numbing sense.
</P>
<P>
   But that doesn't mean there isn't a high price to pay for doing
it. It means 18-hour days and catering to talented but often
childish young men and regularly facing public criticism from
nincompoops who usually don't know whether the ball is puffed or
stuffed.
</P>
<P>
   It means even more pressures on the families of those people,
families like Belichick's who last week had to hear Gutman suggest
that some sort of family or personal breakdown was involved, when
no such thing is the case.
</P>
<P>
   In Belichick's case, one day he was a genius and the next day he
was an evil maniac who didn't know what was best for him. He was
vilified by many Parcells toadies in Manhattan as disloyal,
disingenuous, and disheveled when he made public concerns that he'd
privately expressed to Parcells and Gutman on a number of
occasions. Those concerns continued to grow as the sale of the team
dragged on for one reason _ because John Hess and Gutman were
trying to wring every nickel they could out of it after Leon Hess's
son had already inherited $55 million from his father's estate and
stood to get a few million more when this sale is finalized.
</P>
<P>
   This is not to say Belichick didn't have some sort of
back-channel deal in place with Bob Kraft to replace Pete Carroll
as Patriots coach because he probably does, although no one can
prove it. It's not to say making a last-second decision to bail out
when he obviously had so many doubts was completely aboveboard,
either, but it certainly was understandable. But for people to act
as if no one has ever been in such a situation and opted for what
he or she believed was best for their family is the ravings of
lunatics.
</P>
<P>
   I know. I did the same thing myself about 10 years ago, after
accepting a columnist's job in Denver and then changing my mind
less than 24 hours before I was supposed to write my first column.
There were a lot of reasons, most of them personal.
</P>
<P>
   If that makes me a lunatic _ so be it. No one in my family
thought so, and they were really the only people whose opinion I am
concerned about. Then or now.
</P>
<P>
   Belichick made his decision for several reasons. He expressed
some of them at his press conference, when it was suggested that he
looked uncomfortable and wary. No kidding? He's in a room full of
wiseguys and vultures ready to tear him to shreds for something at
least some of them have probably done at some point in their
careers.
</P>
<P>
   This is not a guy who was ever very media-friendly either, as he
proved in his first head coaching experience in Cleveland. Was it
any surprise that he didn't exactly look or sound comfortable as he
announced that he wasn't going to do what everyone in the building
thought he was going to do?
</P>
<P>
   Several nights ago, a student at Harvard Medical School faxed a
local radio host a two-page letter chastising him for calling
Belichick a lunatic and suggesting that he looked like someone who
belonged in a mental institution.
</P>
<P>
   People are entitled to their opinion, and talk shows are
designed to stir up the masses and prod conversation, but let's get
a little perspective, which admittedly is in short supply when the
Patriots and Jets are involved.
</P>
<P>
   What Belichick did was the right thing for him, regardless of
whether he believes he'll end up coaching the Patriots or not. It
was the right thing because he didn't feel right about the
situation for whatever reason, and he's the one who would have to
live with it.
</P>
<P>
   Gutman knows full well that the contract Belichick supposedly
signed five times can offer him as coach no real protection from a
meddlesome new owner. He knows, for example, that when Cablevision
executive Chuck Dolan bought Madison Square Garden, the Knicks, and
the Rangers, he installed his son, Jimmy, as the boss and had Dave
Checketts reporting to him.
</P>
<P>
   He knows, as Belichick surely must, that it was young Dolan who
ordered Checketts to ax Knicks general manager Ernie Grunfeld.
Jimmy is the operational head of Chuck Dolan's businesses. Chuck
negotiates the deals but he lets Jimmy run them now. I've heard
some real horror stories about Jimmy. I don't know Belichick, but
I'm sure he was asking himself whether he wanted to have to report
to a guy like that. That was probably the uncertainty he kept
talking about.
</P>
<P>
   Certainly one can argue about the sanctity of a contract, and
point out that Belichick agreed to this deal in 1997. Then again,
no one can argue that he has any protection from a new owner
because the opposite has been played out so many times in sports
and in life as to make Gutman's protestations absurd. Anyone who
tries to argue that Belichick _ or any other employee _ is
protected beyond getting paid off when a new sheriff comes into the
organization does sound like a lunatic or a pretty naive person.
</P>
<P>
   Gutman, like Belichick, knows that when you pay $680 million for
a sports franchise, you do what you want with it, and what Dolan
has done in the past is put his own man in over the basketball and
hockey people running the Knicks and Rangers and they answer to his
son, who may be able to dribble and skate but that doesn't make him
knowledgeable in either basketball or hockey.
</P>
<P>
   Gutman also knows that he may not even be around himself to help
protect Belichick (not that he could), and Parcells has made it
clear he'll quit in a minute if the new guy bothers him. So where
would that leave the well-protected Belichick?
</P>
<P>
   Probably fired in a year or two. Fired in what he knows is his
last chance in the NFL, because unlike the NBA, NHL, or Major
League Baseball, the NFL doesn't keep recycling head coaches. Most
of the time, you get two chances. After that, you're driving a
leased Taurus again for the rest of your coaching career while
someone else has the Caddy or the Jag and the suite on the road.
</P>
<P>
   Understanding that, Belichick wanted one thing. He wanted to
have full control. He didn't want Bill Parcells or Jimmy Dolan or
Dave Checketts or anyone else telling him what to do. Not, at
least, in the matters of his football career.
</P>
<P>
   So he walked.
</P>
<P>
   Call that decision what you will. There is no one wearing a
white hat here. There is no moral high ground for anyone involved,
including Kraft. All sides are reaping what they sowed, in one way
or another.
</P>
<P>
   Just don't call it the action of a lunatic or a man suffering
inner turmoil. Even by the NFL's standards, that was a low blow.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Hard reality in Big Easy
</P>
<P>
   When Saints owner Tom Benson called in Mike Ditka and Bill
Kuharich to fire them last week, no one was more shocked than
Ditka, who had convinced himself he would get at least one more
year in New Orleans despite going 6-10, 6-10, and 3-13. Kuharich
was more rational, although he was still shocked to hear the words
eight months after he'd been given a four-year contract extension
as club president and general manager. ``Until somebody actually
says the words, it's hard to believe, although I understand the
record has not been what Tom or any of us had hoped,'' said
Kuharich, who would have entered his 15th year with the Saints next
month. ``This is the first time I haven't had a job in football
since the USFL folded. It was very hard not to get up and go to
work the next day.'' Although Ditka, 60, said he was finished with
coaching, Kuharich is only 46 and hopes to find another
front-office position in personnel. ``I was brought up in
football,'' Kuharich said. ``I've been in it my whole life. But
there are only 31 GM jobs. I know what that means.'' What it
probably means is that Kuharich will have to move back into a
lower-level personnel job. Kuharich defended the move that he and
Ditka made last spring to trade their entire draft for running back
Ricky Williams, whose injury-plagued rookie season was a large part
of the reason things didn't work out for the Saints. ``Everyone was
in agreement in April when we did it,'' Kuharich said. ``That trade
can't be judged on one season. He had over 800 yards and only
played in 10 games. That's well over 1,000 if he'd stayed healthy.
You have to look back on it in three or four years and see how he's
done and how the people taken with those picks do.''. . . Best bet
in the NFL may be for the Rams to reach the Super Bowl. St. Louis
is undefeated at the TWA Dome (8-0), have won by an average margin
of 25 points at home, and have home-field advantage throughout the
playoffs. ``The Rams might run the table and go to the Super
Bowl,'' said Kuharich, whose Saints played the Rams twice and were
battered by their offense. ``They are legit, and as long as they
play at home, they're very tough to beat. They're so confident
there that the only team with a real chance to beat them is
Minnesota. The Vikings are the only team that can win a shootout
against them but their defense may not be able to hold the Rams in
check. Tampa can't play the game close enough because the Rams have
too many explosive weapons. They have three things going for them:
Mike Martz, their offensive coordinator; their quarterback (Kurt
Warner) has not had a bad game; and Marshall (Faulk). They can beat
you with Faulk, and if you try to stop him, they beat you with
(Isaac) Bruce and the quarterback.'' . . . Many have suggested that
the 13-3 Rams are a mirage because they played only three teams
with a winning record (Tennessee, Detroit, and Baltimore) and lost
to two of them while beating teams with an aggregate 38-83 mark. No
one can say that such a schedule wouldn't help anyone, even the
Patriots, but here's what Rams All-Pro defensive end Kevin Carter,
who led the NFL in sacks, had to say about it: ``Our record speaks
for itself. We don't worry about what the critics say. All we can
really control and worry about is what we do on Sunday. Everyone
said the Giants were going to come in and test us because they were
a team with a winning record a couple weeks ago and they had been
known to be tough in December and hadn't lost under (Jim) Fassel in
December, yet we took it to 'em. When they see us playing in the
Super Bowl, then they'll really know.'' . . . Don't bet against the
Titans in the AFC, either. Tennessee went 3-0 against the Rams and
Jaguars while the rest of the NFL went 2-27 against them.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Bonus could be an onus
</P>
<P>
   Linebacker Mo Lewis reportedly has been offered the largest
signing bonus the Jets have handed out since Parcells arrived. It
exceeds the $6.2 million given to quarterback Vinny Testaverde a
year ago but is probably less than the $7.5 million bonus Curtis
Martin took as part of his deal to defect from the Patriots. It
would still be larger than Martin's signing bonus, which was only
$4.2 million; the rest came as a $3.3 million roster bonus received
seven days after signing, a poison pill that prevented the Patriots
from matching. That bonus only complicates things for the Jets,
though. They are more than $10 million over next season's projected
salary cap, and an executive familiar with the team said, ``I see
why Belichick bailed. It's going to be very hard to be better than
8-8 with that team. Parcells is a genius in many ways. One of them
is in knowing when to leave.'' . . . The Dolphins' offense has
stalled for many of the same reasons the Patriots' did. They can't
run the ball and have been abysmal in the red zone. Miami enters
the postseason ranked 23d in red-zone production. Miami has scored
a touchdown only 41.2 percent of the time (21 of 51 attempts) from
inside the 20. The only worse playoff team is Tampa, at 33.3
percent (15 touchdowns in 45 tries). The Patriots were the worst in
the AFC, scoring a touchdown 37 percent of the time (17 of 46).
Tampa was the least-productive team inside the red zone in the NFL
. . . Here's how backward things are in Dallas. Going into the
season, the Cowboys were 53-9 when Emmitt Smith rushed for 100
yards. This season, they went 3-5 when he did it and lost five of
the last six such times. This flies in the face of the league
trend, as teams won better than 75 percent of the time a back ran
for 100 yards or more. Smith, by the way, was supposed to be washed
up two years ago. Well, he was 8 yards shy of the NFC rushing title
this year and finished with 1,397 yards to leave him only 2,764
yards short of breaking Walter Payton's all-time record . . . Is
there any chance the Cleveland Browns will draft anyone but Florida
State wide receiver Peter Warrick with the first pick in April's
draft? Not unless he gets hit by a bus. The show he put on against
Virginia Tech in the Sugar Bowl was a far better advertisement for
his talents than winning the Heisman. Browns quarterback Tim Couch
even joked recently that he plans to walk into personnel director
Dwight Clark's office singing the Florida State fight song . . .
Here's a sad song for Kraft. The Patriots were third, behind the
Browns and Packers, in total salary in 1999, spending $75,072,400.
The six highest-paying teams and seven of the top 10 didn't even
manage winning records . . . Why should ex-Redskins executive
Charley Casserly land himself a job running an NFL team? Here's one
reason: The Redskins were 30th in the league in salary in 1999,
spending $50,641,800, and finished atop the NFC East with a 10-6
record. Casserly was in Houston Friday to talk with owner Bob
McNair about a job running his football operation. Benson and Kraft
could help themselves by bringing Casserly in to run the football
operation. The irony if Casserly landed with the Saints would be
obvious. He's the guy who made the deal that sent Williams there
and set up the Redskins for the future with a shopping cart full of
draft picks.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   In this corner . . .
</P>
<P>
   While the Rams were in Philadelphia over the New Year's holiday
preparing to play a meaningless final game with the Eagles, the
team brass grew concerned about how to keep them focused on the
game. So the players were shown a film of the first Ali-Frazier
fight at Madison Square Garden and, on game day, Frazier was
brought in to address the team. The Rams didn't win, but they
played far better than anyone hoped . . . According to a new rating
system for kickers that began this year, Miami's Olindo Mare was
the league's top kicker in part because he set a league record with
39 field goals in 46 attempts for a total of 1,364 yards. New
England's Adam Vinatieri was, like his team, in the middle of the
pack. Vinatieri finished 14th, going 26 of 33 and 807 yards. San
Francisco's Wade Richey was the most accurate kicker in the league,
hitting 21 of 23 (91.3 percent) . . . When the Redskins were
regularly reaching the playoffs under Joe Gibbs, they would
annually wear T-shirts extolling one of their team's virtues. Few
people in the organization remember those days because Washington
has not been in the playoffs in seven years. But equipment manager
Jay Brunetti does remember, and last week he handed out ``Believe
in Stephen'' T-shirts, a reference to NFC-leading rusher Stephen
Davis. The same company that used to make the shirts that extolled
``The Hogs'' and ``Riggo's Rangers'' cranked out the ones for Davis
in time for the playoffs . . . Somebody had better check the water
up there in Buffalo. Not only did Wade Phillips bench our Doug
(Flutie) after he led the Bills into the playoffs, but wide
receiver Andre Reed went on his Web site this week and ripped the
organization and Flutie. Writing on something called
AthleteDirect.com, Reed criticized the way the Bills got him the
ball last week to allow him to pass Art Monk and become No. 2 in
NFL history in receptions with 941, one more than Monk. Here's how
Reed saw the five catches he made in what may have been his final
regular-season game for the Bills: ``The record was great but I
think I wept because of a lot of other things. It wasn't just a
happy moment for me but also frustration. The five balls that I did
catch weren't even routes and that just makes me look bad, like
they have to give me charity throws. They've just been throwing me
bones to make me happy, but I'm not happy at all . . . They know I
don't want to be here anymore. It'll be a chip on my shoulder for a
long long time.'' What? The fact that they threw him probably twice
as many balls in his career as he caught? Gimme a break. But Reed
wasn't finished. Like Phillips, he piled on Flutie. The benching,
he wrote, ``It ``certainly was a shock to everyone . . . but you
may have heard that I'm not on speaking terms with Doug Flutie.
Doug Flutie has changed as a person over one year and (offensive
coordinator) Joe Pendry has had a plan for me from day one. You
don't do that to people because it comes back to bite you.'' Who is
doing Reed's biographical movie _ Oliver Stone?
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
