<SLUG> BC-FBN-BILLS-REPLAY-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
ALL OLD CONCERNS REPLAYED 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By MICHAEL MADDEN  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   NASHVILLE _ The National Football League re-instituted its
replay process mainly so that playoff games or a Super Bowl would
not be decided by an incorrect call. Saturday the new replay rule
got its first playoff test, and it left many, and not just the
Buffalo Bills, muttering.
</P>
<P>
   On the game's most controversial replay, with 16 seconds left,
the lateral from the Titans' Frank Wycheck to Kevin Dyson that led
to a 75-yard kickoff return for a touchdown that won the game for
Tennessee, referee Phil Luckett gave his interpretation to a pool
reporter.
</P>
<P>
   ``The line judge's intial ruling was that it was not a forward
pass,'' said Luckett. ``Taking from where the pass left the
passer's hand right on that (25-)yard line, the receiver catches it
right there on that yard line. It did not appear to be a forward
pass; therefore there is not a foul.''
</P>
<P>
   Despite Luckett's ruling, it appeared that Wycheck threw his
pass from inside the 25 and, even more clearly, that Dyson caught
the pass over the 25.
</P>
<P>
   Another controversial replay ruling by Luckett just before the
half had him somehow able to distinguish that Titans QB Steve
McNair went out of bounds on a third down scramble about 4 to 5
inches farther upfield than initially ruled.
</P>
<P>
   The Titans were able to get a first down on Luckett's ruling,
and that led to a 40-yard field goal by Al Del Greco as time
expired. Those 3 points, which gave the Titans a 12-0 lead, would
have a direct influence on the wild plays at the end of the game.
</P>
<P>
   Buffalo coach Wade Phillips, though, chose to take the high
road. ``I don't want to comment on that,'' said Phillips when asked
about Luckett's rulings. ``That's what replay is for. That's why we
put it in.''
</P>
<P>
   The Titans had a primitive and cautious offense for much of the
game, making their creative last-second play all the more
astounding. ``I haven't seen anything like that since I've been in
this league,'' said Buffalo receiver Eric Moulds, ``or even in
college.''
</P>
<P>
   Veteran Tenneesee offensive lineman Bruce Matthews said his pain
from the Houston Oilers' (the Titans' predecessors) loss to the
Bills in a 1993 playoff game, after blowing a 35-3 lead, is finally
soothed.
</P>
<P>
   ``They came from 32 points behind, but we did ours in 13
seconds,'' said Matthews. ``It's truly amazing; I've never seen
anything like it.''
</P>
<P>
   And Doug Flutie, shocked as all the Bills were, said he never
had seen an ending like this one.
</P>
<P>
   ``You go from starting, to thinking about next week, to we have
to go back and work on next week, to praying for an official's
overturned call, to dropping to your knees in disbelief,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Of sitting on the bench, Flutie said, ``You'd always rather
start, but it was out of my hands and it wasn't my call. My role
(Saturday) was to back up Rob Johnson. It was a difficult thing not
to start.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
