<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FBN-TITANS-BILLS-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
TITANS RETURN FROM DEAD 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By MICHAEL MADDEN  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   NASHVILLE _ The play, the wild and wacky play, is called ``Home
Run Throw Back.'' A football home run it most certainly was, but it
threw the National Football League back into consternation and
chaos. Replay or no replay.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was do or die,'' said Tennessee tight end Frank Wycheck who
threw one of the most famous _ or infamous _ passes in NFL playoff
history, one that now gives the pros their own California-Stanford
finish, minus a tuba or two. ``And the funny thing is I wasn't even
throwing it to the guy who caught it (Kevin Dyson) but to Isaac
Byrd. It was crazy.''
</P>
<P>
   If only that word ``crazy'' could do justice to how Tennessee
beat Buffalo, 22-16, Saturday in an AFC wild-card game with a
75-yard touchdown run off a ``lateral'' on a kickoff return with 16
seconds left. The play, which caught the Bills by surprise, was
bizarre enough, but then it was up to referee Phil Luckett _ the
infamous Phil Luckett _ to put his head under that black hood on
the sideline and watch replay after replay before ruling whether
Wycheck's toss to Dyson was a forward pass _ and illegal _ or a
lateral.
</P>
<P>
   There being 66,782 vocal souls making noise while Luckett
watched the tape and a whole army of songwriters here in Music City
ready to storm the Grand Ole Opry with new choruses about ``broken
hearts'' and ``cheatin' men,'' Luckett took the safe route.
</P>
<P>
   He ruled Tennessee had its winning TD even though it appeared
Wycheck's pass, which was thrown from a foot or two inside the
Titans' 25 and was caught a foot or two beyond the 25, may have
been forward, indeed.
</P>
<P>
   Luckett, it should be remembered, was the person who ruled the
Jets' Vinny Testaverde scored on a plunge against Seattle last
season even though replays appeared to show he didn't cross the
goal line, and he was the one who botched the Thanksgiving Day coin
toss later in 1998 in a game between Pittsburgh and Detroit. ``We
have nothing to prove that it was a forward pass,'' Luckett said.
</P>
<P>
   But Wycheck, as well as Steve McNair and other Titans, not to
mention a whole posse of Bills, were not sure. ``I'm not sure if it
was forward or not,'' said Wycheck. Said Bills quarterback Rob
Johnson, ``I just hope for the referee's sake that they made the
right call.''
</P>
<P>
   The melodramatic finish was set up first by some dramatics by
the Bills and Johnson, who played well as the replacement for Doug
Flutie. A 36-yard field goal by Tennessee's Al Del Greco with 1:48
left gave the Titans a 15-13 lead. But Johnson, first playing
without timeouts and then without a shoe, needed only six plays to
set Steve Christie up for a 41-yard field goal, and a 16-15 lead,
leaving those 16 seconds.
</P>
<P>
   With 52 seconds left, Johnson had scrambled for 3 yards, losing
his shoe while being tackled. He then rushed back to the line of
scrimmage, his sock and tape dangling from his right foot, and
somehow scrambled and found Peerless Price along the right sideline
for a gain of 9 yards, the final yards Christie needed to attempt
his field goal. The heroics of Shoeless Rob Johnson were sure to
echo in Buffalo.
</P>
<P>
   But . . .
</P>
<P>
   ``Home Run Throw Back'' was called by the Titans, and why not?
It was Tennessee's last chance, a play the Titans work on every
week but never have tried. And Wycheck went a step beyond.
</P>
<P>
   ``When we huddled on the sideline, I made sure to (ask) Lorenzo
(Neal), `If you get the ball, you going to pitch it to me?' '' said
Wycheck. But the Titans were expecting a squib kick from the Bills,
``and that's how we usually work the play, off a squib kick,''
added Wycheck. ``We weren't expecting the bloop kick like they
did.''
</P>
<P>
   Dyson wasn't supposed to be on the field, he said. ``I've never
been on kickoff returns before,'' he said. ``But one of our guys
was cramping up and they just called my name out of the blue.''
</P>
<P>
   And that was merely the start of the serendipity.
</P>
<P>
   Christie's kickoff was fielded by Neal at about the 24, and
Neal, as Wycheck had reminded him, handed the ball off to him.
``I've never been involved in something like that,'' Neal would
say, ``and I'd be lying if I said I had.''
</P>
<P>
   Wycheck's only option then, he explained, ``is to throw the
ball. No matter what. It's do or die then, so you have to throw it,
but I don't think Dyson was supposed to catch the ball. Ike (Byrd)
was supposed to catch it and pitch it back to Dyson.''
</P>
<P>
   Dyson, meanwhile, ``thought the play was over with'' when
Wycheck took the handoff from Neal. Suddenly, though, the ball was
flying his way on the left from Wycheck on the right ``and once I
caught it I thought, `Get yourself a TD or good position for a
field goal.' '' And as Dyson sprinted down the left sideline, nary
a Bill to buffalo out of the way, Wycheck was screaming, ``Get out
of bounds so we can kick a field goal.''
</P>
<P>
   Dyson kept running. Touchdown.
</P>
<P>
   And then came the replay, and Wycheck thought, ``It was a tight
throw. I mean, when they reviewed it, I didn't know which way it
would go. It happened so fast, but I thought I at least got it
level.''
</P>
<P>
   ``I'd say this one now moves into the No. 1 spot,'' said Bud
Adams, the Titans owner and one of only three original American
Football League owners left. ``I've been watching this game for 40
years and I've seen a lot of plays, both for us and against us, but
this is the most weird way to end a game I've seen.''
</P>
<P>
   That last play, said McNair, ``was the magnificent turning point
of my life . . . but did he throw a forward pass or was it a
lateral? And the wait was very frustrating, but it turned out for
the best.''
</P>
<P>
   Flutie, who has made a last-second play or two, could only say,
``I've never seen anything like it.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
