<HEADLINE>
HAMILTON GETS IN LINE FOR JOB 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By NICK CAFARDO  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   FOXBOROUGH _ After preliminary talks with vice president of
player personnel Bobby Grier and owner Bob Kraft, Patriots
defensive line coach Ray Hamilton has the impression he will be
formally interviewed for the team's head coaching job.
</P>
<P>
   ``Both Mr. Grier and Mr. Kraft said they wanted to speak to me
about the head coaching job,'' said Hamilton Saturday.
</P>
<P>
   ``I thought our talks went very well and they know what my
aspirations are. We'll see.''
</P>
<P>
   Of Pete Carroll's staff, only defensive coordinator Steve
Sidwell has been interviewed. But the organization is obviously
looking everywhere for coaching candidates in case the Bill
Belichick situation becomes too sticky or too expensive.
</P>
<P>
   The Jets will answer Belichick's grievance Monday and then NFL
commissioner Paul Tagliabue will schedule a hearing involving Jets
management and Belichick's representation.
</P>
<P>
   Tagliabue may come up with a compensation figure by midweek for
any team interested in the services of the ex-Jet coach.
</P>
<P>
   But if the Jets don't go along with the amount, it could drag
out much longer _ though it would be hard to believe the Jets
wouldn't take draft picks for a coach they no longer want running
their team.
</P>
<P>
   Hamilton has been a longtime player, coach, and loyal soldier
for the Patriots. It appears he would be a strong candidate to stay
in New England no matter who becomes coach.
</P>
<P>
   ``I would love to stay here,'' said Hamilton. ``I've spent so
much of my life in this area. It's home for me. But I feel I've
reached the point in my career where it's time for the next level.
I feel I have a lot to offer.''
</P>
<P>
   One coach the Patriots are considering, but haven't formally
asked permission to speak to yet, is New York Giants defensive
coordinator John Fox.
</P>
<P>
   Fox, 44, said Saturday he had not been contacted by the
Patriots. But he's on the team's short list, and could join Oakland
Raiders defensive coordinator Willie Shaw, Baltimore Ravens
defensive coordinator Marvin Lewis, Chicago Bears offensive
coordinator Gary Crowton, and Sidwell.
</P>
<P>
   The Patriots are also is expected to speak with St. Louis Rams
offensive coordinator Mike Martz, Jacksonville Jaguars defensive
coordinator Dom Capers, and Atlanta Falcons offensive line coach
Art Shell.
</P>
<P>
   Fox has been the Giants' defensive coordinator since 1997 and
was the Raiders' defensive coordinator in 1994. His defenses have
started out fast, but the Giants weren't very good late in the
season.
</P>
<P>
   The Patriots have been quiet, but conducting business as usual
in Foxborough with Grier continuing to do his personnel
evaluations. Patriots employees have commented that nothing has
changed in terms of Grier's powers. At least not yet.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
