<HEADER>
A0733 &Cx1f; ttj-z
u s BC-FBN-TITANS-BILLS-SIDE     01-08 0887
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FBN-TITANS-BILLS-SIDEBAR-HNS </SLUG>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
Lowry knew time was right to break out `throwback'
<TEXT>
<P>
   &UR; By JOHN McCLAIN &LR;  &QL; 
 &UR; c. 1999, Houston Chronicle &LR;  &QL; 
NASHVILLE, Tenn. _ When Titans assistant Alan Lowry switched from
coaching receivers to special teams after the 1998 season, he
installed a kickoff return called ``home run throwback,'' a
desperation play they practiced every week but never used until
Saturday's AFC wild-card game against Buffalo.
</P>
<P>
   After Steve Christie's 41-yard field goal had given the Bills a
16-15 lead with 16 seconds remaining, Lowry figured it was time to
use the special play in an attempt to pull off a miraculous
victory.
</P>
<P>
   Nothing happened the way the Titans practiced it every Saturday,
but they got the results they wanted _ a touchdown that gave them a
22-16 victory.
</P>
<P>
   When Christie popped up the ball, fullback Lorenzo Neal caught
it at the Tennessee 24. Neal handed the ball to tight end Frank
Wycheck going toward the right side.
</P>
<P>
   Wycheck ran a few steps to his right. As the Bills closed in on
him, Wycheck threw the ball back across the field to receiver Kevin
Dyson.
</P>
<P>
   Dyson caught the ball and took off down the left sideline and
didn't stop until he had a 75-yard touchdown return with three
seconds left.
</P>
<P>
   ``As a coach, you live for this,'' Lowry said in the euphoric
Titans dressing room. ``When I was the Cowboys' special teams
coach, I saw SMU beat Texas Tech (34-27) with that play in 1982.
This was the exact situation.''
</P>
<P>
   But it didn't include the same players who had been practicing
it every week. The special play is designed for a squib kick, not a
pop-up kick. Wycheck is supposed to field the ball and throw it
across the field to receiver Isaac Byrd, who would run down the
sideline with Derrick Mason, the regular return man, trailing him
in case Byrd needed to lateral.
</P>
<P>
   ``I wasn't supposed to be out there,'' Dyson said. ``Mason went
down (concussion), and A.D. (Anthony Dorsett) was cramping up. He
(Lowry) just called my name out of the blue. As we were running on
the field, they were trying to explain it to me.
</P>
<P>
   ``When the ball was short, I saw Ike try to catch it when Frank
was supposed to. I saw Frank catch the ball, but I wasn't supposed
to catch the lateral. That was supposed to be Ike. I took one hard
step out to make sure it was a lateral. Once I caught it, I was
thinking I should score a touchdown or get in position for a field
goal.''
</P>
<P>
   The Bills surprised the Titans by having Christie kick the ball
high.
</P>
<P>
   ``We did it so their prime returner wouldn't get a chance to set
up a proper return, but they got it to him, anyway, but in a
roundabout way,'' Christie said, not realizing that Mason was out
and Dyson had replaced him. ``When they pitched it to our left,
everybody went left. Then they threw it back to our right, and we
couldn't recover.''
</P>
<P>
   Said Dan Brandenburg, who was one of the Bills covering the
kick: ``They burned us. You want to play it safe, but you don't
want to play it too safe.''
</P>
<P>
   Christie caught the Titans off guard, but they improvised
exceptionally well.
</P>
<P>
   ``Lorenzo should get a ton of credit because the ball wasn't
supposed to come to him,'' Lowry said. ``We hadn't practiced
against the high, short one. Lorenzo had to improvise. He just
handed the ball to Frank.''
</P>
<P>
   Neal had the presence of mind to react quickly.
</P>
<P>
   ``When we run it in practice, the defense knows what we're
doing, but it always works,'' Neal said. ``Sometimes in practice, I
tell Frank, `I'll catch it, lateral to you and you make the throw.'
That way, we'll get more people thinking we're going to pitch it
around and it leaves no one on the back side.
</P>
<P>
   ``You know the coverage team's going after the ball. They're
trying to pin you deep. Sometimes, you can have success if they
overplay it, and that's what happened. It really was unbelievable.
I've never been involved in something like that. It was an
emotional roller-coaster, but you never give up.''
</P>
<P>
   Wycheck, who threw a 61-yard touchdown pass against Atlanta,
tossed the ball to Dyson because Byrd got tangled in a crowd.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was nice to have that kind of kick because it caught them
off guard,'' Wycheck said. ``I ran to the other side of the field,
and it opened up on the other sideline.
</P>
<P>
   ``Everything happened so fast. Byrd was supposed to catch it,
but Dyson did and he found a seam. It was a tight throw. I thought
I got it level or a yard behind (line of scrimmage). When they
reviewed it, I didn't know which way it would go.''
</P>
<P>
   Linebacker Terry Killens got a clearing block for Dyson. The
question became would he score, or would he get tackled with not
enough time left, or should he go out of bounds?
</P>
<P>
   ``There were some guys going down the sideline screaming for him
to get out of bounds,'' Lowry said, ``but Kevin just kept on
running.''
</P>
<P>
   After he scored, Dyson ran through the end zone and into the
corner of the stadium, where his teammates piled on top of him.
</P>
<P>
   ``If I had been paying attention to the clock, I would have
stopped on the goal line and let the last three seconds run out,''
Dyson said. ``I had time to do it. I had a wall in front of me. The
only thing left was the kicker. If I can't outrun a kicker, I
shouldn't be in the NFL.''
</P>
<P>
   $$$
</P>
</TEXT>
