<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FBN-SEATTLE-MIAMI-HNS </SLUG>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
Seahawks, Dolphins running in reverse
<TEXT>
<P>
   &UR; By TERRY BLOUNT &LR;  &QL; 
 &UR; c. 1999, Houston Chronicle &LR;  &QL; 
SEATTLE _ Believe it or not, an NFL playoff team is going to lose
today in the Kingdome and end the season with six defeats in its
last seven games.
</P>
<P>
   The other team is going to advance to the AFC semifinals with
only its second victory in its last seven games.
</P>
<P>
   Instead of parity _ the NFL's favorite word these days _ it's
more like hilarity that the Miami Dolphins and the Seattle Seahawks
still have a chance to reach the Super Bowl.
</P>
<P>
   At least it should be an even matchup. Both teams are 9-7 after
playing the second half of the season like they were trying to earn
the No. 1 draft pick this spring. And both teams backed into the
playoffs with losses last weekend in their final regular-season
games.
</P>
<P>
   ``The only positive is that we got in,'' said Dolphins fullback
Stanley Pritchett, ``because really, we're not playing well right
now. We have no confidence.''
</P>
<P>
   The Seahawks haven't displayed a lot of confidence either,
failing to reach the end zone last weekend in a 19-9 loss to the
New York Jets.
</P>
<P>
   ``Obviously, we're excited about being in the playoffs,''
Seattle running back Ricky Watters said. ``But when you lose five
of the last six, there's a bad taste in everybody's mouth. We have
not been getting the job done. If we keep playing the way we've
been playing, it isn't going to matter. We're going to get beat.''
</P>
<P>
   Seattle squeaked into the playoffs when Oakland upset Kansas
City with a field goal in overtime. It gave the Seahawks the AFC
West title.
</P>
<P>
   ``Sometimes you need to be lucky,'' Seattle coach Mike Holmgren
said. ``You need the ball to bounce a certain way on occasion. I'll
take it, but usually that won't get you to the Super Bowl.''
</P>
<P>
   The Seahawks, who are hosting a playoff game for the first time
in 16 years, never have made it to the Super Bowl. This is the
first playoff appearance for Seattle since 1988.
</P>
<P>
   This isn't a typical playoff game since it involves two teams
that seem to have lost their way after early-season success. The
Dolphins were 7-1 before the downfall began.
</P>
<P>
   ``Everybody talks about us backing into the playoffs,'' Miami
coach Jimmy Johnson said. ``It's a simple deal. If you win enough
games, you make it in. We won enough games. Unfortunately, our
(wins) were early rather than late. But it's the same talent that
won those early games, and I think we can get it back on track.''
</P>
<P>
   One big problem for the Dolphins has been turnovers. Miami was
minus-13 on the turnover chart in the last six games. Veteran
quarterback Dan Marino has been a big part of the problem, throwing
12 of his 17 interceptions this season in the last six games.
</P>
<P>
   ``We spent this week looking at what we've been successful doing
in the last four or five weeks and decided to take that and go with
it,'' Marino said. ``We looked at what we've been successful doing
as a group, not necessarily just me. Simplifying the offense was
our theme this week.''
</P>
<P>
   Another simple reason for Miami's problems has been an inability
to run the football. The Dolphins are hoping to see the return of
rookie running back J.J. Johnson, who has a team-leading 558
rushing yards. Johnson has been out with a severely pulled right
hamstring.
</P>
<P>
   The Seahawks have given up at least 100 yards rushing in four of
their last six games, so J.J. Johnson's return could help balance
the Miami attack and take some of the pressure off Marino.
</P>
<P>
   Running the ball also has been a problem for Seattle since
Watters sprained a ligament in his right knee two weeks ago.
Watters, who will wear a knee brace for the game, has rushed for
more than 1,200 yards, but he struggled last week and rushed for
only 30 yards on nine carries.
</P>
<P>
   $$$
</P>
</TEXT>
