<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FBN-LIONS-SKINS09-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Erring Lions easy road kill for Redskins
 &HT;    By Matt Winkeljohn
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   LANDOVER, Md. _ It might not have come as a surprise to see most
NFL playoff teams put the clamps on the Lions' offense, but Detroit
wasn't playing a typical playoff team Saturday.
</P>
<P>
   The Lions were playing the league's second-worst defense.
</P>
<P>
   Somebody forgot to tell the Redskins' defenders how bad they're
supposed to be, and they had no problems slowing down the Lions in
a 27-13 Washington win much more lopsided than that.
</P>
<P>
   The Lions (8-9) are 0-20 in Washington now, have lost six
straight playoff games, and their final five games of the season.
</P>
<P>
   No team that has ever entered the NFL postseason with a record
of .500 has won, lending weight to the theory no team in such a
predicament deserved to be here in the first place.
</P>
<P>
   Detroit managed 258 yards of total offense against the league's
No. 30 defense. But get this: Ninety of those yards, and six of the
Lions' 15 first downs came on the game's final drive, when
everybody was backpedaling.
</P>
<P>
   Another 58 yards came on a Hail Mary pass on the final play of
the first half from Detroit quarterback Gus Frerotte to Herman
Moore.
</P>
<P>
   Other than those two possessions, the Lions had five possessions
that lost yardage.
</P>
<P>
   They intercepted Washington quarterback Brad Johnson twice, and
began four possessions in Redskins territory, but didn't score on
any of those possessions.
</P>
<P>
   In their first postseason appearance since the 1992 season, the
NFC East champion Redskins (11-6) looked a bit like their playoff
forefathers.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's been a long time. It's been a long road,'' said 17-year
veteran Redskins cornerback Darrell Green, who played on two of the
three Super Bowl championship teams under former Washington coach
Joe Gibbs. ``And it feels great.''
</P>
<P>
   Hall of Fame running back John Riggins retired long ago, but
running back Stephen Davis ran all over the place behind a hogish
offensive line, rushing for 119 yards and two touchdowns in a
little more than a quarter of action.
</P>
<P>
   He left with a sprained right knee early in the second quarter,
but it hardly mattered. The Redskins took a 20-0 lead on the next
play on Brett Conway's second field goal, and Washington led 27-0
at halftime.
</P>
<P>
   The Redskins outgained the Lions 275-117 in the first half.
Davis' effort was hardly surprising, though, unless you consider he
had a sprained ankle that supposedly crippled him until Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
   Don't forget he led the NFC with 1,405 rushing yards.
</P>
<P>
   But what about that defense?
</P>
<P>
   The Redskins, despite incremental improvement the past two
months, have been dreadful on defense almost all season.
</P>
<P>
   Saturday before an announced crowd of 79,411 at FedEx Field,
however, they dominated, sacking former Redskin Frerotte five
times.
</P>
<P>
   The Lions, it must be said, were mostly awful since beating the
Redskins 33-17 Dec. 5 in Detroit. Injuries, and a lack of
confidence in the secondary led to five straight losses by a team
that began the season 6-2.
</P>
<P>
   ``The defensive line was absolutely fabulous. That was as quick
as we've played, and we got a great pass rush,'' said Washington
coach Norv Turner. ``Offensively, in the first half we were playing
a lot like we did in the first four or five games.''
</P>
<P>
   The Redskins averaged 37.5 points over their first four games.
</P>
<P>
   Although they were sluggish in the second half, when Turner
said, ``I thought we lost some focus,'' Washington looks suddenly
like a pretty good match for its next opponent, the Buccaneers.
</P>
<P>
   Next Saturday's game at Tampa Bay will pit the NFL's No. 2
offense against the Bucs' No. 3 defense.
</P>
<P>
   On the other side, the Bucs' No. 28 offense will go against a
No. 30 defense that could be, if Saturday was any indication,
improving quickly.
</P>
<P>
   The midseason addition of sage defensive specialist Bill
Arnsparger as an adviser appears to have helped embattled defensive
coordinator Mike Nolan.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're tackling better,'' said defensive end Marco Coleman,
former Georgia Tech star. ``We have a lot more confidence in one
another.''
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
