<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FBN-COWBOYS-COLUMN-HNS </SLUG>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
Cowboys great example of NFL parody
<TEXT>
<P>
   &UR; By FRAN BLINEBURY &LR;  &QL; 
 &UR; c. 1999, Houston Chronicle &LR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   MINNEAPOLIS _ In a Cinderella season of fairy-tale turnabouts in
St. Louis and Indianapolis, the truth is no foot fits more
perfectly into the glass slipper than Dallas'.
</P>
<P>
   The NFL's Year of Mediocrity deserves a mediocre champion, and
the Cowboys wear that label as easily as a custom-made hat. They
are a 10-gallon Stetson of average.
</P>
<P>
   Parity or poverty? What's the difference?
</P>
<P>
   In commissioner Paul Tagliabue's 21st century, there are no
great teams anymore, only a great number of fair-to-middling ones,
of which Dallas might be the best of the lot.
</P>
<P>
   If they were a feature film, the Cowboys would be Ordinary
People. If they searched for their proper place to tie up their
horses, it would be the OK Corral.
</P>
<P>
   Over the course of a campaign that was about as easy to swallow
as last year's oatmeal, they were 7-1 at home and 1-7 on the road.
</P>
<P>
   Perfect balance. Perfect harmony. Perfectly passable.
</P>
<P>
   And so the Cowboys bring their even-steven act back to the
Metrodome today, which is fitting, because in their previous
appearance they won the first half and lost the second half, though
by a significantly wider margin.
</P>
<P>
   The NFL tries to pass off a season when a record nine teams
finish 8-8 as breathlessly exciting and evidence that everybody has
a chance.
</P>
<P>
   But history says no team that has shamelessly crawled in through
a crack to the playoffs with an 8-8 record has lived to see another
day. The most recent to try were the 1991 New York Jets under head
coach Bruce Coslet and the 1990 New Orleans Saints led by
quarterback Steve Walsh. And neither of those heroes has a gaudy
Super Bowl ring or a special place in the Hall of Fame at Canton,
Ohio., which tells you all you need to know.
</P>
<P>
   Fish out of water have a longer life expectancy than an 8-8 team
going on the road for the playoffs. And floundering is what the
Cowboys have done since their deceiving 3-0 start.
</P>
<P>
   ``We have an opportunity to do something that has never been
done before,'' says head coach Chan Gailey. ``We'll take them one
game at a time.''
</P>
<P>
   Or maybe they'll just take one more game from the Vikings on the
chin and then continue their talk about how close they are.
</P>
<P>
   Never mind history, Chan. In order for the Cowboys to make this
the first miracle of the new millennium and gallop off all the way
to Atlanta, they will have to do something they haven't done since
September, which is win consecutive games.
</P>
<P>
   The feeling from inside the organization has been that as long
as the Cowboys have Troy Aikman at quarterback and Emmitt Smith in
the backfield, they have the makings of a Super Bowl team.
</P>
<P>
   But even with a handful of Pro Bowlers on defense, who have for
the most part held up their side of the bargain, Aikman and Smith
have not been nearly enough.
</P>
<P>
   There is some belief that it is Gailey's stultifyingly dull
offense _ even with the addition of Rocket Ismail _ that has kept
the Cowboys from reaching their potential and that debate likely
will rage through the offseason.
</P>
<P>
   Club owner Jerry Jones doesn't help the cause by having a team
meeting with 20 veterans that does not include Gailey and by
publicly stating that aspects of the offense must change. Even if
that is true, it sends a message that the head coach is not the
authority who must be respected and adhered to, which is no way to
enter the playoffs.
</P>
<P>
   One big problem is likely more basic _ the Cowboys no longer
have enough championship-caliber talent. Thus, for the long-term
good of the franchise, a final-weekend loss to the Giants, a 7-9
record and missing the playoffs might have provided a more sobering
taste of reality. Not to mention that at 7-9 the Cowboys would have
drafted from the 11th spot instead of 19th, which is a significant
difference.
</P>
<P>
   Nevertheless, they beat the Giants _ or the Giants held the door
open _ and the Cowboys carry their upset hopes and a suspect
secondary into this game against a hot Minnesota quarterback in
Jeff George and a corps of wide receivers _ Randy Moss, Cris
Carter, et al. _ who should start the offseason angst churning in
Dallas soon enough.
</P>
<P>
   But before sweeping them under the rug, remember the kind of NFL
season it's been. Jacksonville and St. Louis earned first-round
byes without beating a single playoff team. Washington is the
champion of the NFC East, but Dallas beat the Redskins twice. What
is there to fear but fear itself?
</P>
<P>
   There is no quality, no greatness. Only mediocrity. And if these
Cowboys can be champions of anything, it is that.
</P>
<P>
   $$$
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
