<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BKC-TEXAS </SLUG>
 TECH-OSU-HNS  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
Oklahoma State struggles to tame Texas Tech
<TEXT>
<P>
   &UR; By JEROME SOLOMON &LR;  &QL; 
 &UR; c. 1999, Houston Chronicle &LR;  &QL; 
STILLWATER, Okla. _ Because of familiarity, better defense and
better competition, conference games are not supposed to be pretty.
But Saturday's Texas Tech-Oklahoma State contest Saturday was a
particularly unsightly affair.
</P>
<P>
   The teams combined to hit only 36.7 percent of their shots
(40-of-109), including less than 25 percent from 3-point territory
(8-for-35).
</P>
<P>
   Tech's best player played the entire game and had more turnovers
than field goals, while Oklahoma State's top player logged 36
minutes and scored only one point for every 12 minutes of play.
</P>
<P>
   Alas, OSU's Desmond Mason got more help from teammates who,
despite his season-low three points and 1-for-9 day from the floor,
managed to claim a 55-47 win over Tech at Gallagher-Iba Arena in
the Big 12 Conference opener for both teams.
</P>
<P>
   OSU, which is ranked 16th in the country, improved to 12-1 on
the season while Tech dropped to 8-3.
</P>
<P>
   Tech point guard Rayford Young struggled to find his touch for
much of the game, though he battled to score 13 points on 5-of-14
shooting (1-for-6 on 3-pointers). But an uncharacteristic six
turnovers for the senior was indicative of how much trouble Tech
had getting into the flow offensively.
</P>
<P>
   ``That's (a credit to) their defense,'' Tech coach James Dickey
said. ``They're very good defensively. They have great help,
they're strong and they talk.
</P>
<P>
   ``We got a little bit fatigued. We just don't have enough
players. We need more players.''
</P>
<P>
   Tech finished with 18 turnovers despite the relatively slow pace
of the action.
</P>
<P>
   ``We kind of knew what they were gonna do and we took them out
of a lot of stuff that they were running offensively,'' said
Oklahoma State forward Brian Montonati, who had a game-high 14
rebounds, 10 on the defensive end.
</P>
<P>
   Montonati also noted the Cowboys' inability to hit ``the broad
side of a barn'' on the offensive end of the floor.
</P>
<P>
   Mason, who entered the game averaging 19.8 per outing, and sixth
man Glendon Alexander, who was scoring 13.7 a game, combined to
score just six points on 2-for-13 shooting.
</P>
<P>
   The only Oklahoma State players to shoot above 50 percent from
the floor were Alex Webber and Fredrik Jonzen, a pair of post
players who are seldom called upon to score in the Cowboys'
offense.
</P>
<P>
   Webber actually thought he would be pulled from the lineup
because of lackluster play of late, but took advantage of one final
reprieve from the Cowboys' coaches.
</P>
<P>
   The 6-10 senior, who had averaged just 4.6 points in the team's
last seven games, scored 11 points in just 11 minutes. Jonzen, who
has been playing more minutes than Webber recently, reached double
figures for the second consecutive game with 10 points and seven
rebounds.
</P>
<P>
   Tech hung tough and with any kind of hot spurt could have
possibly taken control.
</P>
<P>
   OSU took only a 22-18 lead into the half though the Red Raiders
were just 8-for-30 from the floor.
</P>
<P>
   Andy Ellis, who was held to half his average with nine points,
slammed home a follow dunk to pull Tech to within 24-22 less than
two minutes into the second half before OSU went on an 11-0 run to
open its biggest lead of the game.
</P>
<P>
   Tech refused to be blown out, canning enough big shots to stay
within reach of a late run. A 3-pointer from Mario Layne (11
points) and a conventional three-point play by Ellis with 5:46 left
closed the gap to 42-37.
</P>
<P>
   But Tech hit another cold spell, only getting a jump hook from
Ellis over the next three minutes, while OSU got a critical
3-pointer from Alexander, his only field goal of the game, and a
three-point play from Montonati to stretch the lead back to 11
points with three minutes remaining.
</P>
<P>
   Tech again was unwilling to give up, but the Red Raiders could
get no closer than six the rest of the way.
</P>
<P>
   ``I was proud, really proud of the way our guys competed, but
they didn't play well enough to beat a Top 15 team on their home
court or win a conference game on the road,'' Dickey said.
</P>
<P>
   $$$
</P>
</TEXT>
