u s BC-BKC-TEXASA&AMP;M-OKLAHOMA     01-08 0699
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BKC-TEXAS </SLUG>
 A&AMP;M-OKLAHOMA-HNS  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
Oklahoma routs Texas A&AMP;M
<TEXT>
<P>
   &UR; By NEIL HOHLFELD &LR;  &QL; 
 &UR; c. 1999, Houston Chronicle &LR;  &QL; 
NORMAN, Okla. _ The first step of the Texas A&AMP;M tour through the
Top 25 teams in the Big 12 went according to form Saturday.
</P>
<P>
   The Aggies were smothered 78-53 by No. 20 Oklahoma (13-1) at
Lloyd Noble Center. The loss in the Big 12 Conference opener for
both teams wasn't what Texas A&AMP;M coach Melvin Watkins wanted, but
he admitted it wasn't altogether unexpected.
</P>
<P>
   ``Oklahoma is a very talented team, a Top 20 team,'' said
Watkins. ``We knew it would a big, big chore to come to their home
floor and get a win.''
</P>
<P>
   The task ahead does not get any easier for the young Aggies, who
start three freshmen and bring two other first-year players off the
bench for significant minutes.
</P>
<P>
   In the next two weeks, Texas A&AMP;M (4-8) plays No. 17 Texas on
Wednesday, gets a ``breather'' at Texas Tech Jan. 15 and then plays
No. 9 Kansas on Jan. 17 and No. 16 Oklahoma State on Jan. 22.
</P>
<P>
   ``Thanks a lot to the Big 12 office for that schedule,'' said
Watkins. ``But you know what? Every team in the Big 12 is tough, so
you can't really complain about it. It's tough for a young team,
but we're going to work hard and try to keep getting better.''
</P>
<P>
   The Aggies have nowhere to go but up. They provided little in
the way of a challenge to the Sooners, who jumped ahead 7-0 and
didn't allow a point until the 15:24 mark of the first half.
Oklahoma was ahead 19-6 with 11:15 remaining after one of reserve
guard Kelley Newton's five 3-pointers.
</P>
<P>
   Freshman Bernard King, who led the Aggies with 18 points, hit
two 3-pointers to help close the margin to 22-18 with 8:35 left in
the half. It was easily as close as the Aggies would get the rest
of the way.
</P>
<P>
   Newton, who was 5-of-6 on 3-pointers and led all scorers with 19
points, connected on two from behind the arc. Eduardo Najera, who
had 14 points, scored two quick inside baskets to key a 20-7 run
and put the Sooners ahead 42-25 with just under four minutes left
in the half.
</P>
<P>
   Oklahoma hit 8-of-13 from 3-point range in the first half and
built a commanding 47-29 lead after 20 minutes. The second half was
a formality.
</P>
<P>
   ``We had them close midway through the half, but we couldn't
finish,`` said Watkins. ``That's been a problem for us all year. We
play really well in spurts, but we have trouble playing for the
full 40 minutes.
</P>
<P>
   ``What happened, I think, is that their pressure just wore us
down. They were physical, and a lot of our kids haven't been
exposed to that. But as we get into the Big 12, we'll see it a lot
more.''
</P>
<P>
   Oklahoma coach Kelvin Sampson was pleased with his team's
defense and rebounding. The Sooners forced 24 turnovers, held the
Aggies to 37 percent shooting and had a 36-29 rebounding edge.
</P>
<P>
   ``Our traps were good, and we knew how to take the ball away
from them,`` said Sampson. ``Our game plan was to attack. When you
get to January, February and March, defense and rebounding can take
you a long way.''
</P>
<P>
   Of course, it didn't hurt that the Sooners' reserves outscored
the Aggies' bench 42-15. Or that Jameel Heywood came off the bench
to grab a game-high 12 rebounds.
</P>
<P>
   ``They pressured us so much that we were forced into doing
things we don't usually do,'' said King. ``When they hit all those
3s, we didn't do a good job of staying with the (3-point) shooter.
We were jumping in to help, and all they did was keep throwing it
back to the shooter. They weren't missing.''
</P>
<P>
   By the second half, the Aggies were playing only to determine a
final score. Oklahoma ran off 16 straight points to take a 65-36
lead, and King sensed a feeling of frustration among the Aggies.
</P>
<P>
   ``In the second half, we started to hang our heads a little,''
said King. ``We didn't play as hard as we did in the first half.
That's something we can't do. We realize we're a young team, but we
have to keep fighting. We can't give up when we get down.''
</P>
<P>
   ``There's no way around it, you have to play these teams,'' said
Watkins. ``What we have to do is learn from every game we play and
then use what we learn the next time out.''
</P>
<P>
   $$$
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
