<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BKN-NETS-HEAT-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
NETS BEAT HEAT, 90-89  
 (HLW) 
</HEADLINE>
   By CHRIS BROUSSARD   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   MIAMI _ With 5.1 seconds left and Saturday night's game against
the Miami Heat tied, the Nets had an 84 percent free-throw shooter
at the foul line for three attempts. Scott Burrell, fouled by
Alonzo Mourning while attempting a 3-pointer, looked calm, poised
and ready to give the Nets at least a 2-point lead.
</P>
<P>
   But Burrell, who had made 16 of 19 foul shots on the season,
missed the first and third of his attempts. He hit the second free
throw, however, and it was enough to lift the Nets to a 90-89
victory at the brand-new American Airlines Arena.
</P>
<P>
   Miami had a chance to win when Dan Majerle grabbed the rebound
after Burrell's final miss, but after a timeout, the Heat could not
manage anything. It got the ball to center Alonzo Mourning
underneath the basket, but he was stumbling backward and onto his
backside. By the time he caught the ball, he was on the floor and
unable to do anything.
</P>
<P>
   The victory, coming on the heels of consecutive losses to
Indiana and lowly Vancouver, lifted the Nets to 13-20 and dropped
Miami to 21-11. The Nets are now 3-11 on the road. And it was just
the fifth loss in 17 home games for the Heat, which played without
its injured point guard, Tim Hardaway.
</P>
<P>
   Stephon Marbury led the Nets with 20 points and 11 assists,
while Kendall Gill and Kerry Kittles added 16 points apiece.
Mourning led everyone with 23 points, and Majerle followed him for
the Heat with 20.
</P>
<P>
   Ahead by 74-65 at the start of the fourth quarter, the Nets were
outscored by 13-4 over the first half of the period, the Heat tying
the game on a driving layup by the rookie Anthony Carter with just
over five minutes remaining. Part of the Nets' problem was the
absence of Marbury, who left the game after being poked in the eye
at the 9-minute-18-second mark with the Nets ahead by 7 points.
</P>
<P>
   When Marbury returned four minutes later, the Nets were ahead by
only 2. Johnny Newman answered Carter's tying basket with a
3-pointer that made it 81-78, but Mourning followed with a
ferocious dunk. The Nets came right back and scored on a baseline
15-footer by Marbury.
</P>
<P>
   Miami pulled within 83-82 on a basket by Mourning, and Marbury
pushed the led back to 3 points with two free throws. But Majerle
tied the game with 2:22 left with a 3-pointer. Marbury and Jamal
Mashburn exchanged baskets, and then Keith Van Horn hit two free
throws to put the Nets ahead, 89-87, with 1:16 to play. But
Mashburn scored again, tying the game with a minute left.
</P>
<P>
   The Nets could not answer this time, but the Heat was unable to
score as well, and when Michael Cage grabbed a defensive rebound
with 20 seconds remaining the Nets had the last shot. Out of a
timeout, Newman inbounded the ball to Van Horn, who quickly got it
to Marbury. Marbury passed to Burrell, who out of desperation
attempted a 3-pointer. Using a head fake, he got Mourning in the
air and was fouled.
</P>
<P>
   The Nets pulled ahead with a torrid shooting display midway
through the third quarter. Hitting five 3-pointers _ two by Kittles
and one each by Kendall Gill, Johnny Newman and Scott Burrell _
they turned a 57-57 tie at the 6:10 mark into a 74-63 lead with
47.8 seconds left in the period. Miami scored the final basket of
the quarter to cut the lead to 9 points heading into the fourth,
but the Nets maintained the momentum.
</P>
<P>
   Jamie Feick, who ranks fifth in the league with an average of
11.8 rebounds a game, played just 16 minutes and grabbed only 1
rebound against Vancouver while fighting an intestinal virus.
Saturday night, Coach Don Casey chose to rest Feick entirely in
hopes that he would be able to play in Monday's game at Orlando.
</P>
<P>
   Though Feick does not start, Casey shifted his first five,
replacing Jim McIlvaine at center with the 37-year-old Michael
Cage. Casey felt that McIlvaine, who played with goggles for the
first time after being inadvertently poked in the eye by Kittles on
Friday, would get in quick foul trouble against Alonzo Mourning.
</P>
<P>
   Casey's intentions proved correct, as McIlvaine, substituting
for Cage at the 5:43 mark of the first quarter, picked up two fouls
in 1:21. That forced Casey to go to the rookie Evan Eschmeyer, who
surprisingly was more than serviceable.
</P>
<P>
   Though he did not record many points and rebounds (2 points, 1
rebounds), the 6-foot-11-inch center from Northwestern put his
255-pound body on Mourning and battled. He was so effective that
Casey used him for 11 minutes in the second quarter.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
