<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-01-08 22:59 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A0748 &Cx1f; taf-z
u s BC-BKN-KNICKS-CAVALIERS-     01-08 0748
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BKN-KNICKS-CAVALIERS-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
CAVALIERS BEAT KNICKS, 89-86  
 (HLW) 
</HEADLINE>
   By SELENA ROBERTS   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ Patrick Ewing's elasticity failed him as he tried to
play his second game in two nights for the first time this season.
He sat and watched his younger and quicker teammates bounce back
from deficit after deficit until their resilience began to sag.
</P>
<P>
   The Knicks Saturday night had reached into their energy rations
to recover from a 17-point deficit in the second quarter at Madison
Square Garden and took their first lead in the game with just over
11 minutes left on a two-handed dunk by Latrell Sprewell. Then the
bottom fell out.
</P>
<P>
   The Knicks held a 7-point lead with 5 minutes 20 seconds left in
the game but missed eight of their last nine shots. Eventually, the
Cleveland Cavaliers made them pay when Bob Sura sprang free of
Sprewell and hit a 3-pointer with 10.8 seconds in the game to give
his team a 4-point lead.
</P>
<P>
   Chris Childs came back with a 3-pointer with 6.3 seconds left,
but two free throws by Brevin Knight sealed the victory for the
Cavs, 89-86.
</P>
<P>
   The Knicks (20-13) fell to 2-6 when playing back-to-back nights.
Led by Allan Houston's 23 points, they got a big lift from Marcus
Camby (13 points, 8 rebounds) but were unable to sustain their
energy at the end. From the beginning, Ewing was in trouble as he
turned the ball over five times in the first half and finished with
8 points in 23 minutes. The Cavs (14-19) were led by Sura's 25
points.
</P>
<P>
   The Knicks shot 45 percent from the field and had 20 turnovers.
The Cavs shot 41 percent and had 21 turnovers but outrebounded the
Knicks, 39-33. In the end, that extra edge gave the Cavs just what
they needed to counter the Knicks' bevy of comebacks.
</P>
<P>
   To prepare for their second game in less than 24 hours, the
Knicks plunged into the caffeine, rubbed the jelly out of their
legs and steeled themselves for the misery.
</P>
<P>
   They seemed set up to fail. After leaving an aggressive Magic
team behind at Orlando, they were faced with an equally energetic
Cavs team that arrived rested and ready. The disparity in their
energy was obvious. The Cavs turned the Knicks' league-best defense
to mush by building a 17-point advantage with 4:23 left in the
first half.
</P>
<P>
   The Knicks had to either bounce back or give in to the fatigue.
With the help of the fresh-legged and seldom-used John Wallace,
they unearthed some intensity on defense and some crispness on
offense and recovered from their dreadful start by closing the
Cavs' lead to 44-40 at halftime. Although they turned the ball over
12 times, the Knicks were back in the game.
</P>
<P>
   It took a lot out of the Knicks to make their comeback. The
Ewing-led group of starters looked spent as they came back for the
third quarter. Quickly, the Cavs preyed on the languid Ewing inside
and took a 65-53 lead. But once again, Coach Jeff Van Gundy turned
to his bench players and his every-day weapon, Houston. With
Wallace and Camby by his side, Houston, who scored 13 points in the
first half, went on a shooting spurt for 7 straight points near the
end of the third.
</P>
<P>
   Torturing a frustrated Sura, Houston scored on three consecutive
jumpers to pull the Knicks back to within 65-61 with two minutes
left in the third. After two free throws by Charlie Ward, the
Knicks were down by just 65-63 with 1:31 left in the quarter. Once
again, the Knicks had scrambled to make up a double-digit deficit
and trailed after the third quarter, 67-65.
</P>
<P>
   But the Knicks were visibly weary. Although the entire team was
up for inspection, there was special curiosity whether Ewing,
playing two nights in a row for the first time since he returned to
the team a month ago, had any elasticity left in his game at age
37.
</P>
<P>
   It was obvious, at this stage in his comeback, that Ewing
dragged through the first half in a fog. His recent bout of the flu
may have had something to do with it, but he groggily turned the
ball over four times in the first eight minutes of the game.
</P>
<P>
   And yet, Ewing was not the main problem. The Knicks' defense was
slow and uninspired as it allowed the Cavs to hit open jumpers from
3-point range, make uncontested layups and get easy points in
transition. With Sprewell in early foul trouble and the rest of the
Knicks out of the game mentally, the Cavs eased out to a 17-point
lead in the second quarter before the boos rang out from an
impatient crowd and jarred the team to its senses.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
