u a BC-NY-SCHOOLS-CHANCELLOR     01-08 1213
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-NY-SCHOOLS-CHANCELLOR-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
GIULIANI OFFERS A NEW CHOICE FOR SCHOOLS CHANCELLOR  
 (HLW) 
</HEADLINE>
   By ABBY GOODNOUGH   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ The search for an interim New York City schools
chancellor took another abrupt turn Saturday, with Giuliani
administration officials introducing an 11th-hour candidate and
some Board of Education members wondering whether to withdraw their
support for a banking executive whose candidacy is strongly opposed
by the mayor.
</P>
<P>
   Four of the seven board members were supporting that candidate,
Harold O. Levy, on Friday. But Mayor Rudolph Giuliani was
apparently so unhappy with the choice that he persuaded Robert R.
Kiley, chief executive of the New York City Partnership and Chamber
of Commerce, to join the applicant pool at the last minute. The
board was planning to select an interim chancellor in a public vote
this afternoon.
</P>
<P>
   Giuliani's action astounded some board members, a board official
said Saturday, because mayoral allies on the board had eliminated
Kiley's name from the list of candidates earlier in the week. They
did so on the ground that Kiley, a former chairman of the
Metropolitan Transportation Authority, was unacceptable to the
mayor, said the board official, who spoke on the condition of
anonymity.
</P>
<P>
   Officials close to the negotiations said Saturday that Giuliani
did not consider Kiley a strong ally, and that even Saturday
afternoon, mayoral aides were questioning his credentials for the
job of running the nation's largest school system. Giuliani's first
choice for interim chancellor was Joseph P. Viteritti, a research
professor at New York University who has been a policy adviser to
the mayor.
</P>
<P>
   But Viteritti withdrew his candidacy Saturday, after it became
clear that he could not get more than three votes. A board official
said that Terri Thomson, the Queens County representative who often
serves as the swing vote, decided not to support Viteritti mainly
because he lacked managerial experience.
</P>
<P>
   ``The atmosphere has gotten so politically charged that it
doesn't look like a situation that I or anybody could walk into and
make work,'' Viteritti said.
</P>
<P>
   The board met briefly Saturday to discuss Kiley, Levy and a
third candidate, John Jay Iselin, the president of Cooper Union.
William C. Thompson Jr., the board president, emerged from the
meeting to announce that the board would interview Kiley Sunday
afternoon before voting for an interim chancellor at 4 p.m. The
other candidates were interviewed last week.
</P>
<P>
   Further complicating the selection process was the fact that
both Kiley and Levy lack the formal credentials of school
administrators. To serve as interim chancellor, they would need a
waiver from Richard P. Mills, the commissioner of the State
Education Department. Thompson said Saturday that the board was
preparing to request a waiver if necessary, but that it would not
formally do so until after Sunday's vote.
</P>
<P>
   Levy has a bachelor's degree and a law degree from Cornell
University. He is the director of global compliance at Citigroup,
as well as a member of the State Board of Regents. Ms. Thomson, the
Queens County representative on the board, also works at Citigroup,
and Friday she was enthusiastically supporting Levy.
</P>
<P>
   Levy was appointed to the Board of Regents by the Democratic
majority in the state Assembly and several officials have said his
ties to the Democratic Party made his candidacy unacceptable to
Giuliani. Levy's friendship with the Assembly speaker, Sheldon
Silver, was said to be troubling to the mayor.
</P>
<P>
   Giuliani is presumably running for the Senate this year against
Hillary Rodham Clinton, and it would help him to have an interim
chancellor who agrees with his philosophies. The interim chancellor
is to serve until at least late spring, while the board searches
for a permanent replacement for Rudy Crew.
</P>
<P>
   Ms. Thomson was the board member who originally recommended
Kiley for the job, and Saturday, she said that she might end up
supporting him. She said that she would make up her mind after the
board interviewed Kiley on Sunday.
</P>
<P>
   ``These are both well-qualified people who have stepped up to
the plate at great cost to themselves,'' Ms. Thomson said in an
interview.
</P>
<P>
   Kiley graduated magna cum laude from Notre Dame University with
a bachelor's degree. The chairman of the Metropolitan
Transportation Authority from 1983 to 1990, Kiley has had a varied
career, serving as a deputy mayor in Boston, where he took
responsibility for the safety of school children during the 1974
desegregation crisis, and working from 1963 to 1970 at the Central
Intelligence Agency, where he served as an executive assistant to
Richard Helms, the director of central intelligence.
</P>
<P>
   Kiley, 64, also headed the transportation system in Boston from
1975 to 1978, earning high marks for hiring professional managers,
curbing a runaway budget and conducting tough labor negotiations.
At the MTA, he oversaw a vast program to rebuild New York City's
subways, bus lines and commuter railroads. He left the
transportation agency to become president of the Fischbach Corp.,
an electrical engineering concern that did business with the MTA.
</P>
<P>
   In April 1995, Kiley, who was born in Minneapolis, became chief
executive of the New York City Partnership and Chamber of Commerce,
an alliance of corporate executives, educational and civic leaders.
There, he has been a vocal supporter of ending school principals'
tenure, and in 1998 he borrowed an idea from the boardroom to help
the city's troubled school system, suggesting that the city offer
$30 million in incentives to fatten the salaries of
superintendents, principals and teachers if they could raise the
academic performance of students.
</P>
<P>
   The relationship between Kiley and Giuliani has had its rough
patches, with critical comments by Kiley angering the mayor. In
1996, the personality clash reportedly led to the exclusion of
Kiley from an informal mayoral advisory committee.
</P>
<P>
   The year before, Kiley publicly criticized the labor contracts
that Giuliani negotiated with city unions. He also raised the
possibility of letting the State Financial Control Board take
control of the city's finances to solve its fiscal problems.
</P>
<P>
   The mayor's appointees to the board, Irene H. Impellizzeri and
Deputy Mayor Ninfa Segarra, were supporting Kiley Saturday, as was
Jerry Cammarata, the Staten Island representative. Sandra E.
Lerner, the Bronx representative, was supporting Levy. Thompson,
Ms. Thomson and Irving S. Hamer, the Manhattan representative, were
undecided, officials close to the negotiations said.
</P>
<P>
   The officials theorized that Thompson would switch his support
to Kiley if Ms. Thomson and Hamer did the same, because he wants
the interim chancellor to have the support of most board members.
</P>
<P>
   On Dec. 23, the board voted 4 to 3 against renewing Crew's
contract, and last week they terminated it after granting the
outgoing chancellor severance pay and other benefits. Ms. Thomson
cast the crucial vote against Crew, who lost the support of
Giuliani last spring after he refused to implement an experimental
voucher program. Many board members complained in recent months
that he had become ambivalent about the job.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
