<SLUG> BC-BKC-TCU-SOUTHWEST-MISSOURI-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
TCU SQUANDERS LATE LEAD IN LOSS TO SOUTHWEST MISSOURI STATE
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By ARTHUR GARCIA 
c.1999 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   SPRINGFIELD, Mo. _ Coming out of a timeout with 3:12 left and
TCU clinging to a 74-70 lead, Thomas McTyer turned to his teammates
and said: ``This is it right here.''
</P>
<P>
   He was right. Except Southwest Missouri State, not the Horned
Frogs, seized control.
</P>
<P>
   Bears guard Kevin Ault drained a 3-pointer after the timeout,
and Southwest Missouri would complete a 10-0 sprint to close out
the game and the Frogs, 75-74, yesterday afternoon before 8,266 at
the Hammons Student Center and ESPN's national television audience.
</P>
<P>
   The Frogs (9-8) sunk down the stretch, spoiling what would have
been their best effort and biggest victory of the season. The
mistakes, some forced but several not, were typical of a team
struggling to keep above water.
</P>
<P>
   ``Probably 33 or so minutes we played pretty good,'' Frogs coach
Billy Tubbs said. ``I thought the difference was Southwest played
like they were ahead in the game, even though they were seven or
eight points down. We played like we behind. We took chances that
we didn't need to take.''
</P>
<P>
   Such as Derrick Davenport's charge with 4:40 left _ he fouled
out _ or Bingo Merriex's and McTyer's failure to call timeout in
the final seconds to set up one last chance to score.
</P>
<P>
   With 9.8 seconds remaining, Merriex bobbled and then grabbed
Ault's missed free throw and passed to McTyer. McTyer also bobbled
the ball, stopped at half court, and shuffled it back to Merriex,
who never gained control before time expired. TCU still had three
timeouts.
</P>
<P>
   ``We made plays that were not very smart down the stretch,''
Tubbs said. ``We just didn't do things you've got to do to put
people away. They hit some shots and got some offensive rebounds
that really hurt us. At least you should get off a shot with nine
seconds.''
</P>
<P>
   The Frogs talked about calling timeout on the sidelines before
Ault's free throw, which were set up by a Bears offensive rebound.
``A really smart team, which I can't accuse us of, I think takes
its chances on a timeout,'' Tubbs said.
</P>
<P>
   ``We wanted to at least get a shot up,'' said McTyer, who played
all 40 minutes and scored 12 points in his third consecutive start.
``I don't know. I thought Bingo was open. I don't know if he didn't
catch the ball or someone got a hand on it, but we just gave that
one up.''
</P>
<P>
   Ryan Carroll made his first start since Southwest Missouri beat
TCU, 69-60, in Fort Worth on Dec. 11. He scored a team-high 19
points, including five 3-pointers, in 38 minutes. Carroll said the
Frogs played their ``best basketball,'' but had ``a mental
breakdown'' when it counted.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't think we knew we were going to win,'' said Carroll,
who had missed four games due to injury or illness since Dec. 11
and played an average of 21 minutes in the other three. ``I think
we were happy that we were winning, but they had more confidence in
the later stages of the game.''
</P>
<P>
   TCU led 45-42 at the half on the strength of heady play and good
shot selection. McTyer kept the Frogs under control, and Carroll,
McTyer and Estell Laster (14 points) each hit timely 3-pointers.
</P>
<P>
   The Bears (10-4) started the second half strong, with Ault
hitting a couple of 3-pointers as Southwest Missouri moved out to a
58-54 advantage. The Frogs answered the run, outscoring the home
team 18-5 to pull ahead 72-63 with seven minutes left. It wasn't
enough.
</P>
<P>
   ``We made a big step, but we need to learn to finish games
off,'' he said. ``We have to learn to play smart the whole game.''
\Ntagtop:Arthur Garcia, (817) 390-7760
\Ntagbottom:agarcia\Nstar-telegram.com
nn
</P>
</TEXT>
