</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-HKN-RANGERS-MAPLELEAFS-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
RANGERS BEAT LEAFS, 5-3  
 (HLW) 
</HEADLINE>
   By JASON DIAMOS   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   TORONTO _ Petr Nedved, whose name has been mentioned in trade
talks for Carolina's unsigned center Keith Primeau for months, put
on a show Saturday night.
</P>
<P>
   Nedved tallied his third career hat trick to lead the Rangers to
a 5-3 victory over Toronto, their second consecutive victory over
the high-powered Leafs.
</P>
<P>
   Nedved completed his feat at 12 minutes 58 seconds of the third
period when he wristed a picture-perfect shot from the top of the
right-wing circle. Nedved's 11th goal of the season _ his fourth in
the last two games _ sailed past defenseman Tomas Kaberle and over
former Ranger Glenn Healy's right shoulder and into the goal. The
shot broke a 3-3 tie against a team that had been 18-4-2 at home.
</P>
<P>
   John MacLean's tap in off the right wing post on a 2-on-1 break
with Valery Kamensky sealed the come-from-behind victory for Mike
Richter (31 saves).
</P>
<P>
   This was the Nedved the Rangers had been waiting for all season.
Nedved's goal Wednesday in New York in the Rangers' 3-2 overtime
victory over the Leafs was his first since Nov. 24 and had snapped
a 12-game drought for the much-maligned 29-year-old center. Nedved
scored in each of the first two periods Saturday night, both times
erasing one-goal Toronto leads.
</P>
<P>
   Nedved seems revitalized since Wednesday when Coach John Muckler
established the Czech Connection _ Nedved centering Jan Hlavac and
Radek Dvorak.
</P>
<P>
   Kris King gave Toronto a 1-0 lead 5:15 into the contest off a
drop pass from Garry Valk when both Rangers defensemen _ Rich Pilon
and Kevin Hatcher _ went for Valk in the middle of the slot. King
and Kevyn Adams both went for the puck above the left-wing circle
and crisscrossed after King took possession of the puck. King beat
Richter stick-side wide for his first goal of the season.
</P>
<P>
   Nedved tied the score at 10:29 with a wicked wrister. He snapped
it from the top of the right circle through defenseman Tomas
Kaberle's legs to beat former Rangers goaltender Glenn Healy
stick-side wide. And the score was 1-1.
</P>
<P>
   The pattern would repeat itself in each of the next two periods.
Toronto grabbed a 2-1 lead at 6:36 of the second when Mats Sundin
worked a nifty give-and-go with Steve Thomas through the right
circle on the power play. Sundin then beat Richter with a one-timer
from the edge of the circle, blasting it over Richter's left
shoulder for his 18th goal.
</P>
<P>
   Nedved tied things up again at 12:17 with a power-play goal of
his own on a deflection of a Kevin Hatcher shot from the top of the
circles for his 10th goal of the season.
</P>
<P>
   Just 3:01 into the third, the Leafs again took a one-goal lead.
Sergei Berezin fought off Mike York just off the right wing post
and beat Richter after Mike Johnson had skated around the back of
the net and found Berezin with a pass through the slot. Berezin's
17th goal of the season gave Toronto a 3-2 lead. But it did not
even survive a shift.
</P>
<P>
   Adam Graves squared the score a third time at 3:34 with his 14th
goal of the season. Graves tapped in the rebound of a York shot,
after Theo Fleury had pounced on a turnover at the blue line in the
Rangers' offensive zone before finding York in the right circle
with a pretty pass. And so the teams were tied at 3-3.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
