r s BC-BKC-UCLA-WASHINGTONST     01-08 0778
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BKC-UCLA-WASHINGTONSTATE-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
UCLA BEATS WASHINGTON STATE
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By JON WILNER  
 c.2000 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   PULLMAN, Wash. _ The wind blew hard outside Washington State's
Friel Court on Saturday afternoon. There were patches of snow, and
the clouds hung low. It was miserable, with intermittent
dreariness.
</P>
<P>
   Inside, UCLA and Washington State battled for last place in
chilly silence. The announced crowd was 3,189, but the Cougars must
have been counting teeth. It felt like 50. It felt, appropriately
enough, like a game at Palouse High.
</P>
<P>
   Although UCLA played a centimeter better than it did Thursday at
Washington, the Cougars resembled a high school team. They stumbled
and bumbled and let the Bruins do whatever they pleased in an 86-64
victory that meant ... almost nothing.
</P>
<P>
   Sure, the Bruins dodged the Pacific-10 cellar and avoided a
sweep by the league's worst teams. They also moved one win closer
to an NCAA Tournament berth: nine down, nine to go. But in terms of
substantive evaluation, in terms of measuring progress, the game
failed to register.
</P>
<P>
   Not even UCLA coach Steve Lavin, the uber-spinner, could turn
this 22-point victory into value. After all, USC beat the Cougars
by the same margin Thursday night.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's hard to get a barometer as far as what this means,''
Lavin said. ``It's not something we should overreact to. It's not
like a win over North Carolina or USC or Arizona or Stanford.''
</P>
<P>
   Not even close.
</P>
<P>
   File this under Morgan State, Iona and Fairfield and lock the
cabinet. The Bruins (9-3, 1-1) won't have another game this easy
until the Cougars visit Pauley Pavilion in March.
</P>
<P>
   Washington State (5-6, 0-2) has two Pac-10-caliber players,
guard Jan-Michael Thomas and forward Chris Crosby, and both are
3-point specialists. Once the Bruins extended their defense to 20
feet, the Cougars wilted. They made seven 3-pointers in the first
half, one in the second.
</P>
<P>
   ``The scouting report said Thomas and Crosby are good spot-up
shooters, and we come out and the first five minutes they're
hitting 3-pointers,'' UCLA forward Jason Kapono said, a bit
mystified. ``Then we changed our defense.''
</P>
<P>
   The Cougars' frontline is the worst in the league. Their tallest
player is the 6-8 Crosby, a guard in a forward's body. They're so
ravaged by injury and ineptitude they turned to Paul Mencke, the
second-string quarterback who played his second basketball game of
the season.
</P>
<P>
   At 6-5, Mencke had no chance against Bruins center Dan Gadzuric,
who tied his career-high with 16 points and fueled UCLA's
game-breaking 19-6 surge late in the first half.
</P>
<P>
   ``I knew I had to post-up hard and be patient,'' Gadzuric said.
``I think I played a good game.''
</P>
<P>
   Washington State's shoddy defense enabled the go-go Bruins to
find their rhythm and break the 70-point barrier for the first time
in four games.
</P>
<P>
   Five miles from Idaho, UCLA found a slice of Westwood: a pick-up
game delivered straight from the Men's Gym.
</P>
<P>
   Kapono led the Bruins with 20 points, six assists and no
turnovers _ more evidence he has become UCLA's best player just 12
games into his college career.
</P>
<P>
   Forward Rico Hines scored a career-high 12 points. Guard Billy
Knight, who decided to transfer, then changed his mind, made 4 of 7
3-pointers and scored 14 points. The Bruins had 22 assists, shot 50
percent from 3-point range and unleashed their pressure defense for
the first time in weeks. It discombobulated the Cougars (18
turnovers) and turned up the tempo.
</P>
<P>
   Give USC coach Henry Bibby an assist on that decision.
</P>
<P>
   ``In the (Washington State) game, (the Trojans) trapped them,''
Lavin said. ``We're not going to change what we do, but that was
effective. I don't think we're a great pressing team, but in spots
we can be effective.''
</P>
<P>
   Leading 26-22 with 7:41 left in the first half, UCLA took
command. Its press forced three Cougars turnovers, and each time
the Bruins converted the mistakes into baskets. Knight scored from
the right baseline, then Gadzuric fed Kapono for a chippie, then
Gadzuric dunked.
</P>
<P>
   Thomas' 3-pointer cut UCLA's lead to 11, but Gadzuric and Jerome
Moiso countered with back-to-back jumpers, then Knight's 3-pointer
pushed the Bruins' advantage to 17.
</P>
<P>
   Game. Set. USC on Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
   ``After the loss (at Washington), we weren't playing good
basketball, we weren't playing as a team, and we weren't playing
play,'' Kapono said. ``Those are three things that will keep you
from winning.
</P>
<P>
   ``If you're not playing as a team and you're not playing hard,
you might as well play tennis or golf.''
</P>
<P>
   Or Washington State.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
