<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-HKN-KINGSNOTES-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
BLAKE EARNS ALL-STAR NOD
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By MATT McHALE  
 c.2000 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOS ANGELES _ Rob Blake has been to All-Star Games. He has
played in the Stanley Cup Finals and been named the NHL's best
defenseman.
</P>
<P>
   But the Feb. 6 All-Star Game in Toronto will rank up there with
all of them.
</P>
<P>
   Blake, the Los Angeles Kings captain, learned Saturday he has
been voted into the starting lineup for the North American squad in
the 50th anniversary of the All-Star Game, which will be played in
his hometown.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think that is what will make it so special,'' Blake said
Saturday. ``Getting picked by the fans means so much to me, but
playing in the place where I grew up, that's incredible. There will
be so many people there who have had an impact on my life and
career. I don't know if a player could ask for more than that.''
</P>
<P>
   Blake's selection was announced on ABC during halftime of the
NFL playoff game between Buffalo and Tennessee. He was watching the
game from his home in Manhattan Beach, where he has lived most of
his 10 years with the Kings.
</P>
<P>
   Blake, 30, will be joining Paul Kariya of the Mighty Ducks as a
starter on the North American team, which will be facing a team
comprised of players from Europe that includes the Ducks' Teemu
Selanne (Finland).
</P>
<P>
   This is Blake's third All-Star Game, although he did not play in
1997 because of injuries. He is the first Kings player to be named
a starter since Wayne Gretzky in 1996.
</P>
<P>
   Blake said the Kings' success this season contributed to his
selection. They are 18-15-7 and ranked seventh in the Western
Conference. Before this year, the Kings missed the playoffs five of
the past six years.
</P>
<P>
   ``Even though we went through that rough spot last month, it is
clear this is our best team in quite a while,'' he said. ``It has
opened some eyes around the league and that is very gratifying. It
is good to see people recognize who the Los Angeles Kings are.''
</P>
<P>
   More fun: Blake will be participating in the hardest-shot
segment of the Kings Skills Competition this morning at 11 at
Staples Center.
</P>
<P>
   Other events include fastest skater, most accurate shot and
stick handling.
</P>
<P>
   The finals will be held the day before the All-Star Game and
proceeds benefit the players' pension fund. Only season-ticket
holders are invited and 8,000 to 10,000 spectators are expected.
</P>
<P>
   But not all players enjoy the competition, especially after
Florida goaltender Trevor Kidd broke his collarbone trying to stop
a shot during the Panthers' showcase last month. Kidd is expected
to miss 10 weeks.
</P>
<P>
   ``Hell, no, I don't like it,'' Kings goaltender Stephane Fiset
said. ``Anything can happen in a situation like that. The most
important thing you have to do is warm up properly and treat it
like it is a regular practice. A lot of players don't do that and
that is why the injuries happen.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm sure the same thing would have happened to Kidd if it had
been a regular practice. But it always makes you wonder.''
</P>
<P>
   Ziggy Palffy and Jozef Stumpel, two of the league's better stick
handlers, will not participate because of injuries. Blake has one
of the league's hardest shots, but he will be joined by newcomer
Jere Karalahti, who has played well the past few games after a slow
start.
</P>
<P>
   Defenseman Mattias Norstrom is considered the Kings' fastest
skater.
</P>
<P>
   ``There is a little time to show off,'' Norstrom said. ``But
there aren't many players who think it is fun. There just seems to
be a greater chance to get hurt. There isn't contact like practice,
but there are a lot of quick starts and stops. Before you start you
have to ride the bike to get warmed up and do a lot of
stretching.''
</P>
</TEXT>
