<HEADER>
A0769 &Cx1f; taf-z
u s BC-HKN-DEVILS-COYOTES-NY     01-08 0630
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-HKN-DEVILS-COYOTES-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
DEVILS BEAT COYOTES, 4-3  
 (HLW) 
</HEADLINE>
   By JOE LAPOINTE    
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   EAST RUTHERFORD, N.J. _ Claude Lemieux's return to the Devils
this season surprised many of their fans and delighted quite a few,
too. Lemieux left after the Stanley Cup championship of 1995 after
a contract squabble that he initiated and lost. But Lou Lamoriello,
the general manager, brought him back in a trade with Colorado
because the talented Devils lacked a certain straw to stir their
drink in recent seasons. Lamoriello might not have forgotten
Lemieux's transgression, but he forgave it, with the urging of the
owner John McMullen.
</P>
<P>
   The Devils' enlightened management brought them more positive
returns Saturday night when Lemieux scored twice to pace the Devils
to a 4-3 victory over a good Phoenix Coyotes team. Lemieux beat
goalie Sean Burke for the game-winner on a slap shot at 14 minutes
16 seconds of the third period, just as a Phoenix penalty was
ending. The victory put the Devils atop the Eastern Conference
standing, extended their winning streak to four games, extended
their unbeaten streak to eight games (6-0-2) and extended their
winning streak at home to six games.
</P>
<P>
   Scott Gomez and Patrik Elias also scored for the Devils, who put
42 shots on goal. Martin Brodeur, the Devils goalie, faced only 16
shots.
</P>
<P>
   Out of uniform for the Devils for the first time this season was
defenseman Scott Stevens, their veteran captain. The Devils
announced that Stevens was ill and did not come to the arena.
</P>
<P>
   Phoenix scored on its first two shots against Brodeur, who was
starting his 11th consecutive game and his 20th in the last 21. In
between those goals, the Devils got one from Gomez. After one
period, the Devils had a 17-2 edge in shots on goal but the Coyotes
had a 2-1 lead.
</P>
<P>
   The first goal was scored by Shane Doan at 2:34. He beat Brodeur
high on the glove side after taking a pass in the slot from Trevor
Letowski after a Lemieux turnover near the blue line. Gomez, a
candidate for the Calder trophy as the rookie of the year and for
next month's All-Star Game, made the score 1-1 at 5:02 with a nifty
move out of the right-wing corner, skating past Rick Tocchet,
cutting behind a wall of teammates and firing a low wrist shot from
close range to beat Phoenix goalie Sean Burke. It was the 11th goal
of the season for Gomez, who came into the game with 38 points, the
most on the team.
</P>
<P>
   But Jyrki Lumme of Phoenix made the score 2-1 at 6:10 by taking
Dallas Drake's rebound off the end boards and putting the puck past
the lunging Brodeur, who was trying to get back into position.
</P>
<P>
   In the second period, the Devils got the first nine shots on
goal and took a 3-2 lead. Phoenix did not manage its third shot of
the game until nine minutes had been played in the period. By that
time, Elias and Lemieux had scored for the Devils.
</P>
<P>
   Elias, who has been on fire lately, scored at 5:28 to tie the
score at 2-2. Lemieux set him up by skating netward along the right
side and drawing the goalie and the defenders toward him before
sliding the puck from right to left to his open teammate. Elias had
come into the game with six goals in his previous six games and 12
for the season.
</P>
<P>
   The Devils went up by 3-2 at 5:54 on Lemieux's 14th of the
season, set up by Gomez. After Brendan Morrison forced a turnover
high in the Phoenix zone, he passed down to Gomez, who usually
knows where to send it. Despite the disparity in shots, the Coyotes
almost tied the score when, with 4:40 left in the second during a
power play, Jeremy Roenick shot from short range while alone at the
side of the crease. But Brodeur moved his right leg into the path
of the shot and Roenick failed to lift the puck over it. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-01-08-00 2339EST &QL; 
