<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-01-08 23:48 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A0773 &Cx1f; ttj-z
u s BC-FBN-TITANS-BILLS-HNS &LR;      01-08 1016
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FBN-TITANS-BILLS-HNS </SLUG>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
Titans' Immaculate Deception stuns Bills
<TEXT>
<P>
   &UR; By JOHN McCLAIN &LR;  &QL; 
 &UR; c. 1999, Houston Chronicle &LR;  &QL; 
NASHVILLE, Tenn. _ If you are a fan of the Tennessee Titans and you
live to be 100, you will never forget what happened at Adelphia
Coliseum on Saturday.
</P>
<P>
   In an extraordinary AFC wild-card game with a finish so
improbable that some are calling it the Immaculate Deception, the
Titans shocked the Buffalo Bills 22-16 to advance into the second
round of the playoffs at Jacksonville or Indianapolis.
</P>
<P>
   In their first playoff appearance since 1993 when they were
still the Houston Oilers, the Titans staged a fabulous finish that
will become part of NFL legend.
</P>
<P>
   After Al Del Greco kicked a 36-yard field goal to give the
Titans a 15-13 lead with 1:48 remaining, the Bills responded with
Steve Christie's 41-yarder with 16 seconds left that gave them a
16-15 advantage and what should have been an upset victory before a
franchise-record crowd of 66,728.
</P>
<P>
   For the first time, the Titans were on the right side of
history. A kickoff return play, named ``home run throwback,'' was
called for the first time. Lorenzo Neal caught Christie's high,
short kick and handed the ball to Frank Wycheck. After running a
few steps to his right, Wycheck threw back across the field to
receiver Kevin Dyson, who ran down the sideline untouched for a
75-yard touchdown with three seconds remaining.
</P>
<P>
   The replay official in the press box called for a review of the
play, which was close to being a forward lateral. But referee Phil
Luckett reviewed the play and allowed the touchdown to stand, and
pandemonium erupted at Adelphia Coliseum.
</P>
<P>
   ``With 16 seconds left, I was ready to commit suicide,'' Titans
general manager Floyd Reese said. ``I just couldn't decide if I was
going to do it with a bullet, pills or a rope. The next thing I
knew, I was dancing on the table.''
</P>
<P>
   Many of the Bills were livid that Luckett refused to overturn
the call.
</P>
<P>
   ``People who watched this game will clearly understand that we
didn't get a fair shake,'' Buffalo linebacker Sam Rogers said. ``In
a game of this magnitude when lives are on the line, you can't make
a call like that.''
</P>
<P>
   In winning their first playoff game since 1991, the Titans
avenged the most infamous defeat in franchise history _ the 41-38
overtime loss at Buffalo on Jan. 3, 1993, when they blew a 35-3
lead, still the biggest in NFL history.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was poetic justice, vindication for seven years of living
with that stigma,'' said cornerback Steve Jackson, a nine-year
veteran. ``Revenge has been a long time coming, not just for the
guys left on this team but for our former teammates like Cris
(Dishman), Sean (Jones), Warren (Moon), (William) Fuller and
Darryll (Lewis).
</P>
<P>
   ``Winning this game the way we did makes it even sweeter.
Shakespeare couldn't have written a better ending.''
</P>
<P>
   Jackson, free safety Marcus Robertson, guard Bruce Matthews,
kicker Al Del Greco, linebacker Eddie Robinson and linebacker Joe
Bowden are the only Titans players who contributed to blowing a
32-point third-quarter lead to the Bills.
</P>
<P>
   ``People are asking me if this soothes the pain of losing that
game,'' Matthews said. ``Yes, it does. Right now, I can almost feel
the same kind of elation the Bills felt when they beat us. I've
never been part of anything like this. It's truly amazing.''
</P>
<P>
   Robertson, who was injured in a motorcycle accident two weeks
ago and needed 150 stitches in his face, played for the first time
since the accident.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is redemption for us,'' Robertson said. ``That game has
haunted us for seven years. Maybe we exorcised those ghosts today.
</P>
<P>
   ``The Buffalo game in 1993 was their springboard to the Super
Bowl. Maybe this one will be our springboard to the Super Bowl.''
</P>
<P>
   The Titans will have to play a lot better on offense if they
hope to reach the AFC Championship Game. They used a conservative
game plan and finished with only 194 yards against the NFL's No. 1
defense.
</P>
<P>
   Eddie George rushed for 106 yards on 29 carries. Quarterback
Steve McNair completed 13 of 24 passes for 76 yards. Unlike the
last two games in which he was allowed to roll out and throw on the
run, McNair stayed in the pocket most of the time.
</P>
<P>
   The Bills had only 219 yards, including 123 rushing. Quarterback
Rob Johnson, who was elevated to the starting job over Doug Flutie
last week, was 10-of-22 for 131 yards and no touchdowns. He wasn't
intercepted, but he was sacked six times, twice by defensive end
Jevon Kearse.
</P>
<P>
   ``This particular game, from my standpoint, is so big for those
guys who went through everything _ not only that loss at Buffalo
but for all the difficult times they endured in 1995 and 1996 and
the last two years,'' coach Jeff Fisher said. ``We played with
poise, and to be able to win in our first playoff game at home
really makes it all worthwhile.''
</P>
<P>
   The Titans led 12-0 at halftime when Kearse sacked Johnson for a
safety, McNair scored on a one-yard run and Del Greco kicked a
40-yard field goal.
</P>
<P>
   The Bills rallied in the second half on Antowain Smith's
touchdown runs of four and one yards, giving Buffalo a 13-12 lead
with 11:08 left.
</P>
<P>
   When the Titans regained the lead on Del Greco's 36-yard field
goal with 1:48 remaining, it appeared as if they would finally end
the Buffalo jinx.
</P>
<P>
   After Kevin Williams returned the kickoff 33 yards to the
Buffalo 39, the old Oilers reared their ugly heads. Johnson, who
was named the starter over Doug Flutie last week, moved the Bills
to the Tennessee 23. Christie, who won that overtime game in 1993
with a field goal, appeared to eliminate them again, but Buffalo's
celebration was premature.
</P>
<P>
   Like the Oilers in 1993, the Bills found out that games like
this can be all too real.
</P>
<P>
   ``I can't describe how bad I feel,'' Bills defensive end
Marcellus Wiley said. ``It's like they pulled out a gun and shot
down our dream.''
</P>
<P>
   Or, as safety Henry Jones said, ``This hurts more than the three
Super Bowls I was involved in.''
</P>
<P>
   $$$
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
