s e BC-NOTEWORTHY-PAPERBACKS     01-08 0868
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-NOTEWORTHY-PAPERBACKS-$ADV16-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
NEW &AMP; NOTEWORTHY PAPERBACKS 
</HEADLINE>
   (For release Sunday, Jan. 16)  
(lb) 
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   &UR; THE THINGS WE DO TO MAKE IT HOME &LR;  By Beverly Gologorsky.
Ballantine, $12. This generous first novel explores the aftershocks
of the Vietnam War on half a dozen women and their husbands and
lovers who returned from the war scarred and tormented, unable to
blend back into normal civilian life. The dialogue is ``lean and
supple, completely persuasive, full of nuanced turns,'' Jacqueline
Carey wrote in The New York Times Book Review last year.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; OUR KIND OF PEOPLE: Inside America's Black Upper Class &LR;  By
Lawrence Otis Graham. HarperPerennial, $14. The author explores
that little-known segment of black society that has experienced
generations of material well-being and produced many extraordinary
traditions and personalities. The result is ``a fascinating ...
amalgam of popular history, sociological treatise and memoir,''
Andrea Lee wrote last year. ``He has made a major contribution both
to African-American studies and to the larger American picture.''
</P>
<P>
   The same publisher has reissued  &UR; AMERICAN BEACH: How `Progress'
Robbed a Black Town _ and Nation _ of History, Wealth, and Power &LR; ,
by Russ Rymer ($14), an inquiry into race and politics, cultural
erosion, development and powerlessness in a black resort community
in Florida. ``Rymer is a seasoned journalist, precise, attentive,
thought-provoking,'' Eddy L. Harris wrote in 1998.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; THE MUSIC LESSON &LR;  By Katharine Weber. Picador USA, $12. A New
York art historian is recruited by an Irish cousin to take part in
an IRA plot to steal a Vermeer painting owned by Queen Elizabeth II
and hold it for ransom. Last year in The New York Times Book
Review, Sylvia Brownrigg called this an ``affecting and elegant ...
novel about the dangerous subterfuges of politics and the healing
truths of art.''
</P>
<P>
   &UR; CHOCOLAT &LR;  By Joanne Harris. Penguin, $12.95. When a beguiling
stranger opens a candy shop in a small French town and announces
plans for a chocolate festival that coincides with Easter, the
parish priest is driven to sabotage by what he sees as an assault
on the church's teachings. Last year the reviewer Nancy Willard
called this an ``accomplished novel'' that ``few readers will be
able to resist.''
</P>
<P>
   &UR; THE COUSINS' WARS: Religion, Politics, and the Triumph of
Anglo-America &LR;  By Kevin Phillips. Basic Books, $16.50. In this
audacious demographic inquiry into the causes and effects of the
English Civil War, the American Revolution and the American Civil
War, Cavalier aristocrats keep losing out to republican Roundheads.
``Phillips' details are as marvelous as they are copious,'' Richard
Brookhiser wrote last year. ``He has given us a juicy, provocative
account of where we have come from.''
</P>
<P>
   In  &UR; 1898: The Birth of the American Century &LR; , by David Traxel
(Vintage, $15), a historian argues that the year of the
Spanish-American War was a watershed in time that thrust the United
States into world-power status. In 1998 the reviewer Stanley
Weintraub found this to be an uneven popular history that
nevertheless contains ``a fund of good stories.''
</P>
<P>
   &UR; SECRETS &LR;  By Nuruddin Farah. Penguin, $12.95. All the characters
in this Somali novel, which takes place on the eve of the nation's
brutal civil war in the early 1990s, are transformed by magical
intervention and walk the line between the human and animal worlds.
In 1998 the reviewer George Packer admired ``the daring, lush,
urbane voice of the author.''
</P>
<P>
   &UR; THE ART OF SHAKESPEARE'S SONNETS &LR;  By Helen Vendler.
Belknap/Harvard University, $18.95. An impassioned critic dissects
Shakespeare's 154 sonnets and makes a persuasive case that they
``remain intelligible, moving and beautiful'' to contemporary
readers. ``Hers is the most intricately inquiring and ingeniously
responding study of these poems yet to be undertaken,'' Richard
Howard wrote in 1997.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; THE WIDOW KILLER &LR;  By Pavel Kohout. Picador USA, $14. Set in
Prague near the end of World War II, this novel is about a Czech
detective and a Gestapo agent pursuing a serial killer who sees
himself as the avenger of an occupied nation. What begins as ``a
taut and suspenseful thriller ... turns into a powerful and
gripping allegory,'' Richard Bernstein wrote in The New York Times
in 1998.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; BRINGING THE HEAT &LR;  By Mark Bowden. Atlantic Monthly, $15. A
reporter at The Philadelphia Inquirer explores the professional
football industry through the lens of the Eagles' 1992 season.
``His book overflows with stories of pro football dreams,'' Keith
Dixon wrote in 1994. ``Yet it also unflinchingly tells of the
darker side of life in the National Football League: uncontrollable
egos, ruined families, marital infidelity.''
</P>
<P>
   &UR; THE STILLEST DAY &LR;  By Josephine Hart. Overlook, $13.95. A
novelist obsessed with obsession spins a turn-of-the-century tale
about an English art teacher who becomes increasingly preoccupied
with her new neighbor. ``In mood, Hart is something of a
present-day Daphne du Maurier: She writes ominously, creating an
atmosphere laden with mystery,'' Carol Peace Robins wrote in 1998.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
